<html><head><title>The zillion dollar games</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<h1><center>The zillion dollar games</center></h1>

A SPORTING event? Or merely a branch of the advertising and entertainment industry? In the centenary of their reinvention by Baron Pierre de Coubertin, the Olympic Games look more like a celebration of the marketing muscle of Coca-Cola, Kodak and <font size=-1>BMW</font> than a display of human prowess and courage. The gold, silver and bronze that clinks loudest in Atlanta is that handed over for the rights to televise, sponsor and advertise through the games. No wonder so many sports fans blame television and corporate cash for the erosion of amateurism and the endless drug scandals. No wonder they yearn for a return to the days when Eric Liddell pulled on his Scottish tweeds and set off for the 1924 Paris Olympics (where, as every fan of "Chariots of Fire" remembers, he was too high-principled to run on a Sunday).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Of course the Olympics has changed almost beyond recognition in its first modern century. Few of the athletes, especially those in the most popular sports, lead ordinary lives away from the track or pool. Training to Olympic standard takes hours out of the day, years out of a young life. So amateurism has given way to shamateurism: many of those who parade in the stadium owe their running shoes, training facilities and airline tickets to corporate promotional budgets.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For companies, the Olympics is a golden moment. Around the world, some 3.5 billion pairs of eyes will notice their logos, slogans and billboards. Television will bring these Olympics to a larger audience than any previous sporting event (see <a href="sf1.html">page</a>). Moreover sport, with its wholesome image, is a perfect way to pitch products (especially ones that are not particularly wholesome themselves). As ever more brands clamour for public attention, a plug from a world-beating athlete is a way to stand out from the crowd.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The result is that the rewards of sport have vastly increased. Once an athlete can attract an audience of millions or billions of viewers rather than merely hundreds of thousands, his cash value soars. So a top professional sportsman now earns Hollywood money: Michael Jordan, America's basketball star, has just signed a contract that will pay him $25m a year. But those rewards will go not to those who nearly made it to Atlanta, even if their performance is better than earlier sportsmen could have dreamt of. They will go only to the best. It is all very well for the One Great Scorer (in the sonorous words of Grantland Rice) to mark "not that you won, or lost--but how you played the game." All the sponsor wants to know is whether you got the gold.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And getting the gold grows ever tougher. More and more countries compete, as nations fragment: the bands at Atlanta need the music for 197 national anthems. More important, the limits of the human frame in some sports have almost been reached. Champion racehorses run no faster today than they did half a century ago. Eventually, human champions will stop breaking records too. Ever more minute improvements in training regimes, equipment and style lop ever smaller fragments of a second off sporting records. Small wonder many athletes succumb to the temptation to turn sport into a pharmacological challenge, using drugs to push their bodies beyond the natural limits.
</p><p><b>Pay up and play the Games</b>
<br>But is commercial pressure to blame? It is not company money but the ruthless arrogance of undemocratic governments that has done most to give the games their reputation as a pill-poppers' convention. The Communist regimes of the 1970s and 1980s saw the Olympics much as Hitler did in 1936 or China does today: as a chance to prove the superiority of their citizens or systems. If dope was needed to ensure that, then doped their athletes would be. Companies, by contrast, tend to shun athletes found guilty of using drugs: think of the fortune in sponsorship that Ben Johnson sacrificed after drug tests disqualified his win in Seoul in 1988.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The more that companies support athletes, the less sportsmen will have to rely on the state. Is that so bad? Corporate sponsorship ensures that far more money finds its way into sport than would otherwise be the case. Companies, more than governments, have a powerful interest in making sure that sporting events are seen by as many people as possible. They also have an interest in sport that is seen to be clean, fair and exciting. That is surely in fans' interests too.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Television provides the main link between sport and corporate sponsorship. Its effect has been profoundly democratising: people who would once have seen only their local teams can now enjoy ringside seats at world-class events. It has also been, on balance, benign for sport: as television companies spend an increasing share of their budgets on sports rights, they acquire a strong interest in making sure that sporting bodies run their games efficiently and fairly, developing new talent and new audiences.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Above all, the power of corporate hype linked with global television is a marvellous machine for promoting sports. Far more people run or swim or kick a ball for sheer pleasure than ever before. Thanks to television, many have discovered sports they might never have known existed: rock-climbing, perhaps, or archery or synchronised swimming. It is surely better that television and corporate muscle should sell sport and the glory of human achievement than that the Olympics should be merely a way to trumpet national pride.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?838421999,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="sf1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
