<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width=271 height=24  alt="Politics"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>

<h2>Jumbo crash</h2><p>
<p>A <font size=-1>TWA</font> <b>jumbo jet</b> bound for Paris crashed soon after take-off from New York, apparently killing all 229 people on board after exploding.
<p>A <i>New York Times</i>/<font size=-1>CBS</font> poll showed that seven out of ten Americans expect Bob Dole, the Republican candidate, to lose to Bill Clinton in the <b>presidential election</b>. Mr Dole, continuing his gyrations over abortion, named Susan Molinari, a fiercely pro-choice congresswoman from New York, as the keynote speaker at the Republican convention in San Diego.
<p><b>Joe Klein</b>, a <i>Newsweek</i> journalist, admitted that he was the anonymous author of "Primary Colors", a gossipy novel about President Clinton's 1992 campaign. Mr Klein had long denied authorship and said he would stake his credibility as a journalist on the denial.
<p>Oscar Camilion, Argentina's defence minister, resigned in a scandal over the <b>secret sale of weapons</b> to Ecuador and to Croatia. Rodolfo Barra, the justice minister, resigned after a magazine revealed youthful neo-Nazi activities.
<p>Portugal and six of its former colonies launched a <b>Portuguese-speaking commonwealth</b> to protect their common language and promote co-operation. Some 200m people, 160m of them Brazilians, live in Portuguese-speaking countries. Sao Tome and Principe, islands off Africa, have 125,000 Portuguese speakers.
<p><h2>At odds</h2></p>
<p><p>Fierce rioting in Catholic areas of <b>Northern Ireland</b> and the bombing of a hotel followed a decision by police to allow Protestants to march through Catholic areas in Portadown and Belfast. The Irish prime minister accused the British government of backing down in the face of mob rule. Multi-party talks restarted in Belfast but were immediately bogged down amid recriminations and procedural wrangles.
<p>Fearing the collapse of peace in Bosnia, the United States sent <b>Rich</b><b>ard Hol</b><b>brooke</b>, the former diplomat who brokered the peace, to arrange the removal of the Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic, who has been indicted for war crimes.
<p>Russia's President Boris Yeltsin cheered reformers by appointing one of their leaders, <b>Anatoly Chubais</b>, his chief of staff. Igor Rodionov, a hawkish general allied to the new security chief, Alexander Lebed, was appointed defence minister.
<p>Worries about <b>Mr Yeltsin's health</b> persisted. America's vice-president, Al Gore, found him in "very good shape" on a visit to his sanatorium but other witnesses said he found walking hard.

<p>Ukraine's prime minister, Pavel Lazarenko, narrowly escaped death in a <b>bomb attack</b> on his car. He blamed "criminals" opposed to his plans to shut inefficient coal mines. Ukraine's security chief ordered "elements" of a state of emergency, including tighter security for politicians, the sacking of some officials and closer monitoring of state funds.
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%><p>Silvio Berlusconi, a former right-wing prime minister, and Bettino Craxi, a former Socialist one, were indicted on charges relating to <b>illicit financing</b> of Italian political parties by Fininvest, a company Mr Berlusconi controls. A draft law on media ownership would oblige Mr Berlusconi to change one of the three television channels he controls into a satellite or cable service, but he would not have to sell any.
<p>France said it would disband 38 regiments, removing all but 3,000 of its 20,000 troops in Germany, and close barracks, air bases and army hospitals. The plan, part of a change to an all-professional army, is intended to cut <b>military spending</b> by FFr20 billion ($4 billion) a year from its 1994 level.</p>
<p><h2>Open season</h2></p>
<p><p>News leaked of a riot in Libya when spectators at a football match chanted slogans against a son of <b>Muam</b><b>mar Qaddafi</b>. They were fired on by bodyguards, stormed the pitch and attacked the referee. Some 20 people may have died.
<p>Contact began between Israel's new hardline prime minister, <b>Binyamin Netanyahu</b>, and some Arab governments. Jordan's prime minister met him in Tel Aviv; Egypt's president, Hosni Mubarak, met him in Cairo.
<p>Turkey's ruling Islamist party held a secret parliamentary debate on the West's <b>air patrols</b> to protect Kurds in northern Iraq. The debate puts the future of the patrols, which are staged from Turkey, in doubt.
<p>Up to 150<b> Sudanese refugees</b> were killed when their camp in northern Uganda was attacked by a rebel group called the Lord's Resistance Army, which Uganda says is backed by Sudan.</p>
<p><h2>Saving children</h2></p>
<p><p>
<p>
<p>Pakistan ordered officials to raid factories using <b>child labour</b>. The country has often been accused of tolerating the employment of children to make carpets and sports goods.
<p><b>Floods </b>and landslides in Bangladesh and eastern India killed about 130 people and made some 2m homeless. At Ujjain and Hardwar, two Hindu shrines in northern India, 60 people died when crowds of pilgrims panicked.
<p>In the latest of a series of <b>food poisoning</b> cases, more than 5,500 people, mostly children, fell ill in Japan. The chief suspects are roast pork and sea-eel sushi. Four victims have died since May.
<p>At a <font size=-1>UN</font> conference on <b>climate change</b>, the United States called for binding international targets for cutting emissions of gases that cause global warming.
<p>
<p>
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
