<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width=273 height=24  alt="Business"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>



<p><h2>Ups and downs</h2>
<p><p>
<p>(See <a href="wtw1.gif">chart</a>)<br><b>Share prices</b> in New York fell nearly 3% on July 15th but recovered later. The London stockmarket fell to its lowest point this year. Not meltdown, was the initial verdict, just investors nervous about possible overheating in the American economy, falling investment in mutual funds, and disappointing corporate earnings.
<p>Two American high-tech companies, <b>Texas Instruments</b> and <b>Compu</b><b>Serve</b>, gave warning that profits would be lower than expected. But <b>Intel</b>, the world's biggest chip maker, exceeded expectations, reporting a 19% increase in revenues for the second quarter. <b>Apple Computer</b> did much better in its third quarter. It lost only $39m, having lost $800m in the previous two quarters. And Germany's <b>Siemens</b> forecast a 20% rise in earnings.
<p><b>General Motors </b>reported a fall of 17% in net profit for the second quarter, to $1.9 billion. But, excluding the $208.8m cost of spinning off <b>Electronic Data Systems</b>, a subsidiary, this was a slight increase on the previous year. <b>Ford</b> also announced an encouraging rise in earnings, contributed mainly by its financial-services arm.
<p>The two largest American banks both announced unexpectedly good second-quarter results. <b>Chase Manhattan's </b>earnings rose 17% to $856m;<b> Citicorp's</b> were up by 12% to $952m.
<p>A trading quarrel between America and Europe was averted, for a while, when Bill Clinton delayed by six months the right of Americans to sue foreign companies "trafficking" in confiscated Cuban assets. The European Union had threatened to retaliate, and still may. Other provisions of America's controversial <b>Helms-Burton Act </b>are already in force.
<p>Germany and Japan are reducing the extent to which their industrial companies are <b>controlled by banks</b>. A draft law in Germany would limit banks' voting power at shareholders' meetings. The Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan said that poor yields had persuaded it to sell a large but undisclosed portion of its large shareholding in Japanese companies.
<p>The annual general meeting of <b>Lloyd's of London </b>backed its Reconstruction and Renewal (<font size=-1>R</font>&<font size=-1>R</font>) recovery plan. Under it, the "names" who lost money in the London insurance market in 1987-92 will receive compensation of $3.2 billion. Although the 34,000 investors have until the end of August to approve their individual offers, most are likely to accept. Further legal challenges are possible in Britain and America, in spite of a new agreement between Lloyd's and American securities regulators.
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p>There was a truce, of sorts, between investment banks. Germany's Deutsche Morgan Grenfell, which has lured more than 70 staff from <font size=-1>ING</font> Barings, has promised to <b>stop poaching</b> if the Dutch bank drops a lawsuit against it.</p>
<p><h2>Arm's length</h2></p>
<p><p><b>Bertelsmann</b>, Germany's biggest media company, wants an American partner to join its digital-television consortium, which has been stranded by last week's alliance between <b>Kirch </b>and Rupert Murdoch's <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font>.
<p>In a further step towards the convergence of the news and software industries, America's <b>Microsoft</b> launched a broadcast network in conjunction with <b>NBC</b>, a television-news network. The new cable-<font size=-1>TV</font> channel, coupled with a Web site on the Internet, aims to provide an interactive rival to Ted Turner's <b>CNN</b>. 
<p>
<p>Kirk Kerkorian, a veteran corporate raider who was recently stalking Chrysler, helped the managers of <b>MGM</b> to buy the Hollywood studio he formerly owned for an estimated $1.3bn from <b>Cr&eacute;dit Lyonnais</b>, a troubled bank owned by the French state.</p>
<p><h2>Switched off</h2></p>
<p><p>
<p>Britain's sale of <b>British Energy</b>, a nuclear utility, raised a disappointing &#163;1.4 billion ($2.2 billion), about half what the government had hoped for. The shares fell further when trading started.
<p>The European Union's competition commissioner is to investigate the links between America's <b>Philip Morris</b> and Italy's state-owned tobacco monopoly, <b>Azienda dei Monopoli di Stato</b>. The pair control 89% of the market.
<p>Monitoring of trades on America's <b>Nasdaq </b>electronic stock exchange will be increased, including the use of tape recorders, following a two-year investigation by the Justice Department into allegations of price fixing. There will be no other sanctions.

<p><h2>Hard sell</h2></p>
<p><p> 
<p>(See <a href="wtw2.gif">chart</a>)<br>Currency traders, worried by the New York stockmarket's jumpiness, sold <b>the dollar</b> heavily. It fell particularly far against the <font size=-1>D</font>-mark, causing speculation that Germany's central bank might cut interest rates.
<p>To <b>deter currency speculators</b> as Western Europe approaches monetary union, the president of the European Monetary Institute, Alexandre Lamfalussy, suggested that central bankers announce in advance the exchange rate at which their currencies would join.
<p><p>
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
