<html><head><title></title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Public spending</b></p>
<h1>
EDXpendable
</h1><p>FOUR years ago, John Major forged a bright new sword to chop public spending. Tarnished bilateral deals between spending ministers and the Treasury were out. Instead, how much each department got was decided by a new cabinet committee, <font size=-1>EDX</font> (<font size=-1>ED</font> equals "economic and domestic", <font size=-1>X</font> equals expenditure, since you ask). Tough spending limits?--since <font size=-1>EDX</font> was stuffed with non-spending ministers, you got them. Better priorities?--since <font size=-1>EDX</font> weighs all spending bids against each other you got them too. "My bet is that it will survive to become institutionalised, almost constitutionalised," said Sarah Hogg, a former head of Mr Major's policy unit and one of the system's inventors.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;She may have spoken too soon. <font size=-1>EDX</font> will begin its work over the summer, following the cabinet's discussion on overall spending limits at its meeting on July 18th. But, according to some insiders, it has lost its edge.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It used to set about its work with relish. Hapless spending ministers had only a few minutes to present a case, before a summary verdict. Moreover, the system laid down that if one minister got more money out of cabinet after <font size=-1>EDX</font> had fixed his spending, some other minister would get less. Spending ministers tended to back the chancellor against any colleague who asked cabinet for more. Few appeals to cabinet against <font size=-1>EDX</font> decisions as a result succeeded.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Treasury ministers are less impressed with <font size=-1>EDX</font>'s recent record. A particular problem has been the presence of Michael Howard, the home secretary. Originally put on the committee as a right-winger who was tough on spending, Mr Howard now also needs more and more money to send more and more people to jail. Nor is he the only one. The rest of the committee either have biggish budgets (see <a href="br1.gif">table</a>), or have the job of getting cuts through Parliament.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nor is <font size=-1>EDX</font> now any good at setting priorities. The limits on public spending have been tough. The 1995 Budget looked for a real cut of 1.1% between 1995-96 and 1996-97. Never mind priorities: in order to hit their targets, ministers had to cut.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The usual low tricks have come into play, including slashing capital budgets to pay for current spending. The government is thereby storing up trouble for itself--or its successor. For example, the efficiencies it wants to achieve in administering social security benefits require big investment in information technology. But the government has yet to find the cash to pay for it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;How might things be improved? First, the government could move away from the concept that all programmes are re-set every year. Pensions and social security spending is the place to start. Because Britain is now a low-inflation economy (at least for the moment), increases need not be made every year. Had there been no increases this year, the Treasury would have saved &#163;2.7 billion.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Without such big automatic increases, the government would have more room at the margin to fix its priorities. However, under the present system, no minister has an interest in priorities across the government. The chancellor is mostly out to deliver low spending so he can cut taxes. Individual ministers are mostly out to get every penny they can for their own programmes so they look virile. The only person in government with overall responsibility for its performance is the prime minister. But he is not even on <font size=-1>EDX</font>.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He should chair the committee, with his own independent briefing, measuring what was being proposed against his government's political priorities. Until he is, he will remain on the margins of some of the most important decisions his government has to make.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?838421999,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br3.html">Next article</a>
</p>
