<html><head><title>Conviction politician</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>Conviction politician</h1>

<p>"PRISON works," the rallying cry of Michael Howard, the home secretary, has made him unpopular with all sorts of people, not least the Treasury. Although he has been squeezing costs per prisoner, numbers are rising so swiftly that the prison service is unlikely to be able to live within its budget. Still, if the extra money were going to bang up violent offenders, which politicians think the public wants, it might be well spent.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Figures just released, however, indicate that things are going the other way. Between 1993, when the prison population reached its lowest point for nine years, and June 1995, the most recent available figure, there was a slight drop in the proportion of offenders in jail for all categories of violent offences, and a slight increase in those for all categories of non-violent offences. The effect of changes at the margin on the overall figures is small. However, over the years, if current sentencing practice continues, they will be magnified.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The proportion of those in jail for violence against the person is down from 22.7% to 22.3%; mugging is down from 14.9% to 13.6%. Those inside for drug offences are up from 9.7% to 10.8%, those for motoring offences up from 3.2% to 4.3%. As the prison population has gone up by 20% during those two years, the numbers of violent as well as non-violent offenders is increasing, but the numbers of non-violent offenders show a remarkable jump: drug offenders in jail, for instance, are up from 3,208 to 4,260.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One reason for this is probably the 1993 Criminal Justice Act, which made provision for jailing offenders for a series of minor offences. Another may be what is described as the "sentencing climate" for judges. If judges think that the home secretary wants more people in jail, they tend to act accordingly. Paul Cavadino of the National Association for the Care and Resettlement of Offenders speculates that the figures may reflect the fact that violent offenders would have been sent to jail anyway, so if judges wish to send more people to jail, much of the impact is bound to fall on non-violent offenders.



</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?838421999,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br4.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
