<html><head><title>Drug wars</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Price-fixing</b></p>
<h1>Drug wars</h1>

<p>SINCE 1964, it has been illegal for manufacturers to fix retail prices for everything except books and drugs. Last September, the net book agreement, the book industry's price-fixing agreement, collapsed when supermarkets started discounting. Now Britain's last legal resale price maintenance arrangement is in danger. The supermarkets are attacking it, and both the Office of Fair Trading (<font size=-1>OFT</font>) and the European Commission are trying to decide whether it is justified any longer.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The supermarket chain Asda, which is leading the crusade against price-fixing, maintains that it represents a &#163;300m tax on consumers. Of that, Asda claims, 80% goes into the drugs companies' pockets.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The price-fixers' defence is mounted by the Community Pharmacy Action Group (<font size=-1>CPAG</font>) which, despite its grassroots sounding name, is an umbrella organisation representing drug manufacturers and retailers. They maintain that price-fixing must be retained not because it fattens manufacturers' profits, but because it sustains small chemists' shops.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These are important, they say, both because they provide local access to drugs and because the higher mark-up allows them to offer services which cost-paring supermarkets would not. Pharmacists, who receive a basic training, offer free medical advice and their shops hold a wider range of medicines than a supermarket would.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>CPAG</font> maintains that trained pharmacists also help the health service. If they were not available to give advice, more people would go to their doctors.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A report commissioned by <font size=-1>CPAG</font> from Deloitte &amp; Touche, a firm of accountants, predicts apocalyptic consequences should the agreement be scrapped. Some 3,000 chemists' shops, it maintains, would go under, at a net cost of 3,000 jobs. The range of drugs directly available to the public, says the report, would shrink to a tenth of its current level. The additional burden on the <font size=-1>NHS</font> would cost around &#163;4.7 billion.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Similar predictions were made by the publishers and book retailers when they were struggling to maintain the net book agreement. So far, there is little sign that they are being borne out. According to Bookwatch, the industry's sales monitor, sales are running around 1.3% higher than last year. The Booksellers Association says that it has not noticed a net loss of bookshops; rather, its membership has risen by 10% since last year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is also far from certain that scrapping drugs price-fixing would increase the burden on the <font size=-1>NHS</font>. Alan Maynard, a health economist at York University, argues the opposite. He reckons that high prices in pharmacies may drive people to their doctors to get their drugs more cheaply on prescription. Lower prices, accordingly, would promote self-medication and keep people out of the surgery.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>OFT</font> is expected to make up its mind in the autumn. Even if it does decide to ban the arrangement, the government could retain some of the benefits of the present system--for instance by subsidising pharmacists directly to continue to give free medical advice--while slashing the price of drugs. That would benefit consumers, not drugs companies.



