<html><head><title>Ringing the unwired</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>Ringing the unwired</h1>

<p>ONE year ago the idea of using the Internet to make normal telephone calls was risible; nowadays it is supposed to herald the end of the telephone company. The truth is somewhere in between. It is possible to make an Internet call, but only if you are prepared to put up with sound quality that Marconi might have complained about; and there must be two forewarned computer owners with Internet connections and matching software at each end.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What is missing in Internet telephony is a simple device in every home that can notify its owner of an incoming call and then connect it. In short, a telephone. On July 16th, <font size=-1>IDT</font>, a New Jersey firm which is best known for its cut-price "call-back" service for international dialling, launched the first commercial Internet service that rings your telephone.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Internet service, like the call-back one, relies on using <font size=-1>IDT</font>'s calling centre as a conduit. A customer, who still needs a <font size=-1>PC</font> to initiate a call, contacts <font size=-1>IDT</font> via the Internet. <font size=-1>IDT</font>'s calling centre then transfers the call to the normal American telephone network, where it becomes an ordinary call, ring and all. The only clue that such a call has travelled over the Internet is that it sounds terrible.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But, then again, it is cheap: ten cents per minute for calls to America, and American charges for calls elsewhere. Though a "pure" Internet voice call can cost nothing, it is a lot more fuss than <font size=-1>IDT</font>'s hybrid. One consultancy, International Data, is already predicting that by 1997 more than 5m users will be phoning each other over the Internet. Whether they will be able to hear each other is another matter.</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?838421999,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="fn1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
