<html><head><title>Showing Europe's firms the way</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>

<h1><center>Showing Europe's firms the way</center></h1>


IN 1967 a French politician, Jean-Jacques Servan-Schreiber, published a best-seller called "The American Challenge". In it he argued that the influence of transatlantic multinationals in Europe was growing relentlessly and would<b>, </b>if unchecked, destroy Europe's distinctive, "civilised" capitalism.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nearly 30 years later, Europe is facing a new American challenge. As the article on pages 19-21 explains, an aggressive new-world capitalism is spreading all over the old world. Conglomerates are being broken up; shareholders are clamouring for their rights; the old stable links between managers, owners and bankers are being burst apart.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As before, many Europeans fear that this spells the end of Europe's business civilisation. They foresee an American maelstrom of atomistic competition, job insecurity and social division. Are they right to be so worried? Are they even right that something of great significance is afoot? To the second question, the answer must be Yes: the changes are far-reaching already and there will be more to come. But the critics are wrong to conclude that the changes are for the worse. Rather, the new business methods give Europeans a chance to liberate what is distinctive and advantageous in Europe from the things that hold the continent back.
</p><p><b>An end to Eurosclerosis?</b></b>
<br>The changes in Europe mostly concern management technique and business organisation. Such things are not really "European" or "American". On the whole, there are bad ways of managing and good ways. On the whole, Europe has more bad ones than America does. What is happening now--as often in the past--is that Europeans are copying good business methods from America.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That said, it is also clear that firms do affect the societies they work in, and the critics of "Americanisation" are right to say that Europe faces big changes as a consequence. In most continental European countries, strong business relationships are highly valued; the "European model" fosters long-term ties between managers, owners and workers. In contrast, in America and Britain, firms are more influenced by shareholders who rely not on personal ties but on published accounts, straightforward ownership structures and clear goals for managers. The spread of such practices is no small matter.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Critics of Americanisation are also justified when they say that the change from one system to another will be sudden, not smooth. Adopting "shareholder value" as a yardstick is a bit like getting pregnant: nothing much happens at the start but soon your whole life changes. Conglomerates are broken up. Share buy-backs and share-option schemes come in. Those in turn dissolve the old groups of investors, as managers look to the markets for new money and investors wonder whether they want their capital tied up in the new businesses. Suddenly, you are in a different world.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But in lamenting the move from one system to another, critics are mistaking the symptom for the disease--the underlying weakness of the existing system. Remember that Europeans are adopting these ideas willingly. They know that something is badly wrong with the "European model".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Not all indicators of European economic performance suggest that a crisis is at hand. Though profit margins, returns on equity and job creation have all lagged far behind America, European labour productivity has increased twice as fast as America's since 1979. Not much wrong there, you might think. But the truth is that Europe is under great external strain already, and faces worse.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Today, big European firms compete for capital internationally. Their traditional ways of raising cash are too expensive: big firms can save millions by borrowing in New York or London. Europe is also experiencing a delayed response to the single-market programme of 1992. No longer are so many firms dominant suppliers in small, protected markets; no longer do they have such cosy ties with governments. A lot of protection remains, of course--too much--but the direction of reform is unmistakeable. America's more open, market-friendly structure is better suited to this new environment than Europe's traditional opacity.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;More serious still, Europe has a poor record in the knowledge-based industries that will probably drive growth in the future. Europeans ought to do well here: their universities, design schools and scientific establishments are among the best. But except in a few areas (fashion and high-price engineering spring to mind) Europeans are failing--and their failures spring from the "European model" . Where personal reputation is so important, entrepreneurs are unwilling to risk bankruptcy. Where stockmarkets are not transparent and founding families or cautious bankers have big stakes, it is often impossible for outsiders to invest in a business.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For these reasons, it is good news that Europe's bosses are breaking the mould. The changes will be sudden and, to many, alarming. Because aspects of the European system are enshrined in law, such as the social chapter of the Maastricht treaty, the changes may bring managers into conflict with politicians. So be it: Europe's extensive state meddling--its welfare programmes, its labour-market rules--are the worst impediments to growth of all. The new business practices are no impediment at all, but the opposite: a way not just to raise profits, but also to invest more in what Europe is best at.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?837212400,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="sf1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
