<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width=273 height=24  alt="Business"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<h2>All change</h2>

<p>A week after Switzerland's Credit Suisse reorganised itself, another big European bank, <b>Deutsche Bank</b>, announced that it was restructuring. Board members will each be responsible for a single business within four global operating divisions, and a new team will oversee strategy. Deutsche has also taken a 5% stake in a Bavarian rival, Bayerische Vereinsbank, for DM500m ($329m), a move that could foreshadow consolidation of Germany's crowded banking industry.</p>
<p>Another of Deutsche's new ideas meanwhile took a knock. <b>Ekkehard Wenger</b>, Germany's leading shareholder activist, filed a legal challenge to a share-options scheme for the bank's top managers, calling it excessively generous.</p>
<p>Officials said that <b>Russia</b> intended to make a $300m-500m Eurobond issue before the end of the year. The government also announced plans to privatise 200 hotels in Moscow.</p>
<p>Austria's plans to privatise its <b>Creditanstalt</b> bank through a tie-up with First Austrian was said to be in trouble. But First Austrian said no final decision had been taken.</p>
<p>Germany's Securities Trading Supervisory Office began investigating possible insider trading in the shares of <b>Escom</b>, Europe's second-largest computer retailer. The firm, which filed for protection from its creditors last week, has said it will sack 40% of its workers.</p>
<h2>Courting</h2>

<p><font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font>, a satellite-television company part-owned by Rupert Murdoch, unveiled a joint venture with Kirch, a German media group, to offer up to <b>200 digital pay-television channels </b>in Germany within the next few years. <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font> recently pulled out of a similar deal with Bertelsmann.</p>
<p>Prosecutors in Naples said that <b>Philip Morris</b>, the American tobacco-to-food giant, may have to pay $417m in back taxes. The Italians say the company's Italian subsidiary should pay tax as a local company; Philip Morris disagrees. Italian law prohibits the company from manufacturing cigarettes locally.</p>
<p>America's Justice Department launched an investigation into whether the proposed alliance between <b>British Airways</b> and <b>American Airlines </b>is anti-competitive. Combined, the carriers would operate 60% of flights between America and Britain.</p>
<p>Carlsberg, a Danish brewer, and Heineken, a Dutch rival, pulled out of projects to make beer in <b>Myanmar</b> (Burma), and halted exports to the country, in protest against human-rights abuses there. A consumer boycott aimed at Myanmar's military regime is gathering strength in America.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Glaxo Wellcome</b>, the world's largest drug company, said it would appeal against the decision of a North Carolina court to allow competitors to copy its top-selling anti-ulcer drug, Zantac, when the patent expires next year. Novopharm, a Canadian company planning a cheap copy of the drug in America in 1997, threatened a countersuit.</p>
<p><b>Nike</b>, which makes sports shoes, put a spring in the step of analysts by announcing post-tax earnings of $156m in the quarter to May 31st, 38% up on last year.</p>
<p>Europe's <b>Airbus</b> <b>Industrie</b> consortium is being reorganised as an ordinary company to compete better with Boeing, its American rival, in next-generation airliners. The consortium plans to integrate its four partner companies, from Germany, France, Britain and Spain, into a single entity. China meanwhile confirmed that it had chosen Airbus rather than Boeing as a partner to build a 100-seat airliner for its potentially vast market.</p>
<h2>Topsy-turvy</h2>

<p>(See <a href="wtw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>Strong growth in American jobs caused a 2% fall in the <b>Dow Jones</b> index on July 5th, as investors worried about a resurgence of inflation.</p>
<p>(See <a href="wtw2.gif">chart</a>)<br>South Korea's <b>LG Group</b> said it would invest &#163;1.7 billion ($2.6 billion) in two new factories to make chips and <font size=-1>TV</font> monitors in Britain, long one of the world's strongest magnets for foreign direct investment. In the year to April, 477 new projects were announced--a 50% rise on three years earlier. Britain's stock of inward investment stands at &#163;150 billion ($225 billion), up from &#163;44 billion in 1985.</p>
<p>America's <b>Motorola</b> was the latest victim of weak demand and falling prices for computer chips. Its share price fell after it announced a one-third drop in second-quarter earnings. The company has also been damaged by the fading fortunes of Apple, a major customer.</p>
<p>American regulators want <b>Prudential</b>, the country's biggest life-insurance company, to pay $35m in penalties for allowing widespread sales abuses by their agents to persist for more than a decade. It is not the first blow to the firm. Two years ago its securities arm paid up to $1.5 billion to compensate customers for understating the risk in various energy and property investments.</p>
<p><p><b>Hong Kong</b> needs an image makeover before China takes over in 1997, according to a Harvard Business School study. Though one of Asia's most popular business centres, it is threatened by high costs in service industries.</p>
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
<p align=center><a href="wtw1.html">POLITICS THIS WEEK</a></p><br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?837212400,iss">Search</a>
