<html><head><title>Le D&eacute;fi Am&eacute;ricain, again</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="sf.gif"  alt="Special">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>Le D&eacute;fi Am&eacute;ricain, again</h1>

<p><b>The American way of business is winning converts in continental Europe</b></p>

<p>IN THE past three years Daimler-Benz has listed its shares in New York, adopted American accounting standards, sold loss-making subsidiaries and offered its executives bonuses linked to the share-price. Managerial performance used to be measured by a complicated formula unknown outside the company. The firm has now replaced that with the shareholder-friendly aim of increasing return on equity.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is a well-known story but one that bears further scrutiny. Daimler is not only Germany's largest conglomerate. It has also been, for many years, an exemplar of a specifically European way of conducting business. Daimler is connected to Germany's biggest bank (Deutsche Bank owns 24% of Daimler) and to large firms (Daimler owns 7% of Metallgesellschaft, a troubled commodity-trader). The European system tends to blur distinctions of ownership through a complex system of cross-holdings and encourages long-term relations between the suppliers and managers of capital. It also gives more power to "stakeholders", especially workers, than in America: Daimler's workers--as in all large German firms--have half the seats on the supervisory board (which hires and fires the managers) and run a works council which takes some day-to-day decisions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But what is Daimler now? With its New York listing, restructuring plans and managerial incentive scheme, it clearly has some of the features of an American firm. Is that because it is a special case, forced to change by the scale of its losses--DM5.7 billion ($3.98 billion) in 1995? Or is Daimler still a symbol of European business--but this time as an early adopter of new management techniques, closer to the American model, with its shareholder values, opportunistic ways of raising capital and hostile takeovers?
</p><p><b>Busted trust</b></b>
<br>To work out the answer, begin by considering exactly what distinguishes European business practices from American ones. Differences exist at many levels, of course, from the treatment of stakeholders to tax rates, state ownership, the strength of unions, and the tendency of European countries to draw top managers from groups of people who all know one other. But at the heart of the difference is the issue of trust--the trust between those who supply capital and those who manage it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In European capitalism, trust is a personal matter, built up over many years. In Germany and Italy, there are especially close ties between companies and banks. Banks, like workers, often have seats on the supervisory board; bank managers have the friendship of a firm's bosses or founding family. The result has been "relationship" banking, with banks in it for the long haul and with a strong influence over corporate strategy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The bonds between the largest French firms are different, but no less personal. The relations have been built around a framework of cross-shareholdings between banks, insurers and industrial companies--what J&eacute;r&ocirc;me Monod, head of Lyonnaise des Eaux, a conglomerate, recently disparaged as "statist meccano". The system depends upon an elite group of like-minded managers. Most were educated at the same schools and universities--notably the Ecole Nationale d'Administration (<font size=-1>ENA</font>); many polished up their political ties by spending a year or two in some ministry. Italy has a somewhat similar business elite called the <i>salotto buono</i>.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This system is quite different from that which operates in more liberal market economies, such as America. Markets have different ways of establishing who deserves trust. Anonymous lenders and shareholders cannot have seats on the board. They did not go to school with the chairman. Instead, they look for public guarantees of good behaviour, expressed in published accounts and stockmarket performance.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To many Europeans, the American system is not a different way of establishing trust; to them, it discourages trust altogether. Arms-length banking, shareholders' rights, hostile takeovers, opportunistic behaviour of all kinds--these go hand in hand, say critics, with the devil-take-the-hindmost attitude to stakeholders and workers that Europeans find callous and socially irresponsible. This attitude may be tolerable in the freewheeling United States, they argue, but it is fundamentally at odds with Europe's norms of social cohesion.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Books such as "<i>Le D&eacute;fi Am&eacute;ricain</i>" ("The American Challenge") by Jean-Jacques Servan-Schreiber, a politician and journalist, and "<i>Capitalisme contre </i>Capitalism" (ie, the French variety against the American) by Michel Albert, now on the board of the Bank of France, have engraven on European minds the sense that American capitalism is a threat. Despite recession and unemployment, many Europeans remain proud of a brand of capitalism that for decades seemed to offer both prosperity and social justice.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But whatever the social merits of the two systems, in an open trading environment both have to be judged by their long-run ability to produce decent returns on investment. Europe is failing this test  (see <a href="sf1.gif">chart</a>).
</p><p><b>The cost of failure</b>
<br>Research by Fran&ccedil;ois Langlade-Demoyen and David Asserkoff, of Credit Suisse First Boston, a Swiss-owned investment bank, shows that profit margins before tax and provisions, and net profits measured against shareholders' funds (the return on equity), have both been consistently lower among European firms than among American ones. The return on equity in German companies in 1994 was only 7.4%, half that in American firms. The two researchers believe that on average European firms' profits do not even pay for the capital invested in the business.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Part of the explanation for this low profitability is that European firms do not make good use of their capital. A recent study by the McKinsey Global Institute, a management consultancy's think-tank, found that between 1990 and 1993 German business generated a third less output from each unit of capital than American firms did. The return on capital between 1974 and 1993 was only just over 7% in Germany, compared with 9% in America.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Perhaps, you might think, this mediocre performance does not matter. Labour productivity, after all, has risen by an average of 1.8% a year since 1979, twice the American rate. And many European managers have not been trying to succeed in "American terms"--ie, measuring their performance by returns to shareholders. Instead, they seek to pursue a long-term industrial strategy, or aim to keep operating profits high. So long as the providers of finance are willing to be patient, then this can continue. But not if many European firms are failing in their own terms.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For years, German firms proved adept at making the continuous incremental improvements needed to succeed in high-value, high price metal-bashing. But Germany's engineering perfectionism is coming under threat. According to research by <font size=-1>JP</font> Morgan, an American investment bank, output by all European machine-tool makers shrank by almost 3% a year between 1987 and 1994. The older skills of step-by-step improvement have been rendered obsolete in some businesses, such as <font size=-1>X</font>-ray equipment, where electronic-imaging, based on Japanese chip technology, is increasing its share of the market.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Worse, European firms have been bad at getting into new high-tech industries. Europe's high-tech firms are feeble in comparison with American ones. Only two of the top 20 software firms are European. Staid bankers are suspicious of revolutionary ideas. Venture capitalists have no one to sell their investments to. In a world where small, even symbolic stakes give bankers or founding families a great deal of say in the management of firms, it often impossible to get outsiders in to invest.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Worst of all, poor financial discipline has sometimes undermined European firms' supposed strength in long-term planning. A drift into property just before the booming market collapsed in 1990 cost French banks and insurers up to $100 billion. The dream of becoming "an integrated technology business" led Daimler into ill-advised expansion, absorbing Dornier and Fokker, two aerospace firms. It has recently sold both.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Sometimes failures reveal deep flaws in the way European firms work. Every sort of capitalism suffers from corruption, day-to-day mismanagement and strategic errors. But Europe seems to have had more than its share. Hundreds of Italian firms have been found guilty of bribery and corruption. In France in the past two years, around 30 chairmen of large companies have been placed under judicial examination (a step before a trial); a handful have been found guilty; in a poll of businessmen last year, 60% of respondents said they thought corruption was rife in France.
</p><p><b>The cost of capital</b>
<br>It is bad enough for the European system that it is no longer producing the goods. That alone would force it to change. What is worse is that the traditional system based on close ties between borrowers and lenders is up against a market system that has one crucial advantage: it is cheaper. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Lehman Brothers, an American investment bank, says that Daimler and <font size=-1>BMW</font> recently borrowed at rates well below <font size=-1>LIBOR</font>, the interest rate banks pay each other for eurodollars--and far cheaper than ordinary bank loans. This is undermining the traditionally stable ties of lenders and borrowers. As Jean-Ren&eacute; Fourtou, the boss of Rh&ocirc;ne-Poulenc, a French chemicals and drugs firm, admitted to his board in April, his group of shareholders looked as if it might break up: many no longer wanted to see their capital tied up in what was for them a peripheral business. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With a big price advantage, capital markets have grown fast. Partly because of privatisations, more money is tied up in most European stockmarkets as a share of <font size=-1>GDP</font> than a decade ago--though in most countries the proportion is still small compared with America and Britain (see <a href="sf2.gif">chart</a>). In France, for example, 30 new companies were floated on the Bourse during the first six months of this year, compared with 22 in the whole of 1994.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Foreign ownership of shares has increased throughout Europe. Between 1990 and 1994, it more than doubled to 22% in Sweden, rose from 15% to 25% in France and reached almost 20% from nothing in Germany. Foreigners--including, say, Germans in France--are especially keen on American values: they are less likely to buy on the strength of a local reputation, feel at risk in places where a nod and a wink are the principles of investment, and have less to lose by kicking up a fuss.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;No less important--and often forgotten--is the market for debt. A little over a decade ago, the European arm of Standard &amp; Poor's (<font size=-1>S&P</font>), an American agency that specialises in assessing bond risks, had two people in London assessing the bonds of some 30 issuers, mostly connected with governments. Now <font size=-1>S&P </font>has 200 staff following bonds from 500 issuers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And as with market instruments, so with people. Consultancies and investment banks are either opening branches in continental Europe or sending teams out from New York or London. Take Mercer Management Consulting, an American firm. It opened its first office in London in 1984; now it has 250 consultants in Paris, Munich and Madrid. According to Jean Estin, Mercer's European head, all the international management consultants are associated with American business culture. But American capitalism is not being spread by word of mouth. It is being sold.
</p><p><b>The first signs</b>
<br>The combination of falling profitability and the big growth in capital-market instruments has been deadly for the traditional way of doing business in Europe. Managers realise they need to change and have the opportunity to do it. Hence:
<font size=-1><li></font><b>Listing in New York.</b> This is the clearest sign of a firm's conversion to American ways. Daimler was one of the most spectacular, but other European firms, such as Astra, a Swedish drugs company, and Nokia, a Finnish telecoms group, have followed. Deutsche Telekom plans to make a listing after it is privatised in November (see <a href="sf3.gif">table</a>).
<font size=-1><li></font>Companies set themselves explicit <b>profit targets.</b> Typical is Commerzbank, Germany's third largest, or Lyonnaise des Eaux. Both have pledged to earn a return on equity equal to 15%, and 10-15% respectively. And once a firm has made such a commitment to shareholder value, a cascade of changes follows: taking on part of the creed usually means taking on the lot.
<font size=-1><li></font><b>Financial manoeuvres </b>sometimes dismissed as gimmicks by continental capitalists start to make good sense. One way to meet the target is for a firm to buy its own shares, something that promises to become more common as laws change in Europe. In November the Swedish government will publish a white paper likely to suggest that the law allow firms to buy back their shares.
<font size=-1><li></font><b>Restructuring.</b> On June 24th Chargeurs, a French conglomerate, split Path&eacute;, its media arm, from the rest of its business in textiles. This is characteristic of a fad for breaking up conglomerates to please shareholders. Portugal's Sonae will next year separate its wood-products business from retailing. Paribas, a French investment bank, has begun to sell off some of its holdings, including a controlling share in Poliet, a building-materials group. Sweden's Volvo, which had a sprawling empire including firms making drugs and matches, has dedicated itself to vehicles and construction equipment. All in all, according to <font size=-1>JP </font>Morgan, large companies worth over $89 billion were involved in mergers or acquisitions in Europe in the first three months of 1996--a quarterly record.
<font size=-1><li></font><b>Share options.</b> Managers are more likely to renounce empire-building and concentrate on profits if their interests are aligned with those of shareholders: share options are a way of ensuring they are. Share-option schemes are well established in some countries, including France, where they are often exploited to avoid high rates of income tax. In Germany, which has been slow to adopt the idea (partly because high capital-gains tax discourages them), Deutsche Bank and Daimler-Benz recently received shareholder approval for share-option schemes which will be introduced later this year. Siemens and Veba are considering similar plans; so is Deutsche Telekom, once it is privatised. Such schemes, however, are sometimes introduced in the teeth of opposition. Some existing shareholders suspect that the terms of the deals will be too generous to managers: they have pointed out that the options planned for Deutsche Bank's managers will bear fruit if the bank's share price beats its current level by 10% at any point over the next ten years--a 1% annual return is hardly a daunting challenge. Unions object, too: <font size=-1>IG</font> Metall, Germany's largest union, thinks that, by widening the gap between bosses' and workers' income, share options undermine their country's egalitarian pay regime and hurt employees' and companies' long-term interests.
<font size=-1><li></font><b>Corporate governance.</b> This has become a buzz-word in Europe to rein in excessively powerful bosses. A committee set up by the Amsterdam stock exchange will soon report on how better to enforce corporate governance in the Netherlands. In France, the Vi&eacute;not report, named after Marc Vi&eacute;not, the head of Soci&eacute;t&eacute; G&eacute;n&eacute;rale, recommends that executives be more closely monitored by limiting the number of boards that non-executive directors may sit on (the hope is that this will increase non-executive vigilance).
<font size=-1><li></font><b>Shareholder activism.</b> Of course managers might still abuse their powers. But at least they will have more militant shareholders to deal with--often with official encouragement (in France, the financial-markets regulator is encouraging fund managers to use their votes). In one recent case, Banque Nationale de Paris (<font size=-1>BNP</font>) agreed to buy out minority shareholders in a listed subsidiary, called Compagnie d'Investissements de Paris, which had been trading at a large discount to the value of its assets. <font size=-1>BNP</font> was responding to pressure from <font size=-1>SBC</font> Warburg, an investment bank, and Franklin Global Investor Services, a French firm that advises shareholders how to take on managers. Once Warburg had taken the first step, French fund managers followed. Astonishingly, even <font size=-1>BNP</font>'s own investment funds were ready to vote against their parent bank.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Shareholders are restive even in Germany, where there is a long tradition of obedience. This is thanks partly to the tireless efforts of Ekkehard Wenger, a professor of economics at the University of W&uuml;rzburg who has been badgering executives at annual general meetings since 1987. The country now has an organisation called the Association of Critical Shareholders, which led the attack on Deutsche Bank's share-options scheme. Such groups may alarm managers but they are really a sign of progress.
</p><p><b>The revolution to come</b>
<br>To listen to the cries of anguish in Europe, American capitalism is about to bring about the collapse of civilised business as we know it. Certainly, it could impose painful restructuring on companies, which would be no bad thing. The virtual bankruptcies of Air France and <font size=-1>SNCF</font>, the French national railway, show that to delay restructuring often merely makes a bad company worse.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But fears about rampaging Americans are somewhat exaggerated. The greatest spur to shareholder values in Europe will be the creation of millions of individual European shareholders, and that will occur over the next decade or so with the growth of funded pensions. Meanwhile, French firms, for example, do not even have to say whether they are complying with Mr Vi&eacute;not's suggestions. Rules may not be what they seem. French remuneration committees are sometimes there simply to keep the chief executive's salary secret from the unions' representative on the board.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Measured against American standards, European firms have a long way to go. That is the best reason to think that the changes will continue.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?837212400,iss">Search</a>
