<html><head><title>Bob Dole, neighbour and statesman</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width=258 height=26  alt="American Survey">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>Bob Dole, neighbour and statesman</h1>

<p>BOB DOLE's advisers are missing something. To rescue their candidate from gaffes about tobacco and fights over abortion, they need a suitable distraction. Should Mr Dole attack his opponent's economic record? The latest employment figures, showing that Mr Clinton has presided over the creation of 10m new jobs, make this course seem unattractive. Should Mr Dole give another foreign-policy speech? The previous two, though worthy, failed to dent Mr Clinton's lead in the opinion polls. What does this leave? Actually, it leaves the most obvious theme of all. Mr Dole should talk about his own rich life. This will lead him to take back some of the campaign themes that Mr Clinton has stolen from him.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Dolesters have thought of playing up their man's life before; they gave up the idea for an entirely mistaken reason. The trouble with Mr Dole's life story, they thought, is that it is split. Mr Dole is the farm-town boy from Russell, Kansas; but he is also the politician who spent 35 years in Congress. Mr Dole may invoke the neighbourly virtues of Russell on the stump; but his audiences know that he has spent his own career miles from his Kansas home, trading power in the capital. It seemed impossible to reconcile these two sides.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But that was precisely the mistake. Mr Dole's split identity is actually America's as well; and his success in being two seemingly different things could teach his countrymen a useful lesson.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For America is moved by two ideals, and the conflict between them explains much contemporary confusion. Americans feel nostalgia for the fading values of small towns, which is why politicians on all sides have embraced the language of "responsibility" and "community". At the same time, Americans enjoy the grandeur of federal power, the knowledge that Washington is the world's capital. Again, Americans like to recall stable communities, the fellowship of boy-scout troops and village clubs, the civic virtues of the Founders. And yet they are also infatuated with a different myth: of the ambitious youth who leaves his community behind, and makes for the big city. America shares Bob Dole's small-town side, and it shares his big ambition.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All this suggests that Mr Dole could speak out about his divided past, and gain a sympathetic hearing. Moreover, speaking out might also heal a division within his party. Until recently, Republicans were usually clear on which national ideal was theirs. They supported freedom, ambition, dynamism. They stood for Americans who wanted to move up and on, who had no use for the old habits. To this sort of Republican, freedom was both an economic and a moral good. Ronald Reagan promised to cut government in order to promote growth, but also because untrammelled competition would foster an independence of the spirit. Nobody much cared about Ronald Reagan's home town. He was a hero without a village.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This has changed. A new kind of Republican hero has arisen to challenge the community-busting, village-deserting archetypes of the Reagan years. The new sort are solid citizens, faithful fathers, religious leaders who shelter orphans from mean streets. They do battle against dead-beat dads, permissive liberals, and other agents of social decay. To Republicans who prefer this kind of hero, freedom has its darker side: it causes self-expression to displace self-restraint, individualism to degenerate into egotism. When this happens, America is lost. A tolerant society cannot thrive unless its members themselves are tolerant; a free society cannot thrive unless citizens exercise freedom responsibly.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These two Republicanisms now coexist. Many members of the party still invoke Mr Reagan's commitment to a limited state. Others want a government that does more to foster virtue. This has given the Democrats a chance to steal new Republicanism's themes. The Clinton administration has battled the unvirtuous influence of television: it has cajoled networks into rating their programmes for sex and violence, and has ensured that <font size=-1>TV</font> sets will soon be fitted with a chip that enables parents to censor children's viewing. The president now leads a crusade to have television networks air three hours of educational programmes each week. "It Takes a Village", the title of Hillary Clinton's book, invokes the same community virtues that new Republicans are fond of.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Dole cannot match this. He attacked Hollywood for turning out "nightmares of depravity" early on in the campaign; and he has proposed a new tax break for charities, in the hope of promoting local groups that nurture civic virtue. But he opposed the smut-censoring television chip, and he has been mum on educational programming. Both ideas offended the old Reaganite belief in limited government.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For the time being, therefore, the Republicans look weak. Yet their divided instincts need not put them permanently on the retreat. America's longing for community, remember, is balanced by its freedom-loving ambitious side. The Republicans could take the Clintons on, stressing the need to foster virtue, but insisting that this should not involve surrender to big government. They could strike a balance that appeals to both the ideals that animate America.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is a subtle message, difficult to get across. But the Republicans have an extraordinary weapon in their candidate. Mr Dole can tell America how, when he came home from the second world war, paralysed, the neighbours in Russell clubbed together to pay his medical expenses. But the community ties that saved him, he can also point out, were not so tight as to restrain his rise to national prominence later on. Both stories illustrate America's complementary strengths. Together, they might help the country to feel better about its split self. And that would be a good thing, whatever happens to Mr Dole's poll ratings.
</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?837212400,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="ir1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
