<html><head><title>Grab that chance</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/eu.gif" width=105 height=26  alt="Europe">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<p><b>Poland</b></p>
<h1>Grab that chance</h1>

WARSAW
<p>ON THE face of things, Poland is sitting pretty. Its economy, easily the biggest in ex-communist Europe except for Russia's, grew by a stirring 7% last year. At 39m, it has the biggest population in the region after Russia's and Ukraine's, but none of the ethnic or cross-border tensions that trouble most of the other countries. Its president, Alexander Kwasniewski, a smooth ex-communist, has kept Poland looking westwards without enraging its lumbering Russian neighbour to the east. On July 11th Poland agreed to join the <font size=-1>OECD</font>, the mainly western rich countries' club. It is at the top of the queue to join the European Union and <font size=-1>NATO</font>, as President Bill Clinton no doubt assured Mr Kwasniewski on his visit to Washington this week.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Kwasniewski's term started inauspiciously in January when his prime minister, a member of his party, quit amid (unproven) accusations that he had been a <font size=-1>KGB</font> agent. But a new prime minister, Wlodzimierz Cimoszewicz, a technocrat with no formal party membership, calmed the waters--and Mr Kwasniewski has now settled with an uncanny serenity into his new job.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet progress in Poland is rarely straightforward. The "shock therapy" that laid the foundation for Poland's swift growth six years ago also spelled insecurity for millions of farmers, pensioners, bureaucrats and other state employees. That was why, in 1993, Poles voted to retreat into a seemingly safer past. The resultant government coalition brought together Mr Kwasniewski's Alliance of the Democratic Left, whose main component is a reformed version of the old communist party, with the smaller Peasant Party, successor to an obedient sister of that communist party.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So far, so good. The Alliance has managed to reconcile voters' expectations with the demands of free-market reform, above all the tight budget needed to keep the currency sound and the free markets needed to keep the economy competitive. It has cut inflation and kept the bosses of Poland's 2m small businesses happy. Indeed, many of them proved ready to risk Mr Kwasniewski as president instead of Lech Walesa, his heroically anti-communist but increasingly erratic predecessor.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All the same, the Alliance is on a tightrope. The government faces an agenda of painful reform and a parliamentary election next year. A slip could revive right-wing parties, which are showing signs of life after all but one tumbled out of parliament in the 1993 election. Their man of the moment is Jan Olszewski, a former prime minister who came fourth in the first round of last year's presidential contest, with 7% of the vote. One recent poll sees his Movement for the Reconstruction of Poland, known as <font size=-1>ROP</font>, nudging into second spot, with 16%, behind the ex-communists, with 18%. The government cannot be certain of winning next year's election.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Like the ex-communists a few years ago, Mr Olszewski and his group appeal to the disaffected. Their main weapon is a nationalist populism that blames Poland's current ills on the continuing influence of the corrupt communist nomenklatura (under whatever new guise) over business and politics. Mr Olszewski's critics call him "Poland's Le Pen". He denies that he shares the French nationalist's chauvinism but concedes that "the crazy fringe" may be "more visible" in <font size=-1>ROP</font> because its platform is "more revolutionary" than its rivals'.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He is vague about what sort of revolution he has in mind. On some things he sounds like a western liberal. It is "crucial" for Poland to join <font size=-1>NATO</font>, he says. He thinks that Polish membership of the European Union is bound to happen and claims to want more privatisation and foreign investment. Yet Mr Olszewski's party also says it would impose tariffs on some imports and would force down interest rates.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If he is to have a chance of winning power, he must find allies. They could include the Solidarity trade-union movement, whose supporters share his hatred of former communists, his suspicion of foreign influence and his friendliness to the Catholic Church. Anti-communism aside, so do many in the Peasant Party.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But even if he united such disparate malcontents, Mr Olszewski would still be a long way from the winning-post. Poland's right-wingers are a cantankerous lot. Prickly men such as Mr Olszewski and Mr Walesa despise each other. Solidarity and Mr Olszewski's movement have yet to come to terms. The reformed communists are relatively a model of discipline.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The remoulded left is not all harmony, however. Scratchiness between the Alliance's ex-communists and their Peasant partners slows further reform. The Peasant Party, for instance, inveighed against a new law that lets foreigners buy land, though that is not only a condition for Polish membership of the <font size=-1>OECD</font> but also the best way to draw job-creating investment into the countryside. Even so, foreigners wanting to buy land still face obstacles.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ambivalence within the Alliance could undermine reform of social security, which runs an annual deficit of 5% of Poland's <font size=-1>GDP</font>. Without reform, the gap could widen by 1% of <font size=-1>GDP</font> every year, driving up inflation and interest rates and stunting the growth that gives Poland its only chance of controlling its budget deficit (see <a href="eu1.gif">chart</a>). The government must raise retirement ages and slow the growth of benefits but is afraid of enraging Poland's 9m pensioners--nearly a quarter of the population. With the labour ministry suggesting feeble reforms and the finance ministry more robust ones, the government so far has wobbled.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The temptation will be to delay further change, trusting that Poland's buoyant growth will sweep the government back into power next year. But the boom will not last for ever. If Mr Kwasniewski's government dithers now, while the going is good, it could open the door to a populist like Mr Olszewski when things turn rough.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?837212400,iss">Search</a>
