<html><head><title> Whitehall's dark dealings</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Open government</b></p>
<h1> Whitehall's dark dealings</h1>


<p>TWO years ago, the government introduced a code to improve access to official information, supervised by an independent arbiter. The minister who was at the time responsible for open government, William Waldegrave, predicted that his bold initiative would lead to a new climate of openness in Whitehall. His successor, Roger Freeman, recently protested: "There is a common perception that Whitehall operates under a cloak of secrecy. This isn't true."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Journalists are constantly frustrated by the British government's visceral meanness with information, so <i>The Economist </i>was heartened by this enthusiasm for open government. To test it, we asked for details of the sale prices of 27 British Rail businesses listed in a Department of Transport (<font size=-1>DOT</font>) press release in January as having been successfully privatised. When the department refused to hand out the information on the grounds that if it were public knowledge it might prejudice future sales, we complained to the code's arbiter, the Parliamentary Commissioner for Administration, William Reid.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Reid, who is better known as the Ombudsman, has not, so far, had a great deal to do. In his first two years, he has investigated only 97 complaints. Ours was the first from any newspaper.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Complaints to the Ombudsman have to be made through an <font size=-1>MP</font>. On February 10th we wrote to Clare Short, Labour's transport spokesman, saying that we believed the public should know how much publicly owned assets were being sold for. We pointed out that many of the businesses whose sale prices the government was refusing to disclose, such as the Red Star freight business, had nothing in common with the businesses remaining to be sold: thus the information about those sales would not affect future ones. We also noted that the government had broken its own secrecy rule by disclosing the sale for &#163;1.8 billion of the three rolling-stock leasing companies in January 1995.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Ombudsman announced that he would investigate our complaint on February 23rd. Three months later, he issued an initial finding in our favour. The <font size=-1>DOT</font>, he said, had agreed to release the sale prices of four of the smaller businesses that had been privatised. The department has now published the sale prices of some of the other businesses in a parliamentary answer timed to coincide with the Ombudsman's final report and says it will publish the rest soon.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Reid accepts that the department was entitled to refuse to disclose the sale prices of these businesses at the time we requested the information because this might have "prejudiced commercial activities", grounds for exemption under the code. But he says he expects the department to publish the remaining sale prices shortly.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So has open government arrived? Only up to a point. Contrary to our expectations, the Ombudsman's intervention did work. We got the information we wanted. Still, it took him more than five months to prise the information out of Whitehall. Without his intervention, it would still not be available. Whitehall has not yet hung up its cloak.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?837212400,iss">Search</a>
