<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>



<p><b>Machete man</b> &nbsp;Police in Wolverhampton are holding a man suspected of attacking three children and four adults during a picnic at an infants' school.

Blocked tubes<br>
A total shutdown is likely on London Underground on nine days this summer. The <font size=-1>RMT</font>, the largest rail union, has voted to strike.

Postbagged<br>
 Postal workers' leaders announced four days of strikes. The government has hinted that it may abolish the Post Office's monopoly on letters worth less than &#163;1.</p>
<p><b>In a stew</b> &nbsp;Germany has imposed an indefinite ban on British beef imports. This decision overrides the <font size=-1>EU</font>'s partial lifting of its ban last month.</p>
<p><b>Sky-high</b> &nbsp;Trafalgar House has commissioned Sir Norman Foster to build Europe's tallest skyscraper on the bomb-damaged Baltic Exchange site in the City of London.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Wanted</b> &nbsp;Police announced a &#163;1m reward for information leading to the conviction of those who planted an <font size=-1>IRA</font> bomb in Manchester.</p>
<p><b>Pursuing stalkers</b> &nbsp;The government is proposing a new law that would make stalking an offence punishable by up to five years in jail.</p>
<p><b>Chinese takeaway</b> &nbsp;Albert Tong, a Chinese illegal immigrant who Britain was planning to deport after he spent 17 years in Cornwall, married, and had a child, has been offered a home in Ireland.</p>
<p><b>Moral quarrel</b> &nbsp;George Carey, the Archbishop of Canterbury, launched a "crusade" against moral relativism in schools. He urged teachers to inculcate children with Christian morality. Gillian Shephard, the education secretary, promised to support him by enforcing daily worship in schools.</p>
<p><b>Sad tail</b> &nbsp;Police have asked pet shop owners and bird lovers to listen out for Bosun, a stolen West African Grey parrot who speaks with a Devon accent.
</p>
