<html><head><title>The telephone's second chance</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/st.gif" width=371 height=26  alt="Science And Technology">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>The telephone's second chance</h1>
<p><b>Will nifty technology enable the telephone companies to provide fast Internet access over their old copper lines? The second of our briefs rates their odds</b></p>

<p>TELEPHONE companies have long envied the profits cable-television firms make by delivering television programmes into homes. But this was a business that seemed impossible for them to enter. Most telephone networks run on twisted copper wires. Even with the fastest modems, signals on these wires were interrupted by too much noise to carry much more than still pictures and text.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That would have been that, had researchers not spotted a funny thing about the noise on these lines. It is not uniform. Some frequencies are swamped by noise, but on others signals pass through untouched. The trouble is that this varies from line to line and from moment to moment, and hand-tweaking each line to carry more data is impractical. In 1987, however, along came a technology that could do it automatically.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The trick is to use fast computer chips called digital signal processors to test each line constantly and then tailor the data to travel only over the frequencies that are clearest at any time. With such a chip on each end of a line, telephone companies found they could increase the capacity of their old wires thousands of times--enough to deliver high-quality video pictures.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Many firms, notably Bell Atlantic in America and <font size=-1>BT</font> in Britain, bought these boxes, called asymmetric digital subscriber line (<font size=-1>ADSL</font>) modems, to try their hand at the media mania of the moment, interactive television. But subscribers turned out to be a lot less interested in this than the telephone companies were. Trials suggested that they would not pay enough to cover the cost of the expensive equipment. <font size=-1>ADSL</font> looked like another technology that cost too much and offered too little.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Recently two things have rekindled <font size=-1>ADSL</font>'s flame. First, in America, Congress has opened the local telephone markets to competition, confronting Bell Atlantic and the six other "Baby Bells" with the first challengers they have ever seen. Some of these new competitors will be cable-television firms, which are using a different technology to offer telephone calls and high-speed Internet access on their own lines. Compared with the optical fibres such firms use, plain old telephone wires will not for long be the cash cows the phone companies are used to. They will need to offer new services, while making the most of the networks they already have.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The second change is the rise of the Internet. Consumers may not have been wowed by interactive television, but it seems that they cannot get enough of the Internet. The telephone companies reckon that many people would pay a lot for really high-speed Internet access: just the thing to keep revenues up while voice-calling profits fall. Five of America's Baby Bells--<font size=-1>GTE</font>, <font size=-1>US</font> West, BellSouth, Bell Atlantic and <font size=-1>SBC</font> Communications--as well as Bell Canada, have all announced trials using <font size=-1>ADSL</font> to deliver high-speed Internet access.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>ADSL</font>, and related digital subscriber line technologies (known generically as x<font size=-1>DSL</font>), work by exploiting unused capacity in copper wire. Voice calls--and data calls using everyday modems--use barely one-half of one per cent of the capacity of ordinary telephone lines. <font size=-1>ADSL</font> modems make use of the remaining 99.5% or so. In effect, <font size=-1>ADSL</font> divides a copper wire into 255 "bins", each of which is capacious enough to hold one voice call. One of these bins is kept aside for voice calls; together, most of the rest behave like super-efficient conventional modems acting in parallel. So while top-of-the-range analogue modems struggle to reach 33,600 bits per second (bps), <font size=-1>ADSL</font> can race to 300 times that. A sub-set of <font size=-1>ADSL</font>, known as <font size=-1>VDSL</font> (the "v", with a bit of acronymic licence, stands for "very high bit-rate" ), can go five or six times faster still (see <a href="st1.gif">chart</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>ADSL</font> is ideal for providing high-speed Internet access to consumers in many other respects. <font size=-1>ADSL</font> modems are permanently connected, eliminating tiresome delays. Analogue modem users are increasingly hogging expensive telephone switches as they surf the Internet. <font size=-1>ADSL</font> bypasses all that with a direct digital connection, keeping prices down for both customers and the telephone companies.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For the telephone companies, <font size=-1>ADSL</font> also has the advantage of having outgrown its teething pains. Early variants, for example, were almost entirely one-way. Now, <font size=-1>ADSL</font> rushes data in both directions (although it is still around ten times faster going into a house than it is coming out), allowing useful things like video-conferencing.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Another pitfall was variation in the quality of copper lines. Bell Atlantic ran trials in 1993 in the hope that 95% of homes in the Washington, <font size=-1>DC</font> area could be serviced easily using <font size=-1>ADSL</font>. In fact, they found that the real figure was closer to 30%, mostly because of interference from everything from hair-dryers to radio signals. More recent <font size=-1>ADSL</font> systems have proved more flexible. Like the modern analogue modems, newer <font size=-1>ADSL</font> modems alter their speed of transmission according to the conditions; when they encounter interference, they automatically slow down. Pairgain, an <font size=-1>ADSL</font> modem maker, reckons than 85% of America's twisted copper lines will support <font size=-1>ADSL</font> without any modification.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is, however, another worry. Early tests of <font size=-1>ADSL</font> suggested an alarmingly short reach. At a distance of 3,700 metres (12,000 feet) from a telephone company's offices, one type of <font size=-1>ADSL</font> modem will deliver 6m bps downstream. But take it 1,800 metres further away and it drops to 1.5m bps. In densely populated countries, this is not such a problem: more than 95% of Italian homes, 90% of British and nearly 80% of German homes are within 3,700 metres of a telephone central office. But in America this figure hovers around 50%, suggesting that other technologies, such as wireless connections or direct satellite, will be a better route to the Internet in rural areas.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Technical issues aside, the main worry about <font size=-1>ADSL</font> is its cost. Today a pair of modems costs between $1,500 and $3,000. But as Rupert Baines of Analog Devices, a chip maker, points out, one of the most expensive parts of <font size=-1>ADSL</font> modems is their processor chips. Since chip prices tend to halve every 18 months, <font size=-1>ADSL</font> modems should get cheaper, too.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For <font size=-1>ADSL</font> to become the favoured Internet-access technology, the telephone companies may have to change their ways. Their decades-old monopoly of voice telephony has endowed them not only with lots of money but also with slothful habits. They have done almost nothing, for example, to market a slower digital technology called <font size=-1>ISDN</font>, despite having spent billions to upgrade their networks to support it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unless they are to repeat that mistake with <font size=-1>ADSL</font>, they will need to order enough <font size=-1>ADSL</font> modems to push the price down, while marketing the service hard enough to find takers for them. There are, after all, plenty of rival technologies competing to deliver the Internet to the masses: including cable modems, satellites, and (the subject of next week's brief) wireless.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?837212400,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>

</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
