<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width=271 height=24  alt="Politics"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<h2>Yeltsin's victory</h2>
<p>Boris Yeltsin was easily re-elected president of <b>Russia</b>. In a run-off on July 3rd he won 54% of the votes cast, to the Communist Gennady Zyuganov's 40%. Mr Yeltsin, who made no public appearances in the days before the run-off, appeared on television to assuage worries about his health.<p>
The Czech Republic's three-party conservative coalition formed a new government after losing its majority in elections last month. The prime minister, <b>Vaclav Klaus</b>, granted more influence to the smaller partners of his Civic Democratic Party and to the opposition Social Democrats.<p>
Necmettin Erbakan, leader of the Welfare Party, became <b>Turkey's first Islamist prime minister</b> after striking a deal with the secular True Path Party. Turkey would remain a "democratic, secular and social state based on law", he said.<p>
Greece's prime minister, Costas Simitis, was elected leader of the socialist <b>Pasok</b> <b>party </b>days after the death of its founder, Andreas Papandreou. His victory in a hard-fought leadership battle should help Mr Simitis to push through budget cuts and other economic reforms.<p>
A day after the leaders of the <font size=-1>G7</font> rich countries called for his resignation, the Bosnian Serb president, <b>Radovan Karadzic</b>, said he would leave office. He may not relinquish power, however. His successor, Biljana Plavsic, is loyal to Mr Karadzic, who has been indicted for war crimes.<p>
The lower house of Germany's parliament approved cuts in <b>social-welfare benefits</b>, including unemployment and sick pay, health care and job security. Some of these measures require the approval of the upper house, controlled by the opposition Social Democrats.<p>
The European Commission threatened to take four countries to court for failing to enforce <b>European Union laws</b>. Austria refuses to outlaw anonymous bank accounts, France imposes excessive restrictions on advertising, and Greece and Italy are accused of infractions over customs duties and value-added tax.<p>
Hungary's government agreed to a plan for restitution of <b>Jewish property</b> stolen during the 1930s and 1940s that could set an example for other East European countries. A foundation will manage property once owned by Jews and money donated by the government for the benefit of the country's 20,000 remaining Jews.<p>
<b>Iceland</b> has elected a new president, Olafur Ragnar Grimsson, a left-wing former finance minister who has opposed the country's membership of <font size=-1>NATO</font>. He replaces Vigdis Finnbogadottir, a popular leader who stepped down after 16 years in office.<p></td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>



<h2>Age before beauty</h2>
<p>The congress of <b>Vietnam</b>'s Communist Party decided that all businesses should set up a Communist Party organisation. The ruling triumvirate, the president, Le Duc Anh, aged 75, the prime minister, Vo Van Kiet, 73, and the party general secretary, Do Muoi, 79, kept their jobs despite earlier reports that the party was to be "rejuvenated".<p>
Christian opponents of a plan to give Muslims some power in southern <b>Mindanao </b>jeered the Philippine president, Fidel Ramos, when he visited the area. The plan aims to end a 24-year ethnic conflict in which at least 50,000 people have died.<p>
Taiwan's President Lee Teng-hui ruled out <b>reunification with China </b>under the formula, "one country, two systems", noting that Hong Kong's experience with the concept raised doubts.<p>
The People's Revolutionary Party, run by ex-communists, lost power to the Democratic Union Coalition in <b>Mongolia</b>'s general election.

<h2>Changing tack</h2>
<p>Bob Dole, the Republican candidate for president, said he would be willing after all to pick a running-mate who did not share his opposition to <b>abortion</b>. In another show of recklessness, Mr Dole insisted that he did not know whether or not tobacco was addictive, and suggested that a former surgeon-general may have been "a little bit" brainwashed to preach that it was. <p>
The Supreme Court left intact a ruling by a federal court that struck down an <b>affirmative-action </b>admissions plan at the University of Texas law school. The ruling said that race could not be used as a factor in admissions. The court's action affects three states--Texas, Mississippi and Louisiana--with large minority populations.<p>
Federal agents arrested 12 members of an Arizona group called the <b>Viper Militia </b>and charged them with conspiracy to blow up a number of federal buildings.<p>
Leonel Fernandez narrowly won an election to become the <b>Dominican Republic</b>'s next president.

<h2>Less support</h2>
<p>The long-delayed local elections in the<b> KwaZulu-Natal</b> province of South Africa brought clear victory for the African National Congress in urban areas and an equally clear victory for the Inkatha Freedom Party in rural areas. Overall, Inkatha won more votes than its rivals but fewer than in 1994.<p>
As African and western countries prepared a peacekeeping force for <b>Burundi</b>, more than 2,000 people fled from the north-western town of Cibitoke amid reports of a fresh massacre.<p>
David Levy (left), <b>Israel</b>'s new foreign minister, threatened Binyamin Netanyahu with resignation unless Ariel Sharon, the hardest of hardliners, was brought into the cabinet.<p>
<p>
<p>

</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
