<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width=273 height=24  alt="Business"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>

<p>


<h2>Swiss roles</h2>
<p>In an upheaval at one of the world's biggest finance groups, <b>CS Holding</b>, recently rebuffed in its attempt to merge with Union Bank of Switzerland, said it will cut 5,000 jobs, create four core units and take a new name--Credit Suisse Group. Lukas M&uuml;hlemann, drafted in from Swiss Re, a reinsurer, will run the whole under the chairman, Rainer Gut (above).<p>
Growing risks and competition are forcing reinsurers to consolidate. General Re, <b>America's biggest reinsurer</b>, plans to pay $940m for a rival, National Re.<p>
<b>MasterCard</b> has followed Visa in banning its member banks from issuing rival cards--a jab at <b>American Express</b>, which wants to distribute its cards through banks. The European Commission has already warned Visa against using this tactic; in America, the Justice Department is investigating the whole credit-card business.<p>
The <b>dollar</b> rose above &#165;110 for the first time in 2.5 years, though mainly because interest rates in Japan were thought likely to remain at rock-bottom.<p>
<b>Copper</b> futures slid further as supplies of the metal were released from Sumitomo Corp's stockpile. A British metals-trading firm, Rudolf Wolff, suspended three employees in Tokyo after an internal check on the firm's dealings with Sumitomo, which recently admitted huge copper losses.<p>
<b>The London Stock Exchange</b> is to cut costs (and staff) by a third, to become more competitive. The imminent arrival of Crest, a paperless trading system from the Bank of England, is expected to lop off about a third of the exchange's revenues.

<h2>Worth a packet</h2>
<p>(See <a href="wtw1.gif">table</a>)<br>Bill Gates again tops the list of the world's <b>billionaires</b>, with his Microsoft co-founder, Paul Allen, also in the top ten. Of the 447 billionaires listed by <i>Forbes</i>, 149 are from the United States. The number of Japanese billionaires stays at 41; but in five years the number in the rest of Asia has risen fast, from 26 to 82.<p>
An American billionaire, Wayne Huizenga, is paying about $5 billion in an agreed deal for <b>ADT</b>, which sells burglar alarms and second-hand cars. With waste management, these have become big businesses for Mr Huizenga's <b>Republic Industries</b>.<p>
The American Supreme Court ruled that the government broke its promise to some <b>savings and loan </b>institutions (thrifts) when it changed accounting rules on intangible goodwill during the <font size=-1>S&L</font> crisis in the 1980s. The ruling is likely to cost the government $10 billion or more as <font size=-1>S&L</font>s sue for damages.<p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<b>Mediaset</b>, part of Silvio Berlusconi's Fininvest empire, will begin trading on July 15th with a share price that values Italy's biggest commercial-<font size=-1>TV</font> group at around 8.25 trillion lire ($5.4 billion). Mr Berlusconi is floating Mediaset to avert a clash between his media and political interests.<p>
<b>Digital Equipment</b>, the world's second-biggest computer maker, issued a profit warning and said it will cut 7,000 of its 61,000 jobs worldwide in a $475m restructuring, despite strong growth last year after an earlier restructuring. It is refocusing its <font size=-1>PC</font> business from the desktop to "servers".<p>
The Japanese government said it would spend &#165;17 trillion ($155 billion) over the next five years on <b>science and technology</b> to improve Japanese innovation.<p>
(See <a href="wtw2.gif">table</a>)<br>Huge losses and a depreciating yen have pushed Japan's banks down the league table of the world's <b>best-capitalised banks</b>.

<h2>Clipped wings</h2>
<p>Spurred on by a new deal between British Airways and American Airlines, the European Commission is to investigate the implications of six big <b>transatlantic air alliances</b>.<p>
The French government confirmed the merger between state-owned <b>A&eacute;rospatiale</b> and privately controlled <b>Dassault</b>, whose combined sales are around FFr60 billion ($11.6 billion). The government will retain control and said the merger will be complete by next January, a year ahead of schedule.<p>
Boeing is forming a joint venture with America's General Electric to build a long-range private <b>corporate jet </b>based on the new 737-700, in a market that is beginning to grow again. Bombardier of Canada and America's Gulfstream Aircraft are also producing corporate jets; all cost around $35m each.<p>
America rejected Japan's request to open a regular service between Hiroshima and Honolulu. In response, Japan is expected to refuse to let United Airlines run extra flights between Tokyo and Los Angeles. The Japanese complain that the <b>1952 aviation treaty</b> between the two countries is lopsided.<p>
Try paying peanuts. A <b>chimpanzee</b> in Poland earned a 10% return on investments in the Warsaw stockmarket over three months, beating a good local brokerage. Karolina picked the five winners from 70 tangerines each inscribed with the name of a firm on the main market.<p>
<p></p>
