</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>What if he dies?</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/eu.gif" width=105 height=26  alt="Europe">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>What if he dies?</h1>

<font size=1>MOSCOW</font>
<p>ASSUMING that Boris Yeltsin proves fit enough to embark on his second term of office, his first duties under Russia's constitution will be to swear an oath of office and to offer a prime minister for approval by Russia's lower house of parliament, the Duma. The swearing-in ceremony has been provisionally set for August 9th. No more than a fortnight later, Mr Yeltsin must offer the Duma his choice of prime minister. If the Duma rejects three names in succession--which may take up to six weeks--the president must dissolve it and call a new election. If the new Duma also defies the president, the procedure is repeated.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some have suggested that Mr Yeltsin might try to by-pass the Duma by arguing that he was not a "newly elected" but a "re-elected" president and, by the constitution, at liberty to leave in place his incumbent prime minister, Viktor Chernomyrdin, with or without the Duma's consent. Presidential advisers discount this tactic, though Mr Yeltsin has said he wants Mr Chernomyrdin to stay.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Given Mr Yeltsin's poor health, the choice of prime minister may matter more than usual. The constitution provides for the prime minister to become acting president "in all instances where the president...is unable to perform his duties". Should the president display a "persistent inability to exercise his powers for health reasons", he must step down permanently in favour of the prime minister, and a new presidential election must be held within three months.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the constitution identifies no impartial judge of the president's condition. There was no transfer of powers to the prime minister when Mr Yeltsin suffered two heart attacks last year. The question of "who rules" is bound to be raised again if Mr Yeltsin's recent illness continues, or if he recovers enough to have the heart operation that is long overdue.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The mechanics of a mid-term succession could change if Mr Yeltsin yields to pressure from his new right-hand man, Alexander Lebed, and creates a vice-president's post for his benefit. But that would mean amending the constitution, potentially a long and difficult enterprise. An amendment could pass only with a three-quarters majority in the upper house of parliament, the federation council; a two-thirds majority in the Duma; and simple majorities in local legislatures across at least two-thirds of Russia.
</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?836607600,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
