<html><head><title>Less Intel inside</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>



<p><b>Personal computers</b></p>
<h1>Less Intel inside</h1>
<p><b>Intel came within a micron of monopolising the core of the personal-computer market and then backed off. Why?</b></p>


<p>IN LATE 1994, a smouldering dispute in the computer industry erupted in a public confrontation between Eckhard Pfeiffer, boss of Compaq, the largest <font size=-1>PC</font> maker, and Andy Grove, who runs Intel, which makes most of the processor chips at the heart of <font size=-1>PC</font>s. The clash was over Intel's increasing encroachment into the <font size=-1>PC</font> maker's market. Not only was the semiconductor giant promoting its own name and technology ("Intel inside") over those of its partners. It had also begun to sell not just processor chips, but complete "motherboards"--the electronic guts (and most of the value) of a <font size=-1>PC</font>--and even fully assembled machines, ready to be resold under others' brands.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This was not just a feud between Intel and Compaq. The dispute was mirrored across the computer industry. The more of the <font size=-1>PC</font> market--and profit--Intel took, the less was left for the companies that still designed and made their own <font size=-1>PC</font>s. Motherboards were one of the last areas in which a company could still make a mark, and justify higher prices, with its own technology. Now Intel was threatening to take that away, reducing even the biggest <font size=-1>PC</font> makers to little more than assemblers and distributors of other companies' parts.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By mid-1995 Compaq was one of the few big <font size=-1>PC</font> makers that were still profitable, and the only one making money in the booming (but low-price) home market. Even harder hit were those companies, many of them relatively obscure Taiwanese contract manufacturers, that make motherboards themselves. Intel had economies of scale and market power that they could not hope to match; for them the worry was not just lower margins, but bankruptcy. Last year Intel was the market leader in motherboards, making between 10m and 15m of them, nearly a quarter of the industry's total. Analysts expected Intel to turn the screw this year, doubling its motherboard production to about 30m.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet, miraculously, the chip maker has backed off. Intel will probably make fewer motherboards than last year, even though the overall <font size=-1>PC</font> market will grow by a fifth. Even more surprisingly, rather than making most of the boards itself, Intel is licensing its technology to the same Taiwanese manufacturers (and others) it nearly killed by entering the market in the first place. Intel and Compaq are at peace again.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There are two reasons for the shift in strategy. The first is that Intel seems to have achieved what it wanted from its motherboard invasion--which was to bolster its own core business of microprocessors. This required bullying the <font size=-1>PC</font> industry, but not destroying it. After all, <font size=-1>PC</font> makers are Intel's biggest customers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To stay ahead of its competition, Intel reckons it must release a new microprocessor generation (the 486 in 1989, the Pentium in 1993 and the Pentium Pro in 1995) every three years or so. Yet <font size=-1>PC</font> makers (and, for that matter, users) would rather stick to a slower cycle: they want to milk their investment in designs based on the previous generation as long as possible. It was in order to win this argument that Intel got into the motherboard business: if the big <font size=-1>PC</font>-makers would not rush out new designs to push Intel's latest chips, Intel would prime the pump itself by distributing its own designs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now, though, the pump is already primed. Thanks largely to its success in selling its own Pentium motherboards to <font size=-1>PC</font>-makers who could promote Pentium <font size=-1>PC</font>s in the marketplace, Intel is reaping the rewards of massive demand for the Pentium. At the same time, Intel has developed other chips that extend the power of the Pentium and do other essential jobs in the guts of a <font size=-1>PC</font>. The firm is increasingly selling the chips as a package, something its competitors--mainly Cyrix and <font size=-1>AMD</font>--cannot match. Cyrix and <font size=-1>AMD</font>, both profitable last year, expect to declare a loss in this quarter.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is why even the notoriously aggressive Mr Grove ("only the paranoid survive" ) decided to give up a share of the motherboard manufacturing market in order to focus more on the semiconductor business. It seems a safe bet: having tussled with Intel once already, the <font size=-1>PC</font> makers seem happy to promote Intel's next-generation chip, the Pentium Pro, on their own.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But there is a second reason for Intel to retreat from making its own motherboards. They were not much of an earner. Tom Thornhill, an analyst with Montgomery Securities, reckons that Intel was making 10% gross margins at best on motherboards, while its processors earn more than 60% returns. Since Intel started to make motherboards in 1993, its overall gross margins have dropped by 20% (see <a href="wb1.gif">chart</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Worse, the motherboard business cost it an estimated $100m at the end of last year, when it found itself forced to dump million of memory chips (which it bought at high prices from other companies to ship with its motherboards) after memory prices plummeted. If Intel can accomplish its market-moving aims by licensing its designs to Asian manufacturers, while passing on much of the risk of such price fluctuation at the same time, it is no wonder that even Mr Grove is willing to let some <font size=-1>PC</font> territories go unplundered.



<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?836607600,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
