<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width=271 height=24  alt="Politics"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<h2>Explosions</h2>
<p>A huge <b>bomb</b>, carried in a petrol tanker, blew up a housing complex on the King Abdul Aziz air base in Saudi Arabia. Nineteen American servicemen were killed and more than 300 people, mainly Americans, Bangladeshi and Saudis, were wounded. Radical Islamists were suspected.
<p>Leaders of 21 <b>Arab countries</b>, in Cairo to plot their response to Israel's hardline new government, repeated the call of "land for peace". Binyamin Netanyahu accused them of dictating the terms for peace. Warren Christopher flew to the region to limit the damage.</p>
<p>Voting in critical local elections in South Africa's volatile <b>KwaZulu-Natal</b> province passed off relatively peacefully, but turn-out appeared to be low.</p>
<p><b>Burundi</b>, plagued by ethnic violence, asked for help from its neighbours for the first time, at a summit of six African heads of government in Tanzania. They discussed prospects for a regional peacekeeping force if the violence worsened. The <font size=-1>UN</font> High Commissioner for Refugees said it had raised barely a third of the $288m needed to help more than 1m refugees in the region this year.</p>
<p><b>Archbishop Desmond Tutu</b>, irrepressibly jovial campaigner for democracy in South Africa, retired as archbishop of Cape Town after ten years.</p>
<p>Talks in London between the Commonwealth and its suspended member, <b>Nigeria</b>, ended fruitlessly, but Nigeria staved off sanctions by agreeing to more talks.</p>
<h2>Yeltsin poised</h2>
<p>Boris Yeltsin looked well-placed to win re-election as president in a run-off on July 3rd, but <b>ructions within the Kremlin</b> continued to jangle nerves. After a spate of sackings, Mr Yeltsin fired seven top generals, probably at the insistence of his new ally, ex-general Alexander Lebed. But the parties behind fourth-placed Grigory Yavlinsky and a far-right nationalist, Vladimir Zhirinovsky, refused to endorse him.</p>
<p>Britain agreed at a <b>European Union</b> summit in Florence to end its policy of "non-co-operation" in <font size=-1>EU</font> business. The Union agreed to a phased end to the worldwide ban on the sale of British beef and its by-products.</p>
<p>Greece's most durable political leader since the second world war, <b>Andreas Papandreou</b>, died aged 77. He had been prime minister from 1981 to earlier this year, with a break in opposition in 1989-93, and remained leader of the Pan-Hellenic Socialist Party (Pasok), which he founded, until he died. Greece's current prime minister, Costas Simitis, strove to assert his authority at a party congress.</p>
Veronica Guerin, an Irish investigative journalist who persisted in reporting on <b>terrorism and drug gangs </b>despite being shot last year, was murdered in Dublin.</p>
<p>The Organisation for Security and Co-operation in Europe, which is to run elections in <b>Bosnia</b>, said they should be held on September 14th.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><h2>Family life</h2>
<p>House and Senate Democrats unveiled a 21-point <b>"Families First Agenda" </b>tailored to middle-class voters. It aims to protect workers' pensions and offer tax breaks for education costs. The agenda suggested that the budget could be balanced without making deep cuts in Medicare or education, largely by cutting corporate subsidies and closing tax loopholes.</p>
<p>In a new book, "The Choice" , by Bob Woodward, <b>Hillary Clinton</b> was said to have consulted a spiritual adviser who encouraged her to have imaginary conversations with Eleanor Roosevelt and Mahatma Gandhi.</p>
<p>John Deutch, head of the <font size=-1>CIA</font>, announced plans to create a <b>cyberwar centre </b>at the National Security Agency to resist the threat posed by hackers to the government's computers.</p>
<p>The Supreme Court struck down a federal law limiting the money <b>political parties </b>can spend on the general-election campaigns of House and Senate candidates. The justices said it infringed the right to free speech.</p>
<p>Chile signed a free-trade agreement with<b> Mercosur</b>, the customs union between Brazil, Argentina, Uruguay and Paraguay.</p>
<p>Panama's president came clean, admitting that an audit had revealed that a little<b> drug money</b> had got into his party's election fund in 1994.</p>
<h2>Party tricks</h2>
<p>In a rare challenge to the authority of the <b>Indonesian government</b>, members of the opposition Democratic Party demonstrated in the streets of Jakarta. The government had upset the party by engineering a split which forced out Megawati Sukarnoputri as party leader. President Suharto is said to fear the growing support for Megawati, the daughter of Indonesia's first leader.</p>
<p>The new prime minister of <b>Bangladesh</b>, Sheikh Hasina, promised that her government would continue the previous administration's policy of privatisation and support for a market economy.</p>
<p>Four people were killed when police opened fire on a demonstration against new taxes in <b>Pakistan's budget</b>.</p>
<p>A stepsister and a son-in-law of <b>Deng Xiaoping </b>were retired from their government jobs, leading to speculation that the influence of China's paramount leader is waning.</p>
<p>China put off a planned visit by the German foreign minister, Klaus Kinkel, after the German parliament criticised <b>China's record</b> in Tibet.</p>
<p>
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
