<html><head><title>Russia's run-off ructions</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/eu.gif" width=105 height=26  alt="Europe">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>Russia's run-off ructions</h1>

<font size=1>MOSCOW</font>
<p>GIVEN the press of events elbowing their way into Russia's presidential election campaign in recent weeks, it would be rash to presume that no more will do so before the second round on July 3rd between Boris Yeltsin and his Communist challenger, Gennady Zyuganov. That said, Mr Yeltsin was looking well set for victory this week. The 15-point margin predicted by the opinion polls was open to doubt: the polls predicted a 12-point lead for Mr Yeltsin in the first round on June 16th, and in the event Mr Yeltsin beat Mr Zyuganov by a mere three points, taking 35% of the vote to Mr Zyuganov's 32%. But it has grown difficult to find anyone outside Mr Zyuganov's camp--indeed, anyone inside it--who genuinely expects Mr Yeltsin to lose.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Alexander Lebed, a former general who finished third in the first round with 15% of the vote, has been performing strongly in his first days as Mr Yeltsin's new security adviser and right-hand man. This week he was purging generals--seven so far--whose common fault was their closeness to the unpopular former defence minister, Pavel Grachev, ousted last week at Mr Lebed's insistence. Mr Lebed's arrival in the Kremlin has given Mr Yeltsin's ticket a fresh appeal to nationalist and law-and-order voters alike. He also published a "national security" blueprint proposing "strict control over foreign economic relations".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Yeltsin seems to have gained, too, from his sacking last week of three Kremlin hardliners caught out in a "dirty tricks" campaign against Anatoly Chubais, Mr Yeltsin's main campaign strategist. Mr Chubais, a liberal ex-minister who masterminded the privatisation of Russian industry, turned the tables by persuading Mr Yeltsin that the miscreants had become a danger to his re-election effort, and had to be sacked. Mr Lebed rallied to Mr Chubais's support. An opinion poll this week found that six out of ten respondents approved of Mr Yeltsin's action.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Perhaps the only serious worry left for Mr Yeltsin is that the public may have grown as tired as the candidates have visibly done of the whole election business. If voters stayed at home by the million on polling day, they would risk skewing the outcome towards Mr Zyuganov, whose supporters are reckoned to be more committed than Mr Yeltsin's.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But Mr Zyuganov will need all the skewing he can get, to compensate for a campaign fast running out of steam. His main gambit for the second round has been to publish a wish-list of non-communist politicians to whom professedly he would, if elected, offer jobs in government. He has been humiliated horribly in return. Yuri Luzhkov, Moscow's mayor, and others on Mr Zyuganov's list declared themselves appalled by the use of their names.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Zyuganov may well have thrown away his last and best chance of upsetting Mr Yeltsin by failing to capitalise on last week's Kremlin sackings. The three victims were senior figures intimately linked with the president. Alexander Korzhakov was chief of the presidential guard, in charge of 17,000 men. Mikhail Barsukov was head of the federal security service, the main bit of the former <font size=-1>KGB</font>. Oleg Soskovets, a first deputy prime minister, was the third-ranking figure in the government hierarchy after the prime minister, Viktor Chernomyrdin, and Mr Yeltsin himself. In the hands of a skilled propagandist--a commodity the Communist Party used to have in plenty--the whole affair could have been made to reek of slush funds, private armies and treachery. Throw in the sacking of Mr Grachev, and the attempted murder of a Kremlin business crony the previous week, and there was material to hand for a smear-job of Jackson Pollock proportions. Yet Mr Zyuganov made barely an effort. His few contradictory mutterings showed him to be as dazed by the affair as everybody else.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Zyuganov's hesitancy left Mr Yeltsin free to calm the stir--and he seemed to do it rather well. Mr Grachev and Mr Barsukov were reported to be resting this week at their dachas. Mr Korzhakov was thought likely to regain a less exalted position within the Kremlin. Doubtless Mr Soskovets was hoping for something, too. In an interview published on June 26th, Mr Yeltsin said he "owed a lot" to Mr Korzhakov, his bodyguard since 1985, and the two would remain friends.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;No less importantly, there have even been hints that Mr Yeltsin has been having second thoughts about Mr Chubais, blaming him for having forced the issue. Mr Yeltsin said this week that he did not plan to give Mr Chubais another job in government after the election--something Mr Chubais had said earlier he did not in any event want. He had resigned as first deputy prime minister in January after Mr Yeltsin made him a scapegoat for the hardships of economic reform.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Yeltsin's equivocation towards Mr Korzhakov and Mr Chubais, champions of the hardline and liberal forces contending for influence in the Kremlin, suggests he has yet to decide what team he will want around him should he win re-election. In choosing it he will have to deal with the tension already visible between Mr Lebed, the new strongman, and Mr Chernomyrdin, the long-standing prime minister--whether by reining in Mr Lebed, when the votes are safely counted, or changing Mr Chernomyrdin. He will need to bring in a reformist--Grigory Yavlinsky, perhaps--at a high level of government if he is to build on the centre-liberal coalition that he has rallied behind his presidential campaign. He will need to pay due homage to the powerful Mr Luzhkov. He will need, too, to plan for his succession, given the precarious nature of his health. If Mr Lebed thinks the deal already done, good luck to him. He will need it, with Mr Korzhakov at his back.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?836002800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
