<html><head><title>Selection rules</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Education</b></p>
<h1>Selection rules</h1>

<p>"KNOCK, knock. <i>Who's there?</i> Harriet. <i>Harriet who?</i> See, I told you they'd forget." This joke did the rounds in the Labour Party earlier this year as it became clear that the party had suffered little electoral damage from the row which followed the revelation that Harriet Harman, the party's health spokeswoman, was planning to send her son to a selective grammar school. One of the aims of a government white paper on education, published on June 25th, was to try to reopen the split in Labour between those (including Tony Blair, its leader) who want to take a softer line on selection, and those who consider grammar schools the epitome of how British education caters to the better off or more able and fails the vast majority.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Gillian Shephard, the education and employment secretary, accused Labour of "living in the 1970s" in opposing the white paper's proposals to give schools more leeway to select pupils. David Blunkett, her Labour shadow, said she was proposing "selection for the few at the expense of the many". Although there is now a clear difference between the parties on this issue, the white paper falls far short of creating the "grammar school in every town" that John Major, the prime minister, says he wants. And the paper contains other sensible measures (such as giving schools more control over their budgets and encouraging more of them to develop a specialist flavour) which Labour strongly supports.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although Mrs Shephard admits to supporting the abolition of grammar schools in Norfolk when she sat on its county council in the early 1980s, she now argues that giving schools more leeway to choose at least a proportion of their pupils will be a good thing, for two reasons: first, it will be easier for head teachers to build a distinctive ethos for their schools, something which studies suggest makes them better. Second, it will encourage schools to compete for pupils, adding to the pressure on them to improve their performance.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The white paper proposes removing some obstacles to building new grammar schools, but promises no extra money to pay for this. The school-aged population is growing but there are 880,000 surplus school places in England alone, so in many areas the government could not open new schools without facing accusations of wasting taxpayers' money. It may also face embarrassment if a few head teachers use their new-found freedom to select pupils according to their personal prejudices.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Another danger for the Conservatives in pushing for more selection is that many middle-class voters currently pay extra for a house in the catchment area of a good school, to make sure their children get in. In several cases, such as one in Surrey in January, plans to introduce selection have been scrapped after local parents protested that it would mean some places going to outsiders who passed the entrance exam.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, such selection by property prices is hard to defend. It would be better, as the white paper allows, for schools to adopt a wide variety of admissions policies, suited to their individual character and to local circumstances. It certainly makes sense, for example, for schools that specialise in technology to give preference to pupils who can demonstrate a flair for the subject. Many technology schools already do this, even using computer games to test pupils' aptitude.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Blair now promises, in spite of grumbles by some "Old Labour" colleagues, that the remaining 163 grammar schools will be left alone unless there is strong parental pressure to change them. A policy paper on schools, "Diversity and excellence", published last year, even hinted that Labour would let specialist schools take into account pupils' aptitude in their chosen specialism. The party should go further and banish its paranoia about selection altogether. There is no need for a wholesale return to the old "11-plus" exam with its two-tier system of grammar schools for those who pass and secondary moderns for the "failures". If Labour wants diversity and excellence, a wider variety of admissions policies would help to achieve both.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?836002800,iss">Search</a>
