<html><head><title>Trading up</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<h1>Trading up</h1>


LABOUR reckons that changes to trade data due over the next few months are an "outrageous" attempt by the Tories to fiddle the numbers before a general election, "to create an illusion of success." At first glance, this claim seems fair. Figures out on June 27th showed that Britain had a trade deficit with countries outside the <font size=-1>EU</font> of &#163;800m in May, and of &#163;1.3 billion with the whole world in April (see <a href="br1.gif">chart</a>). With the changes in place, these numbers could be halved. They will, however, paint a truer picture of Britain's trade performance.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now, the headline trade figures refer only to "visible" trade--in manufactured goods and raw materials. As our chart shows, Britain has had a "visible" trade deficit in most years since 1970 (and, indeed, in most of the previous century and a half). But Britain's overall trading position during this time has been much healthier, thanks to "invisibles". These include trade in services, international transfers of money, and income from overseas assets. They have been in surplus in every year since 1970 (and, indeed, since the Napoleonic Wars), except 1990. As a result, Britain's current account (its net financial position with the rest of the world) was nowhere near as much in the red as the visible trade data suggested.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By the end of this year, the government will release a new measure, "trade in goods and services", combining visible trade and around 30% of invisibles. The term invisibles will be killed off. The new data will better reflect the current-account position. Although in deficit, this has shrunk in recent years to around 1% of <font size=-1>GDP</font>, less than in the United States and the same as in Germany. In the 1980s, the deficit caused alarm, though not in the government, by soaring to 4% of <font size=-1>GDP</font>.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Michael Saunders, an economist at Salomon Brothers, an investment bank, points out that in the past three years British exports have climbed faster in response to rises in global demand than they did in previous decades. The responsiveness of imports to rising British domestic demand was unchanged.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This improved export competitiveness failed to show up in the current-account data because the British economy grew faster than did the economies of most of Britain's main trading partners. As growth in these economies picks up to British levels, exports to them should rise rapidly. In 1997, reckons Mr Saunders, the current account could be in the black for the first time since 1985.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?836002800,iss">Search</a>
