<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p align=center><table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" width=231 height=24  alt="Britain"></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>
<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<p><b>Peace in our time</b> &nbsp;
The government stopped blocking European Union business after <font size=-1>EU</font> ministers agreed on a framework for lifting the worldwide ban on exports of British beef.</p>
<p><b>Unhealthy</b> &nbsp;
Sandy Macara, chairman of the British Medical Association, said the National Health Service was "sinking like the Titanic" because it was underfinanced by &#163;6 billion a year.</p>
<p><b>Flexible friend</b> &nbsp;
Labour proposed allowing unemployed people to receive up to six months' worth of benefits as a lump sum, to help them start up a business or to pay for training.</p>
<p><b>Bombshell</b> &nbsp;
Tony Blair, Labour's leader, said he would be prepared to use Britain's nuclear weapons, but would not say under what circumstances.</p>
<p><b>Bill of wrongs</b> &nbsp;
<font size=-1>MP</font>s approved a change to the 1689 Bill of Rights to allow them to sue for libel over comments about their parliamentary work.</p>
<p><b>Battle scene</b> &nbsp;
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
The government's plans to raise &#163;1.5 billion by selling 60,000 armed-forces homes were put in doubt after 65 Conservative <font size=-1>MP</font>s signed a motion calling for further consultation before the sale.</p>
<p><b>Money no object</b> &nbsp;
The Court of Appeal ruled that local councils can not withdraw care services from the elderly and disabled on the grounds that the councils had run out of money. The issue will now go to the House of Lords.</p>
<p><b>Last post</b> &nbsp;
After the first in a series of strikes by postal workers, the government said it might suspend the Post Office's monopoly on deliveries costing less than &#163;1 if the dispute continued.</p>
<p><b>Up in the air</b> &nbsp;
The Office of Fair Trading said it regarded the proposed link between British Airways and American Airlines as a merger, and so would investigate the plans.</p>
<p><b>Age no bar</b> &nbsp;
A lawnmower store in Walsall, West Midlands, advertised for staff aged at least 80 because the owner says local youngsters are workshy.
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
