<html><head><title>America Offline</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>America Offline</h1>

<p>THE world's largest on-line information service, America Online (<font size=-1>AOL</font>), has often proved sceptics wrong. In 1991, when it first challenged CompuServe, then the market leader, it looked a lost cause. Thanks to better software, <font size=-1>AOL</font> overtook CompuServe last year. Then, when the Internet's World Wide Web took off in 1994, analysts reckoned <font size=-1>AOL</font> would be its first victim; instead, <font size=-1>AOL</font> added access to the Web to its offering and its subscriptions grew even faster. Now the critics are gathering again--and this time they could be right.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On June 25th <font size=-1>AOL</font>'s president and chief operating officer, William Razzouk, who had been in the job for just four months, resigned. A few days earlier, in an unconnected development, the Federal Trade Commission announced that it was investigating the company for unfair billing practices. And over the past two months, <font size=-1>AOL</font>'s share price has fallen by more than 40%--principally because <font size=-1>AOL</font> has had to cut its prices in the face of stiffer competition.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>AOL</font>, it now seems, delayed, rather than prevented, its clash with the Web. The Internet has always beaten on-line services, such as <font size=-1>AOL</font>, in terms of the diversity of content available, and on cost. <font size=-1>AOL</font>'s selling point has been that it is easy to use (its software is simple and it provides users with technical support and so on). Now Internet providers (which include the likes of <font size=-1>AT&T</font>, America's biggest telephone company) are starting to offer help lines; and Internet software is becoming ever simpler.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The result is that, in the United States, <font size=-1>AOL</font> is still growing phenomenally fast (and faster than direct rivals such as CompuServe), but slower than in its heyday (see <a href="wb2.gif">chart</a>). All but 185,000 of <font size=-1>AOL</font>'s 6m or so subscribers are in America. <font size=-1>AOL</font>'s quarterly growth rate in the United States peaked in the first quarter of 1995 at around 46%; for the same period this year it was 15.5%. Although <font size=-1>AOL</font> more than doubled its subscriber numbers to 4.5m in 1995, the Internet itself grew just as fast over the same period. Forrester Research, a consultancy in Cambridge, Massachusetts, predicts that <font size=-1>AOL</font> will reach 9m American subscribers in 1998--and then decline.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>AOL</font> claims that it is taking a brief rest from its frantic hunt for subscribers so that it can concentrate on launching an improved version of the service later this year. But it admits that the time when it could expect to double its total number of subscribers every years is over.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even if <font size=-1>AOL</font> has peaked, its decline will not be precipitous. <font size=-1>GNN</font>, its Internet-only service, will smoothe the ride. So will <font size=-1>AOL</font>'s foreign operations--it now has joint ventures in France, Germany and Britain, and will be launching in Japan this year. But potential users in these countries will have access to easy-to-use Internet software that was unavailable to their predecessors in the United States, so <font size=-1>AOL</font> is unlikely to see similar growth.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So far, when established companies, including Microsoft, have discovered that they are in competition with the Internet, they have either adapted their strategy, or lost.
</td></tr></table>
