<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width=273 height=24  alt="Business"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>

<p>


<h2>Growth factor</h2>
<p>(See <a href="wtw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>Japan's economy took off in the first quarter at the fastest pace for 23 years, producing year-on-year growth of 5.7% and an even more spectacular 12.7% annualised growth rate. The yen strengthened against the dollar, as did prospects of an early interest-rate rise. But much of the spurt in growth came from a one-off &#165;14 trillion ($138 billion) government stimulus. Stronger consumer spending helped to reduce Japan's <b>trade surplus </b>for the 18th month in a row, to a level 60% lower in May than it had been a year earlier.<p>
Signs of <b>growth in Germany </b>remain sparse, said a Bundesbank report. Hans Tietmeyer, head of the Bundesbank, said that with low inflation likely to continue "for some time", there should be no need to raise German interest rates "in the foreseeable future".<p>
The traditional ritual of a last-minute deal averted $2 billion-worth of American tariffs on Chinese goods, after the two countries reached agreement in their row over <b>intellectual property rights</b>. China's pledge of a crackdown on counterfeiting of <font size=-1>CD</font>s, <font size=-1>CD</font>-<font size=-1>ROM</font>s and laser discs seems a little more concrete than previous promises.<p>
Neil Kinnock, the <font size=-1>EU</font>'s transport commissioner, won his battle for the European Commission to negotiate an <b>open-skies pact </b>with America on behalf of <font size=-1>EU</font> members. <font size=-1>EU</font> transport ministers granted permission for negotiations to be opened, but for now only on such peripheral issues as computer-reservation systems. The more important matter of routes will remain covered by bilateral treaties between America and individual member countries.

<h2>Copper bottoms</h2>
<p>The London Metal Exchange (and copper) recovered some of its equilibrium in the wake of the <b>Sumitomo scandal</b>, in which Yasuo Hamanaka ran up estimated losses of $1.8 billion in unauthorised copper dealing, mainly through the <font size=-1>LME</font>, over ten years, while working for the world's largest copper trader. Authorities in Britain, Japan and America all began investigations. Once again, Japan was criticised for poor risk management and weak oversight by regulators. Sumitomo scrapped a planned share buyback and set aside over $1 billion to help cover losses.

<h2>Grounded</h2>
<p><p>
The Federal Aviation Administration suspended operations at <b>ValuJet</b>, one of whose aircraft crashed last month in Florida with the loss of all 110 people on board. ValuJet's share price plunged 40%. No sooner had the <font size=-1>FAA</font> acted than the Clinton administration, citing the watchdog's "lax" oversight of the no-frills airline, ordered a shake-up at the <font size=-1>FAA</font> and forced its top safety official into early retirement.<p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
Employees of Italy's state-owned airline, <b>Alitalia</b>, accepted a restructuring plan to cut costs in exchange for a 20% stake in the airline. Alitalia, which has lost money for seven years running, may now get more capital from the state.<p>
<b>Lufthansa</b> gave a warning that business was bad, news taken to mean that Germany's flagship airline is heading for a big loss in the first six months of the year.<p>
The seldom-happy alliance between China and South Korea that was meant to build a <b>regional Asian jet </b>broke down irretrievably.<p>
Strikes hit <b>South Korea</b>'s motor industry. Pay disputes brought production to a halt at Kia Motors, the country's second-largest car maker, and at Asia Motors, a lorry maker. Hyundai Motor shut down some production lines because of a strike at a parts maker, Mando.

<h2>Chopped</h2>
<p>The French government said that a plan by <b>Moulinex </b>to lay off 2,600 of its 11,500 workers is "unacceptable" . The French electrical appliances company, which plans to close plants and move some production to Mexico, also disclosed its biggest-ever net loss, of FFr702m ($142m) in the year to end-March, on sales of FFr7.8 billion. Moulinex shares jumped 21% in one day.<p>
A British brewing and catering group, <b>Compass</b>, won its fight for control of <b>Eurest France</b>, the third-largest contract caterer in France, a prime market. It is paying a reluctant Sodexho, France's largest contract caterer, FFr590m ($114m) to buy out its 33.34% stake, plus FFr2.8m to Epargne D&eacute;veloppement for a 0.16% stake.<p>
The shareholders of France's <b>Chargeurs </b>agreed to split the conglomerate into Path&eacute;, devoted to media and communications, and Chargeurs International, devoted to textiles. The companies will start trading on the Paris bourse on June 24th.<p>
The chief executive of <b>CLT</b>, a big Luxembourg-based media group, resigned. Michel Delloye's abrupt departure came on the eve of <font size=-1>CLT</font>'s planned merger with the television arm of Bertelsmann, a German rival.<p>
<b>Sony</b>, Japan's leading consumer-electronics company, entered America's personal-computer market with its first two models, the fruits of a recently formed alliance with Intel, a chip maker.<p>
Acquisitions and strong demand sent profits at <b>British Steel</b> soaring by 90% to a record &#163;1.1 billion ($1.7 billion) in the year to end-March, with sales rising 47% to &#163;7.1 billion. The full-year dividend rose by a third, but, with steel prices and demand now dropping sharply in Europe, the company was gloomier about the outlook for the current year.<p>
Malaysia's state-owned oil and gas company, <b>Petronas</b>, is buying 30% of South Africa's largest oil refiner, <b>Engen</b>, for 1.9 billion rand ($436m).<p>
<p></p>
</td></tr></table></center>
