<html><head><title>From the land of the dead</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width=258 height=26  alt="American Survey">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>From the land of the dead</h1>

<font size=1>SAN BENITO, LLANO AND AUSTIN</font>
<p>THE tiny town of Luckenbach, in the Texas hill country, has little to recommend it but a song ("Let's go to Luckenbach, Texas") and an annual picnic held by Willie Nelson, the state's grizzled country-music star, every Fourth of July. This year, the picnic has a solemn purpose. Profits from it will go to local farmers who have been unable to make a living since the rains failed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In Texas, and all across the south-west, rainfall this year is as much as 70-85% below normal. When the rare rains come, they pummel the cracked earth and withered crops with storms of wind and hail. The death of a young woman on June 4th was a small sign of the suffering. Like three other Mexican women who had died of thirst before her, she had tried to slip into Texas across the baking ranch-lands that guard the American side of the Rio Grande. A border patrol found her body under a shrivelled tree on a desolate stretch of a path nicknamed, because it is used by illegal immigrants, the "Ho Chi Minh Trail". In a normal year, streams and watering holes along the trail help the migrants. This year, there was no water to be found.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Rick Perry, the Texas commissioner of agriculture, is a rancher with an aversion to hyperbole. He calls the drought the worst natural disaster to hit Texas this century. Already, he says, it is worse than the drought of 1956, once considered the definitive Texas dry spell. It was not unexpected; its approach had been watched for the past three years, as it crept up from north-east Mexico. But this is the first year it has affected the whole of Texas (see <a href="am1.gif">map</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Agriculture remains a pillar of the Texas economy. A fifth of the state's jobs are tied to food and fibre production. Income from agriculture came to $14 billion in 1995, with an estimated $46 billion in indirect sales (such as sales of farm equipment and the takings of small-town stores). Losses in 1996 have been catastrophic. Mr Perry commissioned Texas <font size=-1>A&M</font> University to provide an estimate: it found that the state will lose at least $6.5 billion indirectly from the drought this year. The biggest losers will be cotton, cattle and cereal crops.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Across central and west Texas, water holes and wells have dried up and the state's natural limestone aquifers are desperately low. In west Texas the drought has brought fears that the land will turn to desert. The Monahans field of sand dunes in southern New Mexico, among others, is predicted to billow eastward into Texas. The big cities are worried. Houston and Dallas report their lowest rainfalls since the second world war, San Antonio its lowest since records began in 1885.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the High Plains, which stretch north from Lubbock into the Oklahoma panhandle, rains swept in belatedly from the Rockies in the past few weeks, although farmers there now wish they had stayed away. This flat sandy reach of land is the largest cotton-producing region in the country. This year, the crop is ruined. The rain was followed by hailstones an inch in diameter, and the damage to the cotton was "the same as me dropping a 300-pound rock on your head," according to one grower. As if this were not enough, hot winds came from the New Mexico deserts, soaking up moisture and blowing along sand which shredded the cotton on the stalk.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For many years now, farmers in the High Plains have adopted "sandfighting" methods. These are based on rough-tilling, which involves ploughing the land so deep that the resulting ridges act as barriers to stop the topsoil blowing away. As a result, the dustbowl conditions that destroyed farming in much of Texas and Oklahoma six decades ago will not be repeated. Still, the cost will be crippling. The Texas <font size=-1>A&M</font> study estimates that $704m-worth of cotton will be lost this year, and that the direct economic impact of the drought statewide will be more than $2.4 billion.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Cotton may be the biggest loser, but Mr Perry is just as worried for the cattlemen. Ranchers, he says, have taken "a silver bullet in the heart." At Crabapple Crossing Ranch, near Llano in central Texas, one forlorn kingfisher haunts a creek that is now a trough of yellow mud less than a foot wide, and cattle scrape at withered grass. Ranchers must buy feed from as far away as Michigan. Feed prices, especially for beef cattle, have risen so steeply that not a cow in Texas can pay its way. The result is panic selling. The Texas and Southwest Cattle Raisers' Association has reported a 40-50% drop in livestock prices in 1996. Many farmers had $400 loans out on cattle that fetched only $200. Some frustrated ranchers, having liquidated their entire herds, will not be re-entering the market for at least 18 months.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The drought could not have come at a worse time for Texas cattle-ranchers. Mexican ranchers, themselves ravaged by drought, flooded Texan markets with cheap beef in 1995, which pushed down prices even before the drought took them lower. Cattle ranching--dairy and beef--is worth $4.6 billion to the Texas economy. The Texas <font size=-1>A&M</font> study says the drought will cut at least $838m directly and $1.55 billion indirectly off the value of the state's herds.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In south Texas, the water supply is close to failing. Reservoirs fed by the Rio Grande watershed are at a quarter of their normal levels, and things are made worse by agreements that require the Rio Grande's water to be shared between Texas (57%) and Mexico (43%). Cameron County--the southernmost in Texas, on the Gulf of Mexico--is in its third year of drought: reservoirs there are running so low that farmers fear there will be no water for irrigating next year's crops. Even if there is, the salinity of the irrigated water means that farmers still need substantial rainfall to cleanse the soil and bring in a harvest.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The tropical appearance of Brownsville and Harlingen, the county's main towns, is misleading, say local farmers. In 1995 Cameron County faced a collapse of its agriculture when the cotton crop failed, bringing in only a sixth of its predicted yield. The Woodlum cotton gin in San Benito, near Harlingen, expected 12,000 bales of cotton in 1995 but received only 577; a similar shortfall this year will put it out of business.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The drought puts Texas bankers in a quandary. They can choose either to foreclose on farming clients and take a probable 70% loss on sales of farm equipment, or refinance farmers in the hope of a good harvest in 1997. Both Mr Perry and the governor of Texas, George W. Bush, have urged the banks to be flexible in their autumn refinancing of drought-battered farmers. So far, the banks have shown willing. For his part, Mr Perry is pressing the Agriculture Department in Washington to show more generosity in federal crop-insurance programmes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The end of the "Great Drought" in 1957 brought a spree of dam-building across Texas. This was meant to ensure that the state could see out future droughts. Mr Perry is pressing for a similar response to this year's drought--and with good reason. Since 1957, the population of Texas has grown from 9m to 17m; it is predicted to rise to 31m by 2020. And agriculture has diversified in more water-greedy directions. Rice farmers, for instance, use more water, relative to production, than any other sort of Texas farming. Their ten-year water rights are up for renegotiation in 1997, and will be affected by the drought.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Industrial demands have added to the strain. The largest water-users in central Texas are micro-processor plants. The Motorola plant in Austin consumes 11% of the city's water supply, 4.5m gallons a day. New reservoirs are almost certain to be built, and water conservation laws will be tightened; meanwhile, Mr Bush is using the drought to try to change Texans' water-using habits "literally one drop at a time" . It is hard work; Texas is now so urban, and the cities are so oblivious of the hardship in the countryside, that Mr Perry says one of the toughest parts of his job is just to get the message across.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Will rain come to the rescue? No, say most long-range weather forecasts. The consensus seems to be that the drought will ease next year before getting worse in 1998 and 1999. Studies link the drought to a sunspot cycle not due to end until the millennium. All this is bad news for Texas agriculture. Without a bumper harvest, refinancing will saddle many farmers with more debt that they can handle. And so sure are Texans that the drought will go on that one Austin car dealer is offering free cars to customers if it rains on the morning of the Luckenbach picnic.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?835398000,iss">Search</a>
