<html><head><title>A song for Europe</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>A song for Europe</h1>


<p>THE Euro 96 soccer tournament is doing much for English self-esteem but nothing for British national harmony. Before the first ball was kicked, a row broke out over the <font size=-1>BBC</font>'s choice of "Ode to Joy" as the theme tune for its coverage of the contest. After all, noted horrified critics, this was composed by Ludwig von Beethoven, a (wait for it) German. Never mind that German television coverage has been introduced with a song by Oasis, a fashionable Mancunian rock group, called "Don't Look Back in Anger" (a reference, perhaps, to England's defeat of West Germany in the 1966 World Cup final). <font size=-1>ITV</font> opted for the sublime but baffling "Jerusalem", a hymn about a Middle Eastern Jew visiting England.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The fans seem equally confused. Towards the end of England's 4-1 thrashing of the Netherlands on June 18th, the jubilant Wembley crowd sang "Rule Britannia"--hardly appropriate, given that one of the British nations, Scotland, was at that moment being eliminated from the tournament, and another, Wales, had failed even to reach this month's finals. Days earlier, when England played Scotland, "God Save the Queen", the national anthem of the United Kingdom, was played for the English team, to booing by Scottish fans; the Jocks were allowed to sing their own "national anthem", "Flower of Scotland", a sentimental folk song. The <font size=-1>BBC</font>'s radio commentator, Northern Irish, disapproved--a unionist, presumably.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In some ways, England's monopolisation of "God Save the Queen", and Scottish hostility to it, are understandable. The song was written during the uprising by Catholic Scots in 1745, to rekindle support for George <font size=-1>II</font> after his army was defeated at Prestonpans. It included this verse: "Lord grant that Marshal Wade, May bring the mighty aid, victory bring. May he sedition hush, and like a torrent rush, rebellious Scots to crush, God save..." But any bekilted fans upset by these words should note that the reference is to rebellious Scots, not the entire race. England and Scotland, remember, had been joined as a single state under the Act of Union of 1702. And the offending words have long been swapped for well-meaning nonsense about all nations forming "one family, the wide world over".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;No, all British soccer teams should use "God Save the Queen", or none. If Scotland wants its own song, England should have one as well. Perhaps the Eurosceptical "There'll always be an England" would best fit the current mood. On the other hand, there is a song that neatly encompasses both the players and their more zealous supporters: "Mad dogs and Englishmen".



</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?835398000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br4.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
