<html><head><title>Overturning the trough</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Legal aid</b></p>
<h1>Overturning the trough</h1>


<p>MOST politicians desperately want to be loved. Lord Mackay, the Lord Chancellor, appears to be an exception. Fresh from the all-party battering he received on the divorce bill, he is poised to take on the legal profession.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The nation's appetite for justice at the state's expense, like the demand for free health care, has proved to be insatiable. This year the legal-aid budget is expected to exceed &#163;1.5 billion, a five-fold increase in a decade, making it the fastest-growing area of public expenditure (see <a href="br1.gif">chart</a>). As a first step towards introducing a way to limit expenditure, the government is publishing a white paper on June 25th. It heralds the most radical shake-up of legal aid since it was introduced half a century ago.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The nub of the problem is that, aside from plaintiffs or defendants themselves, the people who benefit from legal aid are the same as those who largely determine whether it should be granted: lawyers. The result is supplier-induced demand. The legal-aid budget has been kept from exploding only by excluding more and more people from the scheme. Less than half the population is now eligible, compared with 70% a decade ago. Only the poorest 10% get all their legal bills paid.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"What I am trying to achieve is a method of control," says Lord Mackay. His plan is for a system of block contracts under which the Legal Aid Board, which dispenses the cash, will negotiate with solicitors to take on a specified number of cases.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By replacing an open-ended scheme in which lawyers decide which cases should be fought with a cash-limited system in which ministers determine priorities, the government will deprive the lawyers of influence over the size of the budget. All sorts of changes should follow from that. The incentive to spin out weak cases long after they should have been abandoned will disappear. Costs will be much more tightly monitored. The merits of cases will, it is presumed, be more closely examined.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The other flaw in the current system which the white paper addresses is imbalance of risk. Anybody involved in a legal action against a legally aided plaintiff or defendant is in an unenviable position. Not only is he fighting a litigant backed by unlimited resources but, even if he wins, he will not normally be able to recover his costs. Lord Mackay says he is determined to restore some equality of risk.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The white paper will thus recommend allowing courts to direct that legally aided plaintiffs should pay a share of the costs of a case, depending on their resources. Even if an applicant has no income or realisable assets, the white paper is expected to suggest that he or she pay a nominal amount--say &#163;20-30--before being granted legal aid.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Critics say that the block-grant system may mean that some worthy cases will be rejected because of budget constraints. And, by shifting the burden of risk, these proposals might deter poor people from bringing good cases for fear of having cost orders made against them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The private sector might offer a solution to this problem. The Lord Chancellor believes that if legal costs were made more predictable, then commercial insurers would be prepared to underwrite the risks of losing a case. Officials in the Lord Chancellor's department are studying a scheme which offers &#163;18,000-worth of cover for a &#163;300 premium.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Lawyers are bitterly opposed to these changes. The Law Society, which represents solicitors, claims that the block-contract system will be complex and costly to administer. The Bar Council, which represents barristers, says that cash limits will be impossible to impose fairly and will lead to injustice. Their criticisms would carry more weight if those who made them did not have a direct financial interest in preserving the old system.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?835398000,iss">Search</a>
