<html><head><title>Sold short</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>Sold short</h1>

PREDICTIONS of stronger economic growth over the next 18 months rely on a big rise in consumer spending as tax cuts and windfall gains from building-society shares make people better off. The figures for retail sales in May, published on June 19th, therefore came as a blow (see <a href="br2.gif">chart</a>). A survey by the British Retail Consortium, a trade group, had suggested that the growth in that month's sales would be the strongest for two years. Instead, sales were lower in volume terms than in April. Are hopes of consumer-led growth misplaced?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Retail sales have been disappointing all year. The annual growth rate, which picked up from next to nothing last September to around 2% in December, has failed to accelerate further. It is now lower than in 1993 and 1994.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet the grounds for expecting higher consumption seem strong. Spending power is rising: the gap between average earnings growth and the growth of taxes plus prices, negative at the end of last year, now exceeds three percentage points, its widest for three years. True, much of this extra cash could be saved, but the savings ratio, which measures the proportion of income saved, is already quite high, suggesting that there is scope for more spending. Also, April saw record monthly consumer-credit growth, to an annual rate of more than 14%, and the consumer-confidence index is now at its highest since 1988.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Headline retail sales may simply be a poor guide to consumer sentiment. A better one is sales of household goods, which includes expensive items such as washing machines which people tend to buy only when they feel flush. As our chart shows, these grew by 9.8% in the year to May, and are on a rising trend. Moreover, retail sales account for only part of consumer spending. Total consumption grew by 0.8% in the first quarter of this year, the highest quarterly figure since 1993. Since retail sales rose by only 0.4%, other sorts of spending must have risen by over 1%.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Prospects for a pick-up in Britain's overall economic growth still seem fair, therefore. But would the country's currently depressed manufacturers feel the benefit? Geoffrey Dicks, an economist at NatWest Markets, a stockbroking firm, is sceptical. He calculates that in the past year domestic demand for manufactured goods rose by 4%--yet manufacturing output grew by only 0.8%. In this period imports of finished manufactured goods soared by 12.7%. Consumers are spending again, but British manufacturers are not making what they want to buy.



</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?835398000,iss">Search</a>
