<html><head><title>Past is future</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Trade unions</b></p>
<h1>Past is future</h1>

<p>FIRST there was New Labour; now there is New Unionism, an initiative launched on June 18th by the Trades Union Congress (<font size=-1>TUC</font>) to try to reverse the decline in union membership, which has fallen to 6.75m from 12m in 1979. But while New Labour is keen to dump the baggage of history, New Unionism harks back to the 1880s, when trade unionism spread like wildfire through the British workforce.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At that time, New Unionism was the name given to a movement which transformed unions from the preserves of a few craftsmen to the representatives of a mass of workers in the rapidly growing industrial towns and cities. Now the unions are in a similar situation. In many of their strongholds, employment is shrinking, as it was for the 19th-century craftsmen. And just as the unions had to fight their way into the expanding factories of Victorian Britain, they now find themselves largely shut out of many growing businesses, from computing to fast food.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The 19th-century union leaders realised that in order to have clout with bosses, they had to get most of their workers to join up. That meant putting most of their effort into recruitment. But over the years, unions have spent increasing amounts of time and money on servicing their existing members, less on winning new ones. This has helped them to defend their traditional strongholds, but has stopped them from making inroads into new workplaces.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;American unions, whose memberships have also fallen sharply, have already realised that they need to put more muscle into organising non-union workplaces. Few unions on either side of the Atlantic give details of how much they spend on this (mostly because they do not know), but one exception is America's Oil, Chemical and Atomic Workers' Union. In 1944 it spent 48% of its income on recruitment, but by the early 1990s this had fallen to a mere 2%. Realising that something had to be done, the union raised this proportion to 12% in 1995. The <font size=-1>TUC</font> says the figure in Britain is probably well under 10%.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The trouble is that the number of people leaving unions is as big a problem as the lack of people joining. If less effort were put into satisfying existing members, even more would leave. The solution is to get unpaid shop stewards to do more of the work now done by paid officials--from negotiating pay to representing workers in disciplinary hearings. But union officials are bound to resist a switch from these familiar tasks to the more stressful job of fighting for new members in new industries where most of the workers are indifferent and all of the bosses are hostile.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Faced with similar conditions, the original New Unionists in the 1880s often had to go to great lengths, holding secret meetings whenever and wherever they could reach potential recruits. Sonia McKay of the Labour Research Department (a union-funded research body) says unions will have to revive this spirit of adventure if they want to reverse their decline. She points to a recent example of union officials holding a gathering in a bank at midnight because this was the only time they could reach the cleaners they were trying to recruit.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unions are having to look to history for ways to restore their fortunes because Labour is no longer promising to ride to their rescue if elected. A new policy document on employment rights, to be published by Labour on June 22nd, promises unions a right to recognition but little else. Almost all of the restrictions imposed on unions since 1979 will stay. Perhaps the unions will be tempted to wind down their political funds and ask their members to support a drive for new members instead of a drive for a new government.



