<html><head><title>Not so mobile</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>Not so mobile</h1>
<p>
THE selling point of a mobile telephone is that you can take it with you. But not too far, at least in Europe. Several of Europe's network operators doctor the handsets that they sell subscribers so that they are virtually useless if the subscriber switches network.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The operators subsidise as much as two-thirds of the price of handsets to encourage subscribers to sign up. If subscribers take the telephones to another network before they have paid back the subsidy, the network loses. But doctoring the handset locks subscribers into the first network they sign up for: few throw away a perfectly good digital handset (worth $500 or more, even if they paid considerably less for it) simply to get cheaper calls with another operator.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A case of monopolistic abuse? The European Commission is now investigating one particular scheme, known as subscriber identification module locking. Customers with <font size=-1>SIM</font>-locked telephones who want to change operators either have to buy a new (and often almost identical) handset or pay a hefty fee, sometimes as high as $220, to have their telephones unlocked. Earlier this month, Karel Van Miert, the European competition commissioner, wrote to every mobile-phone operator and manufacturer in the <font size=-1>EU</font>, warning them that <font size=-1>SIM</font>-locking was anti-competitive.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Operators who sell <font size=-1>SIM</font>-locked phones, such as Britain's Orange Personal Communications, argue that they do so for security reasons. A handset will work only with its <font size=-1>SIM</font> card; and that card will work only with its original network, so thieves will not be able to take stolen handsets elsewhere. True, but there are less drastic ways to deal with this. The <font size=-1>GSM</font> specifications, which cover most digital networks, allocate a unique number to each handset; if operators were to share a list of stolen-handset numbers, thieves would be equally hamstrung.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Only a few of Europe's 33 digital phone operators use <font size=-1>SIM</font>-locking. Most others that subsidise handsets use fixed-term contracts to earn back their investment. However, Britain's Office of Fair Trading has already warned British suppliers to stop the practice. Phone users may yet roam free.</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?835398000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="st1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
