<html><head><title>Re-engineering peer review</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/st.gif" width=371 height=26  alt="Science And Technology">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<p><b>The Internet</b></p>
<h1>Re-engineering peer review</h1>

<font size=1>HELSINGOR</font><p><b>The Internet was developed by scientists for scientists, but many now fear that its anarchic style could endanger the quality of research. The threat is an opportunity in disguise</b></p>

<p>SOME may question the purpose of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development, but it certainly knows how to throw a good conference. Its latest bash--"The Global Research Village" has just been held near Helsingor (better known to Shakespeare lovers as Elsinore) in Denmark. The topic was how the Internet might help science. This might be thought ironic, as the thing was largely created by scientists in the first place. But international organisations have to justify their existence somehow, and even scientists are not above a little prompting on how best to use their toys. Those who have done well under the old system are sometimes as suspicious of new machines as any Luddites.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In general, there was wide agreement about the benefits of the Internet for the exchange of scientific information. But there was also concern about what it might do to the quality of that information. In particular, the experts attending the conference were near-unanimous in dismissing electronic challenges to the time-honoured tradition of peer review for scientific publications. They should not have been.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Peer review is what happens when a hopeful scientist submits an article to a distinguished journal. After several months (that is if things go fast), he receives a couple of anonymous reviews from scientific "peers"--experts in his field, chosen by the journal's editor. If the reviews are laudatory, all is well. If not, the rejected author may either revise his manuscript or, if he feels the criticism is unwarranted, take the chance of sending his work to a less exalted publication.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As Stevan Harnad of the University of Southampton points out, the system works in the sense that, in the end, almost everything gets published. Somewhere in the hierarchy of journals ranging from the renowned, such as <i>Nature</i>, to the utterly obscure, it will find a niche. It is then up to the reader to assess the quality of a piece. The quality of the publication will help him do that. But the cost of the service is high, not just in terms of paper and printing (on some estimates, electronic journals will reduce publishing costs by 70%), but also because the author assigns his copyright to the journal in order to reach his audience, in what Dr Harnad terms the scientists' Faustian bargain.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Many scientists grumble about the peer-review system. Much of the discontent is the sour grapes of rejected authors. But even believers in the system recognise its weaknesses. It can be frustratingly slow, it is not immune to abuse by powerful or unscrupulous scientists, and it has a history of remarkable failures, where great discoveries have been rejected by incredulous or uncomprehending peers, or where fraudulent results have won the endorsement of eminent scientists.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Internet has the potential to shake up the established order for the better in three respects. The most humdrum is that, by forcing paper publishers to go electronic, it is bound to speed up peer review (though lackadaisical reviewers will still be a problem).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A more ambitious goal of Internet enthusiasts is to legitimise preprints--unofficial versions of manuscripts that circulate while waiting for peer reviewers' deliberations. Paper preprints are already a common currency of scientific research, and in fast-moving fields hot preprints can be more sought after than stale publications. Paul Ginsparg of the Los Alamos e-Print Archive in New Mexico and his colleagues have developed the Los Alamos Physics Information Service in which 70 preprints a day are put into the archive. This represents about half the current output in physics worldwide, and the database is "visited" by over 40,000 physicists a day. The venture is so successful that so-called mirrors of this database are being established at websites around the world to avoid traffic congestion on the Internet.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But preprint archives are just the tip of the iceberg. The real excitement lies in the possibility of experimenting with alternatives to conventional peer reviewing. Instead of one or two reviewers, simple software would allow any interested scientist to comment on a preprint. In a model originally suggested by Dr Ginsparg, the comments would be appended to the article for subsequent readers to view. The author could delete comments he finds unhelpful or inappropriate, but he would be advised to be selective--an article with no comments is obviously one that has attracted either no attention, or awful reviews.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;An even simpler version of such "open peer commentary" could consist of readers assigning stars, as in a Michelin restaurant guide, to articles. The possibilities are endless. For the moment, though, even pioneers such as Dr Ginsparg are hesitating to take the plunge, at least until the concept of preprint archives is more firmly established. In any case, open commentary is unlikely to occur by fiat. It will, rather, evolve gradually in specialised sub-fields, in response to demand and to the incessant tug of technology.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Critics of open commentary see all sorts of problems ahead. The chief worry is that high-quality work will be drowned in a flood of dubious data and poor prose. In fact, peer review already lets a lot of this through. And although the Internet provides even easier access for the great unwashed of science, it also promises more powerful means of filtering the information they produce. The real challenge is more likely to lie in legal questions of intellectual property and patents. International patent law requires that inventions be kept secret until a patent is filed. Paper preprints, however, are generally exempted from this stricture because they are distributed in such limited numbers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>OECD</font> could help here by setting a high priority on sorting out the legal aspects of Internet publication, although international agreements in this area will take years to forge. In the meantime, politicians can take the initiative in more direct ways. In Helsingor, Denmark's minister of research and information technology, Frank Jensen, announced plans to give scientists cheap access to a high-speed optical fibre network funded by his ministry if, in exchange, they agreed to publish their preprints and articles on the Internet. It would be a modest step towards greater scientific openness, but even this will probably irritate many researchers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That is a shame. The opportunity to experiment with electronic peer review ought to be seized with relish. Experiments, after all, are the essence of science. Peer review is not itself a product of the scientific method (what is the statistical significance of two reviewers?), so there is every reason to believe that it can be improved upon. The Internet provides a wonderful opportunity for such experiments. If scientists do not try, and politicians do not encourage them, no one will ever be much the wiser.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?835398000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>

</p>
