<html><head><title>The only man for Russia</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>

<h1><center>The only man for Russia</center></h1>

THE alternatives are clear. Of the two men leading the race to become Russia's next president, one can fairly claim that he would try to give his country a modern, prosperous and democratic future. The other offers the near-certainty of a return to the surly, squalid isolation of the past. That is not to say that Boris Yeltsin is perfect, or that Gennady Zyuganov is Stalin warmed up. The chances are, however, that Russia under Mr Yeltsin would turn the right corner, and stay there; whereas Russia under his Communist rival would turn its back on reform, at least for a while, and perhaps embrace once again many grim aspects of its Soviet past.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is often said that the market is now too well established in Russia even for Communists to replace it with central planning; that the main reforms already enacted are irreversible; and that Russia's Communists, like those elsewhere in Eastern Europe, will in time, willy-nilly, have to become social democrats. Alas, each of these assertions is based more on hope than on certainty. It is far from sure that a President Zyuganov would be persuaded by the <font size=-1>IMF</font> and Russia's other creditors to junk almost every main promise in his manifesto: price and exchange controls, wage and pension increases, protectionism and subsidies to clapped-out industries. If these were to be abandoned, they would be much more likely to go after the inevitable collapse of the rouble, a drying up of investment, hyperinflation and a further impoverishment of the Russian people.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Zyuganov evinces no faith in democracy. He has failed to reassure the many Russians who do not wish to go back to the old days yet are understandably confused by the buffeting they have received in the past five years. Instead he has pandered to those with a xenophobic or anti-Semitic streak. His strongest appeal is to Russia's core of diehard disgruntlement.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Office sometimes changes politicians. Nonetheless, it is plain that Mr Zyuganov is, at bottom, much more like a Soviet Communist than a modern democrat. Like other members of his party, he is virtually unrepentant about Soviet communism's obscene past. He frequently praises Stalin, shrugging off the tyrant's crimes when not denying them altogether. As president, he would find it hard to act upon his party's dangerous insistence that the Soviet Union still legally exists. Even so, Russia's relations both with its former dominions and with the West would be bound to worsen.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Yeltsin is far from being a presidential paragon. His five years in office have provided roller-coaster excitement, sometimes making him a hero of democracy (bravely defying the back-to-Brezhnev coup-makers of 1991), at other times letting him display the worst tendencies of tsarist authoritarianism. He has overseen the wiping out of private savings (in 1992), the shelling of a rebellious parliament (in autumn 1993), the crash of the rouble (a year later) and a crassly bloody attempt (in winter 1994) to prevent Chechnya's secession. Most Russians feel, rightly or wrongly, less well off than five years ago. Still more are horrified by the upsurge of crime and the blatant new disparities of wealth.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Reformers have been appalled at the president's inconstancy. On occasion, in order to match the jingoism of his rivals, he has been quite ready to give his foreign policy an anti-western tilt. More worryingly, he has chosen, when under pressure, to surround himself with roughnecks and fixers, many of them reeking of the crony capitalism and racketeering that have so disfigured the new order. He has had two heart attacks. He sometimes appears drunk. This newspaper, 18 months ago, declared him "the wrong man" for the job.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet nobody on the ballot this Sunday would do it better. That reflects partly upon the quality of the candidates, but partly also on Mr Yeltsin, who, despite his record of mistakes, also has some notable successes to his name. Indeed, taken in the round, his achievements far outweigh his shortcomings.
</p><p><b>The bright side</b>
<br>He did not do it alone, but Boris Yeltsin helped destroy an evil empire. He has established private property as a foundation of personal liberty. Though it is vastly biased in his favour at this electoral moment, he has freed the press. Millions of Russians, once cooped up in a huge cage, now travel the world. Criminal and civil codes of justice have been enacted, a constitutional court is finding its feet. Above all, an elected Duma has settled down to the business of making laws and checking the powers of a strong executive president. A stockmarket and securities and exchange commission are functioning. Some 40m Russians own shares. The private sector contributes more than 70% of <font size=-1>GDP</font>. Nearly 1m small businesses have sprung up. Queues have gone.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even if Mr Yeltsin wins, though, the battle will not be over. His campaign has been run by reformers, not his bad-hat cronies. But a second-term Mr Yeltsin might well be tempted to relax in the flush of victory. He might soon face an economic and political crisis. The essential task of bringing interest rates down and closing the budget deficit could, probably should, destroy hundreds of dodgy new banks. The choice of a new prime minister (who would at least temporarily succeed the president, should he die in office) will prompt a fierce tussle with a still predominantly hostile Duma. It will be a relentless struggle to ram through essential reforms--of the tax and legal systems, and in agriculture, to name but a few.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even harder will be the job of creating a sense of civic decency among a people whose morals have been warped by 74 years of Communist horror. Russians are not congenitally unsuited to democracy (see <a href="sf1.html">pages</a>). But it is hardly surprising that Mr Yeltsin, in five years, has failed to infect them with liberal values: he is not unequivocally committed to them himself. That may be a task for his successor. It is certainly not one that Mr Zyuganov would tackle. Elections are seldom make-or-break affairs. This one just might be. A Zyuganov victory would be a disaster for Russia. A Yeltsin victory might, by contrast, secure the future of reform. Demography is on its side: the young are much keener on the changes than the old, so four years hence the Communists' electoral chances may be much slimmer. For all his faults, Russia should let Mr Yeltsin continue what he has started.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834793200,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="sf1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
