<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width=271 height=24  alt="Politics"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<h2>In and out</h2>
<p><b>Bob Dole</b>, the Republican presidential candidate, retired from the Senate after 35 years in Congress and 11 years as Republican leader of the Senate. Senator Trent Lott of Mississippi was elected as the new majority leader.<p>
President Clinton apologised for obtaining the <b>confidential FBI files </b>on hundreds of Republicans. Hearings were nevertheless scheduled in Congress, and the Whitewater independent counsel began an investigation.<p>
A federal court declared that a new law restricting "<b>indecency</b>" on the Internet infringed the constitutional right of free speech.<p>
Visiting Canada, Mexico's President Ernesto Zedillo roundly condemned the United States' <b>Helms-Burton law</b> against trade with Cuba, and was roundly applauded by Parliament. The two countries are co-ordinating tactics.<p>
Also visiting, France's prime minister, Alain Jupp&eacute;, told would-be secessionist <b>Quebeckers</b> that they could always count on "the mother country" whatever choices they might make--but carefully did not advise what that should be.<p>
The lower house of <b>Colombia's</b> Congress voted in favour of President Ernesto Samper. As expected; his party controls it.

<h2>A beef thaw</h2>
<p>The rhetoric of <b>Europe's beef war</b> remained heated, but there were signs of compromise. Britain presented a new plan for lifting the <font size=-1>EU</font>'s ban on exports of British beef and eased its own ban on <font size=-1>EU</font> decisions. Jacques Santer, president of the European Commission, predicted that the dispute would be settled before the <font size=-1>EU</font>'s summit in Florence on June 21st-22nd.<p>
Talks on the future of <b>Northern Ireland </b>got off to an inauspicious start in Belfast. The <font size=-1>IRA</font>'s refusal to declare a ceasefire meant that its political wing, Sinn Fein, was excluded. And unionist parties objected to the appointment by the British and Irish governments of George Mitchell, a former American senator, as chairman of the talks.<p>
Negotiators seeking to end the 18-month war in <b>Chechnya </b>agreed that Russian troops would withdraw from the rebel province in August and that Chechen fighters would disarm.<p>
President Yeltsin approached <b>Russia's presidential election </b>on June 16th as firm favourite. A second run-off will be held if no candidate wins more than half the votes on Sunday. An explosion in the Moscow metro, apparently caused by a bomb, killed four people. The mayor of Moscow, Yuri Luzhkov, who is running for re-election on Sunday, blamed extremist political groups for that and two other incidents.<p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
Germany's Christian Democrats, senior partners in the ruling coalition, agreed to liberalise the country's notoriously restrictive <b>shopping hours</b>. The cabinet agreed to changes in <b>unemployment benefits </b>to save DM17 billion ($11 billion) by 2000.<p>
<b>Spain</b> introduced measures to boost growth and make its economy more flexible. They include land reform and more competition in energy and telecoms. A package of business-friendly tax cuts is expected to reduce government revenues by Pta200 billion ($1.55 billion) this year.<p>
Necmettin Erbakan, leader of <b>Turkey</b>'s Islamist Welfare Party, began talks on forming a new government after the collapse of the centre-right coalition. Tansu Ciller said her True Path Party, one of the two parties in the failed coalition, would consider an alliance with Welfare.

<h2>Arabs take stock</h2>
<p>Responding to Israel's election of Binyamin Netanyahu, Egypt invited all Arab League countries--bar Iraq--to a <b>Cairo summit</b>, starting on June 21st. In occupied southern Lebanon, Hizbullah guerrillas killed five soldiers in an Israeli patrol. Israel hit back with artillery fire, and threatened worse. Inside Israel, unidentified terrorists murdered an Israeli couple.<p>
Iran's government offered to send a delegation to look into charges that it backs an armed plot in <b>Bahrain</b>. Bahrain's government gave it a flea in the ear, and announced the arrest of the alleged (Bahraini) mastermind of the affair.<p>
<b>Nigeria</b> softened its legal rules. People detained under one decree of the military regime will be able to seek release through the courts. And army officers will no longer sit on "disturbances" tribunals like the one that convicted Ken Saro-Wiwa; tribunal verdicts will also be subject to appeal.

<h2>Testing</h2>
<p>A ship owned by Greenpeace, an environmental group, anchored off Shanghai in protest at <b>China's nuclear tests</b>. The ship was boarded by Chinese officials and later left.<p>
In a campaign called Strike Hard, China <b>executed 66 people </b>convicted of murder, rape, drug dealing and other crimes.<p>
A report by India's Central Bureau of Investigation alleged that Narasimha Rao, leader of the Congress party and until recently prime minister, had been involved in <b>vote buying</b>. Mr Rao has denied the allegation.<p>
In an exchange of letters the prime ministers of <b>India and Pakistan </b>proposed peace talks to "stabilise" the subcontinent. The last such talks were in 1994.<p>
In a general election deemed by foreign observers to be mostly peaceful and fair, <b>Bangladeshis</b> turned out in record numbers. Sheikh Hasina's Awami League seemed to have won most seats, but not enough to govern on its own.<p>
<p>
<p>

</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
