<html><head><title>Eco-nomics</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Taxes</b></p>
<h1>Eco-nomics</h1>


<p>GREEN taxes have a seductive appeal. To environmentalists, they represent a way of cutting pollution and meeting environmental targets. To fiscal reformers, they offer a source of untapped tax revenues. To politicians of all stripes, they suggest a means of avoiding raising the most painful tax of all, the income tax. But any businessman will tell you there is no such thing as a free lunch--or a painless tax.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The search for that elusive meal nevertheless continues. The latest advocate of green taxes is the Institute for Public Policy Research (<font size=-1>IPPR</font>), a left-of-centre think-tank. It claims in a report to be published on June 17th that a shift from national-insurance taxes to those directed against waste and pollution would not only curb pollution but create thousands of new jobs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>IPPR</font>'s package of green taxes is designed to raise &#163;21 billion a year by 2005, which is expected to be equivalent to 3% of <font size=-1>GDP</font>. It would include: a commercial and industrial energy tax; a real annual rise in existing fuel duties of 8% over the decade rather than the 5% promised by the government; a waste-disposal tax on landfill sites; a levy on quarrying; and a tax on car parking at work. These taxes, according to the report's authors, Stephen Tindale and Gerald Holtham, would cut carbon emissions in Britain by 10% and waste disposal by 16% over a decade. An accompanying study by Cambridge Econometrics, a research firm, suggests that, if the resulting revenues were used to cut employers' national-insurance contributions, more than 700,000 new jobs would be created by 2005.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This sounds too good to be true. And, unfortunately, it probably is. Economists are divided on whether a switch from employment to green taxes would result in large numbers of new jobs. Some believe that the change would raise wages rather than employment, primarily because green taxes might increase living costs and reduce the returns on capital investment. In particular, Stephen Smith, deputy director of the Institute for Fiscal Studies, says that he is not convinced that there would be large economic gains from green taxes because of their adverse impact on energy-intensive industries.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some countries have already found this to be true. Five European countries--Denmark, Finland, the Netherlands, Norway and Sweden--have introduced carbon taxes on which rates of duty vary according to the carbon content or "dirtiness" of the fuel. But Sweden has had to modify its proposals because of the greater-than-expected effect on energy-intensive industries such as steel<b>.
</b><br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The politics of greenery also has pitfalls. A storm of protest forced the British government to backtrack on its proposal to raise the rate of <font size=-1>VAT</font> on domestic fuel to 17.5% in November 1994. Similarly, plans by Germany's Green Party for an energy tax on fossil fuels and electricity rising by 7% a year over a decade have provoked opposition from both industrialists and taxpayers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All this suggests that it would be unwise to pitch the economic claims for green taxes too high. At the same time, it would be simply wrong to suppose that taxes cannot be used to promote environmental change. Both Britain and Germany have successfully encouraged the use of unleaded petrol by taxing it more lightly than the leaded variety. In Britain the proportion of unleaded petrol rose from a negligible share of petrol sales in 1986 to well over half today. Similarly, Sweden's lower tax on low-sulphur fuels has led to the almost universal adoption of cleaner diesel fuel.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As Britain's chancellor, Kenneth Clarke, noted when introducing Britain's landfill levy in November 1994, "in some cases taxes can actually do some good by discouraging harmful or wasteful activity." At present, Britain raises less than a tenth of its revenues from "green" taxes (and most of that from tax on petrol). The case for making polluters pay more makes good sense, even if the gains are likely to be more environmental than "economic".


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834793200,iss">Search</a>
