<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p align=center><table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" width=231 height=24  alt="Britain"></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>
<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>




<p><b>Fed up</b> &nbsp;
British exports of feeds containing ground-up animal remains trebled in the year after they were banned from sale for feeding cows and sheep at home. The revelation, in the journal <i>Nature</i>, caused outrage in continental Europe, where Britain is struggling to get the <font size=-1>EU</font> ban on beef exports lifted.</p>
<p><b>Birtspeak</b> &nbsp;
John Birt said he would remain as director-general of the <font size=-1>BBC</font> for another four years and oversee a further radical restructuring. <font size=-1>BBC</font> World Service Radio will no longer make its own programmes but will have to buy them from other parts of the corporation.</p>
<p><b>Blackmail</b> &nbsp;
The government came under pressure to drop plans to close a casualty unit at a London hospital after two local Tory <font size=-1>MPs</font> threatened to boycott Commons votes unless it did. John Major was furious.</p>
<p>

<b>Headache</b> &nbsp;Asda, a big supermarket chain, stopped selling "Anadin" painkillers after their maker, Whitehall Laboratories, won a High Court injunction banning the retailer from selling them at prices below those set in a legally sanctioned price-fixing agreement.</p>
<p></td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%><b>Lower charge</b> &nbsp;
Stephen Littlechild, the electricity-industry regulator, cut the levy which is charged to electricity consumers to pay for the eventual dismantling of nuclear-power stations. He said households' annual bills should fall by up to &#163;20 as a result.</p>
<p><b>Batwomen</b> &nbsp;
Two women were bitten by the first rabid bat to have been found in Britain.</p>
<p><b>Gay grants</b> &nbsp;
The National Lottery Charities Board stood by its decision to give grants to charities which support homosexuals, prostitutes and people facing deportation, after the prime minister said some awards were "ill founded and ill judged" .
</p>
<p><b>Down the tubes</b> &nbsp;
Adding to the ever-increasing list of health scares, a government scientist said infants' schools should stop letting pupils make models out of cardboard toilet-roll tubes because they may be spreading germs.
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
