<html><head><title></title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>



<table border=6><tr><td>

<h1>The software scavenger</h1><p><b>Charles Wang built a massive software empire by snapping up sickly rivals. It is a nobler calling than he seems to think</b><p>THE oceans have crabs. The land has beetles and grubs. The software industry has Charles Wang. All survive at least in part by consuming the dead and dying. In the 20 years since Mr Wang started his firm, Computer Associates, it has bought more than 60 companies and products (most of them fading at the time). With each new meal he has carefully digested the good bits--usually an odd mixture of customers and technology--and spat out the rest--often many of the staff. The result: 
<font size=-1>CA</font> has grown to more than $3 billion in annual revenues, becoming the world's third-biggest software company, behind only Microsoft and Oracle (see <a href="wb1.gif">chart</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Most people would be happy with such an achievement, but Mr Wang (pronounced "Wong") wants to be more than the software industry's vulture. <font size=-1>CA</font>, he is quick to point out, has developed lots of its own software--mostly arcane stuff for mainframes and other industrial-strength systems (which explains why so few from outside that world know the firm). Mr Wang considers himself more of a technologist than a turnaround artist. These days he is even casting himself as something of a management guru, promoting both his 1994 book, "Techno Vision" (McGraw-Hill), a homespun guide to managing information technology, and a <font size=-1>CA</font>-sponsored boot camp for techno-illiterate bosses.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is only recently that Mr Wang has had the luxury of such reinvention. The second son of Chinese immigrants escaping communism, he grew up in the gritty borough of Queens, New York, and was only an average student at a local university. He stumbled into software (it seemed to have the most help-wanted ads at the time), and started his own firm in 1976 to market a program sold by a small Swiss company. Five years later he took his firm public, and within months had made his first acquisition, buying a firm nearly three times <font size=-1>CA</font>'s size. Over the next six years, Mr Wang snapped up 16 companies, mostly small fry that happened to have a technology Mr Wang wanted.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On the way, <font size=-1>CA</font> has developed its own technology, notably a core "architecture" that can weave together the products of companies it buys. But most of its revenue growth has come from acquisitions: <font size=-1>CA</font> has spent some $4 billion buying other firms over the past 15 years, adding nearly that much to its revenues in fees from the acquired firms' customers, who are worried about being left orphaned.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Wang's speciality is wringing profit out of a tired old technology franchise. The most recent example is Legent, one of <font size=-1>CA</font>'s competitors in managing networks of mainframes and smaller computers, which Mr Wang bought for $1.8 billion last year. Existing Legent customers, who depended on the software to run their businesses, were encouraged to sign new "maintenance" contracts with <font size=-1>CA</font>, which often locked them into other <font size=-1>CA</font> products. For Legent's employees, however, the takeover seems to have turned into an enormous exercise in downsizing. By one count, less than 20% of Legent's 2,000 workers are still with the group.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Wang admits that he can be a ruthless cost cutter, but argues that he is a humane one. Within days of the acquisition, he met Legent's employees and told them where they stood. (Other firms, he says, would have dithered to avoid bad press.) The main victims of his purges tend to be administrators, marketers and others who fall under what he calls overhead: "I don't need two legal departments and two accounting departments." Among those who survive, Mr Wang seems to inspire considerable loyalty, thanks to relatively high pay and such perks as free breakfast (in the early years, Mr Wang would push around a trolley of bagels and doughnuts himself), fitness centres and child care. That said, he rejects the free-wheeling anarchy of most software companies: he has even imposed e-mail curfews for much of the day to cut unproductive electronic chatter.
</p><p><b>Smart shopping</b></b>
<br>In an industry full of self-styled technology visionaries, Mr Wang's modus operandi has attracted scorn. Larry Ellison, the boss of Oracle, has called him a "bottom feeder". <font size=-1>CA</font> has also irritated customers with its strong-arm tactics, which include some of the most aggressive enforcement of licensing conditions in the industry, plenty of lawsuits, and even software "time bombs" that can shut down the operation of an awkward or cussed customer (a tactic that so outraged customers in Virginia that they got the state to ban it).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mention such things to Mr Wang, and he will reply, first, that rumours of customer discontent are spread by self-interested consultancies (adding that he has made talking to one of them a firing offence), and, second, that <font size=-1>CA</font> is a kinder, gentler firm today. This may be true; but, rather than worrying about his role, Mr Wang would do better to revel in it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Most other industries have companies that pick at the carcasses of those who fall behind. Such firms not only tidy up; they also keep other beasts on their toes and protect customers. For all its T-shirted bravado, the software industry produces more losers than winners. As one competing software executive puts it, with a sort of grudging admiration, "every ecosystem needs a scavenger" . It may not be a pretty job, but somebody has to do it. Not many do so as successfully as Mr Wang.
</td></tr></table><br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834793200,iss">Search</a>
