<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width=271 height=24  alt="Politics"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<h2>Reformers stumble</h2>
<p><p>
A bad week for reformers in ex-communist countries. In a general election in the <b>Czech Republic</b>, the coalition headed by Vaclav Klaus unexpectedly lost its majority. In <b>Russia</b>, St Petersburg's reforming mayor, Anatoli Sobchak, lost to his former deputy, Vladimir Yakovlev. And <b>Bulgaria's</b> President Zhelyu Zhelev, a veteran reformer, failed to secure nomination in Eastern Europe's first American-style primary.<p>
Members of <b>NATO</b> agreed on ways to allow European countries to conduct military operations without American participation. At a meeting in Berlin, Russia acknowledged that <font size=-1>NATO</font> would expand eastward.<p>
Russia made the <b>rouble</b> fully convertible for foreign-trade transactions, offering foreign investors a more attractive home for their money.<p>
In Istanbul, delegates at a <font size=-1>UN</font> conference on <b>cities </b>were divided on environmental concerns, women's rights and the obligation of states to provide housing.<p>
European finance ministers added Germany to the blacklist of countries whose public-sector deficits in 1995 breached the <b>Maastricht criteria</b> for economic and monetary union. Over Germany's objections, they removed Denmark from the list even though its debt is still higher than the Maastricht ceiling.<p>
In a ceremony witnessed by the defence chiefs of America and Russia, <b>Ukraine</b> ceased to be a nuclear power as the last of its 1,900 strategic warheads was sent to Russia for destruction.<p>
Mesut Yilmaz, the <b>Turkish</b> prime minister, resigned ending a three-month-old conservative coalition. He will remain caretaker until a new government is formed.<p>
Britain, claiming a turning-point in its policy of <b>non-co-operation</b> with the European Union to be imminent, chose not to veto an <font size=-1>EU</font> agreement with Slovenia.

<h2>Netanyahu rules</h2>
<p><p>
<b>Binyamin Netanyahu </b>set about coalition-building after Israel's election. In a conciliatory victory speech he called for peace at home and with the Arabs. Arab leaders, not greatly comforted, held a series of meetings in search of a common response. Yasser Arafat said his people would "soon" declare a Palestinian state. In Gaza, an Israeli soldier shot dead an unarmed Arab. A policeman did the same in Jerusalem.<p>
<b>Bahrain's</b> rulers promised a speck more democracy. The next day they claimed to have uncovered an Iranian-sponsored plot against them.<p>
<b>Kudirat</b> <b>Abiola</b>, wife of the jailed winner of the 1993 Nigerian election, Moshood Abiola, was shot dead in her car in Lagos.<p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
President Eduardo dos Santos of <b>Angola</b> sacked his government and the governor of the central bank.

<h2>Children's crusade</h2>
<p><p>
About 200,000 children and their parents marched in Washington to draw attention to the needs of <b>children</b>. Conservatives called it the last stand for big government.<p>
In separate speeches, President Bill Clinton and his Republican rival, Bob Dole, both endorsed the idea of nightly <b>curfews for teenagers</b> to reduce violent crime.<p>
The <font size=-1>FBI</font> reported that Hillary Clinton's fingerprints had been found on legal billing records sought in connection with the <b>Whitewater</b> investigation. The papers, which had been missing, turned up mysteriously in the White House last August.<p>
Trade partners hit back at the United States' first efforts to use its <b>Helms-Burton law</b> against firms active in Cuba. Canada, one of whose companies got a threatening letter last week, called it "unacceptable". Mexico (ditto) sent a stiff diplomatic note. Defying heavy arm-twisting, the Organisation of American States passed a resolution denouncing the law. EU and American officials began formal talks at the World Trade Organisation.<p>
<b>Colombia</b>'s Congress began debating the case of President Ernesto Samper. The United States, which had criticised a committee vote in his favour, was accused of threatening trade sanctions if the full Congress voted the same way.<p>
<b>Peru</b> signed a letter of intent with the <font size=-1>IMF</font>. An American economist, Rudiger Dornbusch, said that <b>Brazil</b> risks a Mexican-style meltdown. Markets twitched. Most Brazil-watchers did not.

<h2>Death mines</h2>
<p><p>
In China's third major <b>mining disaster </b>in two weeks, 66 people were killed and 162 were missing when landslides buried mine-shafts in Yunnan province. Earlier, nearly 80 people had died in disasters in Hunan and Gansu provinces. Mining accidents kill up to 10,000 people a year, according to the government.<p>
India's liberal <b>economic policies </b>seemed likely to continue with the appointment of a reformer, P. Chidambaram, as finance minister in the new government.<p>
Tung Chee-hwa, who is tipped to become governor of <b>Hong Kong </b>when it is returned to China in mid-1997, resigned from a senior position with the government of the British colony to avoid "conflict of interest" .<p>
Japan and South Korea were chosen as joint hosts of football's <b>World Cup </b>in 2002.<p>
<p>
<p>

