<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width=273 height=24  alt="Business"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>

<p>


<h2>Downward</h2>
<p> <p>
The European Space Agency saw $500m-worth of uninsured spacecraft and scientific satellites come down in flames when <b>Ariane</b> <b>5</b> had to be blown up 40 seconds after taking off on its maiden flight from French Guiana. The disaster, apparently caused by faulty computer software sending the rocket off course, sets back the agency's plans to dominate the competitive market for commercial space transport, worth $3 billion a year.<p>
<b>Boeing</b> pulled out of a partnership with <b>McDonnell Douglas</b> to build a new American space shuttle. <font size=-1>NASA</font> will award a $900m contract for a prototype next month.<p>
German banks devised a plan to save <b>Kl&ouml;ckner-Humboldt-Deutz</b> from bankruptcy. The stumbling engineering firm will receive more than DM650m ($425m) in cash and forgiven loans, most of it from Deutsche Bank, which owns 48% of <font size=-1>KHD</font>. The survival of the firm still depends, however, on whether two Saudi Arabian companies will forgo DM300m that <font size=-1>KHD</font> owes them in penalties for late completion of work.<p>
The French government will build <b>Paris's third airport</b> at Beauvilliers, near Chartres.<p>
Consternation reigned at <b>Lucas</b>, a British car-parts maker, and <b>Varity</b>, which dominates the American market for anti-lock brakes, when their plan to merge and form a company with revenues of about $6.7 billion was threatened by talk of a hostile takeover bid. Five days after they announced their intentions, <b>BBA Group</b>, a British engineering firm, said it was considering buying Lucas.

<h2>Fair play and foul</h2>
<p><p>
The boss of <b>South Korea</b>'s chief securities watchdog and the head of the finance ministry's treasury division, which oversees the stockmarket, were arrested. They are accused of taking bribes to help firms jump the queue for listing shares.<p>
(See <a href="wtw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>Transparency International, an organisation devoted to stamping out <b>corrupt business practices</b>, gathered the results of ten international surveys into a league table ranking countries by the amount of bribery, embezzlement and skullduggery involved in doing business in them. New Zealand and the Scandinavian countries came out cleanest, Nigeria the worst. Britain, Germany, America and France all made it into the top 20 for honesty.<p>
Donald Johnston, formerly a Canadian cabinet minister, took over as secretary-general of the <b>Organisation for</b> <b>Economic Co-operation and Development</b> and declared that promoting free trade would be his top priority.<p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
The American economy continued to give encouraging signals of growth ahead. The <font size=-1>US</font> index of <b>leading indicators</b> went up 0.3% in April, the third month running it has risen. Together with figures from the Commerce Department showing more new construction, this led analysts to speculate that the Federal Reserve will raise short-term interest rates next month.<p>
Kenneth Clarke, Britain's chancellor of the exchequer, <b>unexpectedly</b> cut interest rates by a quarter of one percentage point.

<h2>Bankrolling</h2>
<p><p>
Russia's president, Boris Yeltsin, ordered the <b>central bank</b> to give the government 5 trillion roubles ($1 billion) to help cover a budget shortfall. The central bank said it would fight the order.<p>
<b>Rabobank</b>, the Netherlands' largest co-operative bank, agreed to take control of Robecam, the main asset-management arm of Robeco, a leading Dutch financial group. The deal, for an initial 50% stake, is worth over 500m guilders ($292m).<p>
Bankers argued over how much to pay their hot-shot employees. The chairman of Barclays Bank said they should earn less and leave more for shareholders, but <b>Deutsche Morgan Grenfell</b> continued to poach people from its rivals<b>. </b>Its latest coup was to carry off 44 Latin American specialists from the much-raided Dutch investment bank, <b>ING Barings</b>.<p>
Barclays Bank appointed Bill Harrison, a mergers-and-acquisitions expert, as head of BZW, its investment-banking arm.

<h2>Crossed</h2>
<p><p>
The plan of three European media groups, BSkyB, Canal+ and Bertelsmann, to stitch up <b>digital television</b> in Germany unravelled. In any case, the European Commission takes a stern view of pay-<font size=-1>TV</font> deals. Karel Van Miert, the competition commissioner, said that recent deals between satellite and cable television companies would be unacceptable if they led to monopolies.<p>
<b>Deutsche Telekom</b> announced that its net profits in 1995 were DM5.3 billion ($3.7 billion), 47% higher than the previous year. This augurs well for its partial privatisation in November. Uncertainty remains, however, over regulations that will govern competition with other firms.<p>
(See <a href="wtw2.gif">chart</a>)<br>Eager to fight its way further into the American personal-computer market, <font size=-1>NEC</font>, a Japanese electronics giant, said it would merge its international <font size=-1>PC</font> business with that of <b>Packard Bell</b>, in which it has a controlling interest. The new company will command a share of 15% in America's consumer <font size=-1>PC</font> market.<p></p>
