<html><head><title>Time to split</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Airports</b></p>
<h1>Time to split</h1>


<p>SINCE the British Airports Authority (<font size=-1>BAA</font>) was privatised in 1987, its shareholders have enjoyed a wonderful ride (see <a href="br2.gif">chart</a>). This heady stockmarket performance reflects the fact that <font size=-1>BAA</font>'s dividends have grown at more than 10% a year, five times the post-war stockmarket average. Shareholders have already recouped nearly two-thirds of their original investment in dividends alone. Not bad for a low-risk regulated firm which faces virtually no competition to its lucrative ownership of Heathrow, Gatwick and Stansted, the three biggest airports around London.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Whether <font size=-1>BAA</font>'s excessively cosy regulatory regime should continue unchanged is now under consideration by the Monopolies and Mergers Commission (<font size=-1>MMC</font>). The <font size=-1>MMC</font> is due to deliver its judgment on the airport authority's future on June 10th, as part of a regular five-year review. The commission's proposals will be submitted to the Civil Aviation Authority with which it shares the task of regulating <font size=-1>BAA</font>. In its last review the <font size=-1>MMC</font> swept aside in a single paragraph the case for breaking up the company. This time the case for doing so, made by airlines and consumer interests, will be more difficult to dismiss.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Regulation by price control has, for a start, proved ineffective. <font size=-1>BAA</font>'s rate of return on capital of more than 10% is a third more than the limit set in the 1991 review. <font size=-1>BAA</font> claims the higher-than-expected return is due to lower-than-expected construction costs and higher productivity. But there will always be such excuses to hand. The ability of regulated monopolies to pull the wool over regulators' eyes on cost issues is almost infinite.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The system of price regulation, under which <font size=-1>BAA</font> has to keep its charges 4% below the rate of inflation, has brought some particularly perverse results. The larger the profits it earns from its unregulated businesses such as shop rentals, the more it has to reduce its regulated fees to airlines. The ludicrous result has been that airport charges at Heathrow, already grossly congested, are among the lowest in the world. Airport charges at Heathrow average about &#163;5 a passenger, a third of those at the privately-owned Luton airport which is struggling for custom.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Price incentives working the wrong way around have helped to starve Stansted, and to a lesser extent Gatwick, of passengers, while further overloading Heathrow. Sir Christopher Chataway, the former chairman of the Civil Aviation Authority, has admitted that <font size=-1>BAA</font>'s current price-control regime could one day result in airlines actually being paid to land at Heathrow.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The best way to end this nonsense is to introduce competition. The House of Commons Transport Select Committee, in a report published last month, recommended that the ownership of Heathrow should be separated from that of Gatwick and Stansted. That makes good sense. There is no reason why the three airports should be controlled by a single operator.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Splitting up <font size=-1>BAA</font> would hardly produce perfect competition. There are many constraints on running an airport, not least geography and transport links. Some subsidy for Gatwick and Stansted, or an excess profits levy on Heathrow, might be needed to make competition viable. But some sort of rivalry between operators could bring real benefits, just as the government hopes it will in the privatised rail network. In the same spirit the <font size=-1>MMC</font> should insist that <font size=-1>BAA</font>'s proposed Terminal 5 at Heathrow, if it ever wins planning permission, be put out to competitive tender.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834188400,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
