<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p align=center><table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" width=231 height=24  alt="Britain"></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>
<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>



<p><b>Hot Rod</b> &nbsp;
Rod Richards, a Welsh Office minister and proponent of "family values", resigned after newspaper allegations about his private life. His replacement is Jonathan Evans, a minister in the Lord Chancellor's Department.</p>
<p><b>Traumatic</b> &nbsp;
Fourteen police officers won a total of &#163;1.2m compensation for trauma they suffered when rescuing victims of the Hillsborough stadium disaster in 1989. The award was condemned by families of some of the 96 people who died in the disaster--they have received little or no compensation.</p>
<p><b>Royal rebellion</b> &nbsp;
The queen was forced to cancel a visit to the University of Wales in Aberystwyth because of protests by Welsh nationalists. But there were no protests five days later when the Prince of Wales opened the new Severn bridge, linking Wales to England.</p>
<p><b>Jackpot</b> &nbsp;
Camelot, the operator of the National Lottery, came under fresh attack after it announced annual profits of &#163;77.5m in its first full year.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Losing face</b> &nbsp;
Facia, owner of more than 500 shops including the Sock Shop chain and the Salisburys luggage stores, went into receivership.</p>
<p><b>Economics lesson</b> &nbsp;
The Universities and Colleges Admissions Service advised students to grab any university place they are offered this year, in case the universities go ahead with their threat to impose &#163;300 enrolment fees from 1997.</p>
<p><b>Pet passports</b> &nbsp;
A bill to replace quarantine for animals being brought into Britain with "pet passports" , showing they had been vaccinated against rabies, had its first reading in the House of Commons. But the government is not expected to allow the bill enough parliamentary time to become law.
</p>
<p><b>Hot property</b> &nbsp;
The London, Tilbury and Southend railway said thieves who have apparently been stealing luggage racks from trains, to turn into barbecues, would be disappointed. The racks are made of aluminium, which melts easily, and have a poisonous coating.</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
