<html><head><title>Call me</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>Call me</h1>

<font size=1>GENEVA</font><p>IF YOU want people to buy from you over the telephone, why should your customer pay the cost of the call? That simple logic has made freephone numbers big business in the service-conscious United States, where they account for 100m calls a day and more than 40% of the traffic on <font size=-1>AT&T</font>'s vast network. But in other parts of the world, they have been less successful: only 10% of the world's 9m freephone numbers are held outside North America.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now this may change. The International Telecommunication Union (<font size=-1>ITU</font>), which represents the world's telephone industry, has approved a new standard for global freephone numbers. Up to now, freephone services could be offered only nationally. As a result, anybody travelling with a telephone credit card spends hours fumbling in draughty telephone boxes for the correct number to dial out from that particular country. From next February, callers will need to dial only the international exit code and then 800 and eight more digits.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Companies will have to register the numbers they want with the <font size=-1>ITU</font> from October, and they will be shared out more or less on a first come, first served basis. Any number already in use will get preference, though most national freephone numbers have only seven digits. Settling for eight will allow a theoretical 100m: America's seven digits have allowed only 10m, and are now exhausted.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Foolishly, the <font size=-1>ITU</font> decided not to auction popular numbers: combinations of eights are prized as lucky in Asia, and combinations that spell words on a dial (such as 1-800 FLOWERS) are valuable in the United States--although in Europe only about one-third of handsets have letters as well as numerals, and they are differently configured.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One effect of global freephone numbers may be to add to the downward pressure on international call charges: it will help callback companies, which allow subscribers to route a call through a low-tariff country, if subscribers can be offered a single global number to call. Another effect may be to boost cross-border electronic shopping. In 1994, guesses <font size=-1>AT&T</font>, some $100 billion of commerce was done over freephone numbers in the United States alone, a vastly larger amount than either television shopping or Internet commerce accounts for. Many companies include their (American) freephone number on their Internet site; some even allow customers to click on the number and be routed straight through to an operator. Now such companies will be able to sell to the world by giving their global number.



</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?834188400,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="wb4.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
