<html><head><title>Democrats at NATO's door</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>

<h1><center>Democrats at NATO's door</center></h1>

FOR more than 40 years after its foundation in 1950, while its military sinews kept the Russians at bay, <font size=-1>NATO</font> had little need to change. But in the past couple of years its 16 governments have come to realise that their alliance does not have much of a future unless it reforms: the loss of its enemy has meant the loss of its purpose. As it happens, <font size=-1>NATO</font> has plenty of other tasks to perform, ranging from peacekeeping to the provision of security among the new democracies of Central and Eastern Europe. It has already stepped into a peacekeeping role in Bosnia. The next big event is enlargement. Next year the alliance will pick a group of prospective new members, which, all being well, will be admitted in about 2000. But already doubts are setting in. Though many of these doubts are reasonable, it would be disastrous if the alliance were to go back on its word.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At the moment that is not likely, but perhaps only because the question is not being openly discussed. One of the main arguments against enlargement is that it would annoy Russia, or at least some Russians, by bringing their historic enemy well nigh to their front door. It is recognised by everyone in <font size=-1>NATO</font>, whether for or against enlargement, that this is not the moment to conduct a public debate on the subject: Boris Yeltsin is fighting for re-election as president of Russia against nationalists and communists who want to restore Russia's "greatness" and regard <font size=-1>NATO</font> as nothing but a threat.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So when <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s foreign ministers meet in Berlin next week the formal order of business will not be enlargement but the approval of a plan for combined joint task-forces--flexible outfits to run missions that do not concern territorial defence, such as peacekeeping. And they will launch a review of the integrated military structure, <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s cumbersome hierarchy of 46 headquarters. These, and the other issues facing the alliance, are discussed on <a href="sf1.html">page</a>. But the biggest and most controversial matter that <font size=-1>NATO</font> has to settle is which countries to take in, and when.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The arguments against enlargement are not trivial. The main one concerns the effect on Russia, whose evolution towards democracy, prosperity and stability should be a central objective of all <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s members. This will remain true even after the Russian election this summer, and whether or not Mr Yeltsin (two heart attacks already) is returned to power. For the foreseeable future Russia will remain a fragile political entity, torn between Slavophiles and westernisers, liberalism and nationalism, market economics and state intervention. It is not fanciful to imagine it, or even part of it, falling under the sway of a nationalist leader who might seek to shore up his support by xenophobic adventurism. Since Russia contains tens of thousands of nuclear warheads, and chemical and biological weapons to match, the West has a powerful interest in ensuring that they are kept under responsible control. Needlessly feeding Russian paranoia is not something to be done lightly.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Needlessly? A second argument against enlargement is that none of the applicants to <font size=-1>NATO</font> is actually under threat from any other country. Their interest in membership is clear: it would give them security guarantees and the benefits of belonging to an exclusive western club. But they can take advantage of <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s Partnership for Peace programme, which has already given 27 countries a kind of associate membership and the chance to take part in <font size=-1>NATO</font> ventures like the Bosnian peace-implementation force. On the face of it, membership of the European Union, with all the advantages that would bring, looks more valuable than membership of the Atlantic alliance.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Then there is the effect on <font size=-1>NATO</font> itself. Many American politicians want enlargement--not least because their voters have roots in Eastern Europe. The Germans are even keener. Looking east, they fret about economic and political turmoil, mass migration, environmental disaster and even war. On the other hand, some members of the alliance worry about the costs of enlargement, the difficulties of integrating new armies into the alliance, the plausibility of the defence guarantees that would have to be given and the possibility that a new line would be drawn in Europe between those that had full membership and those that did not. In other words, enlargement might weaken <font size=-1>NATO</font>, not strengthen it.

</p><p><b>Enlarge or die</b>
<br>None of these arguments should be ignored. None, however, is weighty enough to rule out membership for those countries that qualify--probably, in the first round, Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic. They all have good reason to fear the possibility of renewed Russian aggression. They all deserve the West's help in supporting their democracy-building endeavours. That does not mean the Russians' fears must be ignored: <font size=-1>NATO</font> can and should do what it reasonably can to reassure them, and the presence of the Russian foreign minister in Berlin next week will show that this need not be impossible. But neither Russia nor anyone else should be allowed to veto any of <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s plans. If that were to happen, the alliance would lose all credibility.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That, however, is not the main reason for saying yes to new applicants. The main reason is that, if <font size=-1>NATO</font> is resolutely tied to its existing membership, it can hardly fulfil the new roles that the ending of the cold war has thrust upon it. Looking backwards, it will wither and die in irrelevance.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?833583600,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="sf1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
