<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width=273 height=24  alt="Business"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>

<p>


<h2>Power struggle</h2>
<p><p>
(See <a href="wtw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>There was more jostling between British utilities. Scottish Power offered &#163;1.56 billion ($2.36 billion) for control of <b>Southern Water</b>, valuing the south of England utility at 975 pence a share. Southern Electric countered with a $1.6 billion agreed takeover. The share price of Southern Water soared.<p>
A cloud darkened the future of one of Germany's biggest but ailing engineering companies. <b>Kl&ouml;ckner-Humboldt-Deutz</b> had been hoping to return to profit next year, but said its survival was threatened by its discovery of long-hidden losses of up to DM650m ($420m) at its Humboldt Wedag subsidiary. <font size=-1>KHD</font> filed criminal charges against several of the unit's board members. <font size=-1>KHD</font>'s largest shareholder, with a 48% stake, is <b>Deutsche Bank</b>. The news overshadowed the bank's 32% jump in net profit for the first four months.<p>
The French government approved a bill to transform <b>France T&eacute;l&eacute;com</b> from an arm of the state into a company, in preparation for partial privatisation in 1997.

<h2>Debt effect</h2>
<p>Japan's 20 biggest banks wrote off &#165;10.3 trillion ($95 billion) of <b>bad loans</b> and turned in net losses of &#165;3.2 billion. Only four managed to stay in the black. Meanwhile the government is stepping up its campaign to have the banks contribute more to the scheme to liquidate seven near-bankrupt <i>jusen</i> mortgage firms.<p>
Unsettled times continue at <b>Moody's</b>. The president of the powerful American credit-rating agency had departed just ahead of news that the Justice Department was investigating the company's practice of giving bond issuers unsolicited ratings. Now two more senior managers have left as part of an internal reorganisation.<p>
Two Swiss organisations published competing "competitiveness" reports. The Institute for Management Development put America top, whereas the world economic forum ranked it fourth, after Singapore, Hong Kong and New Zealand. The reports also differed over Japan (13th on the forum's index, 4th on <font size=-1>IMD</font>'s) and Germany (22nd versus 10th).<p>
Shareholders grumbled at the annual general meeting of <b>Daimler-Benz</b>, after a financial year in which Germany's leading industrial company recorded the largest loss in the country's corporate history, sacked thousands, suspended its dividend for the first time in 45 years--and, adding insult to injury in the eyes of some--gave its executives a bonus of DM600,000 ($388,000) each for "the great burden they bore".<p>
<p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
Germany's <b>Commerzbank</b>, which received a demand for DM500m ($323m) in back taxes only days after details of its tax dispute were published in <i>Der Spiegel</i>, said it will sue the tax authorities for leaking information to the magazine. Commerzbank says it is outraged less by the demand (though it contests the amount) than by the way it was disclosed.<p>
(See <a href="wtw2.gif">chart</a>)<br>The <b>Russian stockmarket </b>rose after a ceasefire agreement with the Chechens gave investors further cause to believe that Boris Yeltsin will be returned to power in next month's presidential election. The tiny, and therefore still turbulent, <i>Moscow Times</i> index has nearly doubled from a record low in March.

<h2>Warning shots</h2>
<p>The United States told three companies they could face sanctions for investing in confiscated property in <b>Cuba</b>. Under controversial new laws, Sherritt International, a Canadian mining and energy firm, <font size=-1>STET</font>, Italy's telecoms giant, and Grupo Domos, a Mexican conglomerate, could find that top employees and their families, and shareholders are denied visas to the United States.<p>
Rather than cut the excise duty on foreign liquor, the Japanese finance ministry plans to raise the tax on locally distilled <i>shochu</i> by up to sixfold. This is to counter criticism by the World Trade Organisation of <b>discriminatory taxation</b> of imported spirits.<p>
All five of Japan's top <b>car makers</b> reported pre-tax profits for the year ending in March--Nissan's first in two years and Mazda's first in three years. Mitsubishi had record sales for the second straight year. All five are projecting operating profits for the first time in five years. Honda expects a pre-tax profit this year of &#165;90 billion and Toyota a whopping &#165;500 billion, its biggest in six years.<p>
America's <b>General Motors</b> picked a site in Eastern Thailand for a $500m plant that will make 100,000 cars a year, mainly for export to the regional market. The Philippines was on <font size=-1>GM</font>'s shortlist, but the company said the Thai car industry was more developed.<p>
A decision by a court of appeal in New Orleans to throw out a class-action lawsuit in which millions of smokers set out to sue <b>America's tobacco industry</b>, upset the anti-smoking lobby. The court would not commit "the fate of an entire industry or, indeed, the fate of a class of millions, to a single jury" .<p>
The economies of <b>Belgium, Portugal and Greece</b>, with large shadow economies, could be a fifth larger than they appear, says Eurostat, the <font size=-1>EU</font>'s statistical outfit, which is trying to harmonise the union's statistics.<p>
<p></p>
