<html><head><title>Masters of the cartoon universe</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>Masters of the cartoon universe</h1>

WHO wants old-fashioned two-dimensional cartoons when they can have flashy 3-<font size=-1>D</font> computer graphics? Ruth McCall, joint managing director of Cambridge Animation Systems (<font size=-1>CAS</font>), is tired of people asking this. In fact, 2-<font size=-1>D</font> cartoons, which have entertained the masses since Mickey Mouse's 1928 debut in "Steamboat Willie", are booming. Disney is raking in mega-bucks from new features such as "Pocahontas", and there is a huge and growing demand for cartoons to fill the schedules of new children's channels on satellite and cable television. However snazzy 3-<font size=-1>D</font> graphics become, 2-<font size=-1>D</font> cartoons will live on. As Ms McCall says: "Painting did not die out just because sculpture was invented."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unlike most high-tech firms, <font size=-1>CAS</font> did not start with a scientific breakthrough and then seek markets for it. Ms McCall and her two co-founders, all working in the computer-graphics industry, saw that few firms were making animation software, and set up <font size=-1>CAS</font> to invent a product to sell to them. Five years on, they have 72 staff and hope to reach break-even in the year to June, on sales of around &#163;5m.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To get this far, they have had to convince animators, a stubborn lot, that computers really can do the laborious work with ink and paint that has traditionally been farmed out to a small army of artists. In most cartoons, a chief animator sketches the key frames for each scene, leaving others to draw the "fill-in" frames and paint the backgrounds. To save money, the studios usually export this work to low-wage countries like China. But often the work sent back is not up to scratch, and has to be re-done. This is where <font size=-1>CAS</font> saw its opportunity.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The firm spent two years perfecting a piece of software that could turn a set of key frames into a finished cartoon, in which every frame looked as though it had been drawn by the original artist. Now it is the world leader in its market, and has signed up two of Hollywood's leading cartoon studios: Warner Brothers and DreamWorks. Industry sources say <font size=-1>CAS</font> is close to a deal with Walt Disney, which will buy its product to run alongside the 2-<font size=-1>D</font> animation software it has developed in-house.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is hard to estimate the potential market for <font size=-1>CAS</font>'s product: animation studios are secretive about their costs, and about what they would be prepared to pay for new technology. There is also a fast-growing market for computer games, in which the share that 2-<font size=-1>D</font> animation will get is anybody's guess.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The biggest competitive threat to <font size=-1>CAS</font> is a rival product called Toonz, from Microsoft, the world's largest software maker. So far Microsoft has let <font size=-1>CAS</font> grab the best customers, apparently having decided that, compared with spreadsheets and word-processor programs, the market for 2-<font size=-1>D</font> animation is too puny. But this market is growing, and if Microsoft wants a piece of the action, its pockets are deep enough for it to choose between trying to wipe out <font size=-1>CAS</font>, doing a licensing deal with it or, of course, buying the firm.


</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?833583600,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br3.html">Next article</a>
</p>
