<html><head><title>Keeping up appearances</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Poverty</b></p>
<h1>Keeping up appearances</h1>


<p>ONE of the mothers interviewed in a new book on poverty, to be published on June 4th by the Joseph Rowntree Foundation, tells how she bought a cheap cola in a supermarket, then decanted it into a Coke bottle, so that her children's friends would not know they could not afford the real thing. This, as the book shows, is the stuff of poverty. The poor have to be ingenious and organised to keep their heads above water. If they are to pay the bills, feed a family and keep up appearances, they have to manage their resources better than the well-off.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some 14m people--a quarter of the population--live on less than half average earnings. Most of them are in households run by women: three out of ten low-income households are lone parents or widows, and among the six out of ten who are couples, the man tends to hand over management of the budget to the woman.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Life on a Low Income" confirms some of the common impressions of poverty--the boredom, the shame, the isolation--but it does not bear out the widespread suspicion that the poor are feckless. Its study of 74 poor families showed that two-thirds of them were careful with money, with most of them writing down and costing a budget for the week. Some people allocated money for different purposes, putting cash in envelopes or jars. Others kept records of their spending, but did not plan in advance. A third neither planned nor recorded.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Food is the biggest item in their budget and the one offering most scope for resourcefulness. Women from poor families say they prefer to shop without their partner or children, because they tend to spend more in company. They avoid supermarkets in favour of street markets, and tend to shop at the end of the day, because stalls and shops then sell off fruit, vegetables and bread cheap. The less badly-off households surveyed tended to do a weekly shop, but the poorest ones shopped daily--partly because they were often short of cash, but also because of the danger that family members would eat more than the budget could bear if there was food around.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Of the 74 families, 32 were keeping their heads above water, 20 seemed to be drowning, and the rest were somewhere in- between. For those who were sinking, taking out a loan was not a sensible option. High-street lenders would not look at them. Loan sharks would gobble them up. One such was charging the equivalent of a 353% annual interest rate on a 20-week loan.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?833583600,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br4.html">Next article</a>
</p>
