<html><head><title>Crackdown</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Crime</b></p>
<h1>Crackdown</h1>

<font size=1>NEW YORK</font>
<p>NOBODY ever lost an election by underestimating the enthusiasm of the public for cracking down on crime. Accordingly, Michael Howard, the home secretary, is putting it about that the government is planning to import the techniques that reduced crime by 27% in New York between 1993 and 1995. Jack Straw, the shadow home secretary, is not critical, but miffed: he says he thought of it first.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The idea behind the policing strategy that was adopted by William Bratton, New York's former police commissioner, comes from James Q. Wilson, an academic at the University of California. His "broken windows" theory maintains that small bits of disorder lead to larger crimes. A building with a broken window signals to potential criminals that the authorities are not bothering to keep order, so they are more likely to attempt a burglary. Hence policemen were told to arrest people for minor infringements as well as for serious crimes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At the same time, Mr Bratton revolutionised management. Crime figures used to take two months to emerge from the precincts. Now they take four days. Headquarters thus knows quickly what is going on. At regular meetings, precinct commanders are hauled up before their colleagues and held to account by their superiors.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The high-profile Mr Bratton has gone, but his methods remain. Not everybody, however, is convinced. There is some doubt, for instance, about how closely the figures reflect reality. Vinne Bavaro, a cop in the Midtown South precinct, says of Mr Bratton: "He knew how to play the numbers game." Caroline Nicholl, a British chief superintendent from Milton Keynes who is on a Harkness Fellowship studying American policing, says that she has seen precinct commanders manipulating their statistics.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ms Nicholl is also worried about the contrast between the style of policing in New York and Britain. The first is aggressive, the second aims to build up trust. "New York policing," says Ms Nicholl, "sets up perverse incentives. For instance, if a precinct commander builds up a relationship with a community, then the reported crime figures are bound to go up." Crime might not have gone up, policing might have improved, but the precinct commander would get stick.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Another worry is that, while New York-style policing may reduce crime, it may create other problems. One of the techniques adopted under Mr Bratton, for instance, is "doing a vertical"--going through a tower block in a deprived area, arresting everybody who does not live there, and taking them down to the police station for questioning. This discourages people from carrying guns casually, and it helps the police gather information about drug dealers. But it also means harassing young (mostly black) people who may be minding their own business. It was this style of policing that led to the riots in Brixton in London in 1981, and which was condemned by Lord Scarman's report on the incidents.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is also some doubt about whether new policing techniques have really been responsible for the falling crime figures. Crime has dropped as sharply in other cities--Kansas City and Houston, for instance--which have not adopted New York's policing practices. Criminologists tend to attribute the drop in crime to a decline in the use of crack--whose introduction in the mid-1980s was generally thought to be responsible for the rise in violence in the second half of the decade--and to a fall in the proportion of young men in the population. But since crack use is barely affected by policy, and the number of young people not at all, such explanations are not popular with policymakers.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?833583600,iss">Search</a>
