<html><head><title>Game over</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Casinos</b></p>
<h1>Game over</h1>

<p>CONSIDER the following set of proposals for the deregulation of a major British industry. Its product will be legal in Oxford, but not in Cambridge. It will be legal to buy it with a debit card, but not to buy it with a credit card. It may be sold to those who want to buy it so long as they decide to do so at least 24 hours before they want it; but sell it on the day, and you will be breaking the law. Do not, however, think of helping your customers to apply for it by advertising in local newspapers. This will be illegal, though it will be perfectly legal to advertise it in the Yellow Pages.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;You would think that only a minister with mad-cow disease could come up with such a mess. But in fact these proposals for the deregulation of Britain's casinos have been produced by a Home Office minister, Timothy Kirkhope, who is an enthusiast for deregulation. Unbelievably, it took his department six years since the matter was first considered, and nearly two years since a promise of change from the home secretary, to the end of the consultation period on the detailed proposals on May 31st. An early general election would leave the proposals stranded.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Why has it taken so long to produce such a dog's dinner? The answers would make a case study in bad government. First, ministers kept changing--three in 15 months, one of whom, Nicholas Baker, was not keen on the whole business. Second, ministers were told that if they deregulated more thoroughly, they might need to introduce a new law, instead of acting under the powers vested in them by existing deregulation law. New legislation would introduce further delays.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Third, the Home Office ran into obstruction from the Treasury over the number of towns that could be allowed extra casinos. More towns, the Treasury said, would mean more gaming inspectors which would add to public spending. In vain did the industry argue that it would also mean more revenue for the Treasury, much of it from tourists, amounting to many times the cost of the inspectors. Eventually a compromise was reached. Gaming would be permitted in 13 more areas on top of the 53 where it was already legal. They include Oxford, but not Cambridge. The casino industry would rather have half a loaf than no loaf at all, so the plans will probably go through.



<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?833583600,iss">Search</a>
