<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p align=center><table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" width=231 height=24  alt="Britain"></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>
<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>




<p><b>Milk of unkindness</b> &nbsp;
The British Medical Association criticised the government for refusing to name nine brands of baby milk found to contain traces of chemicals suspected of affecting the reproductive system.</p>
<p><b>The wages of sin</b> &nbsp;
The government revealed plans to allow employers to check on the criminal records of those being recruited to "sensitive" jobs--from doctors to lottery-ticket sellers.</p>
<p><b>Peace poll</b> &nbsp;
The people of Northern Ireland went to the polls to choose which parties will take part in next month's talks on the future of the province. The British and Irish governments again failed to agree a formula for disarmament, which they had hoped might coax the <font size=-1>IRA</font> to restore its ceasefire.</p>
<p><b>Parents from hell</b> &nbsp;
The National Association of Head Teachers said teachers were being assaulted more often by parents, and demanded powers to expel pupils whose parents attacked staff.</p>
<p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%><b>Going nuclear</b> &nbsp;
The government launched its privatisation programme for British Energy, owner of eight of Britain's 15 nuclear-power stations. Stockbrokers involved in the privatisation put values ranging from &#163;1.5 billion to &#163;2.6 billion on the company.</p>
<p><b>Free</b> &nbsp;
Sara Thornton, released last year after five years in jail for killing her violent husband, was found guilty of manslaughter in a second trial but set free by the judge because of the sentence she had already served.</p>
<p><b>Left turn</b> &nbsp;
The Tory Reform Group, a left-wing faction of the Conservative Party, proposed a cut in the number of <font size=-1>MP</font>s at Westminster, higher taxes on businesses to pay for better public transport, and the eventual abolition of tax relief on mortgages.
</p>
<p><b>Balls-up</b> &nbsp;
"Mastermind", a television quiz, was censored for the first time in its 24-year history. The <font size=-1>BBC</font> bleeped out the naughty word in a question about the punk-rock album "Never Mind The Bollocks Here's The Sex Pistols" .</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
