<html><head><title>Fidelity's fallen star</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/fn.gif" width=360 height=26  alt="Finance And Economics">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>Fidelity's fallen star</h1>

<font size=1>NEW YORK AND LONDON</font><p><b>The surprise departure of Jeffrey Vinik, the manager of America's biggest mutual fund, is a warning to other financial wizards--and their employers</b></p>

<p>IT IS easy to see why they are often portrayed as demi-gods. They can move billions of dollars at will. They are fabulously rich. At times, they seem to hold the fate of financial markets in their hands. So it is no surprise that investors such as George Soros and Warren Buffett have been hyped by the media. Or that fund-management companies make strenuous efforts to lionise the managers who perform well.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The contribution of such stars is one of the issues raised by the fall of Jeffrey Vinik, who on May 23rd resigned as captain of the $56 billion Magellan Fund, America's largest mutual fund and the flagship of Fidelity, the country's biggest fund-management group, which has over 200 funds and some $400 billion under management. Mr Vinik is leaving, he says, to start a fund-management firm of his own.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Magellan's former boss had not had an easy passage recently. Last year he was accused of misusing Magellan's muscle in the stockmarket. Several widely reported lawsuits were launched by shareholders in Micron Technology, a computer company, alleging that the fund manager had quietly sold shares in Micron even as he was publicly talking favourably about the company's prospects. Mr Vinik and Fidelity vigorously denied any wrongdoing. However, it was not this incident that led to his downfall. Rather, it was an ill-timed bet.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At the start of this year, worried by the sharp rise in American share prices in 1995, Mr Vinik reduced Magellan's equity holdings to around 65% of its assets and invested the rest in bonds and cash. Because the stockmarket continued to boom, the fund's returns have trailed behind those of the <font size=-1>S&P</font> 500 index, the industry's benchmark. That, it seems, was unacceptable.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Other mutual-fund firms may choose to ignore Mr Vinik's troubles. When a tide of cash is crashing into your coffers, there is little time to contemplate the fate of rivals. During the past 15 years, as the top chart on the next page shows, the amount of new cash pouring into long-term mutual funds (ie, equity and bond funds) has remained impressive, reaching a net $123 billion or so last year. In the first four months of this year, such funds got another $108 billion, or about four times as much as in the same period in 1995. In April alone, some $26 billion poured into equity funds, the second biggest monthly inflow ever.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This flow of money has enabled many fund-management groups to prosper by means of a simple strategy: market successful funds (and managers) as hard as possible and keep starting up new ones. In the past two years alone, over 1,100 new funds have been added (see <a href="fn1.gif"> chart</a>). But when this heady pace slows, perhaps with the onset of a bear market, the morals of the Vinik story may become clear.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One such moral is that, in an overcrowded industry, fund-management firms are becoming increasingly accountable to their investors, and the freedom of their managers to manage funds in their own way is becoming correspondingly narrower. In recent years an entire sub-industry has arisen to rate the performance of various funds against their "peers" . The reports of firms such as Morningstar, which award coveted stars to the most successful funds, are zealously followed by investors seeking the best home for their money.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This has been a boon to the marketing departments of funds with managers who achieve star status for a time. But, by raising expectations so high, the emphasis on performance also makes any subsequent disappointment all the greater when managers underperform.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although Mr Vinik's fall from grace provides a dramatic example of a long-term record that was not stellar enough to help him over a short-term blip in performance, it is not an isolated case. Paul Wick, the manager of a successful technology fund for <font size=-1>J&W</font> Seligman, a New York firm, became a sought-after guru when his fund performed spectacularly in 1994 and early 1995. After sagging technology shares dragged the fund down by nearly a fifth late last year, Mr Wick was no longer widely quoted--only to resurface recently as his fund's performance improved.
</p><p><b>Under the microscope</b>
<br>The growing scrutiny by outsiders such as Morningstar has put new pressure on managers to conform strictly to investment guidelines. In attacking Mr Vinik for moving the Magellan fund so decisively away from equities, some investors seem to be taking the view that there can never be a case for more prudent investment in bonds and cash. The demand for disclosure is also narrowing the autonomy of fund managers. In March Piper Jaffray, a fund manager, was censured by the National Association of Securities Dealers and fined $1.25m after it was found that a supposedly staid bond fund marketed by the firm between 1991 and mid-1994 was in fact investing in highly risky mortgage bonds.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Other regulators have entered this disclosure debate. To help investors, the Securities and Exchange Commission (<font size=-1>SEC</font>), America's stockmarket watchdog, has floated the idea of simple, two-page mutual-fund risk prospectuses designed to lay out clearly the goals and policies of each fund. Eight fund managers are currently testing such prospectuses alongside the more complicated traditional offering.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In addition, as Mr Vinik's clash with Micron Technology shows, star managers have to be especially careful about what they say in public. Indeed, the Micron affair prompted Fidelity to ban all of its managers from discussing shares in individual firms, and has also prompted the <font size=-1>SEC</font> to begin a broad review of fund managers' trading patterns.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All these trends point in the same direction. It is becoming increasingly hard for individual managers, even the stars, to run their funds with the freedom that they have come to expect. This is not, however, a message that the industry seems willing to hear. Fidelity responded to Mr Vinik's resignation by reshuffling six of its fund managers and appointing one of them, Robert Stansky, to manage Magellan. No sooner was he anointed than the first articles picking over his investment style appeared in the press. No sign here of a retreat from the cult of personality.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Arguably, in the case of a fund as big as Magellan, the attention paid to the man at the top is justified. But many on Wall Street reckon that the fund is now too big for its own good. Outperforming the market is inherently tricky for a fund whose sheer size makes it difficult for it to move money without signalling its strategy to its competitors. It is also questionable whether a single person, however gifted, can handle such a large responsibility.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Just think: if, in addition to some cash, Magellan holds positions in, say, 100 different firms, then each holding could be worth as much as $500m. Yet most fund managers struggle to follow more than 50 firms at once. Unusually, Peter Lynch, a successful former manager of Magellan when the fund was much smaller, is supposed to have held shares in more than 1,000 different firms, buying into every company in the industry sectors he favoured.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Perhaps that is a clue as to what Fidelity should do with Magellan. Why not turn it into an index fund--that is, one which seeks merely to mimic the market's overall performance? That way the fund's 4m investors could be mathematically certain that it would not underperform, and Mr Stansky could avoid becoming another Icarus. Whether investors would put up with the loss of their demi-gods, and their divine performance, is another matter.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?833583600,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>

</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
