<html><head><title>The estate we're in</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>The estate we're in</h1>

THERE are few starker illustrations of the changes in British society after 17 years of Tory rule than the revolution in "social housing"--that is, homes rented by local councils and housing associations.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A report to be issued on May 24th by the Institute for Fiscal Studies, an independent research group, shows that in 1961 a third of British families lived in social homes. Now less than a quarter do, and they are far likelier to be poor than even 20 years ago. Average real incomes of social renters were 20% lower in 1993 than in 1973. In 1979 less than a third of families in social housing came from the poorest 20% of the population, and around a tenth from the richest 20%. The poorest now account for half of social renters, the richest virtually none. Until the mid-1970s, unemployment of male heads-of-household was not much higher in social housing than average (see <a href="br1.gif">chart</a>). By 1992, barely half of male heads-of-household in the social sector had a job, compared with 85% elsewhere.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mostly, this reflects success, not failure. Allowing renters to buy their home took many of the better-off out of social housing, reduced dependency on the state and improved maintenance of the country's housing. Stricter rules on eligibility meant that only the truly needy stood much of a chance of obtaining social housing, which also makes sense.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet there is a drawback to limiting social housing to the poor: it makes it harder for them to become less poor. To cut the subsidies to social renters who are not poor, the government has forced up rents, by 30% in real terms between 1989 and 1993 alone. Those unable to pay can claim means-tested housing benefit, which 60% of social tenants now do. Because means-tested benefits are withdrawn as a claimant's income rises, however, they are a disincentive to the jobless finding work. The <font size=-1>IFS</font> calculates that, because of taxes and withdrawal of benefit, 70% of unemployed men in social housing would increase their net income by less than 40p for every &#163;1 received in income from employment.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One solution is to raise the threshold at which benefit is withdrawn, or to withdraw it more slowly. This would be costly, and claimants would still depend on means-tested benefit. An alternative is to cut social-housing rents. This would benefit not just the unemployed but also those in work, those unfit for work, and the retired--and so would be even costlier. If rents were cut only for people under 60 and not disabled, the price would come down. But presumably that is to think the unthinkable.



</td></tr></table>
