<html><head><title>Biotech blooms</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>




<h1>Biotech blooms</h1>

CAN British Biotech, a firm that is still several years away from any products, even if things go well, really be worth &#163;2 billion--putting it on a par with such solid profit-makers as Tate &amp; Lyle and WH Smith? This question divided City analysts on May 21st, when the company announced encouraging results from clinical tests on marimastat, a cancer treatment it is developing. The drug will now undergo a final set of trials, and if successful, may go on sale in 1999.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The firm's share price soared to more than &#163;33 on the news, from less than &#163;5 a year ago. It will go much further if marimastat lives up to the expectations of the optimists. They include Anthony Colletta of <font size=-1>ABN</font> Amro Hoare Govett, an investment bank, who says British Biotech is perhaps four years ahead of other firms which are working on similar drugs. The latest tests on marimastat showed that more than half of 232 patients with prostate, bowel and pancreatic cancer showed an improvement, having failed to respond to other treatments. Mr Colletta says there are currently about 5m patients in rich countries with such cancers, and reckons that if marimastat won just 15% of this market its sales could reach &#163;3.5 billion a year, with a profit margin of up to 50%.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The pessimists hear echoes of America's recent biotech boom and bust, when investors stampeded into buying shares in firms which failed to live up to the hype. Steve Plag of <font size=-1>BZW</font>, another investment bank, is among the doubters; he says the optimists underestimate the possibility that marimastat may have long-term side-effects which are more serious than the aching joints reported in the trials carried out so far. It may take years for British Biotech to convince regulators if any new worries over side-effects do arise, allowing its rivals to catch up. There are also many pitfalls in manufacturing and marketing a new drug, and Mr Plag points out that British Biotech has no experience in these areas yet.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So British Biotech could be the most successful high-tech firm of the 1990s, or a spectacular flop--or something in between, if its drugs prove to be effective in only a limited number of cases or face serious competition. The penalty for failing to make the stockmarket's dreams come true would be severe. The lesson for the bosses of Britain's current breed of high-tech companies is that in addition to their scientific and financial skills, there is another vital skill they need--that of managing expectations.

</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832978800,iss">Search</a>
