<html><head><title>Peering into the shadow</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Roads</b></p>
<h1>Peering into the shadow</h1>


<p>THROUGHOUT the ages, the lure of the lender has been to "take the waiting out of wanting". But rarely has a borrower been more enthusiastically hooked than the British government. In its adoption of shadow tolling as an apparently painless way to pay for new roads, it has all the fervour of a convert. Since 1994 more than 40 schemes, with a construction cost of more than &#163;1 billion, have been announced. Under the shadow-toll proposals, contractors design, build, finance and operate new roads. The government pays them back according to how many vehicles use the road over the following 30 years.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Earlier this month, the Department of Transport invited businesses to tender for three new shadow-toll roads. Four contracts have already been awarded. The winner of the fifth, a consortium led by <font size=-1>BICC</font> and W.S. Atkins, was announced on May 21st. Many more are in the pipeline.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With the exception of the Channel tunnel rail link, the Department of Transport is by far the biggest user of the government's private finance initiative (<font size=-1>PFI</font>). Shadow tolling seems to offer something for everyone. To free-market enthusiasts it looks like an extension of privatisation. To public-sector adherents it appears as the most promising way to secure much-needed long-term capital investment. For politicians of all persuasions, desperate to escape the shackles of public-expenditure constraints, it offers a way to get off-balance-sheet finance for new roads. And for the numerous consortia of construction companies, banks, and city law firms with an interest in road building, it offers a feast of contracts after a long period of famine.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Is it, however, a good deal for the taxpayer? The Metropolitan Transport Research Unit, an independent consultancy, is to publish a study later this month which claims that it is an expensive form of hire-purchase finance. The study, commissioned by Transport 2000 and other public-transport pressure groups, examines one proposed shadow-toll contract, the <font size=-1>A36</font> Salisbury by-pass, and concludes that it would cost roughly twice as much as it would if it were financed directly by the public sector. The study's author, Keith Buchan, a former local-authority transport planner, says that the cost will be higher by between 84% and 131%, assuming a conservative 12.5-15% rate of return.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Peter Collis, director of the Highways Agency's private-finance division, dismisses such estimates out of hand. "We have achieved very substantial value for money. Significant savings are being achieved," he insists.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is impossible to judge who is right, because the government refuses to say what it is paying for shadow-toll roads, or how the costs compare with a publicly financed road. <i>The Economist</i> has asked the Department of Transport to reveal the details of shadow-toll contracts, but it has so far refused, claiming that the information is commercially confidential and revealing it would prejudice future negotiations. If the department maintains that stance, we shall refer our request for information to William Reid, the Parliamentary Commissioner for Administration, who supervises the government's code of access to official information.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The lack of openness about shadow tolls may suit ministers, but it does nothing to reassure voters, who may justifiably wonder if they are being taken for an expensive ride. The Automobile Association claims that the government's enthusiasm for shadow tolling is driven more by expediency than by a wish to develop an efficient financial structure for new road construction. The National Audit Office, which is currently looking at shadow tolling, will eventually report on the matter.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the meantime, only a stab at the truth can be made. Evidence given to the House of Commons Treasury Select Committee, whose report on the private-finance initiative was published last month, suggests that the transaction costs of shadow tolling are high. Tendering costs are up to five times more expensive than for a publicly financed road, while borrowing costs can be twice as much.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On top of those extra costs there is the contractor's profit. Jonathan Scott, executive director of <font size=-1>SBC</font> Warburg, a merchant bank which is one of the key players in the shadow-tolling business, says that investors in such schemes are looking for a return on their equity investment somewhere in the range of 15-20%.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Against these potential additional costs there are undoubted efficiency gains from using the private-sector. There are large savings to be made, according to John Connally, who is engineering task-force leader for Howard Humphrey, the design engineers for the first shadow-toll contract, the <font size=-1>A1(M)</font> in Cambridgeshire, which was awarded last year. "We are taking the outline design and turning it into detailed design in five rather than 12 months," he says. The Highways Agency says that the crucial advantage of shadow tolling is that it links together design, construction and maintenance in a single contract, allowing builders to achieve long-term savings by building roads to a higher specification.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In addition to the question of cost, shadow tolling raises other contentious issues. Transport 2000 warns that it will increase traffic, because the companies building the new roads will have a direct incentive to maximise traffic flows. However, the point that more roads will reduce blockages and thus ensure the efficient use of roads is also one of the strongest arguments for the idea.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Transport 2000 is also worried that a rush of private finance into road-building may trample other considerations. Stephen Joseph, its director, thinks that it is one thing for the government to bulldoze an ecological site or compulsorily purchase somebody's house, but quite another for a private company to do so for profit. Whatever the rights and wrongs of his argument, it could have political force when old ladies are turfed out of their houses.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Shadow tolling may well make sense, and road planning is still the preserve of the government, not the private sector. But allaying fears of expensive sweet-heart deals or abuses of government powers will be impossible without much greater transparency. Taxpayers surely have a right to know what long-term commitments are being made on their behalf, and to have some way of judging whether their money is being spent wisely.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832978800,iss">Search</a>
