<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p align=center><table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" width=231 height=24  alt="Britain"></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>
<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>



<p><b>Money mystery</b> &nbsp;
Brian Mawhinney, the Conservative Party chairman, launched an inquiry into claims that the party had received donations of more than &#163;100,000 from a businessman linked to Radovan Karadzic, the Bosnian Serb leader who has been indicted on war-crimes charges.</p>
<p><b>Going down</b> &nbsp;
Owen Oyston, a Labour-supporting millionaire and chairman of Blackpool Football Club, was jailed for raping a 16-year-old.</p>
<p><b>Wigging</b> &nbsp;
The Lord Chief Justice, who is retiring because of ill-health, attacked the government's proposals for tougher sentences. Lord Taylor warned against "production-line justice" and accused the government of misusing statistics to make its case.</p>
<p><b>Learning loans</b> &nbsp;
The Labour Party proposed that grants for students' living expenses be scrapped and replaced by an improved loans scheme, in which graduates would spread their repayments over 20 years.</p>
<p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<b>Jobs row &nbsp;</b>Labour disowned a magazine article purportedly written by Michael Meacher, its employment spokesman, in which he promised to change the rules on unemployment benefit. Mr Meacher's researcher actually wrote the article, and had made a mistake. In future, it appears, Mr Meacher will read all articles appearing under his name.</p>
<p><b>Steaming ahead</b> &nbsp;
Shares in Railtrack, the newly privatised owner of most of Britain's rail infrastructure, ended their first day on the stockmarket at 220.5p, giving private investors who applied through share shops an instant profit of 30.5p a share.</p>
<p><b>Paddy goes to Liverpool</b> &nbsp;
Patrick Kelly, bishop of Salford, was appointed as Catholic archbishop of Liverpool. He was chosen for his appeal to both conservatives and progressives in the church, who have been arguing since Derek Worlock, his predecessor, died.
</p>
<p><b>Constable nicked</b> &nbsp;
A painting attributed to Constable went missing, apparently taken by a thief, from the headquarters of the City of London police.
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
