<html><head><title>How Bob Dole should fight</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>

<h1><center>How Bob Dole should fight</center></h1>

IF YOU believe the opinion polls, America's presidential election is all but over, six months before the voting booths open. To believe that would be foolish, given that voters seem to change their minds even more often than before, and presidential campaigns are strewn with elephant traps. Yet what is extraordinary is that talk that Bill Clinton has already as good as won is coming not from complacent Democrats but from despairing Republicans--the same party that barely two months ago made Bob Dole its candidate-presumptive by an overwhelming margin. Mr Dole's cause is hopeless, they mutter noisily, because, well, so is he. His speeches ramble, his campaigning is dire. The despair may be justified; or it may not be. Let Mr Dole prove his detractors wrong; this week he made a bold effort to do so by resigning from the Senate, his political home of 36 years (see <a href="am1.html">page</a>). Still, prediction is not the business of this article.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That business is the argument that Mr Dole and the Republicans should make in this campaign. The remarkable feature of American politics is the way in which the Republicans--not just, or even mainly, Mr Dole--have given away the policy high-ground which they seized at Congress's mid-term elections in 1994. That victory forced President Clinton to swing to the right, trimming his views on the federal budget and the role of government, and re-positioning himself as a moderating force against congressional zealotry. He bent to the Republican arguments, and even smartened up his foreign policy, albeit for other reasons. Yet now it is conceivable that a landslide re-election for Mr Clinton could also lose the Republicans their control of Congress, opening the way for yet another re-positioning of the Clinton White House, this time back to the interventionist left. That prospect is what makes Mr Dole's task important--win or lose.
</p><p><b>The arguments against Bill Clinton</b>
<br>To Mr Dole, what matters is getting elected. To the wider world, what will matter is what kind of government America will have in the next few years. Which is why the first argument to be made is that it should not have the kind Bill Clinton wanted when he was elected in 1992.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Clinton's instinct is to meddle and intervene in the economy. The saving grace of his first two years was that Congress wouldn't let him. His plan to "kick-start" economic growth was rejected, and notions from his labour secretary, Robert Reich, and others for wider intervention were blocked, chiefly by Robert Rubin, now at the Treasury. America's economy is doing well, a fact that could help Mr Clinton in November, because policy has been guided by Alan Greenspan (a Republican) at the Federal Reserve and Mr Clinton has paid heed to the worldly Mr Rubin. Yet interventionist ideas keep flowing, most recently ways to "encourage" good corporate behaviour. That flow must be dammed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On the federal budget, the popular view is not only that Mr Clinton came out the winner of last winter's long impasse but also that he is committed to eliminating the deficit. The truth is that his victory came on tactics rather than strategy: the plan to balance the budget by 2002 was a Republican one. And his commitment to spending cuts is doubtful, especially given his refusal to countenance the ending of welfare's status as an automatic entitlement. Neither party can be relied on to curb spending further, and both dabble with the electoral bribery of tax cuts. But the plan is likelier to unravel under Second-Term Clinton and a Democrat-run Congress, and with it the hope of reviving America's paltry savings rate. It is the importance of the budget for that which needs to be brought out in this campaign, and with it the hard choices required for a leaner government.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Most telling, perhaps, are the arguments about foreign affairs. On paper, and once extremists' views about withdrawal from <font size=-1>NATO</font> or the United Nations have been discounted, Republican foreign policies differ little from President Clinton's. It is not hard to list the challenges America faces, and to recommend that they must be dealt with boldly, with leadership, and so on. But in diplomacy style matters almost as much as substance, and it is in this regard that President Clinton's weaknesses emerge most clearly. Take virtually any topic--Bosnia, the Middle East, Northern Ireland, Russia, China, Japan--and in the end the Clinton administration has hit on more or less the right policy. But only after its first idea, or second or third, was wrong.
</p><p><b>The arguments for a different sort of president</b>
<br>This mixture of talk-first-think-later and wavering in the face of domestic lobbies has created a damaging uncertainty about America, in the eyes of friends and foes alike. Uncertainty about where it stands, but also uncertainty about whether it means what it says. To conduct foreign policy in this manner would be wrong at any time. To do so now, with China likely to pose increasing dangers in Asia and Russia liable to be troublesome whoever wins its presidential vote this summer, would be folly, grand scale.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;You might argue, and many surely will, that the Clinton administration has finally learnt how to govern; that this is not the time to bring in another bunch of neophytes. If that proves to be so, then fine. But can that be depended on? Mr Clinton and his team have above all proved creatures of circumstance; if their circumstances change, so might they. That gives Mr Dole his opportunity, as well as making it important that a mediocre president be faced with a credible challenge.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Dole can, and should, stand for a different sort of government. The president was originally meant to be a moderating influence, a person who would take a statesman-like view of the dangers facing the nation rather than getting up to his elbows in day-to-day legislation. Mr Dole's decision to stand for election "without office or authority...a private citizen...just a man," is a welcome sign that he will take this stance, and will make it more plausible that as president he would be a counterbalance to a Republican Congress rather than simply an agent of one.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As the campaign gathers pace, the usual temptations will present themselves: the buying off of domestic lobbies, the making of expansive promises to act here, there and everywhere. Mr Dole does not come with a smarty-pants agenda, and should not seek one, whether in tax-cut pledges or (a looming weakness) bashing Japan over trade. For that is the mode of government, and of the presidency in particular, away from which America should be turning. Against a meddlesome Democratic candidate, the argument Mr Dole must make is that the presidency needs a different, more stable, more dignified sort of occupant. Even Mr Clinton might be convinced. For the point will hold regardless of who wins.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="sf1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
