<html><head><title>Unpopular capitalism</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Individual shareholders</b></p>
<h1>Unpopular capitalism</h1>


IF YOU see Sid, try to cheer him up. Thousands of Sids, as the government's advertisements called small investors during the campaign to privatise British Gas ten years ago, saw the price of their shares in the firm plunge after the gas industry's regulator announced strict new price controls on May 13th (see <a href="br2.html">page</a>). The announcement was unwelcome news for the government, too: it is currently trying to tempt small investors to buy shares in Railtrack, which owns the rail network. The sale of Railtrack, scheduled for May 20th, is the latest exercise in "popular capitalism"--the attempt to spread share ownership, traditionally the preserve of the wealthy, throughout the land. Once one of the Tories' favourite policies, the effort to build popular capitalism has been less successful than its architects hoped.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;True, the number of people owning shares has risen sharply, thanks to the government's policy of allocating a large slice of privatisation shares to individuals, rather than selling them only to big financial institutions. About 3m people owned shares in 1979; 11m did so in 1991. The total has since fallen back, to 9m. But the advocates of popular capitalism had grander designs than merely to increase the number of shareholders. They believed that wider share ownership would inspire a new enthusiasm for capitalism. People would follow the performance of the firms they owned shares in, relishing the thought that they had a stake in the economy. Oh yes, and these budding new capitalists would probably vote Conservative.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It has proved otherwise. A survey by <font size=-1>MORI</font> in 1992 found that of those who first bought shares during a privatisation, a mere 200,000 (just 2% of all shareholders at that time) went on to buy a share in a non-privatised firm. Many first-time investors quickly sold their privatisation shares (issued at rock-bottom prices to entice individuals to buy) for a nice profit.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Because buyers of privatised shares have not moved on to other shares, their holdings are typically small and narrow. Half of all individual shareholders own shares in only one firm; three-quarters own shares in three firms or less. Only 4% have invested in more than ten firms. And although the number of shareholders has soared, the percentage of British equities owned by individuals has continued to fall, from 66% in 1957 and 38% in 1975, to around 20% (see <a href="br1.gif">chart</a>). Share-ownership is wider, but more thinly spread.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In a recent pamphlet, "All Capitalists Now," Proshare, a group which lobbies for wider share ownership, argues that the government could have done a better promotional job by giving away the shares of privatised firms to the entire adult population rather than selling them (the public, after all, already owned the companies). Alternatively, says Proshare, the government could have bundled the shares of several privatised firms together in diversified portfolios run by investment trusts, and then given shares in these trusts to the public. It is not too late for the government to heed such advice, should it choose to: shares in publicly-owned businesses including the Post Office, the <font size=-1>BBC</font>, Channel Four, Forest Enterprise, British Waterways, London Underground, as well as the motorway network, could yet be given away. As well as fostering wider share ownership, such a move could also make privatisation itself more popular.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In addition, the government could do more to encourage employee share-ownership, which has also grown rapidly thanks to privatisation. Employee share-option schemes still remain typically a perk for senior managers, rather than for all the firm's workforce. Employees who do receive shares or options usually sell their shares or exercise their options at the earliest opportunity, rather than retaining them as long-term investments.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On the other hand, argues Proshare, promoting share ownership is not a task for government alone. Many building societies plan to become public companies. They should encourage (Proshare doesn't say how) the millions of savers and borrowers who will receive free shares to hold on to them rather than sell.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The flaw in all this--and the reason why the proportion of shares owned directly by individuals is likely to go on shrinking--is that for most people buying the shares of individual companies is an imprudent way to invest in the stockmarket. Far better to invest with a big institution such as a pension fund, insurer or mutual fund. These have in-house expertise and--more important--are able to reduce risk by holding shares in many different firms.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This fact is widely recognised by the public. Most savers prefer to hold the bulk of their exposure to the stockmarket (if any) in the form of a pension or endowment insurance policy. In the same way, sales of personal equity plans (<font size=-1>PEP</font>s), which allow tax-favoured investment in shares, have soared only since a new rule allowed savers to buy shares in investment companies with diversified portfolios.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What of the broader aim of popular capitalism--to make capitalism popular? This is often seen as no more than a Tory ruse to make cheap privatisation seem respectable (an unnecessary one, by the way, now that Labour loves capitalism). Certainly, financial institutions are sceptical: all the signs are that they regard communicating with their small investors as a waste of time.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This may be unwise. Future governments, Tory or Labour, reluctant to raise taxes on incomes, are increasingly likely to raise taxes on company profits, and to tap the assets held by financial institutions. Those assets are for many people the "stake" in the economy that Tony Blair, Labour's leader, says they so desperately need. If financial institutions can help individuals not merely to "own" this stake, but to understand and take an interest in its value, it would be far more difficult for politicians to do anything that hurts them.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br2.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
