<html><head><title>Don't you just love being in control?</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>Don't you just love being in control?</h1>
<p>
BRITAIN is in for another prolonged spat over utility regulation. On May 13th Clare Spottiswoode, the head of Ofgas, the industry regulator, hit British Gas with strict new rules on pricing. She proposed that the prices charged by TransCo, the gas-transportation arm of British Gas, should be cut by 20-28% next April. And she insisted that prices then be cut by 5% a year in real terms until 2002.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;After Ms Spottiswoode's announcement, the firm's share price dropped by 12%. Analysts said that dividends might be halved. The company thundered that, under Ofgas's plan, TransCo might have to sack thousands of workers. It is all but certain that British Gas, once again, will ask the Monopolies and Mergers Commission (<font size=-1>MMC</font>) to arbitrate.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Among many points of disagreement, two stand out. First is the question of whether TransCo can be better run. Ofgas plainly thinks there is much room for improvement. The firm claims that the regulator has underestimated its future operating costs by about 25%. Ofgas says that the firm's figures are well-padded.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The second issue is more arcane. In principle, TransCo's revenue should allow it to make a reasonable rate of return on its assets. But how much are its assets worth? This already fiddly bit of guesswork is complicated by the fact that British utilities were privatised cheaply: British Gas's shareholders paid only about 40% of the cost of replacing the company's pipelines, buildings and so forth. In calculating the return that shareholders should receive, regulators use a notional figure for assets which allows for this.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In its 1993 report, the <font size=-1>MMC</font> proposed a formula for that notional figure. Up to a point, Ofgas has followed its suggestion by proposing that, in effect, TransCo's pre-1991 assets be valued for regulatory purposes at 60% of their book value; later assets count in full. But it also wants a big change. The <font size=-1>MMC</font> said that the depreciation charge for the older assets should reflect their full book value, because this would reflect the cost of eventual replacement. Too generous, says Ms Spottiswoode. It is better to allow the company a lower depreciation charge now, reflecting what shareholders actually paid, and to present customers with the bill for replacing assets when they are needed--and their price will be better known.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ms Spottiswoode has certainly been harsh--but she has probably been fair, too. No one knows whether her cost estimates or the company's are nearer the mark. In the past, however, utilities have been remarkably good at meeting "impossible" targets. If Ms Spottiswoode's pricing formula proves after all to be a little too tight, it can be loosened in 2002. That is how Britain's regulatory regime is supposed to work.



</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br3.html">Next article</a>
