<html><head><title>The threat of salt</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Health</b></p>
<h1>The threat of salt</h1>


<p>FOR decades the tobacco industry sought to deny the link between smoking and lung cancer. The billions it spent in research to disprove this and the money it lavished on lobbying campaigns denying it were wasted. The money would have been better spent in seeking to reduce the dangers of the product. Processed-food manufacturers may now be in danger of travelling down a similar cul-de-sac in the face of growing evidence of the dangers to health of an excessively salty diet.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;New research published in the British Medical Journal (<font size=-1>BMJ</font>) on May 17th confirms that high levels of salt in western diets are a prime cause of strokes and heart disease among older people. "Intersalt", a study of 10,000 people in 52 countries, confirms the direct link between salt and high blood pressure. At present, salt consumption among adults in Britain averages 9 grammes a day, ten times the basic sodium requirement. The study points out that, because three-quarters of salt in western diets comes from processed food, a significant reduction in salt consumption is possible only if the food industry takes some salt out of its products.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A similar message was voiced just over a year ago by the Committee on the Medical Aspects of Food Policy, an official body advising the government on nutrition. However, after heavy lobbying from the processed-food industry, Kenneth Calman, the chief medical officer, disassociated the government from the committee's recommendation that salt consumption by adults should be cut by a third.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In an editorial, the <font size=-1>BMJ</font> criticises this as a failure of nerve and says that, if ministers are serious about reducing premature deaths from heart disease, they will have to learn to ignore vested interests. In an accompanying article, Graham MacGregor, professor of cardio-vascular medicine at St George's Hospital, accuses the government of having abdicated responsibility for the welfare of its citizens.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Action to reduce salt need not wait on government action. In the 1980s large baking companies were persuaded to cut salt in breads by 12.5%. Heinz and Brooke Bond have also made small reductions in their canned goods. But most processed-food manufacturers are unwilling to act. All 16 food-industry trade associations recently refused to conduct an audit of the salt content of their products requested by a nutrition task force set up by the government in 1994. Even without the imprimatur of government committees, an alliance of scientists and consumers could find such information for themselves, and force food firms to rethink their opposition to using less salt in their products.



<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,iss">Search</a>
