<html><head><title>Explosive</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>



<p><b>Forensic laboratories</b></p>
<h1>Explosive</h1>

<p>THE last thing the government needed as it attempts to get the Anglo-Irish peace process back on course was another set of miscarriage-of-justice cases, like those of the Birmingham Six and Judith Ward, which cast doubt on the reliability of forensic evidence and on British justice in general. But that is exactly what it now faces. On May 14th Michael Howard, the home secretary, said that equipment at a government forensic-science laboratory had been found to be contaminated with a component of Semtex explosive.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The contaminated machine is in a laboratory run by an offshoot of the defence ministry at Fort Halstead in Kent. This is the only place in mainland Britain where prosecutors send swabs from the bodies and clothing of suspected bombers to be tested for traces of explosives. Convictions in about 12 <font size=-1>IRA</font> bombing cases, going back as far as 1989, may be in doubt.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Human error was to blame for the failure to detect the contamination, and human error can never be ruled out. Yet this fiasco might have been less serious if ministers had acted on recommendations made in 1993 by the Royal Commission on Criminal Justice.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The commission noted improvements in controls at forensic-science laboratories since the uncovering of earlier mistakes, but said, "we nevertheless feel bound to question the absence of external scrutiny and assessment" of the laboratories. It also said that scientists working in them tended "to see themselves as part of the prosecution", and not as impartial seekers of truth. The commission said an advisory council should be set up to inspect the laboratories' quality controls and to impose a strict code of conduct on the scientists. Three years on, the government has yet to act.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even if an advisory council had been set up, the contaminated equipment might not have been spotted any sooner. But such a body could have recommended other changes, and these too might have lessened the blow to confidence in the justice system which this affair has brought about. For instance, the commission said that scientists hired by the defence should be able to witness any tests carried out after the arrest of the suspect, and be able to examine the notebooks and other records of those who carried them out. It said that defence lawyers should be able to have samples re-tested at a different laboratory, and that legal aid should be available to pay for this.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Russell Stockdale of Forensic Access, a forensic-science consultancy which mainly advises defence lawyers, says the Fort Halstead laboratory still restricts the access of scientists such as himself to check the results of its tests. Michael Mansfield, a prominent defence barrister, says that when he has asked the Legal Aid Board to pay for further tests, it objected because it saw no reason to doubt the findings of Fort Halstead. Because of the government's unwillingness to accept even the relatively modest proposals of the royal commission on these matters, defence lawyers have been prevented from questioning the findings of a secretive laboratory whose reliability is now in doubt.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Mansfield claims that the government has failed to take action because it does not see any votes in providing an independent, reliable forensic-science service, open equally to defence and prosecution lawyers alike. Whether or not this is so, there are certainly votes to be lost if, as is now possible, more convictions in high-profile terrorism cases are overturned, and the government can be accused of contributing to this by its complacency.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,iss">Search</a>
