<html><head><title>After the party</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<p><b>Softbank</b></p>
<h1>After the party</h1>

<font size=1>TOKYO</font><p><b>Is the success of this acquisitive Japanese firm based on software engineering or financial engineering?</b></p>


<p>JAPANESE investors might be forgiven for getting a little overexcited about Softbank. Its domestic businesses include Japan's biggest computer-software distributor and its leading publisher of <font size=-1>PC</font> magazines. It is the only company on the Tokyo stockmarket to have an Internet interest; and on May 15th it announced a joint venture with Dentsu, a giant ad agency, to develop Internet advertising. Masayoshi Son, its Berkeley-educated founder and president has an outgoing manner which is the antithesis of the dull Japanese <i>sarariman</i>. But is it really worth &#165;1 trillion ($9.5 billion)--160 times last year's earnings?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is no denying Softbank's momentum. Its net profits in the year to March 1996 rose by 210%, to &#165;6.3 billion, an even headier rise than in previous years (see <a href="wb1.gif">chart</a>). By contrast, Nintendo, a games maker that is also worth &#165;1 trillion, made net profits of &#165;56 billion. But then Nintendo is not headed by the "Bill Gates of Japan".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Son's corporate strategy is beguilingly simple: to control as much of the infrastructure of the <font size=-1>PC</font> market--from distribution to publications, information services and associated conferences--as he can. Initially, this vision seemed limited to Japan. Founded in 1981, Softbank concentrated on two domestic markets: publishing and computer-software distribution. Softbank now has 30% of the <font size=-1>PC</font>-magazine market in Japan and about 40% of Japan's software-distribution market.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, ever since its listing on Japan's over-the-counter stockmarket in 1994, the firm has been obsessed with foreign investments. In the past year alone it has spent $3 billion buying American high-tech companies. This year, says the Nomura Research Institute, &#165;18 billion of Softbank's estimated &#165;25 billion in pre-tax profits will come from overseas.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This portfolio includes investments in several American Internet-related companies. Its chief financial officer, Yoshitaka Kitao, is not sure how many, but it is talking to 57 Internet-related companies and is in "serious discussions" with 15 of these. Last month Softbank increased its stake in Yahoo!, which provides a directory for the Internet, from 5% to 37%. Last October, it bought a 12% stake in Nihon Cisco Systems, the Japanese subsidiary of the American firm that leads the booming market in networking equipment. It also has a 30% stake in Unitech, a Californian software supplier that is developing software to offer Internet services in China. And it owns a quarter of the Japanese subsidiary of Novell, the leader in networking software.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, these Internet-related firms are relative minnows compared with Softbank's biggest purchases: Comdex, a giant computer exhibition bought in April last year for $800m, and Ziff-Davis, a publisher of <font size=-1>PC</font> magazines, bought for $2.1 billion in February. Both prices were considered to be generous, yet Softbank's share price has bounded ahead with each purchase.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Softbank pays for its acquisitions with cash. Some of this has come from issuing &#165;69 billion of new shares last November, but a lot has been financed by debt: this has increased from &#165;51 billion to &#165;240 billion over the past year (although &#165;70 billion of this was in convertible bonds). Softbank's interest expenses jumped from &#165;377m in 1994-95 to &#165;3.4 billion in 1995-96. This year analysts expect interest charges of &#165;9 billion.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;How does Mr Son manage to do it? His success has a lot to do with the difference between American and Japanese stockmarket valuations. Even in its current slightly battered state, the market in Japan trades at more than twice the average American price-to-earnings ratio; Softbank trades at an even heftier premium. This allows Mr Son to buy an American firm at a generous premium over its American valuation, and still see his own firm's valuation climb by even more, simply because the American profits are now valued by Japanese standards. That, in turn, allows him to raise more cash from his bankers and the capital markets.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Another feature of Softbank's acquisition strategy is its aggressive accounting techniques. Each time Mr Son buys a company, almost all the value is in "goodwill" (the difference between the purchase price and the firm's net assets). Softbank depreciates this goodwill over 30 years, some six times the usual depreciation period for Japanese firms. This helps the company's earnings, because the acquisition costs are spread out over three decades, while the profits show up immediately. On the other hand, many of Softbank's American purchases are fickle, people businesses, where the "goodwill" could leave tomorrow.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the West similar acquisition machines have struggled to find the ever-bigger targets needed to sustain their high share prices. One recent example is Britain's Hanson, a conglomerate which is now breaking itself up. However, Hanson was also famous for two other things: buying cheaply and managing its assets extremely well.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If Mr Son has a grand strategy for extracting more value out of his ragbag of assets, it is hard to spot. The only "synergy" seems to be that they have something to do with computers. Indeed, Mr Son makes a point of not changing the management of Softbank's newly acquired overseas companies. The main use of its biggest acquisitions is to send cash home. Last year most of Comdex's net profits were paid to Softbank as dividends; without them, Softbank's pre-tax operating profits last year would have almost halved.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is little room for expansion in Softbank's existing businesses. Although Softbank is bringing Comdex to Japan and other parts of Asia, Comdex cannot get much larger in America: more than 200,000 people already attend its exhibitions in Las Vegas. As for Ziff-Davis, the market for computer magazines is already competitive and growing more so.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Expansion by acquiring overseas companies is usually considered risky, particularly for Japanese companies, which have a dismal record. The last companies to put their faith in creative Americans were Sony and Matsushita, which both bought studios in Hollywood. Softbank claims that it is better at picking winners and that it is buying into a growth industry. Perhaps. But Nintendo looks a safer bet.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="wb2.html">Next article</a>
</p>
