<html><head><title>Built on thin air</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>

<p><b>Wireless telephony</b></p>
<h1>Built on thin air</h1>
<p>ON MAY 14th Britain's first radio telephone--or "fixed wireless"--service was launched by Ionica, a small company in Cambridge. Around the world, telephone companies are transfixed. For if Ionica is a success, its technology could rip up the big telephone monopolies: fixed wireless is by far the cheapest way to build a competing network from scratch.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But is that single advantage enough to build a profitable business in a mature market like Britain? For Britons, fixed wireless offers no special technical advantage. Indeed, apart from a pizza-box-sized aerial on the roof, they should notice no difference at all compared with their normal wired service. Unlike its technological cousin, the mobile telephone, wireless goes nowhere. It offers a familiar handset attached to a cord. It is just a cheap way to connect a home to a telephone network.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is this economic advantage that gives Ionica, with a modest &#163;150m ($230m) in the bank, the courage to challenge Britain's mighty <font size=-1>BT</font>. The cable-television companies have to spend some &#163;600 for each home they pass, regardless of whether the householder wants the television or telephone services they offer. But Ionica claims that its fixed costs are only &#163;5-10 for each potential customer: the price of a base station divided by all the homes it could reach. The added cost of installing an aerial and electronics in a customer's home are incurred only when a customer is willing to pay.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ionica claims that, because its costs are lower, it can undercut <font size=-1>BT</font> and still make money. Its prices will be 15% below <font size=-1>BT</font>'s for most calls, although because of the initial costs of switching, most subscribers will not see much difference for the first year. It also has a new, all-digital network, so that it can offer a few fancy services (such as three numbers, each with distinctive rings, for each line) that <font size=-1>BT</font> cannot match. And, because it has a direct link to the home, it can provide national and international services more cheaply than other firms that must piggyback on <font size=-1>BT</font>'s lines, for a fee, for the final few miles.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But Ionica faces considerable disadvantages. It is fiendishly hard for any company to compete with a former monopoly in the "local loop" --the connections from individual homes to the main telephone networks. Local calls and line-rental rates are subsidised in Britain, as in most other countries, by long-distance calls. And <font size=-1>BT</font>, toughened by years of competition, is a leaner target than most of Europe's monopolies. Its rates are already among the world's lowest--and falling.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Cable companies, facing the same squeeze, have nevertheless been able to lure nearly 1.5m telephone subscribers away from <font size=-1>BT</font>. But they have two advantages over Ionica: television (only 20% of subscribers take the telephone service alone), and the promise of future multimedia services, such as high-speed Internet access. Ionica claims its network can be upgraded to offer multimedia, but that will increase its cost dramatically. Besides, it will never be able to carry as much data as the fibre-optic cable networks. And even the cable companies now complain that they will not be able to make money in a market where regulators keep tightening price controls.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ionica is aiming for 5% of the British market--about 1.4m homes--by the end of the decade, although it says it can break even with half as many. Its target is ambitious: it took the cable companies four years to reach that number.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ionica's is not the only trial of this sort: Telecom Finland launched a similar service in March. But Herschel Shosteck Associates, a telecoms consultancy in Wheaton, Maryland, notes that the economics of fixed wireless are much better in Finland, thanks to a chilling $900 connection fee for ordinary telephone lines.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the developed world, fixed wireless may always be a niche market. On the other hand, it is the ideal technology for the developing world, where there are few existing lines to compete with and little money to lay new ones. In poor countries the potential market for mobile and fixed wireless, says Herschel Shosteck, could reach more than 300m subscribers by the end of 2000. Whether Ionica succeeds or not in Britain is almost beside the point; the real game is elsewhere.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?832374000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="fn1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
