<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width=271 height=24  alt="Politics"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<h2>Spain slims</h2>
<p>Jose Maria Aznar became <b>Spain's first conservative prime minister</b> since the Franco era. He promised to cut unemployment and prepare Spain for European economic and monetary union in 1999. His new government plans to cut Pta250 billion ($2 billion) from spending this year.
<p>The European Commission inched towards lifting the world-wide ban on the export of <b>British beef</b>, imposed because of "mad-cow" disease. It said it would recommend allowing the export of gelatin, tallow and semen derived from British cattle. But Germany and other governments may not agree.</p>
<p>Russia said it would expel nine British diplomats on charges of <b>spying</b>. Britain countered that the charges were unproved and hinted that it might deport some Russians. The two countries may yet reach a negotiated solution. Russia's threat was seen by some as an attempt by President Yeltsin to improve his re-election prospects; a new poll shows him far behind his Communist rival, Gennady Zyuganov.</p>
<p>Proceedings against <b>alleged war criminals</b> from former Yugoslavia opened in The Hague with the trial of Dusan Tadic, a Bosnian Serb caf&eacute; owner. It is the first international war-crimes trial since the end of the second world war.</p>
<p>European diplomats rebuked Hans van den Broek, external affairs commissioner of the European Union, for suggesting that the <font size=-1>EU</font> could take over <b>peacekeeping in Bosnia</b> when the current peacekeeping mission ends in December. America, they fear, would be happy to leave the job solely to the Europeans.</p>
<p>The citizens of the eastern German state of Brandenburg rejected a <b>merger with Berlin</b> in a referendum.</p>
<p>Umberto Bossi, leader of the Northern League, called for a formal <b>secession of northern Italy</b> from the rest of the country. He wants to call the new country Padania.</p>
<p>Slovakia's president, Michal Kovac, postponed passage of a controversial <b>subversion law</b>. It would have allowed prison sentences for activities like organising anti-government rallies and spreading "false information" abroad.</p>
<h2>Into opposition</h2>
<p><b>South Africa</b>'s white-led National Party pulled out of the government of national unity the day after agreement was reached on a new constitution for the country, ending the transitional agreement of the past two years. F.W. de Klerk, the party leader, said the birth of a new nation now demands a strong multi-party system. The markets shook. Meanwhile, local voting in troubled KwaZulu-Natal was postponed.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p>New rules were agreed by 57 countries at a United Nations meeting in Geneva to restrict the sale and use of anti-personnel <b>landmines</b>. Non-detectable mines are to be banned, though not for at least nine years, and the rules on mine use will apply to internal conflicts, not just inter-state ones. Disgusted anti-mine campaigners have vowed to fight on for a complete ban.</p>
<p>The evidence suggests, said a <font size=-1>UN</font> report presented to the Security Council, that Israel's shelling of the <font size=-1>UN</font> compound at <b>Qana</b>, which killed 100 Lebanese civilians, was probably not accidental. Israel, supported by America, angrily rejected the report.</p>
<p>Demonstrations by the <b>Bahraini</b> <b>opposition </b>grew more violent after a protester was killed by security men.</p>
<h2>Fiscal spanner</h2>
<p>Democrats in Congress blocked Republican attempts to repeal the <b>petrol tax</b> of 4.3 cents a gallon, insisting it should be coupled with a rise in the minimum wage from $4.25 to $5.15 an hour. Both measures are politically popular but threaten to wreak havoc on attempts to reduce the federal budget deficit.</p>
<p>President Clinton widened his lead over the Republican presidential nominee, <b>Bob Dole</b>, to 25 percentage points in the latest Harris poll. The poll also predicted that Ross Perot, if he ran, would take 16% of the vote.</p>
<p><b>Colombia</b>'s army and air force struck at its ever-bolder and bloodier guerrillas.</p>
<p>Pressure mounted against <b>Argentina</b>'s defence minister, over revelations that</p>
<p>Argentine weapons were sold to Croatia (while under <font size=-1>UN</font> embargo) and to Ecuador during last year's fighting with Peru (a quarrel in which, by treaty, Argentina has to remain neutral).</p>
<h2>Indian limbo</h2>
<p>A weak coalition seemed the likeliest outcome of the <b>Indian general election</b>, based on early results. The Congress party of Narasimha Rao seemed likely to lose half its seats, with the Hindu-nationalist <font size=-1>BJP</font> becoming the single largest party in Parliament. But no single party was in a position to form a government on its own.</p>
<p>A new confrontation between China and America loomed, this time over <b>intellectual property</b>. The White House threatened to impose trade sanctions unless China improved its compliance with previous agreements by May 15th. China made a show of closing several pirate compact-disc factories.</p>
<p>Fires have devastated the <b>Mongolian </b>province of Arhangay, killing at least 17 people and making more than 1,000 homeless.</p>
<p>An <b>Indonesian </b>member of parliament, Sri Bintang Pamungkas, was sentenced to 34 months in jail by a Jakarta court for allegedly calling President Suharto a dictator in a speech in Germany.</p>
<p>The Philippines' president, <b>Fidel Ramos</b>, promised new taxes, and a better collection system, expected to bring in an extra $500m a year.</p>
<p>
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
