<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width=273 height=24  alt="Business"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<h2>Getting airborne</h2>
<p><b>General Electric</b> and <b>Pratt &amp; Whitney</b> are setting up a joint venture to build an engine for the next century's "super-jumbo" airliners from Boeing. Collaboration between the two American firms could damage Rolls-Royce, Britain's engine manufacturer.</p>
<p>With less than a year to full competition in Western Europe's skyways, some airlines are still struggling. The near-trebling of pre-tax profits in the first quarter by <b>Scandinavian Airlines System</b> failed to impress investors. They chiefly noticed that operating profits slumped by 67%, that costs rose and that gains from last year's alliance with Lufthansa have not yet shown up.</p>
<p>Two frail airlines unveiled recovery plans. Italy's <b>Alitalia</b> plans to reduce the number of employees by 11% and inject 3 trillion lire ($1.9 billion), while making its pilots fly more. Belgium's <b>Sabena</b>, pressed by its 49.5% owner, Swissair, is offering employees a choice: a payroll cut of 18%, a pay cut of 15% or changes in working practices.</p>
<h2>Team spirit</h2>
<p>Talks between <b>Lucas Industries</b>, a British automotive and aerospace group, and <b>Varity </b>of America, a maker of car components and diesel engines, that could lead to a merger or strategic alliance of their braking operations lifted their share prices. Talk of a takeover bid by Varity was scotched.</p>
<p><b>Turner Broadcasting</b> put a brave face on reports that the Federal Trade Commission was ready to block its proposed $7.5 billion merger with <b>Time Warner </b>on the grounds that the combination of the two cable-television giants would hurt competition.</p>
<p>Adia of Switzerland and Ecco of France are to merge, creating a <b>temp agency</b> with revenues of SFr7.7 billion ($6.2 billion)--just a whisker below America's Manpower, which remains the world's biggest employment firm.</p>
<p><b>Saint-Gobain</b>, a glass-to-building materials group, is back in expansionary mode with the FFr15.5 billion ($3 billion) purchase of 56.6% of Poliet from asset-shedding Paribas in one of the biggest buys in France in recent years.</p>
<p>More twists and turns in Britain's electricity saga. A distributor, <b>Midlands Electricity</b>, accepted a &#163;1.73 billion ($2.6 billion) bid from New Jersey's General Public Utilities and Ohio's Cinergy. But the British government now says it will use its golden share in National Power, a generator, to block a bid from Southern Company of America.</p>
<h2>Doldrums</h2>
<p><b>Eurotunnel</b> haggled with its 225 creditor banks over the refinancing of its massive &#163;8.4 billion ($12.7 billion) debt. One option is a debt-for-equity swap, giving the banks 49% ownership of the Channel tunnel operator in exchange for &#163;3.5 billion in debt. Shareholders would prefer banks to write off 30% of the debt and issue a FFr28 billion ($5.5 billion) bond, convertible into shares.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p>Despite 8% growth in its British newspapers, <b>News Corp </b>reported net profits 3% lower in the three months to March, pushed down by its television operations in America and Asia. That, together with a one-off charge of A$204m ($163m) associated with the sale of its HarperCollins educational-books unit, left net profits at A$77m, from $251m a year earlier.</p>
<p>(See <a href="wtw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>For the first time in its 22 years on the stock exchange, pre-tax annual profits at <b>J. Sainsbury</b> fell. This British supermarket giant is now second to Tesco in market share. Profits slipped to &#163;764m ($1.2 billion) in 1995 from &#163;808m a year earlier.</p>
<h2>A ray of light</h2>
<p>Shares in <b>Sun Alliance </b>and<b> Royal Insurance </b>soared after they unveiled plans for a &#163;6 billion ($9 billion) merger to form the largest composite insurance company in Britain, the first such merger in more than a decade.</p>
<p>Japan's prime minister, Ryutaro Hashimoto, called on Japanese banks to pay more towards liquidating <b>bankrupt mortgage firms</b>. The government's plan to use money to pay for the liquidation has met bitter political opposition.</p>
<p>The former chief executive of <b>Barings</b>, a British merchant bank, was barred by the Securities and Futures Authority from any management post in British financial-service firms for at least three years. Peter Norris accepts that he shares responsibility for the collapse of the bank last year after a rogue trader, Nick Leeson, ran up &#163;860m ($1.4 billion) in dealing losses.</p>
<p>Just as <b>Lloyd's of London </b>is trying to persuade its members ("names") to back a &#163;3.2 billion ($4.8 billion) plan to settle the twin problems of its losses and names' debts, the Securities and Exchange Commission may have opened the door to more litigation in America. It asked a Californian appeal court to overturn a lower court ruling that names could not sue Lloyd's in American courts.</p>
<h2>Smoke and mirrors</h2>

<p>It is the bank that can do no right. A fire destroyed the elegant 19th century Paris headquarters of<b> Cr&eacute;dit Lyonnais, </b>France's sickly state-owned bank. The cost of the fire could run to more than FFr1 billion ($195m), said Jean Peyrelevade, the chairman, adding that "the bank might be affected, but certainly not its clients." </p>
<p><p>Belgium issued an international arrest warrant for <b>Serge Dassault</b>, chairman of France's Dassault Aviation, in connection with a contract to modernise Belgian fighter planes. Last October a Belgian prosecutor alleged that Dassault had paid BFr90m ($2.9m) in bribes to the country's socialist party.</p>
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
