<html><head><title>The e-mail of the species</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=right><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>


<h1><left>The e-mail of the species</center></h1>
<p><b>Some people just don't know when to shut up</b></p>

IT IS a characteristic of nets and webs that they catch things, so perhaps those who venture on to the Internet and its multimedia offshoot, the World Wide Web, should not complain when they find themselves ensnared. Still, a good grumble sometimes works wonders. This one is about the difficulty of extricating oneself from Internet entanglements, and specifically about bringing e-mail exchanges to an end.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Once upon a time, not all that long ago, readers who wanted to make a comment about something they had read in <i>The Economist</i> had to pick up a pen and paper and compose a letter, which they wrote in longhand. Even when the typewriter came along, the paper still had to be inserted, first in the machine, then in the envelope, ultimately in the letter-box. It was a fairly time-consuming business, and it had a tax on it in the shape of a stamp--all of which served to concentrate the minds of would-be letter-writers to make them stop and think whether they really had something to say that was worth saying. Often they had, and if so might expect to receive a polite reply. Sometimes that reply was enough to satisfy the reader, occasionally it was not, but only rarely did the correspondence drag tediously on.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nowadays many people make their comments by e-mail. Some who are not regular readers have articles drawn to their attention by other e-mail users who urge fellow-members of an interest-group to zap us a message. Usually these orchestrated messages are the standard stuff of generalised protest: written without much forethought, and aimed at the media in general. Sometimes they are intemperate: users of e-mail say it has only a "narrow emotional bandwidth", meaning they find it difficult to express inflexions of the voice by the mere use of words on a screen, so all their criticisms tend to come across as rude. (Never mind that the bandwidth of the typewriter never stopped letter-writers making their points politely, nor did that of the quill pen inhibit Shakespeare and company from putting quite complicated thoughts and emotions into words.) Still, whatever the inadequacies of the e-mailer, it seems discourteous to ignore him. Yet a polite, reasoned reply seldom puts a stop to the exchange. Sitting at a keyboard, it is so easy to send a reply to a reply, and for just the price of a local telephone call, or less.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Just as it is an art to say no without giving offence, so it is an art to bring a correspondence to a polite stop. Edmund Burke declared in the 18th century that the age of chivalry was dead, and that of sophisters and economists had come instead. Yet <i>The Economist</i> would like to believe that it is still possible to end an electronic exchange in a civil, if not necessarily chivalrous, manner. What is needed is a formula of the kind used by Mr Bennet in "Pride and Prejudice" when he told his daughter, "You have delighted us long enough." 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;An alternative would be to discourage the correspondence at the outset. The beauty of e-mail is the ease and cheapness with which it can be used, but could it not be made selectively more difficult or expensive? Making it electronically more difficult would almost certainly discriminate against the old and in favour of the young, thus falling foul of the laws of fair play. But would it be possible to levy a tax--call it a stamp, if you will--on silly or tiresome e-mails? Or, still more tempting, to send an electric shock interactively to senders of the more offensive messages? Answers on a postcard, please.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?831769200,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="sf1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
