<DOCNO>WT21-B39-153</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA026-000276-B032-29</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.economist.com:80/issue/11-05-96/sf1.html 199.173.162.110 19970113165841 text/html 17112
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 16:54:42 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 08-Aug-96 14:03:58 GMT
Content-length: 16926
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Stop smoking!</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="sf.gif"  alt="Special">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>Stop smoking!</h1>
<p><b>Legal challenges to American tobacco companies are raising two big questions: how much damage might product-liability suits do to the tobacco firms? And might cigarettes be classified as a drug?</b></p>

<p>SMOKING is one of the most ubiquitous activities of mankind. And, to its opponents, one of the more iniquitous. Around the world, people smoke 15 billion cigarettes every day; in America alone, they smoke over one billion a day (see <a href="sf1.gif">chart</a>). America's largest cigarette producer, Philip Morris, earns over $30 billion a year from selling tobacco. The tobacco business is one of the country's most profitable industries.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is the Goliath that the Davids with briefcases are challenging in America's courts. The scale of the battle is huge, as will be the size of the awards and the significance of the outcome if the tobacco firms lose. But before that happens, the plaintiffs have decades of failed lawsuits to reverse.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Americans have been suing tobacco firms without success since the early 1950s, when epidemiological studies by Richard Doll and Ernst Wynder first demonstrated a link between smoking and lung cancer. The law suits have come in three waves.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The first were product-liability cases brought by individuals in the 1950s and 1960s. The firms fought them by nagging at the causal link between the plaintiff's history of smoking and his or her illness: the link was hard to prove. The firms also argued that plaintiffs freely chose to smoke and therefore assumed any risk themselves. The strategy worked: the firms won.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At the same time, the industry set about trying to shake public confidence in the epidemiological studies, again by playing on the absence of a clear causal link. This campaign did not work: popular awareness that smoking is bad for you grew--especially after 1966, when America's surgeon general insisted that all cigarette packets bear a health warning. Ironically, however, while that helped turn public feelings against the tobacco firms, it strengthened their legal argument that smokers did know about the dangers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The second wave of litigation began after 1984, when lawyers won an individual lawsuit against three tobacco companies, Philip Morris, Lorillard and Liggett, on behalf of Rose Cipollone, who had died earlier that year. A federal court ruled that the companies were liable for the lung cancer which had killed her. The verdict, however, was overturned on appeal in 1988 and Mrs Cipollone's lawyers gave up the case four years later when the cost of the battle became overwhelming. A wrongful-death suit filed immediately after the initial <i>Ci</i><i>pol</i><i>lone </i>victory is still going through the courts in New Jersey, but most anti-tobacco campaigners see little mileage left in pursuing suits on behalf of individuals.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The third wave of litigation has gathered force in the past three years, thanks to several new tactics designed to get around the difficulty of proving individual causation. This wave has three elements:
<p><font size=-1><li></font>
Reasoning that illness caused by smoking increased the charges to Medicaid, America's health system for the poor, Michael Moore, the attorney general of Mississippi, argued that the state was a victim of wrongdoing by the industry and sued the main tobacco companies to recover its extra costs. Seven more states (Florida, Louisiana, Massachusetts, Minnesota, Texas, West Virginia and, on May 1st, Maryland) have followed suit. Florida passed laws in May 1994 intended to allow statistical evidence to be used in court and to force the industry away from assumption-of-risk arguments. The state government has just maintained these laws in the face of lobbying to have them struck down by tobacco firms and other businesses worried that the provisions might one day affect them.
<p><font size=-1><li></font>
The second recent innovation drew inspiration--and several lawyers--from the attempts of asbestosis sufferers in the 1980s to win compensation from big producers of the mineral. These took the form of class-action suits, in which thousands of individual claims are bundled together in a single trial. The size of the potential payout meant that high-powered lawyers, whose fees would normally have been beyond the means of most individual plaintiffs, were ready to take on the cases. One of the largest such class-action suits, <i>Castano v American Tobacco Company</i>, was filed in New Orleans in March 1994 on behalf of all smokers in America addicted to nicotine, plus their heirs and relations (Mr Castano is simply a representative). The legal guns are correspondingly big-bore: 65 firms are involved and each has pledged to spend at least $100,000-worth of time a year on the case. A judge certified the class as legally valid in February 1995, but the defendants at once appealed. A ruling is likely in July.
<p><font size=-1><li></font>
The <i>Castano</i> suit involves one further tactical refinement. Rather than concentrate directly on the harm tobacco does to health, the case focuses on the addictiveness of nicotine and the tobacco industry's alleged mendacity about it. The significance of the addiction argument is that it undercuts the "free-choice" defence of the tobacco companies. The plaintiffs' lawyers argue that, after an initial free decision to try cigarettes--often taken well before adulthood--many smokers are no longer making an unimpeded choice but are instead compelled to go on buying cigarettes to feed their habit. (For an explanation of how the addition works, see <a href="sf2.html">page</a>.)
</p><p><b>Tar wars</b>
<br>Whether the plaintiffs win their case is, obviously, a matter for the courts. But there are several reasons for thinking that, this time, the tobacco firms have a much tougher fight on their hands than ever before--not only in the courts but outside, too.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The first reason is that one company has already bowed to some of the plaintiffs' demands. On March 13th Liggett, the smallest of the big American cigarette companies and a producer of Chesterfield cigarettes (see <a href="sf2.gif">chart</a>) and unbranded "generics", shocked everyone by announcing that it had reached a settlement with the <i>Castano</i> plaintiffs. Two days later it announced a similar settlement in five of the state Medicaid suits. Under the deals, the <i>Castano</i> class would receive up to 5% of Liggett's income for 25 years, and the states a percentage which would depend on the final number that joined the agreement, as well as a lump sum of $5m spread over ten years. Liggett also agreed to abide by restrictions on advertising said to appeal to children.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Liggett case has several special features which means that the deal may not necessarily set a precedent for others. The company settled partly for particular reasons of corporate strategy. Bennett LeBow, the chairman of Liggett's parent company, wanted his firm to merge with the tobacco interests of <font size=-1>RJR</font> Nabisco, America's second largest tobacco firm. He hoped Liggett's settlement would facilitate a merger since the deal included a provision that its terms would extend to any cigarette company Liggett might merge with. In the event, Mr LeBow's bid failed--his slate of directors were not elected to the <font size=-1>RJR</font> board. Moreover, Liggett has not conceded an important principle at stake: in accepting the advertising restrictions, it did not accept that children have become hooked on cigarettes as a result of the publicity. The company has been dropped from the cases but has retained the right to hop back aboard should the remaining tobacco companies eventually prevail. In other words, if the worse comes to the worst, Liggett has capped its liabilities but, if the other firms win, Liggett does not have to pay anything: a one-way bet. For all these reasons, the plaintiffs may find it hard to say that, because Liggett settled, other firms must too. Nevertheless, the settlement is important because it is the first occasion on which a tobacco company has ever ended a lawsuit in anything other than victory.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The second reason for thinking that this time may be different is that a number of recent disclosures, based on internal scientific work by the tobacco firms, have reached the public domain and, say anti-smoking campaigners, cast new light on what the tobacco firms knew and did not know about addiction.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On May 12th 1994, a crate of 4,000 pages of memoranda, letters and reports from Brown &amp; Williamson and British American Tobacco (<font size=-1>B</font>.<font size=-1>A</font>.<font size=-1>T</font>), its international parent, arrived in the office of Stanton Glantz, a cardiologist at the University of California, San Francisco. The documents reflect internal debates about disease, addiction and research into making cigarettes safer. They include a statement, made in 1963 by Addison Yeaman, general counsel of Brown &amp; Williamson, that "Nicotine is addictive. We are, then, in the business of selling nicotine, an addictive drug." Anti-smoking campaigners claim that this calls into question evidence given to Congress by the bosses of the main American tobacco companies: in 1994, they stood before a congressional investigatory committee and testified on oath that they did not believe nicotine to be addictive.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The companies are sticking to their testimony and say that it was given according to their best authority. Meanwhile, the debate has entered the public domain. Though Brown &amp; Williamson won a restraining order preventing the man who leaked the documents, Merrell Williams (a former temporary employee), from discussing them with anyone, Dr Glantz and his colleagues at the university library made the entire set available on the World Wide Web (they are to be found at <a href="http://www.library.ucsf.edu/tobacco">http://www.library.ucsf.edu/tobacco</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The legal significance of these (and other) leaked documents remains in question. The tobacco firms say the documents were taken illegally and will not comment on their contents. Anti-smoking campaigners say that the documents suggest the firms have long understood nicotine pharmacology and have experimented with how to control the level of nicotine in a cigarette. Until that dispute is resolved, the most that can be said for sure is that the allegations have increased public suspicion of the tobacco firms.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But that itself is significant because it has added to the third reason for thinking the lawyers might have the tobacco firms on the run: companies are coming under increased legislative pressure as a result of successful lobbying to restrict smoking in public. This is something that should not weigh with the courts, but might.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Several cities, including New York, have already banned smoking in public places, such as sports stadiums. Some towns in New Jersey have banned smoking on public beaches. Two Californian towns, Davis and Palo Alto, have banned smoking near public buildings--a response to the crowds of smokers gathered round entrances after being driven from their offices by no-smoking policies. And in one town in Florida (Fort Pierce), the local housing authority has required new tenants to sign an agreement not to smoke in their apartments. This is the first time people have been banned from smoking at home by a public body.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The growing power of the anti-smoking lobby might not only influence juries but could also increase the possibility that the federal government might step in to regulate the tobacco business. This possibility came closer as a result of testimony before Congress in March 1994 from David Kessler, the commissioner of the Food and Drug Administration (<font size=-1>FDA</font>).
</p><p><b>Are cigarettes a drug?</b></b>
<br>The act which set up the <font size=-1>FDA</font> gave it jurisdiction over consumer products "intended to affect the structure or any function of the body" . The agency argues that the effects of nicotine on the nervous system qualify it as a drug under this definition.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The tobacco industries have hit the ceiling. In August 1995 the <font size=-1>FDA</font> proposed a set of rules for regulating the sale of tobacco, along with a detailed analysis of its claim to jurisdiction over nicotine. It then waited for responses. Over 710,000 flooded in, more letters than the agency has received on any other business. The industry wrote to dispute the <font size=-1>FDA</font>'s claim to jurisdiction, arguing over the definition of addiction (Philip Morris has taken its argument to the Internet, with 300 pages at <a href="http://pmusainfo.webbed.com">http://pmusainfo.webbed.com</a>). Eleven tobacco companies and 20 other groups, including advertisers, shop-owners and distributors have filed four further lawsuits challenging the <font size=-1>FDA</font>'s proposals.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If granted jurisdiction, the agency would in theory be able to ban tobacco outright, or to demand maximum levels of tar or nicotine in cigarettes. In practice, the agency has wide discretion and the sense to see that prohibiting 50m Americans from smoking could be a disaster--not least for health (because people would then smoke illegally-made and possibly more dangerous cigarettes and because the prospect of 50m bad-tempered Americans all trying to give up at once hardly bears thinking about). Instead, the agency will try to reduce the number of future smokers by concentrating on under-age smoking today.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nine-tenths of all smokers start before they are 18, so the <font size=-1>FDA</font> has made it its goal to reduce by half, within seven years of gaining jurisdiction, the 3,000 Americans under 18 who start the habit every day. It wants to restrict the use of colour and pictures in advertisements likely to be seen by young people and to ban the production of branded freebies such as hats and tee-shirts. It would also make 18 a national minimum age to buy tobacco (at the moment this age limit is imposed by each state separately).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Getting the power to enforce its proposals depends on Mr Kessler, the <font size=-1>FDA</font>'s commissioner, persuading the president to enact them. Mr Clinton is more sympathetic than any previous president: his White House was quickly declared a no-smoking zone. But the proposal has got tangled up with the presidential election. A Republican victory would undoubtedly scupper the <font size=-1>FDA</font>'s efforts. Victory by the incumbent would help its cause, though the agency would still face opposition from some congressmen working on legislation to prevent the <font size=-1>FDA</font> from winning its battle.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In short, the fight against the multi-billion dollar tobacco business is getting fiercer both in government and the courts. An enormous amount is at stake. In the past, some businesses have been driven into bankruptcy by product-liability suits--notably asbestos firms in the 1970s and 1980s and, more recently, producers of silicon breast-implants (plus their insurers). The tobacco firms seem in a better position to ride out the storm than the firms involved in those cases. The lawsuits are not yet won in the courts; the <font size=-1>FDA</font>'s attempt to classify cigarettes as a drug is facing a lot of legislative opposition. What is clear is that they are under attack as never before. The next few months will determine in what shape they will survive.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?831769200,iss">Search</a>
