<html><head><title>A is for appal</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Education</b></p>
<h1>A is for appal</h1>

<p>GILLIAN SHEPHARD, the education and employment secretary, and Chris Woodhead, chief inspector of schools in England, have added universities' education faculties to their list of those to blame for low academic standards. Poor teaching, in part due to poor training of teachers, was the main reason for the alarming findings of a new study of children's reading abilities in 45 inner-London primary schools, published on May 7th. Responding to the study, Mrs Shephard announced extra powers for inspectors to set reading tests in schools, and to question local councils on what they are doing to improve their schools. But teacher training also faces a drastic shake-up: there will be a league table of training institutions, and the worst performers may be closed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Inspectors found that an astonishing 80% of seven-year-olds in the 45 schools were behind with their reading. They also found, which is no less astonishing, that many of the teachers had no idea how to teach pupils to read. In particular, pupils were not being taught phonics (the sounds made by each letter of the alphabet) properly. Mrs Shephard and Mr Woodhead accepted the claims of some of these teachers that their initial training courses did not teach them how to teach phonics, and that they had been given little further training since the start of their careers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Until recently, inspections of teacher-training institutions were rare, and inspectors' reports were kept under wraps. Now, all institutions are being inspected. The reports are being published along with a league table based on inspectors' gradings. Those teacher-training courses at the bottom of the table may be closed down. On May 3rd, a damning report on Charlotte Mason College (part of Lancaster University) was published which concluded that "a high proportion of students were not competent in teaching reading".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Anthea Millett, chief executive of the Teacher Training Agency, the government's regulatory body, says she expects the reports will show a wide variation in how well universities equip their students to teach reading and other key subjects. As well as being used to compile league tables, evidence from the inspectors' reports may be used to justify the agency imposing more detailed specifications on what trainee teachers are taught.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So future primary-school teachers are likely to arrive in their first job with a much better grasp of how to teach pupils to read. But Jim Campbell, professor of education at Warwick University (which has just received a more flattering report on its teacher-training courses), points out that the majority of primary-school teachers are in their 40s, and so were trained at a time when relatively little attention was paid to the teaching of reading.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These teachers, with perhaps 20 years' experience, are often reluctant to go on retraining courses. At the moment these are voluntary. Giving head teachers the right to insist that teachers attend retraining would provoke a furious reaction. And since there are more than 200,000 primary-school teachers, sending even a fraction of them on courses would be hugely expensive (the current cost of in-service training for teachers is already around &#163;400m). Not only are head teachers reluctant to upset their staff by sending them on courses, there is currently no effective mechanism for finding out whether those sent for retraining are actually better teachers when they return to the classroom.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So the government faces an unenviable choice in its vital drive to stamp out illiteracy. Either wait years for older teachers to retire and be replaced by a new generation of better-trained ones. Or spend a fortune and risk a rumpus by insisting that large numbers of primary teachers go back to school and learn things they should have known all along.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?831769200,iss">Search</a>
