<html><head><title>Riches through the looking-glass</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>Riches through the looking-glass</h1>

THE stockmarket launch of Chiroscience in 1994 was a flop. Analysts doubted whether it was a serious competitor in a crowded part of the biotechnology business. But in the past week its market valuation has surged to &#163;400m, four times its value at flotation--even though on May 7th it said it had raised &#163;40m from its shareholders to keep it going. The firm seems to have dispelled investors' doubts by showing that, with its links to a worldwide network of university laboratories, it can come up with a string of potentially money-spinning drugs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Chiroscience specialises in chiral compounds--molecules that exist in two forms, each the mirror-image of the other. The two forms often have different effects: one may be a useful drug, the other may have nasty side-effects. Attempts to make such compounds usually produce a mixture of both forms. Chiroscience and other firms have been trawling a list of drugs which are a mixture of both chiral forms, and which had been rejected because of side-effects or were coming to the ends of their patents. Their aim is to discover whether either chiral form on its own makes a better drug, and then to work out how to make this good version without its malevolent mirror-image.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Chiroscience's closest rivals are Sepracor and Celgene, two American firms with their own methods for making chiral compounds. But Erling Refsum, an analyst at Yamaichi Securities in London, says that they have got bogged down in their hunt through the drug industry's back catalogue. Meanwhile Chiroscience has persuaded most of the world's top ten drug companies that its manufacturing technology is best, and has sold them licences to use these methods for their own chiral chemistry projects. And it has been working on some newly discovered chiral compounds called matrix metalloproteinase inhibitors (<font size=-1>MMPI</font>s). Its first <font size=-1>MMPI</font>, a possible arthritis treatment, has just begun clinical trials; preliminary tests on another one suggest it could be an effective cancer treatment.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Treating the world's ageing population for arthritis could be a huge money-spinner. Doctors can currently offer sufferers little more than pain relievers. Mr Refsum reckons that if <font size=-1>MMPI</font>s turn out to be good at treating the underlying causes of arthritis, the global market for them could be $25 billion a year. The market for cancer treatments based on <font size=-1>MMPI</font>s is also vast. Even if some of the other firms working on <font size=-1>MMPI</font>s also succeed, Mr Refsum says there is room for many of them to make vast profits.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Chiroscience's future suddenly looks brighter. But biotechnology is a fast-moving business, and is littered with firms which soared and then crashed. If the firm loses its touch at tapping academic specialists, or rival firms prove better at the same game, the stockmarket's doubts could quickly return.


</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?831769200,iss">Search</a>
