<html><head><title>Digital decade</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Broadcasting</b></p>
<h1>Digital decade</h1>

<p>WHEN John Birt, the <font size=-1>BBC</font>'s director general, set out his vision for the next decade on May 9th, the future came across in ones and zeros. For multi-channel digital television is going to replace the meagre choice of four analogue channels now on offer in four out of five British homes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Plenty of channels creates plenty of opportunity, but mainly for pay-television. Subscriptions are the fastest-growing source of new television revenues and the lion's share goes to <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font>, 40% owned by Rupert Murdoch's News International. <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font>'s revenues and profits are already rising rapidly and its market capitalisation makes it Britain's second-largest media group. The firm is using its river of cash to buy sports rights and to invest in a digital service which it plans to launch next year. It hopes to dominate the market: the satellite it plans to use will be in a different orbit from Europe's other television satellites, creating a deterrent to potential rivals.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>BBC</font> will get a chance to launch its own digital services if, as the government plans, it is offered space in the spectrum for digital terrestrial broadcasting. Those services will include wide-screen television and 24-hour news. But some are likely to be sold to viewers, which will lead to charges of cross-subsidy. The <font size=-1>BBC</font> can rebut those charges, but it faces a bigger quandary. Will <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font> build a proprietary system into the set-top box its viewers will buy, forcing them to acquire a second box if they want to receive the <font size=-1>BBC</font>'s digital channels?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Given the modest size of the British market, even <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font> would probably like some way to share the cost of the set-top box with others. One radical solution, canvassed by the Labour Party, is to sell in advance the spectrum that would subsequently be freed by switching off analogue transmission, and use the cash to buy people digital sets. Alternatively, <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font> may be persuaded to team up with the <font size=-1>BBC</font> to launch a common digital system. That would coax the <font size=-1>BBC</font>'s up-market viewers to taste the delights of pay television. It would leave <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font> with more money to spend on buying sports and film rights. And it might convince the Office of Fair Trading, now investigating <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font>, that the company was not out to thwart competition.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But is it in the <font size=-1>BBC</font>'s interest to encourage people to view so many channels? In homes with satellite or cable services, its viewing share is only 30%, compared with almost 46% for the whole country. In fact, the <font size=-1>BBC</font> has little choice: if it does not create upmarket digital subscription services, <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font> will do so--just as Classic <font size=-1>FM</font>, a commercial station devoted to classical music, has pinched many <font size=-1>BBC</font> music lovers.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?831769200,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br4.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
