<html><head><title>Martyred marketeers</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>Martyred marketeers</h1>

<p>THE Football Association's commercial director resigned on May 8th during an investigation into illegal ticket sales; the police rounded up ticket touts in the run-up to the Cup Final on May 11th and the Euro 96 football championship next month. Television news bulletins obediently showed pixellated faces being dragged into vans to prove the police's determination to purge society of these vermin.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Britain's hostility to those who sell on the open market tickets that are in theory available only through official channels seems odd. In almost all of the economy it is illegal for a cartel to rig the market, and the government spends much time and effort trying to prevent this happening. In the sports-ticket business, however, the market-riggers have the state's protection, and it is illegal to try to bust the cartel. Indeed, the law against the free-marketeers has been tightened: the police used to rely on bye-laws, but they now have the Criminal Justice Act behind them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It seems even odder that, when the Football Association (<font size=-1>FA</font>) and the clubs know about the excess demand for their tickets, they do not charge more to retain the excess profit that currently goes to the touts. But that is not, as it were, football. Running a football club may be big business, but the fans also think they have a right to affordable tickets. Most fans reckon ticket prices are already too high, and would rather rely on clubs to ration them than pay higher prices. And nobody wants to make football fans angry. As for ticket touts, according to Steve Double of the <font size=-1>FA</font>, they are not generally seen as beneficent agents of the invisible hand. "We get hammered for letting them live."


</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?831769200,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br5.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT21-B39-158</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA026-000276-B032-174</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.economist.com:80/issue/11-05-96/br5.html 199.173.162.110 19970113170108 text/html 6512
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
