</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Short of a miracle</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Local elections</b></p>
<h1>Short of a miracle</h1>

<p>THE Tories were routed, so John Major stays leader. Thus runs the paradoxical story of May 2nd's local elections, confirmed by the most detailed examination of the results yet, conducted on the basis of <i>The Economist</i>'s regular ward-by-ward local-election survey carried out by John Curtice of Strathclyde University.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Tories lost over half--581 out of 1,092--of the seats they were defending. Projected into a nationwide general-election vote, their performance was worth just 27%, 16 points behind Labour and only one point ahead of the Liberal Democrats. By any standards, it was a bad result.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But it was also a recovery. The Conservative vote, in line with the opinion polls, was two points up on last year. And the losses were certainly no worse than expected. This was enough to quell speculation about the Tory leadership.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Tory spokesmen did their best to talk up their performance. They argued that the party had lost fewer seats than in either 1986 or 1991, also 12 months before a general election which they went on to win. They could have used much better arguments. Labour invited voters to use the elections to hit the Tories "where it hurts" . They do not seem to have done so. The results suggest that voters are no longer angry with the government, simply disillusioned.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Angry voters could be expected to vote for opposition parties, but disillusioned voters stay at home. This is precisely what happened last week: only 31% went to the polls, fewer than at any district election since 1973. Those who did stay at home were more likely to be Conservatives. The party did best where turnout held up most.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This was vividly illustrated in the four councils the party was defending, Broxbourne, Huntingdon, Macclesfield, and Runnymede. Turnout rose in all four. And in all four the Tory vote rose by as much as 7-8%. As a result, the party retained its majority in all but Runnymede.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Moreover, the Tory recovery is not as modest as some observers claimed. Many said that the result was the party's second-worst local election performance ever. It was not. The party's vote was not only higher than last year, but 0.4 percentage points up on 1994 as well.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The recovery was strongest where the Tories most wanted it. As our table (see <a href="br1.gif">table</a>) shows, the Tory vote rose most since last year in those wards it was defending. The party's traditional heartlands are beginning to return to the fold.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Above all, the Tories' misfortunes were grossly exaggerated by the electoral system. It took fewer than 2,000 votes to elect a Labour councillor, nearly 3,000 to elect a Liberal Democrat one, but nearly 6,000 to elect a Conservative. The Tories have caught the old Liberal disease of coming second often and winning rarely.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Meanwhile, both opposition parties have problems. Although the Liberal Democrats did better than their opinion poll ratings yet again, their vote was on average still more than four percentage points lower than in 1994 in those wards that had elections this year and two years ago. And Labour's projected vote was a full eight points below its average performance in opinion polls. According to the British Election Panel Survey, an academic survey which tracks voters through this Parliament, only one-sixth of this gap can be attributed to tactical voters switching from Labour to the Liberal Democrats.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So are the prospects for the Tories in the general election better than most pundits claim? Alas for Mr Major, the answer is no.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Imagine an election next spring. Imagine that the Tories secure a two-and-a-half percentage point swing from Labour over the next year, as they have over the past year. Imagine, finally, that they do even better than that in seats they are defending, achieving an extra swing of 1% in the south of England. The result is still a disaster. On these assumptions, the Conservatives would have only 186 <font size=-1>MP</font>s, fewer even than the 209 Labour won in its <i>annus horribilis</i> of 1983. More than one Tory seat in three would fall.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Why so bleak? Our table gives the answer. The recovery in the party's heartlands since last year has done little to reverse an adverse longer-term trend. Compared with four years ago (as opposed to one year ago), Tory support was down far more in those wards it was defending than elsewhere. Moreover, voters in those wards are opting for whichever of Labour or the Liberal Democrats are best placed to defeat the Tories. As a result, the electoral system threatens to magnify Tory unpopularity in a general election, as voters treat the Liberal Democrats and Labour as if they had an electoral pact.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For now, Mr Major is safe. The progress which the Tories made last week saw to that. But progress is not enough. To win, he needs a miracle.


