<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p align=center><table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" width=231 height=24  alt="Britain"></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>
<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>




<p><b>Housing bill</b> &nbsp;
Westminster council's district auditor has found six top officials and councillors, including the former leader, Dame Shirley Porter, guilty of selling housing to buy votes. They face a &#163;32m bill to cover losses to the council incurred by the policy, but are expected to appeal.</p>
<p><b>Little earners</b> &nbsp;
Members of Parliament, forced to disclose for the first time how much they earn from other jobs related to their role as <font size=-1>MP</font>s, declared outside earnings totalling &#163;3m.</p>
<p><b>Bill of wrongs</b> &nbsp;
The House of Lords passed an amendment to a new defamation bill, overturning part of the 1689 Bill of Rights which prevents <font size=-1>MP</font>s from suing for defamation over criticisms of their parliamentary work.</p>
<p><b>Men's lib</b> &nbsp;
The Equal Opportunities Commission said that for the first time it was getting more complaints about sexual discrimination in the jobs market from men than from women.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Taylor quits</b> &nbsp;
Lord Taylor, the Lord Chief Justice, unexpectedly resigned because of ill health.</p>
<p><b>Royal Sun</b> &nbsp;
Royal Insurance and Sun Alliance said they would merge to form Britain's largest insurance firm, with a stockmarket valuation of &#163;6.3 billion.</p>
<p><b>Driving ahead</b> &nbsp;
Car retailers announced an unexpected 17% rise in sales last month compared with March, to the highest level for almost two years.</p>
<p><b>Video nasty</b> &nbsp;
The Ministry of Defence launched an inquiry into how secret army training videos on counter-terrorism turned up at a car-boot sale.</p>
<p><b>Mad</b> &nbsp;
Germany threatened to block a European Commission proposal to lift the ban on exports of some products derived from British beef.</p>
<p><b>Rock bottom</b> &nbsp;
Stanford Arms Football Club was confirmed as the worst performer of the Football Association's 42,000 teams, coming bottom of the Lowestoft Sunday League with minus two points.</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
