<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width=271 height=24  alt="Politics"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<h2>Five months to go</h2>
<p>Seven months into the fiscal year, the Republican Congress and the Clinton administration agreed at last on a $160 billion <b>budget</b> for 1996. The spending bill included a cut of $20 billion in money terms, but provided an extra $5 billion for the education, training and environment programmes President Clinton wanted.<p>
Mr Clinton was questioned under oath in the bank-fraud trial of his former Arkansas business partners, James and Susan McDougal, giving his evidence on videotape at the White House. The McDougals and the Clintons were co-sponsors of the ill-fated <b>Whitewater </b>property development.<p>
The Justice Department said it would investigate whether illegal industry collusion had contributed to a recent surge in <b>petrol prices</b>, which have increased by 12% since mid-February. Mr Clinton ordered the Energy Department to sell 12m barrels of crude oil from the country's reserves in an effort to drive down prices.<p>
<b>William Colby</b>, a former head of the <font size=-1>CIA</font>, was missing after his canoe was found capsized near his holiday home in Maryland.<p>
<b>Paraguay</b>'s mutinous army chief, General Lino Oviedo, lost his gamble. Sacked, but refusing to quit until he was promised the post of defence minister, he resigned--to find President Juan Carlos Wasmosy, under pressure from democrats at home and abroad, had resolved not to give him the job.<p>
<b>Colombia</b>'s beleaguered President Ernesto Samper lost another minister, his finance chief, Guillermo Perry. He has not been accused of involvement in the ruling party's scandal over drug money and campaign finance.

<h2>Germany bruised</h2>
<p>The German government announced a DM70 billion ($46 billion) <b>savings package </b>for 1997, which includes cutting sick pay and other health benefits, delaying a rise in family benefits and denying a pay rise to civil servants. Other proposed reforms include raising the retirement age, introducing competition into the energy market and liberalising restrictive shopping hours. The package met fierce resistance from unions.<p>
Nine weeks after the general election, <b>Jose Maria Aznar</b>, leader of Spain's conservative People's Party, is to be invested as prime minister at the head of a loose parliamentary majority including the main Catalan and Basque parties. The supreme court cleared the outgoing prime minister, <b>Felipe Gonzalez</b>, of charges that he oversaw a "dirty war" in the 1980s against Basque terrorists.<p>
Leaders of the <b>Nordic and Baltic</b> countries, together with those of Germany, Russia and Poland, were due to meet on a Swedish island to discuss peaceful co-operation in the region.<p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
Within a week of one rebel leader of <b>Chechnya</b>--Jokar Dudaev--being killed, probably by a Russian rocket, it was rumoured that his apparent successor, Zelimkhan Yandarbiev, had met a similar fate--until he appeared, smiling, on television.<p>
Britain's prime minister, John Major, said that if a referendum were held now, the British people would<b> refuse to join</b> Europe's economic and monetary union.<p>
(See <a href="wtw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>The impasse over a worldwide ban on </b><b>British beef </b>continued, with uncertainties remaining over Britain's readiness to initiate a cull deemed satisfactory by the European Union.

<h2>Back to base</h2>
<p>A truce, restating rules designed to protect civilians, ended Israel's <b>blitz on Lebanon</b> and Hizbullah's rocketing of northern Galilee. Israeli evacuees returned to their homes. So did the Lebanese but often found them shattered. They buried their dead, including the 102 people killed at Qana.<p>
Shimon Peres was warmly welcomed by Bill Clinton, and offered <b>laser weapons</b> that might, but probably would not, disable an approaching Katyusha rocket. Yasser Arafat followed him to Washington, claiming his reward for changing the <font size=-1>PLO</font>'s covenant. A Jewish rabbi was stabbed by a Palestinian in Hebron, casting further doubt on Israel's early redeployment from the city.<p>
<b>South Africa</b>'s trade unions held a one-day strike to protest a clause in the proposed constitution giving employers the right to <b>lock strikers out</b>. The rand, which fell further in the run-up to the strike, stabilised after the government raised interest rates.<p>
A ceasefire in the Liberian capital, <b>Monrovia</b>, collapsed. In renewed fighting American marines shot dead three Liberians.

<h2>India elects</h2>
<p>The first two rounds of <b>India's general election </b>were said by the authorities to have been "largely peaceful". About 25 people died.<p>
At least 38 people died when a <b>bomb </b>blew up a bus near Lahore. The Pakistani government blamed "terrorists" linked, it hinted, to India.<p>
Australians observed a minute's silence in memory of 35 people killed by a gunman who ran amok in <b>Tasmania</b>.<p>
Members of a gang that stole a cable supplying electricity to a statue of <b>Kim Il Sung</b>, the former North Korean leader, have been shot as political enemies, according to a South Korean newspaper.<p>
The <b>Hong Kong </b>government said it would not co-operate with the puppet legislature that will replace the democratically elected Legco when China takes over the British colony in July 1997.<p>
<p>

</p>
