<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width=273 height=24  alt="Business"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>



<h2>Uncommunicative</h2>
<p>After two years of trying to bring about a global pact on <b>liberalising telecommunications</b>, the World Trade Organisation failed to win an agreement by this week's deadline. They set a new deadline of February 15th next year, after the Americans complained that other countries had offered to open their markets too little, especially in the case of satellite communications.<p>
The United States said it would complain formally to the World Trade Organisation about the failure of its trading partners to protect <b>intellectual property</b>. China headed America's annual list of transgressors; other culprits were Portugal, Turkey, India and Pakistan.<p>
In the largest rescheduling ever negotiated by the Paris Club of western creditors, nearly $40 billion of <b>Russian debt </b>was rescheduled over 25 years. Russia is required, in return, to adhere to the radical economic and market reforms that the <font size=-1>IMF</font> insisted upon in negotiating its own recent $10 billion loan.<p>
The European Commission halted state aid of 23 billion drachmas ($94m) to <b>Olympic Airways</b>, on the grounds that the Greek government is interfering too much in the airline's management. The commission wants a promise that this will stop before it agrees to release this second slice of a restructuring worth 54 billion drachmas.<p>
Albacom, a joint venture between <b>British Telecom </b>and its Italian partner, Banca Nazionale del Lavoro, is forming an alliance with <b>Mediaset</b>, the television and media arm of Silvio Berlusconi's Fininvest group. Each will take a stake in the other. The alliance plans to compete in Italy's liberalising telecoms market.<p>
<font size=-1>MFS</font> Communications, an American telecoms firm, agreed to pay $2 billion in shares for <font size=-1>UU</font>Net Technologies, an <b>Internet </b>service provider. The deal reflects the growing importance of the Internet to businesses, which make up most of <font size=-1>MFS</font>'s customers; it also adds to the growing domination of large telecoms companies in the Internet access market.<p>
<b>America's economy</b> expanded at an annual rate of 2.8% in the first quarter, much faster than Wall Street had expected. Consumer confidence also leapt unexpectedly in April.<p>
<b>Rentokil</b> won its &#163;2.2 billion ($3.3 billion) takeover battle for <b>BET</b>. Combining the two British groups will create the world's largest business-services group, providing anything from pest control to catering to bulk distribution.<p>
(See <a href="wtw2.gif">chart</a>)<br>
<b>China</b>'s central bank, confident that it has once-rampant inflation under control, cut 0.75 of a percentage point off the commercial loan rate of 12.06% and 0.98 percentage points off the 10.98% deposit rate, to ease the financial burden on state firms in particular. Shares soared.
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>In the air</h2>
<p>A transatlantic romance soured. <b>KLM Royal Dutch Airlines</b> declined to comment on reports that it was thinking of ending its link with America's <b>Northwest Airlines</b>, in which it has a 25% stake.<p>
First-quarter net profits at <b>Boeing</b> plunged 34% to $119m as deliveries dropped from 59 commercial aircraft a year ago to 40. The fall was partly the after-effect of a strike late last year. Separately, a Boeing executive said that the American aircraft maker was falling behind in the hard-fought competition to help China build a 100-seat airliner.<p>
(See <a href="wtw3.gif">chart</a>)<br>
A share shake-up in <b>Cathay Pacific </b>and <b>Dragonair </b>will give the Chinese bigger stakes in the two Hong Kong airlines in the run-up to the colony's return to China next year. Swire Pacific reduced its stake in both airlines, while <font size=-1>CITIC</font> Pacific, China's investment arm in Hong Kong, increased its stake in Cathay and lowered its holding in Dragonair, in which <font size=-1>CNAC</font>, the commercial arm of China's air regulator, took a 36% stake. <font size=-1>CNAC</font> had threatened to start up a rival to Cathay after the handover; it now says it will expand Dragonair instead. The price of Cathay (and Swire) shares jumped.<p>
Richard Branson's <b>Virgin Atlantic</b> completed its BFr1.8 billion ($57m) 90% takeover of Euro Belgian Airlines, which now becomes Virgin Express. With this no-frills airline, Virgin plans a cut-price war in overpriced Europe.

<h2>In sickness</h2>
<p><b>Cr&eacute;dit Agricole</b>, France's biggest and healthiest bank, is taking a 51% stake in unhealthy <b>Banque Indosuez</b>, the investment-banking arm of Suez, a sprawling--and restructuring--holding company, in a deal reckoned to be worth FFr6 billion ($1.2 billion). Even unhealthier <b>Cr&eacute;dit Foncier de France</b> declared a 1995 loss of FFr10.8 billion, after provisions of FFr13.6 billion against its property-loan portfolio, compared with a profit the year before of FFr274m. The bank could become the first casualty among France's sclerotic banks and financial institutions.<p>
<b>Bremer Vulkan</b>, Germany's biggest shipbuilder, began bankruptcy proceedings. The group's demise was expected after it announced a DM1 billion ($698m) loss for 1995.<p>
Two big American companies specialising in disability-income insurance are coming together. <b>Provident</b>, with a contribution of $300m from Zurich Insurance, is buying <b>Paul Revere</b> from Textron for $1.2 billion to create a giant with more than $4 billion in annual revenues.<p>
<p></p>
