<html><head><title>The best of both worlds</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Rural development</b></p>
<h1>The best of both worlds</h1>

<font size=1>INVERNESS</font>


<p>A PERENNIAL problem for Britain's rural economies is the steady exodus of talented young people, lured away not just by the excitement of big cities, but also to city-based higher education as a route to high-earning jobs. This brain drain has meant that any idea of having something as swanky as a university in a remote area to try and reverse the tide has looked hopelessly over-ambitious.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, planners at Highlands and Islands Enterprise (<font size=-1>HIE</font>), Britain's most northerly economic-development agency, think that technology now makes just such a dream possible. For the past four years, <font size=-1>HIE</font> and academics at a dozen small further education colleges scattered across the region--which is bigger than Belgium but has only 370,000 people living in it--have been working on a plan to set up a University of the Highlands and Islands.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;They think that the colleges can be linked electronically to allow interactive learning within a multi-campus university. This idea goes a step further than the distance teaching offered by institutions such as the Open University. For example, students in Stornoway or Elgin could take part in two-way television tutorials given by a professor 250 miles (400km) away in the Shetland Isles.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The government agrees that this is worth pursuing. Michael Forsyth, the Scottish secretary, recently announced that the colleges, which currently have 2,700 students between them, can start expanding to reach the 4,000 students needed to qualify for university status. In due course, the colleges might attract the public cash and academic talent needed to establish a university granting full degrees. The additional students need not be exclusively highlanders; lowlanders keen to escape cities, to study topics such as rural development in a rural setting, might also be interested.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The venture will be expensive. But <font size=-1>HIE</font> officials have been given nods and winks about getting lottery money for half of the &#163;76m cost of building halls of residence and teaching facilities. The rest will come from central and local government, the European Union and private sources.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some of the outlay will have to be spent on information technology but, as it happens, much of the communications network has been built already. In 1989 <font size=-1>HIE</font> persuaded the government to let it give British Telecom &#163;4.9m towards the &#163;20m cost of installing <font size=-1>ISDN</font> (integrated systems digital network) telephone exchanges and fibre-optic cables in the region. This has not only made establishing such a university possible, it has also attracted firms to the region to take advantage of the new communications links, providing jobs for future local graduates.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One such firm is Hoskyns, a computer-services company with 3,800 employees in Britain. It opened an office in Forres, near Inverness, in 1994. It now has a staff of 50 with jobs such as pursuing parking-fine defaulters in four London boroughs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The telecommunications network also means that local people have become attuned to the possibilities offered by information technology. These include training provided by community teleworking centres, which also do desktop publishing of news-sheets and local histories. Small computer-software firms have sprung up. One of these, <font size=-1>QDATA</font> of Evanton, has produced software enabling a tutor to teach pupils at 16 different locations simultaneously, by means of video. The region's police force has used the system to train village constables.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These developments have already enabled the Highlands and Islands to attract some new jobs despite its reputation as a remote backwater. For example, Selfcare, an American medical-supplies firm, decided last year after looking at a number of sites in Britain and Ireland to set up a factory in Inverness. It will employ 375 people making medical-testing kits. The Highlands' hills and glens remain as tranquil as ever. But now it seems that tranquillity and employment, or even ambition, are entirely compatible.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?831164400,iss">Search</a>
