<html><head><title>Flat as a pancake</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<p><b>Japanese semiconductors</b></p>
<h1>Flat as a pancake</h1>

<font size=1>TOKYO</font>
<p>THIS is a nervous time for semiconductor firms. The industry's most watched barometer, America's book-to-bill ratio for semiconductors (the monthly value of new orders divided by sales) was a balmy 1.12 at the end of 1995; it is now 0.8, its lowest level since 1985. Dataquest, a consultancy, recently cut its forecast for world chip growth this year to 7.6%, down from 37% in 1995. At the same time, new semiconductor factories are springing up around Asia faster than noodle shops.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is particularly bad news for Toshiba, Fujitsu, <font size=-1>NEC</font>, Hitachi and Mitsubishi Electric, the five big Japanese firms that make around 40% of the world's chips. They are being squeezed from two sides. American firms, notably Intel, possess better technology. And other Asian producers, notably in South Korea and Taiwan, can make commodity chips more cheaply.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Japanese firms concentrate on memory chips, over 60% of which end up in personal computers. But growth in worldwide <font size=-1>PC</font> sales has dropped from 42% in 1994 to 25% in 1995, and forecasters expect it to be under 20% this year. Short of cash, computer firms have slashed orders for new components and dumped excess memory chips on the spot market. In the past nine months the price of a standard 4-megabit <font size=-1>DRAM</font> (dynamic random-access memory) has more than halved, from around $13 to below $6. Even the newer 16-megabit <font size=-1>DRAM</font> has seen its price tumble by a third to below $20.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To make matters worse, Japan's semiconductor firms together spent a record &#165;855 billion ($8.1 billion) on new fabrication facilities (" fabs" ) in 1995, a whopping 62% increase over the previous year. Although all five of Japan's big semiconductor firms swear that they have no intention of slashing their capital spending (indeed, Hitachi, Mitsubishi Electric and <font size=-1>NEC</font> have just announced plans to build new plants and refurbish old ones), they will not increase it much either. Naoko Ito, an analyst in Tokyo with Goldman Sachs, an American investment bank, reckons that spending on new fabs in Japan will rise by a mere 3% this year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Merely cutting back production will not, however, solve Japan's long-term chip-making woes. Lower-cost manufacturers in South Korea have begun to crank up their own <font size=-1>DRAM</font> capacity. Samsung Electronics of South Korea is already the world's largest producer of memory chips, having overtaken <font size=-1>NEC</font> in 1993. Between them, South Korea's big three chip makers (Samsung, Hyundai and <font size=-1>LG</font> Electronics) supplied more than 10% of the global semiconductor market in 1995. Analysts expect them to have doubled that share by 2000. By then, South Korea will probably have become the world's biggest producer of <font size=-1>DRAM</font>s; and Samsung may have $20 billion of semiconductor sales.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The softening of demand for chips has coincided with a tricky switch to a new generation of memory chips. Both the Japanese and their rivals are shutting their 4-megabit production lines and ramping up their capacity for 16-megabit <font size=-1>DRAM</font>s. The Japanese makers claim that their products will be better, pointing to their swifter introduction of the latest memory design, needed to keep up with Intel's racy new Pentium microprocessors. But Samsung, Hyundai and <font size=-1>LG</font> Electronics are hustling their own speedy new <font size=-1>DRAM</font>s into production, too.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In order to acquire some edge, ten of Japan's biggest electronics firms have put &#165;500m apiece into a co-operative venture. This consortium, Advanced Semiconductor Technologies, will try to make chips on 12-inch wafers of silicon instead of the present 8-inch ones. With more than twice the surface area on which to etch batches of chips, a chip-making factory could, in theory, work twice as fast, significantly reducing the price of each <font size=-1>DRAM</font>. The trouble is that, even if the Japanese firms can find a successful way to squeeze more chips on to a wafer, it will not be long before the South Koreans learn to copy them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If Japan fell behind in semiconductors, that could have consequences that extend far beyond the chip industry. It is likely to have a big impact on the consumer-electronics industry as a whole. On the face of it, this industry is robust in Japan. Last year, the five big electrical groups turned in &#165;990 billion of pre-tax profits between them--nearly 50% up on the previous year. But these earnings depended disproportionately on profit from chips.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although Toshiba's product range stretches all the way from laptops to nuclear reactors, it probably earns 80% of its consolidated operating profit from microchips. Toshiba's competitors are not far behind (see <a href="wb1.gif">chart</a>). This year, in spite of the end of Japan's recession, the chip makers will be lucky to wring out an increase of 10% in earnings.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That will increase the pressure on the most broadly diversified firms to sort out their far-flung portfolios. Hitachi and Toshiba, for instance, might be forced to give up making toasters and fridges on the back of subsidies from chip making. The days when Japanese firms could count on using their semiconductor factories to bankroll their unprofitable businesses may be drawing to an end.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?831164400,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="st1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
