<html><head><title>A new kind of quangocrat</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>

<h1>A new kind of quangocrat</h1>
<p>THE old school tie, already tattered, is about to be thoroughly shredded. On April 23rd, Sir Leonard Peach, the first commissioner for public appointments, published a new code of practice for 8,300 ministerial appointments to executive quangos, ranging from the London Docklands Development Corporation to the Wine Standards Board of the Vintners' Company. The code, which will come into force on July 1st, marks the beginning of the end of the patronage state.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In future, such appointments are to be made on merit. All will be subject to scrutiny by non-partisan panels. The appointments process will be made transparent, with jobs widely advertised. Those active politically will not be barred from appointment, but their political allegiance will become a matter of public record. Appointments will be audited for Sir Leonard. Anyone who feels ill-treated will be able to appeal to him, and his annual report will publicly chastise backsliders.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The new code, like Sir Leonard's appointment, stems from Lord Nolan's report on standards in public life. That followed growing public alarm that the Tories were bending the system to reward their friends. Sir Leonard's code will discourage ministers from using the system to bolster their political favourites, or to advance those they trust to implement their policies without question.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A public-spirited man from a private-sector background, Sir Leonard admits that the new system may need to be extended in the light of experience. Though it includes the high-paying quangos, it excludes the 10,000 members of purely advisory bodies, and a further 22,000 appointments to tribunals. And the ultimate power of appointment remains with ministers, rather than being transferred to independent commissioners.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the biggest question mark against the exercise may arise if there is a change of government. Labour officially supports Sir Leonard. Indeed, some Labour people would have liked him to go further, making it compulsory for appointees to disclose any large political donations they have made. Unofficially, though, some shadow-cabinet members sing a different tune. For 17 years, they say, the Tories have been stuffing quangos with second-rate businessmen. To redress the balance, they would like to do some stuffing of their own. But they can achieve that result without resorting to corrupt practices, by expanding the criteria of merit, so that wider public-service values as well as business values count.

</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?830559600,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
