<html><head><title>Kerb-crawling</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Transport policy</b></p>
<h1>Kerb-crawling</h1>


<p>ANYONE who wonders why the government has failed to produce a transport policy document for 17 years has only to read the green (ie, consultative) paper published on April 25th to discover the answer. Paralysis in policy-making, caused by an ideological obsession with the motor car and a terror of unpopular measures to restrain traffic, is the culprit. The resulting legacy of worsening congestion on the roads and under-used, under-invested public transport has now become too obvious to ignore.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The fact that the government felt compelled, after so many years of silence, to publish a green paper is a sign that the political sands are beginning to shift. Nevertheless with a general election looming, Sir George Young, the greenest transport secretary since Labour's Barbara Castle in the 1960s, has not been able to push his colleagues into saying much.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Sir George had two big ideas. He wanted to create road corporations as the first step to privatising most main roads, and he wanted to overhaul vehicle taxation. Both ideas, eminently sensible, were shot down by cabinet colleagues as far too dangerous. Instead ministers have fallen back on the time-worn and largely ineffective formula of giving more powers to local authorities to plan and restrain traffic in their areas.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The green paper endorses the switch in spending from new roads to public transport, foreshadowed in the last budget. But it offers no clear answer to the question of how congestion from growing car usage can be tackled.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The paper rejects the idea of setting targets, which was advocated by a Royal Commission on Environmental Pollution 18 months ago. That report called for a trebling in the use of public transport and in the amount of freight carried by rail by 2020. "Our view is that you have got to have a consensus on measures to restrain traffic before setting targets," explains one transport department official. The commission's demand for a doubling in the real price of petrol and diesel fuels by the year 2000 to stabilise carbon dioxide emissions is studiously ignored. Ironically, the commission's call for a halving of expenditure on motorways and new trunk roads is already being delivered by default, thanks to public-expenditure cuts.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Leaving difficult decisions to local councils has its attractions in the run-up to an election. It may even result in a few interesting traffic-control experiments. But no amount of local decision-making can substitute for a clear national policy on how to deal with road traffic which is forecast to double by 2025.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The green paper avoids committing the government even to such an obvious measure as changing the system of company-car taxation which rewards drivers for driving more. Four out of five cars coming into London in the hours of peak congestion are company-owned cars. Most of their drivers enjoy free parking at their place of work, a benefit which will remain untaxed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The failure to address such arguments is excused at Westminster on the grounds that changes to car taxation and traffic restraint are political poison. But a study of public attitudes, published as an annexe to the green paper, found that three-quarters of those questioned accepted that additional measures for controlling traffic growth were urgently needed. An earlier study found that 54% of respondents would accept being unable to drive in town or city centres in order to reduce environmental damage.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Transport issues are also heading up the political agenda. A <font size=-1>MORI</font> poll last year found that 12% of people said transport policies were important in determining how they would vote at a general election. Asked which party had the better policies, a paltry 5% said the Conservatives. A whopping 61% backed Labour's transport policies, apparently unaware that Labour, like the government, has so far offered little in the way of new policies.

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?830559600,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br4.html">Next article</a>
