<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p align=center><table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" width=231 height=24  alt="Britain"></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>
<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<p><b>Marital row</b> &nbsp;
In a free vote, <font size=-1>MP</font>s amended the family reform bill to impose a cooling-off period of 18 months before divorce, instead of one year, as proposed by ministers. The Lord Chancellor accepted the amendment.</p>
<p><b>Courting disaster</b> &nbsp;
Defying the government's wishes, 66 Tory <font size=-1>MP</font>s voted for a private member's bill to give Parliament the power to overrule the judgments of the European Court of Justice. The bill was defeated by six votes.</p>
<p><b>Tortured</b> &nbsp;
The House of Lords also defied the government--inserting a clause in its asylum bill, giving extra rights to refugees alleged to have been tortured.</p>
<p><b>Green light</b> &nbsp;
The <font size=-1>SDLP</font> and Sinn Fein said they would take part in next month's elections in Northern Ireland for a consultative forum which is intended to lead to all-party peace talks. No one was hurt when an <font size=-1>IRA</font> bomb partly exploded in London.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Queen of hearts?</b> &nbsp;
The Royal College of Surgeons attacked the Princess of Wales for being present during open-heart surgery on a seven-year-old boy. Television pictures showed that the princess's hair and earrings were uncovered during the operation.</p><p><b>Successful try</b> &nbsp;
In the first case of its kind, a rugby player crippled for life when a scrum collapsed won damages against the referee, for failing to take reasonable care.</p>
<p><b>Unsuccessful try</b> &nbsp;
School inspectors said that &#163;50m spent by the government on regular appraisals of individual teachers was wasted because schools were not using the reports to decide which staff needed re-training.</p>
<p><b>Dispute</b> &nbsp;
Immigration officers voted overwhelmingly for strikes at airports and ports over plans to change their shift patterns to ease congestion for early-morning passengers.
</p>
<p><b>Endless agenda</b> &nbsp;
The typical British manager spends 20 years of his life in meetings, a survey found. Those questioned said that in at least one meeting out of six, nothing was achieved</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
