<html><head><title>Free-mail</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>

<h1>Free-mail</h1>
<p>AS THE morning post too often demonstrates, direct-mail advertising is a sloppy business. Without much knowledge of people's likes and dislikes, advertisers resort to the shotgun approach. They send out lots of letters, hoping that some are opened, and maybe even a few read and responded to. It is grossly inefficient: the letters cost a fortune to send, waste time, and consume a lot of trees.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The main problems have been that it is hard to find an audience, to work out who is in it, and to discover what they like. Yet on the Internet, people willingly reveal such details all the time as the price of admission to useful sites.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now Juno Online, a New York company in which D.E. Shaw, an investment bank, has a $20m stake, has found a way to put the two worlds together. It is offering free e-mail access to anybody in America with a personal computer and modem. In exchange, subscribers part with their demographic details--and put up with advertisements in the corner of their computer screens.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So far Juno, which launched its e-mail service on April 22nd, has attracted 15 advertisers, including Snapple, a soft-drinks company, and Lands' End, a clothing retailer. For them, the advantages are manifold. They can use advertising like direct mail, to deliver a specific message to, say, nobody but tennis-playing women in their 30s.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Because subscribers know that they will receive advertising anyway, they have a strong interest in describing themselves to Juno as accurately as possible. Unlike direct mail, which may go unopened and unread, advertising on Juno is paid for only when the recipient gets it. And there is a cost saving: Juno, and FreeMark Communications, which launches a rival free e-mail service on May 6th, both reckon they will be around eight times cheaper than direct mail, while offering advertising that consumers are more likely to respond to.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But why should consumers agree to part with their intimate details and a corner of their screens? Juno and FreeMark argue that the simplicity of their software will attract technophobes. Both companies, unlike employers, schools and universities, are offering people the same e-mail address for life. Josh Bernoff, a consultant with Forrester Research in Boston, thinks that millions of households may want e-mail only, rather than the Internet's complex delights.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Both firms know that success will depend on signing up plenty of users quickly. FreeMark, for example, has arranged to distribute its software to Citibank's west-coast clients and will offer free sports reports by e-mail. However, without several hundred thousand customers logging on fairly soon, no advertiser will stay for long.</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?830559600,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="fn1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
