</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Squidgy forever</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/st.gif" width=371 height=26  alt="Science And Technology">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>

<h1>Squidgy forever</h1>

<p>IN A veritable lifetime of embarrassments, one of the worst for the Princess of Wales came after eavesdroppers listened in on a conversation with a boyfriend who called her "Squidgy" . They could do this because her mobile telephone used analogue rather than digital technology, and could not therefore be protected by the fancy encryption technology available on digital networks.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In many parts of the world, however, eavesdroppers can listen in even on digital cellphones. This is because the American government will not allow the encryption technology to be exported, for fear that it will protect the privacy of (other countries') spies and drug traffickers. The export ban is part of a long-standing effort to protect America's lead in making and breaking codes. Much of the relevant mathematics is secret.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This ban, a relic of the cold war, nowadays infuriates westerners visiting countries such as Russia to do business. Given the ramshackle local telephones, many such visitors take along their own cellphones. They were not--until America's Commerce Department relented in February--allowed to take along the encryption technology that would prevent Russian gangsters from eavesdropping on their business deals.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Under an amendment to America's International Trafficking in Arms Regulations, the export of encryption technologies is now exempted for personal use. In other words, Americans are now allowed to leave the country with a secure cellphone (and encryption software loaded on their computers), provided they keep it to themselves.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But there is a catch. A secure cellphone is not secure unless it is used on a secure network, and both the United States and the European Union continue to ban the export of the necessary networking equipment. That is why, in March, two American senators introduced separate bills that would allow the unrestricted export of encryption technology, opening the burgeoning communications security market to American companies overseas. Whether the <font size=-1>EU</font> countries, big cellphone exporters, will change their policies accordingly is not clear. Russia's gangsters, and tabloid journalists, are no doubt praying for years of indecision.
</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?830559600,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT21-B39-183</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA026-000276-B035-23</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.economist.com:80/issue/20-04-96/covcredit.html 199.173.162.110 19970113171315 text/html 925
