<html><head><title>Over the top</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<h1><center>Over the top</center></h1>

ISRAEL has the right, and indeed the duty, to protect its people. And it would be excellent for the peace of the region if Shimon Peres, Israel's prime minister, were to win re-election next month. But neither the protection of its citizens in northern Galilee, nor the hope of a comprehensive Middle Eastern peace, justifies the forcible displacement of up to half a million inoffensive Lebanese, and the savaging of their homes and livelihoods. Those consequences were planned. The death of more than 50 refugees sheltering in a <font size=-1>UN</font> base in southern Lebanon, reported as <i>The Economist</i> went to press on April 18th, was merely a foreseeable contingency. It brought the toll of fatalities close to 100. Operation Grapes of Wrath, launched a week ago, requires the ends to justify the means. They do not.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When Israel was surrounded by enemies, convinced that a lost battle would be a last battle, its disproportionate response to Arab acts of aggression was understandable. But those days are long gone. Israel is either at peace with its neighbours, or negotiating peace. Since, as a state, it is no longer in danger, the world should no longer smile when it claims two eyes for an eye.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That said, Israel had a dilemma, as do all countries, in responding effectively to a guerrilla threat. The Hizbullah campaign against Israel's occupation of a slice of south Lebanon had grown fiercer; the guerrillas were killing Israeli soldiers and firing rockets into Israel--though still keeping to the rough tit-for-tat rules worked out after Israel's last pounding of Lebanon in 1993 (see <a href="sf1.html">pages</a>). Mr Peres, facing an election and under attack from the opposition for not being "strong", decided he had to do something.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He had a number of options. With its spies in Lebanon, Israel can pick out Hizbullah chieftains. Yet this has been tried before: Hizbullah leaders have been killed and kidnapped and the guerrillas carried on. Hizbullah positions could be destroyed but, again, the guerrillas' response would be yet another salvo of rockets into Israel. Action that was demonstrably ineffective would do no good to Mr Peres's electoral prospects. If there was to be a reaction, suggested advisers, it should be over-reaction. Mr Peres, wrongly rejecting a more modest, albeit imperfect, response, gave way.
</p><p><b>Trampling out the vintage</b>
<br>The massive bombardment of Lebanon that followed, bombing and shelling targets as far north as Beirut, putting most of southern Lebanon to flight, has not, in fact, silenced the guerrillas: the number of rockets falling on the fields and townships of northern Galilee has increased. But Israelis are delighted, after a prolonged period of morose self-examination, to see somebody--anybody--being punished.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;American diplomacy, which ended the 1993 onslaught, is again taking over. The result could be no more than a refinement of the 1993 rules of engagement. On the other hand, if a grain of good sense enters the argument, the new agreement could point, under clear conditions, to Israel's early withdrawal from Lebanon--a country that Israel insists it has no designs on. This, by removing the guerrillas'<i> raison d'tre</i>, would indeed help.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But these American-led consultations--with Israel, Lebanon and Syria--highlight the true purpose of Grapes of Wrath. Forget the talk of Hizbullah targets. The bombardment was not to hurt Hizbullah, which like most guerrilla bands is pretty invulnerable to such attacks, but to hurt the governments that allow Hizbullah to operate. The creation of a mass refugee problem in Beirut, the bombing of power stations that returned the capital to the black-out of the civil war, the threat to the airport: all this seems to have been designed to frighten away the investors now creating a new Lebanon.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although the Lebanese government itself has no power to curb the guerrillas, it reports to its patron, Syria. And although Syria's President Hafez Assad cares not a jot for Lebanese casualties or Lebanese refugees, he has a big stake in Lebanon's reconstruction through its prime minister, Rafik Hariri. Under pressure, both Syria and Lebanon are likely to listen to America's suggestions, particularly if there is a nod in the direction of taking Syria off the State Department's list of countries that sponsor terrorism.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Hizbullah, which gets its money from far-away Iran, would find it difficult to defy Syria, the master-power on the spot. But it could try. Its boasts about fanatical recruits lining up for paradise through the martyrdom of suicide-bombing may be bluster. On the other hand, they may not. If Hizbullah, which last month sent a suicide-bomber to kill a soldier, decides that this is the route to follow, Mr Peres's bright electoral prospects would, once again, be darkened.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It would be wrong to imply that Mr Peres has been guided entirely by opinion-poll considerations. But if the election had not been pressing on him, the need to show himself a "strong" leader so urgent, he might well have resisted the temptation to turn much of southern Lebanon into a crater. The electoral framework makes the operation particularly cynical: a pounding of people who in no way deserved it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Good may eventually come out of evil. But Israel, at this turning-point in its history, needed to show itself an honest, as well as a strong, neighbour. The punishment of Lebanon reveals that Israel the peace-seeker is still Israel the embattled, punching first and talking afterwards.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="sf1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
