<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width=271 height=24  alt="Politics"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<h2>Middle East blitz</h2>
<p>Israel continued its air and artillery bombardment of <b>Lebanon</b>. It killed more than 50 people sheltering at a <font size=-1>UN</font> peacekeepers' base near Tyre. And it struck power stations, Beirut suburbs and a Palestinian refugee camp. Hizbullah continued to fire rockets into northern Israel. The <font size=-1>UN</font> Security Council got nowhere, but the French and American governments embarked on diplomatic initiatives.
<p>Four gunmen--thought to be Islamic extremists--opened fire on <b>tourists </b>outside a hotel near Cairo, killing 18 people and wounding 15.</p>
<p>Fighting continued in <b>Liberia</b>. Charles Taylor's forces attacked an army barracks in the capital, Monrovia, where 10,000 people took refuge, and looting by young fighters continued as food and water in the city ran short. America said it would land 1,500 marines to secure its embassy.</p>
<p>South Africa's <b>Truth</b> <b>and Reconciliation</b> Commission, whose chairman is Archbishop Desmond Tutu, held its first sessions. It will hear the tales both of victims (or relatives who survived them) and of perpetrators of political crime in apartheid days.</p>
<p><b>Cyril Ramaphosa</b>, secretary-general of the African National Congress and once considered a possible successor to President Nelson Mandela, is giving up active politics to go into business.</p>
<h2>Indomitable</h2>
<p><b>Pat Buchanan</b>, Bob Dole's sole remaining challenger in the Republican presidential campaign, said he would not campaign for the Pennsylvania primary but was staying in the race. His sister, Bay, who manages his campaign, said a third-party bid was "very much an open option".</p>
<p>President Clinton vetoed a $13 billion bill that would have obliged America to give more political support to <b>Taiwan</b>. He said it would "restrict presidential authority".</p>
<p><b>Mickey Kantor</b>, formerly the United States trade representative, was appointed commerce secretary to replace Ron Brown, who was killed earlier this month in an air crash in Croatia.</p>
<p><b>Venezuela's</b> President Rafael Caldera joined the rest of 1990s Latin America with a <font size=-1>U</font>-turn on economic policy: petrol prices rose fivefold, exchange controls are to go and interest rates to be freed. As a cushion, some social measures and a 70% public-sector wage increase are promised. Protests were mild; the last such measures, in 1989, left 300 dead.</p>
<p>In <b>Brazil</b>, a Supreme Court judge dealt the government a heavy blow, ordering suspension of work on a bill to reform the welfare system.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p>The ruling <font size=-1>PRI</font> and two leftish opposition parties reached agreement on electoral reform in <b>Mexico</b>. But the right-wing <font size=-1>PAN</font>, the leading opposition party, stayed aloof.</p>
<h2>America abroad</h2>
<p>Bill Clinton paid a visit to South Korea and Japan. In South Korea, a joint American-South Korean proposal was announced for <b>peace talks</b>, aimed at finally ending the Korean war. They would involve the two Koreas, America and China. In Japan, America agreed to the closure of some of its bases, including a large air base, on the southern island of Okinawa. But other agreements strengthened American-Japanese military co-operation.</p>
<p>In South Korea, the ruling <b>New Korea Party</b>, led by President Kim Young Sam, lost its overall majority in elections to the National Assembly, but avoided the severe setback that opinion polls had predicted.</p>
<p>China struck a conciliatory note in its disputes with South-East Asian countries over rival territorial claims in the <b>South China Sea</b>. The Chinese suggested all sides sign a joint declaration of principles, aimed at maintaining good relations.</p>
<p>A bomb went off in Pakistan at a charitable hospital built by <b>Imran Khan</b>, a former cricket hero. Six people were killed. Mr Khan reiterated his intention to enter politics.</p>
<p>Yozo Yokota, the <font size=-1>UN</font> "special rapporteur" on <b>Myanmar</b> told a <font size=-1>UN</font> committee that forced labour, torture and arbitrary killing were "still widespread" in the country.</p>
<h2>Rebuilding Bosnia</h2>
<p>A conference called to muster aid to rebuild <b>Bosnia</b> raised the $1.8 billion that the World Bank and the <font size=-1>EU</font> want to spend there this year. The Bosnian Serbs did not turn up, because they were told they could come only as part of an all-Bosnia delegation. Many donors said the Bosnian Serbs should receive no aid until they kick out Radovan Karadzic and Ratko Mladic, two of their leaders who have been indicted as alleged war criminals.</p>
<p>Up to 17 candidates may run in <b>Russia</b>'s presidential election in June, the Central Electoral Commission reported. Boris Yeltsin, Gennady Zyuganov, Vladimir Zhirinovsky and Mikhail Gorbachev completed formalities and are assured of places on the ballot. The commission will rule on another 13 candidates by April 26th.</p>
<p>After Franz Fischler, the <font size=-1>EU</font> farm commissioner, said he would willingly eat British beef, John Major accused Britain's partners of imposing a <b>ban on British beef</b> <b>exports</b> for the sake of their own markets rather than on grounds of public health.</p>
<p>
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
