<html><head><title>Gerrymander</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Northern Ireland</b></p>
<h1>Gerrymander</h1><font size=1>BELFAST</font><p>NORTHERN IRELAND'S strange politics have produced what will be one of history's oddest elections. The rules, which were published on April 16th, are convoluted and illogical, and blatantly manipulate the electoral process. But the rationale behind them is simple: if peace is to be made, the tiny parties which speak for loyalist paramilitaries must be at the table negotiating a peace settlement, though they have never won so much as 1% of the vote.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On May 30th, voters will elect five people in each of Northern Ireland's 18 Westminster constituencies. The ten parties with the highest total vote will then be allowed to choose two delegates each.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The 110 people thus elected and delegated form the pool from which their parties will choose negotiators for the all-party talks. Votes will not determine negotiating strength. Large and small parties will send similar-sized teams. None is to exceed three, with three in support.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The 110 delegates will also be entitled "to discuss issues relevant to promoting dialogue and understanding within Northern Ireland". The forum will be "deliberative only" and will not have the power to influence negotiations.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Or so the draft legislation says. The government wants to pass it by May 3rd, but there will be discordant voices. Unionists who exacted these elections from John Major as the price for sitting down with the <font size=-1>IRA</font>'s political voice, Sinn Fein, are not disposed to abandon the idea of an assembly which could debate and approve negotiating positions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Of course, unless and until the <font size=-1>IRA</font> calls another ceasefire (a prospect which seemed more remote after a bomb went off in west London on April 18th), Sinn Fein is excluded from negotiations. If it contests the election and wins, however, its members are entitled to sit in the forum. But both Sinn Fein and the larger, non-violent nationalist party, the <font size=-1>SDLP</font>, see the forum as no more than a throwback to the bigoted unionist-dominated assemblies of old.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Messing with the electoral process can get you into trouble. The government originally proposed that no more than 15 parties should contest the election. One step ahead of threatened judicial challenges they have now published a list of 30 eligible names. Several, bizarrely, are those of individuals: "Independent Chambers", "Independent Kerr", "Independent McCaffrey". One of these individuals had threatened to go to court if not included.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet the manipulation still may not bring the desired result: those intended to benefit may not make the "top ten". The transcendentalist Natural Law Party, levitating on the votes of those alienated from local politics, may end up negotiating Ulster's future in seats reserved for Loyalist paramilitary frontmen, as may the Green Party. Worse from the government's point of view, Northern Irish Conservatives standing in defiance of the party seem certain to make it. This election looks likely to create more difficulties than it solves.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
