<html><head><title>New mayors</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>London government</b></p>
<h1>New mayors</h1>

<p>THERE is a strong case that Britain's big local governments should be run by mayors, directly elected by the people, rather than, as now, by leaders who are indirectly elected by local councillors. There is a weaker but not negligible case that London should have an elected authority, responsible for strategic planning and transport, and replacing the old Greater London Council (<font size=-1>GLC</font>) which the government abolished in 1986. However, if you put both these ideas together, as did Tony Blair, the Labour leader, in a speech on April 17th, you end up with a nonsense.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For what is the case for an elected mayor? As embraced not only by Mr Blair, but also by Michael Heseltine, the deputy prime minister, and many local government gurus, it is to create local politicians with the clout of a Rudolph Giuliani in New York, or a Jacques Chirac when he ran Paris. Head-to-head contests between strong candidates would make local elections real, and not just verdicts on the national standing of the political parties. They would also give the winners direct electoral mandates. The nearest London has got to a leader was when the newt-loving Ken Livingstone ran the <font size=-1>GLC</font>, just before its abolition.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unfortunately, Mr Blair's London mayor would have a mandate but not much power. His base, the proposed new London authority, would not provide the main services for which local councils are responsible. Real power would lie with the 32 London boroughs, and with non-elected officials of central government.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is a recipe for instability. In the days of the <font size=-1>GLC</font>, which was also less powerful than the boroughs, its leaders were prone to grandstanding. Indeed Mr Livingstone got it abolished by using the council as a political base for socialism rather than for services. Since the new authority proposed by Labour will have even less power than did the <font size=-1>GLC</font>, the new mayor will be sorely tempted to play the same game. He will be driven to spend his time, for example, pestering Whitehall for more money for the capital.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nor will his appointment do anything for accountability. As he is visible, Londoners will blame him for the failings of local government. However most of these will really be down to their local councils.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Fortunately, Labour is consulting Londoners before finalising its plans. They should give it a clear message. Yes, we would like an elected mayor, providing that he really is running the city. But no, we do not want an elected mayor if he is not going to do anything for us except to play party politics.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829954800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br4.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
