<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p><p align=center><img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width=273 height=24  alt="Business"></p><hr size=6 align=center width=65%><center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%><h2>Mulling merger</h2><p>(See <a href="wtw1.gif">chart</a>)<br><b>Switzerland</b>'s two biggest banks held merger talks. Union Bank of Switzerland, the biggest by market capitalisation and profits, and <font size=-1>CS</font> Holding, just ahead on assets, together would control a third of banking in Switzerland, where nearly 500 banks vie for diminishing profits.</p><p><b>Suez</b>, a French banking and industrial conglomerate, reported a net loss of FFr4 billion ($800m) in 1995, compared with FFr4.8 billion in 1994. The group expects to return to profit in 1996, even though it thinks it might again have to increase its provisions against dud loans.</p><p>More Americans than expected went back to work in March, jolting Wall Street, again. The <b>Dow</b> fell 1.6% on April 8th and a further 1.3% on April 10th. The dollar hit a 26-month high against the yen and a 14-month high against the <font size=-1>D</font>-mark. In Tokyo, the <b>Nikkei </b>dropped on the news but later recovered to set a four-year high.</p><p>The <b>rand </b>sank to new dollar lows as investors, nervous about South Africa's economy, reacted badly to rumours about an easing of foreign-exchange controls, as they did to earlier rumours about Nelson Mandela's health. The new finance minister has not restored calm.</p><p>About one in five of <b>Russia's banks </b>is either bankrupt or in serious trouble, said the Association of Russian Banks. But the central bank said it would not save weak ones. A recent report on Russian banking, sponsored by the European Union, predicted that more than half the country's banks will disappear over the next few years.</p><h2>Driving force</h2><p><b>Chrysler</b> agreed a $475m sale of most of its defence-electronics and airborne-systems operations to <b>Raytheon</b>, which has been expanding in those areas. The sale is part of the car maker's agreement with its biggest shareholder, Kirk Kerkorian, who has waged a long battle with Chrysler to return some of its cash hoard to shareholders.</p><p>Japan's second-biggest car maker, <b>Nissan</b>, is changing its boss. Yoshifumi Tsuji (above) is moving a year early and handing the job of president to Yoshikazu Hanawa.</p><p>America's big car makers made big profits last year but tough targets meant that their chief executives all had <b>pay cuts</b>. General Motors cut John Smith's pay by 9.2% and Ford's Alex Trotman lost 33% of his. Chrysler disclosed last month that it paid Robert Eaton 22% less.</p></td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%><p>Bulgaria's attempts to attract foreign investors took a battering when the German-owned <b>Rover Group </b>said it would close its new $20m car factory in the Black Sea port of Varna. It blames broken government promises, extra duties and tariffs, and cashless consumers.</p><p>China announced that it was buying another 30 new aircraft from <b>Airbus</b>, the European rival to Boeing, in a deal worth $1.5 billion.</p><h2>Wrathless grapes</h2><p>(See <a href="wtw2.gif">chart</a>)<br><b>French wine makers </b>had a good year for exports in 1995, despite threats of boycotts when France carried out a series of nuclear tests in the Pacific; the number of bottles sold in Australia, admittedly a tiny number, rose by 130%. Germany remained the biggest importer by volume; Britain again by value.</p><p>Digital Equipment, Microsoft and <font size=-1>MCI</font> Communications have teamed up to provide fully integrated products and services for <b>intranets</b>, the private ghettos many firms are creating within the Internet.</p><p>Two big media groups formed an alliance, backdated to January 1st, under which <b>Kirch Gruppe </b>of Germany acquires the German-language rights to television programmes and films made by Paramount Pictures, a subsidiary of America's <b>Viacom</b>. The alliance gives Viacom a presence in Germany and Kirch more control over American <font size=-1>TV</font> shows and films as it gets ready to start a digital pay-<font size=-1>TV</font> service in Europe.</p><p>Among mixed results from chip makers, America's <b>Motorola</b>, which also makes cellular phones, reported first-quarter earnings up 3% to $384m. Investors took it as a sign that the semiconductor industry might be reviving and its shares jumped.</p><p><b>Apple Computer</b>'s battered shares jumped 7% on rumours that its old rival, <font size=-1>IBM</font>, would sign a deal to license Apple's Macintosh operating-system software. Last month, Apple warned shareholders it will lose $700m in the first quarter of 1996.</p><p><b>Airtouch</b>, an American cellular-phone company spun off by Pacific Telesis in 1993, is buying the 60% of <b>Cellular Communications </b>it does not already own, in a deal it values at $1.65 billion.</p><p><b>Strikes </b>are at a 50-year low in western industrial countries, according to the <font size=-1>OECD</font>. In the five years to 1994, an annual average of 100 working days were lost per 1,000 employees, compared with 145 in the previous five years. Biggest drops were in Denmark, New Zealand and Britain. But the countries with the most harmonious relations were Switzerland (in the ten years since 1985, it lost an annual average of one working day per 1,000 workers) and Japan; worst were Greece (3,729 working days) and Spain.</p><p></p></td></tr></table></center><p align=center><a href="wtw1.html">POLITICS THIS WEEK</a></p><br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829350000,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="ld1.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
