<html><head><title>Love fest</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>

</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Blair's American visit</b></p>
<h1>Love fest</h1>

<p>AS EXPECTED, Tony Blair received a warm welcome in Washington this week from Bill Clinton. Can they ever be as close as Ronnie and Margaret? Perhaps, but it may not matter much if they are.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Both men already have a lot in common. Both are Oxford-educated 40-somethings, enjoy middle-of-the-road rock music, claim a Christian basis for their politics and are married to successful, independent-minded lawyers. Above all, each has modernised an ailing left-of-centre party.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Blair and his new Labour advisers identify strongly with Mr Clinton's new Democrats. This partly reflects personal ties. Jonathan Powell, Mr Blair's chief of staff, was working at the British embassy in Washington during the Clinton campaign of 1992 and followed it closely. Phillip Gould, Mr Blair's pollster, played a minor advisory role in the Clinton campaign. David Milliband, a Blair aide, and Ed Balls, an adviser to Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, have forged strong links with members of the Clinton administration, such as Larry Summers at the Treasury and Robert Reich, the secretary of labour.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Blair's desire to emulate Mr Clinton's success is evident in his espousal of Clintonite policies such as workfare, and his endorsement of communitarianism. Moreover, Mr Blair's big idea, the "stakeholder society", has led leftish thinkers on both sides of the Atlantic to talk of possible common policies, much as Margaret (now Lady) Thatcher and Ronald Reagan jointly pursued income-tax cuts and deregulation. Mr Reich is a keen advocate of "stakeholder capitalism": he advocates making companies "good citizens" by giving them new duties to stakeholders such as employees and the "community". A group of congressional Democrats is exploring ways to promote the "responsible corporation" as, in Britain, Will Hutton has done in a best-selling book, "The State We're In" .
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But it seems unlikely that many concrete policies will emerge from all this chatter and communing. Mr Blair is wisely distancing himself from talk of tampering directly with firms; one goal of this week's visit was to persuade American investors of his economic solidity. Mr Clinton has been careful not to let Mr Reich turn many of his words into actions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Those close to Mr Blair prefer to emphasise the lessons to be learnt from Mr Clinton's experiences as a left-wing moderniser running for office. To them, Mr Clinton is good at campaigning, bad at governing. He allowed voters' hopes for change to rise too high, and failed to think through his biggest campaign commitment, to reform health care. As a result his efforts at reform were an embarrassing flop.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Thus Blairites are attempting to restrain public expectations before Britain's general election and are grappling with the practicalities of constitutional reform, the policy most likely to provide Mr Blair's equivalent of the health-care fiasco.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Whatever else they do, however, neither Mr Clinton nor Mr Blair plans to reverse the economic reforms of their right-wing predecessors. History may judge that to be the most significant thing these leaders of the left had in common.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?829350000,iss">Search</a>
