<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p align=center><table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" width=231 height=24  alt="Britain"></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>

</font></p></td></tr></table></center>
<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>



<p><b>Off the rails</b> &nbsp;
Roger Salmon said he would resign in October as head of Opraf, the rail-franchising regulator--two years early--because by then he would have achieved all he had set out to do. Labour claimed he was leaving because it would sack him if elected.</p>
<p><b>Off the air</b> &nbsp;
The <font size=-1>BBC</font> announced the closure of its Arabic television service after Orbit, a Saudi-run firm which transmitted the service by satellite, withdrew from their joint venture in protest at a documentary featuring Muhammad Massari, a Saudi dissident.</p>
<p><b>Testing time</b> &nbsp;
<font size=-1>AIDS</font> clinics and charities received thousands of calls from people who had taken tests for <font size=-1>HIV</font>, after an announcement that some tests may have falsely shown that the patient was free of the virus.</p>
<p><b>Mad bomber</b> &nbsp;
Police said they are investigating a 16-month parcel-bomb campaign against London branches of Barclays Bank. The bomber has demanded more than &#163;1m ($1.5m).</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Mad teachers</b> &nbsp;
Left-wing delegates to the annual conference of the National Union of Teachers blocked the union leadership's plans to widen the use of secret ballots of union members. Doug McAvoy, the general secretary, vowed to press on with the reforms nevertheless.</p>
<p><b>Miracle</b> &nbsp;
George Carey, the Archbishop of Canterbury, said a strong performance by the Church of England's property investments helped its assets grow by &#163;300m ($450m) last year. The church now claims to have recovered almost all of the heavy losses caused by property speculation in the late 1980s.</p>
<p><b>Cuts</b> &nbsp;
The mortgage-price war continued with the Nationwide and Yorkshire building societies cutting their standard lending rates by 0.25% to 6.74%--more than 0.5% below that of the Halifax, the largest home-loans provider.
</p>
<p><b>Vampires beware</b> &nbsp;
What is claimed to be Europe's first shop devoted entirely to garlic-based products (ranging from ice cream to shampoo) opened in Hastings, West Sussex.</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
