<html><head><title>Learning to cope</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></p>
<h1><center>Learning to cope</center></h1>

ECONOMIC insecurity is all the rage. It is a theme that will dominate the forthcoming elections in Britain and America, even though both are enjoying steady growth and low unemployment by international standards. Today most of the big economies feel anxious in a way that is not explained by the usual economic statistics. What worries people is not the fact of joblessness so much as the threat of it; not the lack of economic growth so much as its distribution. People who used to think their jobs were safe and their standard of living would rise each year can no longer take either for granted.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The scale of the problem tends to be exaggerated. In many economies, competition (domestic as much as foreign) and new technology are touching people who were hitherto immune from such forces. It may seem to them that the world has changed in a terrifying way; often, it is merely that their corner has become more like the world at large. Moreover, crucial aspects of "insecurity" are shrouded in statistical fog. Have real household earnings stagnated in America? It depends what you mean by "real" (because adjusting for inflation is a tricky business). It depends what you mean by "household" (because the pattern of household composition has changed a lot). It depends what you mean by "earnings" (because employers now pay their workers more in the form of non-wage benefits).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nonetheless, the issue raises questions well worth answering. Two, for now. What can governments do to promote growth in productivity and hence in overall living standards? And what can they do to reduce persistent unemployment--so that the benefits of growth are more widely shared, and the possibility of unemployment becomes a bit less scary?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Predictably, at this week's meeting of rich-country labour ministers in Lille, many Europeans objected to America's insistence that a large part of the cure for European unemployment was lighter regulation of labour markets. That way, the Europeans said, lies falling wages and even greater insecurity. This is a familiar quarrel and little more needs to be said about it. America's phenomenal success in creating new jobs and Europe's abject failure to do so speak for themselves.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;More interesting perhaps is another proposed remedy for insecurity: state-supported training. Everybody loves this idea. Here is the best way to help workers cope with a changing jobs market. With more training, governments can encourage not only lots of new jobs, but lots of good jobs. It is a prescription temptingly in tune with the times: knowledge workers...flexibility...human capital. Training is a kind of investment, after all. Who ever objected to investment?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Well, since you ask. Deregulating labour markets is controversial but should not be; spending more public money on training, whether on public schemes or on subsidies for private schemes, is not controversial but should be. The standard argument is that the market is bound to provide too little training: why should a firm bear the cost when trained workers can take their new skills elsewhere? But people accept this idea much too quickly. The fact is, the great bulk of training actually carried out in a modern economy is on-the-job training arranged at the employer's initiative. There is no mystery about it. Spending money on training can make sense, despite poaching, if one of two things is true. Either the firm must be able to pay a comparatively low wage during training (recovering some of the cost from the worker), or else the training must be firm-specific (and therefore of little interest to a would-be poacher). Often both are true.
</p><p><b>Floors and bridges</b>
<br>If training is under-provided, and it sometimes may be, it must be for deeper reasons than the specious " market failure" argument. For instance, if there is a floor below which wages cannot fall (either because of a minimum wage, or because of the way the welfare system works), the private bargain over training will be blocked for workers at the bottom of the income scale. In the same way, the "tax wedge" between the costs of employment to the firm (wages plus payroll taxes and other mandated costs) and the benefits of employment to the worker (wages minus taxes) militates against private arrangements. So if training is under-provided, this may be the unintended consequence of other policies--and, if so, a good way to promote training would be to change those other policies.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This conclusion is reinforced when you consider the evidence of state-run training schemes in America and Europe. By and large, their record is disappointing (see <a href="sf1.html">page</a>). There are exceptions. In some ways, Germany's "dual-education system" is one--but for revealing reasons. Its success, such as it is, may have less to do with imparting valuable skills than with giving German employers cheap labour and German apprentices continuing education in very basic (as opposed to job-related) skills. The first point reaffirms the importance of a labour market that lets deals be struck between workers and employers--in a word, deregulation. The second point, echoed in many other countries, suggests that the skills which companies are unwilling to provide for themselves are the elementary ones of literacy and numeracy. In short, firms mainly want not trained workers but trainable ones.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In many countries, persistent unemployment among young people is a failure not of the training regime but of the education system. In this way, the problem of economic insecurity at the bottom of the income scale goes broader than questions of the labour market, narrowly understood. The same is true of insecurity in its other, middle-class, guise. State-run training for displaced-but-educated workers is likely, in itself, to do little the market cannot. More to the point would be measures to reduce the dread with which middle-class workers regard the possibility of a spell of unemployment. Such fears are often bound up with long-term financial arrangements. In many industrial countries, workers who lose their job see the value of their pension eroded (even if they move smartly to another firm). In countries where company-provided health insurance is the norm, even more may be at stake when a spell of unemployment looms.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Arrangements of this kind are once again partly, if not largely, the unintended consequence of other kinds of government policy. Typically, regulation has combined with personal and corporate tax rules to promote arrangements that make workers dependent on employers for more than wages. That may once have seemed in the workers' interests. It no longer does. Financial independence from one's employer is far better suited to modern conditions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Economic insecurity is a broader and subtler question than it seems at first sight. Labour ministers, with all their little fixes and palliatives, may be the people least likely to say anything wise about it. And that goes double for Europeans.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?828745200,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="sf1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
