<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw1.gif" alt="Politics"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<h2>Union meeting</h2>
<p>The <b>European Union</b>'s 15 leaders opened their inter-governmental conference in Turin to revise the Maastricht treaty and pave the way towards a larger Union of up to 27 members. Worries about Britain's beef crisis helped the leaders briefly to put aside deeper differences over how the <font size=-1>EU</font> should change.<p>
After three days of talks on the <b>mad-cow crisis</b>, <font size=-1>EU</font> farm ministers agreed to pay 70% of the costs of the slaughter of 4.6m older cattle in Britain. But they refused to lift the ban on British beef until the government proposes a more extensive slaughter policy.<p>
President Yeltsin unveiled a plan for <b>peace in Chechnya</b>. He suggested the Chechens' rebel leader, Jokar Dudaev, could be involved in negotiations and that Chechnya could have far-reaching autonomy that would still fall just short of independence.<p>An American air-force plane carrying <B>Ron Brown, America's commerce secretary,</b> was reported missing, believed crashed, over Croatia. It was on a flight from Tuzla to Dubrovnik, carrying a delegation of businessmen and government officials.<P><b>Fran&ccedil;ois L&eacuteotard</b>, a former defence minister, was elected to replace Val&eacutery Giscard d'Estaing as head of the Union for French Democracy (<font size=-1>UDF</font>), the junior partner in the ruling coalition, beating Alain Madelin, a former finance minister. Mr L&eacuteotard will now be seen as a candidate for the presidency in 2002.<p>
<b>Portugal</b>'s conservative Social Democrats, in opposition after 14 years in power, elected a new leader, Marcelo Rebelo de Sousa, following the resignation of Anibal Cavaco Silva, the country's former prime minister.<p>
The Group of Seven industrial countries, with 23m unemployed between them, met in Lille to discuss ways of <b>creating jobs</b> without letting labour standards fall. The group tried to chart a course between free-marketeers and interventionists.<p>
Complaining of a lack of provision for ex-presidents in Poland, Lech Walesa returned--in a Mercedes--to his old job in the <b>Gdansk shipyard</b>, 16 years after he left it to found the Solidarity movement that helped destroy communism in the country. The government also put part of its stake in the near-bankrupt shipyard up for sale.

<h2>Bowing out</h2>
<p>The Bangladeshi prime minister, Khaleda Zia, <b>resigned </b>and dissolved parliament, bowing to opposition demands for a general election to be held under a neutral transitional government.<p>
More than 50,000 people in <b>Hong Kong </b>applied for British travel documents on their last day of issue. The documents are an alternative to passports that will be issued by China, after the end of British rule in 1997.<p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
With President Clinton due to visit <b>Japan </b>for security talks on April 16th, the Japanese government sought to assure the Chinese that any defence agreements with America were not designed to "contain" China.<p>
An opinion poll indicated that the Congress party is likely to lose its majority in the <b>Indian general election </b>which begins on April 27th, but with a predicted 191 seats (out of 543 in the lower house) will remain the biggest party. The opposition <font size=-1>BJP</font> is expected to win 170 seats.<p>
Yoshimi Tanaka, wanted in Japan for allegedly <b>hijacking </b>a Japanese airliner to North Korea in 1970, was arrested in Pattaya, Thailand, with millions of counterfeit American dollars in his possession. Mr Tanaka tried unsuccessfully to escape to Vietnam in a North Korean embassy car.

<h2>Behemoth slims</h2>
<p>Owed $3 billion by its members and with no cash in hand, the <b>United Nations</b> is to cut its staff by 10% over the next four months and slash many programmes.<p>
With an election coming up, Shimon Peres, Israel's prime minister, promised that he would subject any final peace accord with the Palestinians to a<b> referendum</b>. Yasser Arafat claimed that this violates earlier agreements.<p>
Egypt's security court sentenced three <b>Muslim militants </b>to death for killing three policemen in southern Egypt in 1993.<p>
A delegation of Italian, Spanish and Irish officials, visiting Tehran, pressed<b> Iran</b> to condemn terrorism if its dialogue with the European Union is to continue.<p>
<b>South Africa</b> saw markets react calmly to the replacement of Chris Liebenberg, its non-political finance minister, by Trevor Manuel, an <font size=-1>ANC</font> man. The special ministry for reconstruction and development was abolished. It had not worked.<p>
Correction: 11 <font size=-1>ANC</font> supporters involved in a <b>South African</b> <b>massacre </b>mentioned here last week were the victims, not the perpetrators.

<h2>Shades of Waco</h2>
<p>For the second week, more than 100 <font size=-1>FBI</font> agents surrounded a remote ranch in Montana belonging to a militant group called the <b>Montana Freemen</b>. Randy Weaver, whose wife and son were killed in an <font size=-1>FBI</font> siege in Idaho in 1992, offered to mediate.<p>
In Caracas, 34 western-hemisphere countries put together an <b>anti-corruption convention</b>; 21 signed it.<p>
<b>Peru's</b> prime minister, Dante Cordova, resigned; seemingly, because he thought President Alberto Fujimori's market-freeing reforms were being pushed ahead too fast.<p>
<p>

</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
