<html><head><title>Triumph of the Will</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Huttonomics</b></p>
<h1>Triumph of the Will</h1>

<p>THE transformation of Will Hutton from humble television reporter to Britain's leading leftist guru took another step forward on March 29th with his appointment as editor of the<i> Observer</i>. The loss-making Sunday newspaper hopes to tap a rich vein of success. Mr Hutton's book, " The State We're In", has sold more than 125,000 copies. Many give Mr Hutton the credit for inspiring Tony Blair's big idea, the "stakeholder society".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is all very odd. Mr Hutton did not invent the stakeholder idea: it goes way back. He did not even rediscover it: the idea had never faded away. Oddest of all, given Mr Hutton's supposedly inspirational role, he and Mr Blair disagree about nearly everything. They share a preference for constitutional change and a vocation to transform all our lives for the better, but otherwise have nothing in common.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What matters about Mr Blair is his willingness to accept most of the Tories' economic reforms. By "stakeholder society", he seems to mean only that Labour will try harder to help the poor, the unemployed and the disadvantaged. He has avoided suggesting that he wants to reform the basic workings of the economy. But that is precisely what Mr Hutton advocates.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He does not mince words about this. Unimpressed by evidence that Britain's economy has become much more competitive since the 1970s, that the City of London is envied the world over and that public services have become more efficient than before, Mr Hutton argues that the country's economic, political and social institutions require far-reaching reform. So far-reaching that other countries have achieved similar change only after "defeat in war, economic collapse or revolution".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In developing these arguments, Mr Hutton's trademark is to link, and thereby explain, apparently disparate events by means of cod economic theory and an encompassing loathing for "Thatcherism", the cause of all bad things. His ingenuity in application of this method knows no bounds. He recently discussed the massacre of schoolchildren in Dunblane in the context of Britain's "winner-take-all culture", with reference to economic theories of trust. These theories are not fully bogus: he isn't just making them up. But they were devised to explain why businesses succeed, not the behaviour of homicidal maniacs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unlike Mr Blair, Mr Hutton objects to the government's anti-inflation policies. He favours a "Keynesian" fiscal boost to promote full employment. He differs, too, in regarding fundamental changes in the financing and management of firms as crucial to the creation of a stakeholder society.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In a review for <i>Prospect</i> of "The Blair Revolution", a book by Peter Mandelson and Roger Liddle (close advisers to Mr Blair), Mr Hutton approved of the authors' attacks on short-termism in the City of London, but not the "minimalist stakeholder reforms" they proposed. (They, in turn, accused him of using "pseudo-Marxist language".) He wants the state to encourage investors to act like committed long-term owners; to expand the supply of cheap, long-term debt; to make firms lower the returns they expect from investing; and to make employers more loyal to their workers. If this is stakeholding, Mr Blair wants nothing to do with it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At the<i> Observer</i> Mr Hutton has a chance to put his theories to work. Presumably, the paper's returns are already adequately low. Radical reform is bound to be needed, though, because it is always needed. The task will be to combine it with due respect for the networks of loyalty and trust that define the ethos of the institution (Fukuyama, <i>passim</i>). Radicalism without change, that is the challenge. Good luck to him.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?828745200,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
