<html><head><title>May mayhem </title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Local elections</b></p>
<h1>May mayhem </h1>


<p>BRIAN MAWHINNEY, the Tory chairman, has recently claimed that his party is on the road to electoral recovery. But some 700 Tory councillors may disagree if, as seems likely, they lose their seats in next month's local elections, for which nominations closed on April 3rd.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Despite Mr Mawhinney's heroic optimism, the Tories are facing another sharp electoral rebuke. Most of the seats up for grabs on May 2nd were last contested just four weeks after the Tory triumph in the 1992 general election. Labour then was demoralised and dejected, and the party's vote slumped. The Tories' victory was equivalent to a huge national lead of 15 percentage points, compared with eight points in the general election .
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now those Conservative gains have to be defended in a harsher political climate. Although the Tories have done better in local by-elections (see <a href="br4.html">box</a>), and although opinion polls show Labour's lead cut by three points since Christmas, Labour remains 22 points ahead.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour's performance in local elections since 1992 has yet to match its national poll ratings. But even if the gap between the two is the same this year as it was last, Labour can still expect to secure the equivalent of an 18-point national lead. That means a swing to Labour of 16.5% since the 1992 local elections. The Liberal Democrats can also expect more votes. That is why the Tories may lose as many as 700 of the 1,100 seats they are defending.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ironically, even such drastic losses will not actually shift power in many town halls. Labour already has majority control of 31 of the 36 metropolitan districts outside London where elections are taking place, and ten of the 14 new unitary councils. In the rest of the metropolitan districts no party now has overall control. But with just one-third of seats to be contested in most places, the only significant Labour gain is likely to be Trafford, a once solidly Tory suburb just south of Manchester.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the 100 less powerful non-metropolitan districts the pattern is more mixed: 36 of these are already controlled by Labour and 16 by the Liberal Democrats. The Conservatives are defending just four non-metropolitan districts, with no political party enjoying control of the rest. In three of the four, Broxbourne, Macclesfield and Runnymede, the Tory majority looks vulnerable. John Major's best hope of avoiding a wipe-out rests on the Tories' ability to cling on to his own local council, Huntingdon.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour has a good chance of wresting control of Basildon, famous as the home of upwardly-mobile "Essex man", who supposedly delivered victory to Margaret Thatcher. And the Liberal Democrats need only a small swing to win control of middle-class Tunbridge Wells, which now seems on the whole to be fairly disgusted with the Tories. With the Conservatives set for another resounding rejection by new as well as long-established Tory areas, even Mr Mawhinney must, in his heart, be wondering whether they stand a ghost of a chance at the general election.



<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?828745200,iss">Search</a>
