<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p align=center><table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" alt="Britain"></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<p><b>Terrorist ambush</b> &nbsp;
Fears of an Easter <font size=-1>IRA</font> bombing campaign led the government to rush through Parliament an anti-terrorist package giving police powers to stop and search people in the streets. The Labour leadership supported the package, but some Labour <font size=-1>MP</font>s opposed it.</p>
<p><b>Clink stink</b> &nbsp;
A report by the Board of Visitors on Holloway Prison, Britain's largest women's prison, said that inmates were locked in their cells for up to 23 hours a day and that the place was infested with rats.</p>
<p><b>Liquid gold</b> &nbsp;
The government announced plans to introduce competition into the water business. Companies other than the existing local suppliers will be allowed to serve large industrial customers, using existing suppliers' mains.</p>
<p><b>Green giant</b> &nbsp;
A new regulator, the Environment Agency, came into being. It has a staff of 9,000 and a budget of over &#163;500m a year. Lord Crickhowell, its predecessor's chairman, gave warning that it was too close to Whitehall to be managed sensibly.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Debt relief</b> &nbsp;
The government rescued the planned privatisation of British Energy by slashing the amount of debt it intends to load on the nuclear industry from &#163;1.5 billion to &#163;700m.
</P><P><b>Private on parade</b> The government revealed that in 1995-96 it signed deals worth a record &#163;4.8 billion under the private finance initiative, a scheme to fund public projects with private cash.</p>
<p><b>Death and dishonour</b> &nbsp;
Three British soldiers were found guilty of killing a Danish tour guide in Cyprus in 1994.</p>
<p><b>Soldier black</b> &nbsp;
Following a critical report by the Commission for Racial Equality, the armed forces committed themselves to a five-year programme to combat racism.</p><P><b>Sic joke</b><br>
The education department is planning a new literacy centre to combat spelling problems. It is, according to the press release, to be based on the Isle of White.

</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
