<html><head><title>The lure of distance</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>The lure of distance</h1>

NEW YORK<p><b>In general, the further a telephone call travels, the more profitable it is. Telecoms companies around the world are now scampering to take advantage of this. But how long will it last?</b></p>


<p>THIS spring the world's telephone lines are abuzz with telecoms firms whispering sweet nothings in each other's ears. In America, <font size=-1>SBC</font> Communications and Pacific Telesis, two big local telephone firms (or " Baby Bells"), are merging to create a telecoms giant worth $45 billion. Some of the other five Baby Bells--notably Nynex and Bell Atlantic--are also thought to be dialing up dates with each other. And across the Atlantic, a mooted merger between British Telecom (<font size=-1>BT</font>) and Cable and Wireless (<font size=-1>C&W</font>) would hand <font size=-1>BT</font> control of Hongkong Telecom, the island's dominant carrier, and create an Anglo-Asian colossus valued at some $55 billion.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At first glance, these appear to be very different kinds of deals, but they share a common fixation: the lure of long-distance telephony. Although the cost of transmitting a long-distance telephone call is usually no greater than that for a local call, telephone calls are priced by distance (as well as by time). In the United States, domestic long-distance calls yield gross profit margins of well over 40%, and international calls can be even more profitable. Even better, in most telephone markets, the volume of long-distance and international calls is increasing much faster than local ones.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The hitch is that this telephonic treasure trove is currently split between a series of different local, long-distance and overseas telephone companies, depending on the kind of call and the route it takes. The basic aim of the new mergers is to grab a bigger slice of revenues from each call--ideally by carrying it from end to end.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>BT</font> has been crafting a strategy to grab a larger share of international call revenues since 1993, when it paid $4.3 billion for a 20% stake in <font size=-1>MCI</font>, America's second-biggest long-distance telephone company. Since then, <font size=-1>BT</font> has formed alliances with utilities such as Viag and <font size=-1>RWE</font>, whose fibre-optic networks <font size=-1>BT</font> hopes will help it conquer the lucrative German market when Europe's telecoms industry is deregulated in 1998. Merging with <font size=-1>C&W</font>, in which Germany's fibre-optic-rich Veba has a 10.5% stake, might also help that cause. And--Hongkong Telecom aside--the deal would also allow <font size=-1>BT</font>, aided by <font size=-1>C&W</font>'s extensive undersea fibre-optic network, to win business in Asia.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>SBC</font>'s $16.7 billion takeover of PacTel, unveiled on April 1st, has a little to do with opportunism: PacTel looks weak and cheap. But the main strategic benefit will come from long-distance and international calls. A fifth of America's calls to Asia, and more than half of those to Mexico, originate on the duo's home patch--and the new group will be able to consolidate its Mexican strength thanks to <font size=-1>SBC</font>'s 10% stake in Telefonos de Mexico. At the same time, the merger will cut billing costs and other overheads, giving PacTel and <font size=-1>SBC</font> the financial muscle and economies of scale to compete in the long-distance market--and, in time, to attract an overseas partner.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Will these mergers achieve their goal? The way in which telephone revenues are shared out is a complicated business. Overseas calls are passed from one country to another according to a system of international accounting rates, which usually splits the price for handling the call between the dominant telecoms operator in each country. If there is an imbalance in payments between operators at the end of the year, a settlement is paid to even things up--usually by the firm which charges its customers the lowest rates. In America's case, its long-distance telecoms firms run a $4-billion-a-year "deficit" with the rest of the world that eats into their (still healthy) profits from the business.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is also a carve-up within America's domestic market. Of every dollar of domestic revenues the long-distance firms earn, about 45 cents is paid to the Baby Bells, which until recently had a monopoly on the local portion of each call. But since the passage of America's telecoms bill earlier this year, the Baby Bells and the long-distance carriers have been allowed to compete on each other's telephonic turf; the chief aim of both groups is to get their hands on the long-distance business.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A particular target of telecoms firms fascinated by distance are large multinational customers. After all, such companies pay hefty telephone bills to a gaggle of local and international carriers around the world. The theory: rather than deal with a dozen or more telephone firms, multinationals can simply call a single telecoms giant and sign up for both global and local services.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Internationally, the first ventures to connect with this market were Concert, <font size=-1>MCI</font>'s global alliance with <font size=-1>BT</font>, and <font size=-1>AT&T</font>'s WorldPartners alliance with Japan's <font size=-1>KDD</font> and others. In February, Sprint, America's third-biggest long-distance carrier, closed a deal to sell 10% stakes in itself to both France T&eacutel&eacutecom and Deutsche Telekom for $1.8 billion apiece. The threesome has formed Global One, selling telecoms services to clients such as <font size=-1>LVMH</font> M&ouml;et-Hennessy Louis Vuitton and the Swedish government.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In time, these ventures promise business (and, eventually, non-business) customers much more than plain old telephone services. Sprint talks excitedly about integrating products such as e-mail and voicemail. <font size=-1>MCI</font> is spicing up its services with Internet and networking products based largely on software made by Microsoft (with which it formed an alliance in January), and served up with the help of <font size=-1>SHL</font> Systemhouse, a big computer-services group <font size=-1>MCI</font> bought for $1.1 billion last November. And <font size=-1>AT&T</font>, in an on-again, off-again alliance with <font size=-1>IBM</font>, is building a host of corporate Internet services based on the Notes software developed by Big Blue's Lotus Development subsidiary.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;How much all these grand plans will ever amount to is hard to gauge. Concert earned revenues of only $228m in 1995, barely a beep in <font size=-1>MCI</font>'s and <font size=-1>BT</font>'s combined total sales of close to $40 billion. The venture does, however, have more than $1 billion-worth of contracts in the bag--although these are unlikely to turn much of a profit until the end of the decade. Global One boasts that revenues in its first year will total $800m.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>AT&T</font>'s alliance, by contrast, seems to be little more than a marketing venture. To make it pay, the company really needs to take a stake in an overseas telecoms firm. <font size=-1>AT&T</font> has shown interest in buying Britain's Mercury Communications from Cable and Wireless, which will have to sell <font size=-1>BT</font>'s biggest domestic rival if it merges with <font size=-1>BT</font>. Fearful of ending up with <font size=-1>AT&T</font> as its biggest competitor, <font size=-1>BT</font> is doing its best to make sure that Mercury gets sold to somebody--anybody--else (see <a href="wb2.html">box</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is easy to understand why ambitious telecoms giants are so enchanted by the long-distance and international market: big profits, big customers and a big pot in which to dip their greedy hands. Contrast that with local telephone services: in most rich countries these are growing slowly, if at all, and will largely remain highly regulated. Local calls may generate 50% more revenue than long-distance calls in America, but winning new growth in the market--or breaking an incumbent's stranglehold--is prohibitively expensive.
</p><p><b>The death of distance</b></b>
<br>There are, however, two big drawbacks to going long rather than local. The first is that big telecoms firms are not the only ones to have spotted the golden opportunities. One set of rivals consists of the various international "call-back" services that undercut telecoms tariffs by a huge margin. Call-back firms already sell over $300m of calls each year, mostly to the same corporate customers being courted by telecoms giants. And other cut-price rivals abound, including "systems integrators" that buy long-distance capacity in bulk from telecoms firms, reselling it to customers at big discounts, and the cable <font size=-1>TV</font> companies that are plotting to offer cheap telephone services down their lines.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, the bigger threat could be the Internet (ironically one of the areas in which every telecoms company is trying to prove its prowess). Telephone calls made over the Internet, using software such as that sold by America's VocalTec, are unlikely to prove a direct threat to telecoms companies, mainly because the Net simply does not have the capacity to handle large call volumes. But Internet calls, which cost customers the same regardless of whether they are international or local, are starting to make a nonsense of the concept of charging for distance--just as <font size=-1>PC</font>s made the idea of paying for time on a shared mainframe computer obsolete.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As more of the world's messages--be they spoken or written--are carried via a network that imposes incremental charges for neither distance nor time, the pressure on long-distance and international call tariffs will intensify. Worse, the biggest users of the Internet are the very companies telecoms firms hope will buy their new global and long-distance offerings. Add to all this the effects of competition and deregulation, and the long-distance and global telephone market starts to look less like a growth business and more like a commodity combat zone.



