<html><head><title>Made in Britain</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></p>
<h1 align=center><img src="ld1.gif" alt="Made in Britain"></h1>
THE initial shock of last week's revelations about the transmissibility of mad-cow disease to humans has faded. Unfortunately, it is giving way not to a sober assessment of choices, but to a party-political quarrel of dispiriting, albeit predictable, vapidity. The Labour Party charges the government with "reckless disregard" for public safety and excessive zeal for deregulation. The Tories reply with accusations of scaremongering. British beef is safe, the government says. To imply otherwise supposedly shows reckless disregard for the economy; with Europe ganging up on us (the European Union has imposed a worldwide ban on exports of British beef), to do so is also downright unpatriotic.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is unfair to accuse the Tories of recklessness, and fatuous to connect the <font size=-1>BSE</font> scare with deregulation. But in learning lessons from what has happened, and in deciding what to do next, the government does need to accept that mistakes have been made. This is a time when a little wisdom among Britain's political leaders would go a long way. In the past week, Britain's citizens have looked for it in vain.
</p><p><b>Past and present</b>
<br>Two questions remain uppermost in people's minds. First, did they or their families become infected with the human equivalent of <font size=-1>BSE</font> during the 1980s, before the government introduced measures to prevent suspect material entering the food chain? Second, is there still a risk from eating beef?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In answer to the first, the government has said almost nothing. This is understandable, because there is little to say that is reassuring. Too little is known about <font size=-1>BSE</font> and its human counterpart, Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (<font size=-1>CJD</font>), to tell how many people (if any) have already caught it from beef. Most experts now accept that exposure to <font size=-1>BSE</font> may cause <font size=-1>CJD</font>--the finding that sparked the current uproar--but even this is uncertain. If infection is possible, crucial questions remain. Does susceptibility depend on the victim's genetic make-up? How long and how variable is the incubation period? And so on. Without answers, there is no basis for estimating how bad an outbreak might be. Up to a point, the reasons long advanced for thinking that humans could not be infected by <font size=-1>BSE</font> suggest that an epidemic is unlikely. However, these arguments are not conclusive. Research is under way, but the answers will come slowly (see <a href="sf1.html">pages</a>). For now, the only real guide to the scale of the problem will be the rate at which new cases of anomalous <font size=-1>CJD</font> appear over the next year or two.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Has enough been done to ensure that beef is now safe? Undoubtedly, due to measures introduced in the late 1980s, it is much safer than before. The chief risk is that the new rules will not be complied with, either because of evasion or because meat for consumption becomes accidentally contaminated by infected offal (abattoirs are not operating theatres). Stricter supervision might reduce but not eliminate the first; as for the second, on any policy short of total destruction of Britain's cattle, at least some infected cows (not yet showing symptoms) will find their way into abattoirs. In short, if <font size=-1>BSE</font> causes <font size=-1>CJD</font>, there will be new victims despite the measures. But the number will be tiny in relation to the number (if any) who have already caught <font size=-1>CJD</font> from beef.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Evidently, a lot depends on what you mean by "safe". Three months ago the health secretary, Stephen Dorrell, said that "we've removed from the human food chain the organs that could conceivably be linked to a transmission". Even before last week's revelations, that was an egregious remark: it was and is conceivable that <font size=-1>BSE</font> might be transmitted not merely by contamination of otherwise safe meat but also through offal such as liver, through nervous tissue in steak, and even through milk. These last three are very, very unlikely, but that is all one can say. This week Mr Dorrell adjusted his vocabulary, and talked about "safe in the common usage of the term". On that definition, British beef probably is now safe.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This more careful use of language is welcome. If the government is to restore its credibility, it must seek chiefly to inform, not to reassure by whatever means. Yet it keeps forgetting this. The current wavering over a selective cull of Britain's cattle is being presented not as a matter of balancing cost against additional safety--which is how it should be judged--but as a question of how to "restore confidence" (see <a href="br1.html">page</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This has been the government's biggest mistake throughout. The charge of recklessness is unfair because ministers have, on the whole, reacted promptly to new scientific advice. With hindsight, they should have tried to eradicate <font size=-1>BSE</font> when it was first identified in 1986, but at the time the decision not to do so was reasonable. Even without benefit of hindsight, the government should have done more to spur research on <font size=-1>BSE</font> and <font size=-1>CJD</font>. It should have enforced its post-1986 regulations more effectively. And it should have planned for the contingency that <font size=-1>BSE</font> might after all cause <font size=-1>CJD</font>. It is astonishing that the government, if its statements of the past week are any guide, was entirely unprepared for that possibility.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These mistakes all flow from the same source: a reluctance to take seriously a tiny, but greater-than-zero, risk of a dreadful outcome. This reluctance, in turn, was presumably based on "the damage to confidence" that would result from acknowledging, exploring and discussing the risk. Apparently, despite everything, British ministers are not yet ready to abandon that attitude.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?828136800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="sf1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
