<DOCHDR>
http://www.economist.com:80/issue/30-03-96/wtw1.html 199.173.162.110 19970113172633 text/html 6684
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 17:22:48 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 08-Aug-96 14:04:00 GMT
Content-length: 6499
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw1.gif" alt="Politics"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<h2>Europe disposes</h2>
The European Union imposed a worldwide ban on exports of beef from Britain after the British government conceded a possible link between a new strain of the deadly Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease and eating beef products infected with <font size=-1>BSE</font>, known as <b>mad-cow disease</b>. British ministers claimed that the country's beef is safe. But a large part of Britain's almost 12m-strong cattle herd may have to be destroyed before the ban is lifted.
<p>An inter-governmental conference was due to open in Turin on March 29th to map out the <b>European Union's future</b>. The conference--with foreign ministers due to meet monthly--is expected to run for at least a year.
<p>The <font size=-1>IMF</font> voted to approve a $10.1 billion three-year <b>loan to Russia</b>. But it said the disbursement of the money might be halted if a future Russian government implemented "communist" economic policies. The terms of the loan oblige Russia to restrict monetary growth and to reduce import tariffs.</p>
<p>France again refused to implement the <b>Schengen agreement</b>, designed to lead to the free movement of people in Europe, citing worries about drugs coming into France from the Netherlands. Six countries are implementing the accord.</p>
<p>The position of Germany's chancellor, <b>Helmut Kohl</b>, was strengthened when the main opposition party, the Social Democrats, did badly in elections to three state parliaments. The embattled Free Democrats, junior partners with Mr Kohl's Christian Democrats in the ruling coalition, did relatively well.</p>
<p>French and German finance ministers and central bankers together proclaimed that a <b>single European currency </b>could be launched on schedule in 1999. The head of Germany's Bundesbank, Hans Tietmeyer, had recently expressed doubts that the timetable could be adhered to.</p>
<p>(See <a href="wtw1.gif">chart</a>)<br><b>Slovakia</b>'s parliament signed a friendship treaty with neighbouring <b>Hungary </b>to convince the <font size=-1>EU</font> that they will respect each other's ethnic minorities. But Slovakia also passed two repressive "anti-subversion" laws that could be used to squash dissent. Hungary also became a member of the <font size=-1>OECD</font>.
<h2>A Chinese first</h2>
Lee Teng-hui was elected president of <b>Taiwan </b>in what was called the first democratic election in 5,000 years of Chinese history. China ended its military exercises, designed to intimidate Taiwan, and America withdrew one of two aircraft carriers that had monitored the war games.</p>
<p>Civil servants in <b>Hong Kong </b>were told by China they must promise to support the puppet legislature that will replace the elected representatives when the British colony is handed over to the Chinese next year.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p>India's hopes of bringing peace to <b>Kashmir </b>suffered a blow when nine militants seeking independence for the state were shot dead at a Muslim shrine. One policeman was killed. But a police siege of the shrine was ended after negotiations.</p>
<p>France, Britain and the United States signed a treaty banning nuclear weapons from the <b>South Pacific</b>. Countries in the region signed the treaty 11 years ago.
<h2>Short on ideas</h2>
Bob Dole officially clinched the <b>Republican presidential nomination </b>with victories in primaries in California, Nevada and Washington state. But 52% of those who voted for him in California said he had no new ideas, and 45% said they wished there had been someone else on the ballot (other than Pat Buchanan, that is).</p>
<p>William Bratton, <b>New York's police commissioner</b>, is resigning to work in the private sector. In his 27 months in office, serious crime in New York has fallen by 32%.</p>
<p>Scientists began to flood the <b>Grand Canyon </b>with 117 billion gallons of water from the Colorado River in order to distribute sand and mud more evenly along the canyon floor. This "periodic disturbance" will cost $4.3m.</p>
<p>Talks reopened between <b>Guatemala</b>'s government and rebels. Both hope for a deal by September.</p>
<p><b>Brazil's</b> government celebrated two successes in Congress: the reversal of an earlier vote against its pensions reforms, and the sidelining of a banking inquiry.</p>
<p><b>Cuba</b> claimed further incursions into its airspace.
<h2>Rising tension</h2>
In <b>South Africa</b>'s turbulent KwaZulu-Natal province, a massacre cost 11 lives: <font size=-1>ANC</font> supporters were responsible, said police. The <font size=-1>ANC</font>-dominated central government banned the carrying of "traditional weapons" at rallies in many districts. Its target: Zulu supporters of the Inkatha Freedom Party. At a march in Johannesburg, they largely obeyed the ban.</p>
<p>An Israeli court sentenced <b>Yigal Amir</b> to life imprisonment for the premeditated murder of Yitzhak Rabin.</p>
<p>Iraq held a <b>parliamentary election</b>, the first since 1989, claiming that 93.5% of the electorate voted. All 160 candidates from the ruling Baath Party won seats in the powerless 220-member assembly.</p>
<p><b>Bahrain executed </b>Isa Qambar, an opposition activist, for killing a policeman last year, after a trial that Amnesty International and local lawyers said was flawed.</p>
<p>The Egyptian president, Hosni Mubarak, appointed a<b> liberal cleric</b>, Mohammad Tantawi, as grand sheikh of al-Azhar. Succeeding a hardliner, he will be spiritual guide to hundreds of millions of Sunni Muslims.</p>
<p>
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
