<html><head><title>Mad cows and Englishmen</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="sf.gif" alt="Special">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>Mad cows and Englishmen</h1>

<p><b>Ignorance and confusion surround mad-cow disease. These pages look at what is, and is not, known about it and its human equivalent</b></p>


<p>"HASTY, ill-prepared, disproportionate and unscientific." Those were the words of Britain's top vet, Keith Meldrum, condemning his European colleagues for imposing a ban on the international sale of all meat, offal, semen, embryos, and other products of British cattle. After the ban was confirmed by the European Commission on March 27th, the only people allowed to eat the roast beef of old England were the British themselves.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But Mr Meldrum's words might more aptly be applied to the whole terrible tale. Hasty and ill-prepared? The description fits the statement in the British parliament on March 20th that began the uproar. The British government has had years to prepare the public for the possibility that there is a link between Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (<font size=-1>CJD</font>), an infection that rots the human brain, and <font size=-1>BSE</font>, a fatal ailment in cattle. Yet ever since Britain's health secretary, Stephen Dorrell, announced that ten young people had contracted a new strain of <font size=-1>CJD</font> that could be related to cows, the minister has appeared like a man caught by surprise. He has spent most of his time hiding behind the advice of scientists.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Dorrell's colleague, the agriculture minister Douglas Hogg, has come out of the affair no better. Though his department has had a decade to think about how to cope with <font size=-1>BSE</font>--ever since the first case in 1986--he has lurched from one policy to another. Having first suggested that millions of British cattle might be slaughtered, Mr Hogg then appeared to back away from the possibility. Many Britons suspected that he had been overruled by a conservative government fearful of electoral and economic consequences. But after burger chains, airlines, and the farmers themselves began to call for culling older cattle, Mr Hogg looked as if he might change tack again.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Disproportionate and unscientific? That is an appropriate description of the panic that has swept Britain. One scientist has said that between 500 and 500,000 Britons could die from <font size=-1>CJD</font> each year. It would be more accurate to say that the outcome will be between zero (because no one yet knows for sure whether <font size=-1>CJD</font> can be caused by eating diseased beef) and tens of millions (that is, everyone who has eaten the stuff).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What little of sense that can be said about mad-cow disease has been buried beneath a mountain of ill-founded speculation. To help sort through the confusion, this article addresses three questions: what is known about the science involved? How does the disease spread from one species to other? And what is the link between the diseases in cattle and in humans? The box on the final page asks why is the disease concentrated in Britain? And is mad-cow disease now out of the food chain?
</p><p><b>What is known about the disease?</b>
<br>A fair amount is known about the basic science involved in both <font size=-1>CJD</font> and <font size=-1>BSE</font>. Unfortunately, the picture that emerges is extremely odd--and because of that, quick solutions to the most pressing policy problems are highly unlikely.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Both <font size=-1>CJD</font> and <font size=-1>BSE</font> belong to a rare and curious group of diseases called spongiform encephalopathies. These are scientific oddities. Other diseases are caused by bacteria and viruses, which need their own bacterial and viral proteins to survive. Such proteins can be attacked and destroyed by the host's own immune system<b>. </b>Encephalopathies are different because the infection seems to depend on the infected animal's own proteins. Lacking foreign protein, the infection remains invisible to the victim's immune system.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This group of diseases has been known for some time. The best-known human form, Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, was described early this century; another form, known as kuru, was identified in Papua New Guinea in 1957. The diseases are extremely rare: <font size=-1>CJD</font> affects about one person in a million worldwide; there have been about 2,600 cases of kuru in all. (See <a href="sf1.gif">table</a>)
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The most startling feature of the diseases was defined only as recently as 1980 by Stanley Prusiner, of the University of California, San Francisco. He argued that encephalopathies are caused by a misshapen protein called a prion. Like all proteins, prions are made by reading a genetic message, but they do not themselves contain any genetic material. The idea that something without genetic material could be infectious was regarded as heresy at the time Dr Prusiner suggested it, because something without genes could not, according to biological theory, reproduce. Some scientists still think prions may contain a tiny amount of genetic material. But most now accept that they have none.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The protein in question comes in two forms. One is healthy, produced by ordinary nerve cells in the brain. But there is another, mis-shapen variety. Dr Prusiner argued that encephalopathies are spread when the mis-shapen form wraps itself round the healthy one, converting it into another mis-shapen kind. This begins a chain reaction, destroying healthy protein and finally rotting the brain. Exactly how this happens is unclear, though research published in this week's <i>Nature</i>, a British magazine, suggests the malignant protein might stimulate the oxidation of nerve tissue. At any rate, by the end, the brain looks like a sponge, hence the term for the cattle version of the disease, bovine spongiform encephalopathy. It is possible that similar mechanisms might underlie other degenerative diseases such as Alzheimer's.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The nature of such diseases makes them hard to study. The only way to detect whether one is present in a piece of tissue is to inject it into mice and wait 700 days to see if they develop any symptoms. So research is time-consuming, and a cure will be slow to come. The mis-shapen prion resists being broken down by the cell's enzymes, or by heat or radiation. It is almost certainly resistant to vaccination. The best hope lies in finding drugs that prevent prion proteins from changing shape, hence preventing the disease from developing. Such treatment is many years away.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The peculiar nature of the diseases also explains how they spread within a species. Most cases of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, for example, seem to have occurred as a result of spontaneous mutation of the nerve cells, causing the brain to produce the malign form of prion protein. Other human forms of the disease--one called Gerstmann-Str&aumlt;ussler-Scheinker disease and another called fatal familial insomnia--are inherited. As far as is known, none of the diseases can be spread by contagion, nor through the blood, nor through sexual contact. But they can be spread by eating infected nerve cells. This is known from the outbreak of kuru among the Fore highlanders of Papua New Guinea. The disease, known as " laughing death", seems to have been spread by ritual cannibalism: the Fore honoured dead relatives by eating their brain or smearing it on their bodies.
</p><p><b>Crossing the species barrier</b></b>
<br>So diseases like <font size=-1>CJD</font> can be transmitted within a single species by eating infected nerve cells. Such diseases can also cross from one species to another.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Research by Richard Marsh of the University of Madison, Wisconsin, strongly suggests that outbreaks of encephalopathy in mink during recent decades (there have been 20 in all) were caused by feeding them meat from infected sheep or cows. Dr Marsh also thinks that some cases in America were spread to mink from cows that died on the hoof in the 1960s; if so, then very low levels of <font size=-1>BSE</font> could have long existed in America--though that has never been officially accepted. Most, if not all, encephalopathies also seem able to move to a new species if an animal gets a large enough dose.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, the vulnerability of one species to the diseases of another varies considerably. Mice can be infected with <font size=-1>BSE</font>; hamsters cannot. In Britain in 1991 it became clear that Max, a cat, had eaten up the disease with his food. Around 80 cats have followed him to the grave, but not one dog.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Perhaps most striking, the most common prion disease, scrapie (which affects sheep and goats), has been around for hundreds of years but in that time, no link has ever been shown between scrapie and <font size=-1>CJD</font>. There is no scrapie reported in Australia, but <font size=-1>CJD</font> is as common there as it is in Britain, where scrapie is rife. Farmers, abattoir workers and those eating sheep offal do not get <font size=-1>CJD</font> any more often than teachers, social workers and vegetarians (at least they did not until <font size=-1>BSE</font> came along).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In sum, while <font size=-1>CJD</font>-like diseases can spread from one species to another, the pattern is varied. Some species can get a disease. Others cannot.
</p><p><b>Can humans catch mad-cow disease?</b>
<br>Now put two questions together: if a disease like <font size=-1>CJD</font> can be transmitted by eating infected nerve cells and if such diseases can cross from one species to another, does that mean that humans could get a form of the disease from cattle? In other words, could <font size=-1>CJD</font> be caused by infected beef?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Evidence that it might emerged after ten recent cases of <font size=-1>CJD</font> were examined by James Ironside, of the Western General Hospital in Edinburgh. He says that the symptoms of the victims and the anatomy of their brains were unusual. Typically, <font size=-1>CJD</font> is a disease of old age, usually striking people older than 60. The best-known victim of the disease was George Balanchine, a Russian choreographer, who died of <font size=-1>CJD</font> at 79.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Dr Ironside found that his cases departed from this pattern. Their average age at death was only 27. Patients had taken longer than usual to die. The first symptom was a loss of co-ordination. Loss of reason and memory, which are usually seen at an early stage in the disease, occurred later on. The brains of all ten contained large quantities of identical, florid plaques that are rare in normal <font size=-1>CJD</font>. Nothing like it had been seen in people before. If <font size=-1>BSE</font> were to pass into man, it could look like this.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That is the new evidence of a link between the two diseases. It is partly circumstantial. There is also geographical evidence: this form of <font size=-1>CJD</font> is occurring in Britain, the country which has by far the largest number of cases of <font size=-1>BSE</font>. However, the fact remains that there is, as yet, no scientific proof linking human encephalopathies with their animal occurrence.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To grasp how the disease can leap easily between some species and not others, it helps to understand something of the organisation of genes and proteins. First bear in mind that genetic material is made up of twisted ladders of <font size=-1>DNA</font>. Groups of three rungs in the ladder work together to tell a cell in what order to assemble the amino acids that make up a protein.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now remember that diseases such as <font size=-1>CJD</font> develop when a malign prion protein subverts a normal one. The mechanism is not known but it is likely to happen more readily if the proteins are similar. Within one species, proteins tend to be identical. Between species, barriers exist, but at different heights. Sheep and cows, for instance, share a lot of genetic material: their prion proteins differ by only seven amino acids. That could explain why scrapie could have crossed the species barrier to infect cattle.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But human prion proteins differ from those of cattle at more than 30 places. That is why, for so many years, many scientists thought that mad-cow disease would not be transmitted to humans. This basic fact of molecular biology has not, of course, been changed by the recent outbreak of <font size=-1>CJD</font> in Britain. So if (it remains a big if), <font size=-1>BSE</font> has leaped over the species barrier to man, then it remains a scientific curiosity why the leap occurred.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is one possible explanation. It might be that certain parts of the prion-protein molecule are more important than others for breaking the species barrier. If so, and if it turns out that the prion proteins of cattle resemble those in humans at critical points, then <font size=-1>BSE</font> might sometimes be able to cross the barrier even though the genetic material of cattle and humans is so different. All that, however, is just speculation: there has been no proof.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The conclusions seem to be as follows. There is circumstantial evidence of a link between mad-cow disease and <font size=-1>CJD</font> but no scientific proof. The science does indicate where a link between the two diseases might be found, though one has not been discovered. And, the remarks of the British health minister notwithstanding, such a link is "conceivable" , if unlikely.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What does that mean for the progress of <font size=-1>CJD</font> in Britain now? To judge by other forms of the disease, this new strain has a dormant period in the body, though nobody knows how long it is, nor how it varies between infected individuals. The new cases were probably infected before 1989, when the government took steps to keep <font size=-1>BSE</font>-infected food away from humans. Infected food had been floating around for at least three years before the government acted. So even if infection is no longer occurring, there are likely to be more new cases. On the other hand, there does seem to be a species barrier (though it might sometimes be crossed). That remains the best reason for thinking that, though there will almost certainly be more cases of <font size=-1>CJD</font>, an epidemic of hundreds of thousands is extremely unlikely.

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?828136800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="sf2.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
