<html><head><title>Exam success</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>A-levels</b></p>
<h1>Exam success</h1>

<p>EDUCATION'S Mr Fixit does it again. Having already organised a truce between the government and teachers over the national curriculum for children between five and 16, Sir Ron Dearing, a former Post Office boss, has now come up with a peace plan for another educational war: reform of the exams taken by those between 16 and 19. Sir Ron's proposals, published on March 27th, contain something to please both traditionalists (academic <font size=-1>A</font>-levels will not be abolished and "general national vocational qualifications", <font size=-1>GNVQ</font>s, will be made harder) and modernisers (young people will study a wider range of subjects). Well done, Sir Ron, said the government, the opposition, employers and universities. But this does not mean that his reforms will be the last.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Sir Ron's trouble-shooting skills were certainly needed. The courses offered as stepping-stones from school to either university or work are a jumble. In particular, <font size=-1>GNVQ</font>s, introduced in 1993 as a practical alternative to academically oriented <font size=-1>A</font>-levels, have created confusion and suspicion.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some subjects, such as business, are offered as both <font size=-1>A</font>-levels and <font size=-1>GNVQ</font>s, leaving students baffled over which to take. Each <font size=-1>GNVQ</font> is supposed to be worth two <font size=-1>A</font>-levels, but few believe it. One exam-board chief has described <font size=-1>GNVQ</font>s as "a doddle". Employers and university tutors lament that even young people with top <font size=-1>A</font>-level grades are poor at communicating, worse at maths and hopeless in computing and languages.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Under Sir Ron's reforms, pupils in England, Wales and Northern Ireland will no longer have to narrow their studies to two or three subjects at the age of 16. As already happens in Scotland, for their first year in the sixth form they will be able to take perhaps five subjects, plus a course on "key skills" (communication, maths and use of computers). They will take new tests, to be called <font size=-1>AS</font>-levels, at the end of the first year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But whereas Scottish pupils go straight to university or work after taking a broad range of "highers" at age 17, those south of the border will do another year in the sixth form. They will take up to four specialist courses: traditional <font size=-1>A</font>-levels, new Applied <font size=-1>A</font>-levels (a tougher version of <font size=-1>GNVQ</font>s), super-tough <font size=-1>S</font>-levels, or a mixture. This approach gives pupils an extra year to decide which subjects to specialise in. It should reduce failures, currently 30% for <font size=-1>A</font>-levels and 40% for <font size=-1>GNVQ</font>s.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Dearing plan is a compromise. It bridges the gap between those employers and universities which wanted <font size=-1>A</font>-levels to be replaced with a broader course of study and the demands of those (including ministers) who saw them as the untouchable "gold standard" of the education system.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The traditionalists have a point. <font size=-1>A</font>-levels may be old-fashioned, but they are respected as a test of a pupil's academic capabilities, and no credible alternative has yet been established. But many employers believe that young people need a broader range of knowledge than past generations did. Even postponing the point at which pupils specialise by a further year, as proposed in these reforms, may not be enough.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Fortunately, Sir Ron has designed the new system so that it can easily be reformed again. Once the present mess is replaced by a coherent set of courses, in which academic studies and practical subjects share the same high standards, then both <font size=-1>A</font>-levels and the new Applied <font size=-1>A</font>-levels could be split up into smaller units. This would allow sixth-formers to take, say, five topics in their second year instead of two or three. The traditionalists may have won this battle. In time, the modernisers may get their way.

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?828136800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br6.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
