<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p align=center><table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" alt="Britain"></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>

</font></p></td></tr></table></center>
<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<p><b>Manifesto pledge</b> &nbsp;
Tony Blair, the Labour leader, promised a ballot of the party's 365,000 members this autumn on its general-election manifesto.</p>
<p><b>War of nerves</b> &nbsp;
Scientists investigating the "Gulf-war syndrome" found that some of those who served in the 1991 conflict do seem to have suffered damage to their nervous systems.</p>
<p><b>On the record</b> &nbsp;
The European Court of Human Rights upheld the right of journalists to protect their sources. It overturned the conviction of Bill Goodwin, a British journalist, for contempt of court after he refused to name the source of a story about a company's financial difficulties.</p>
<p><b>Asil's nadir</b> &nbsp;
Elizabeth Forsyth, a former aide to Asil Nadir, head of the collapsed Polly Peck business empire, was found guilty of handling almost &#163;400,000 stolen from the company to pay Mr Nadir's private debts.</p>
<p><b>Royal row</b> &nbsp; The queen rearranged her first visit to Poland to include a visit to a memorial to victims of Nazi death camps, after protests from Jewish leaders. But a planned tribute to Holocaust victims was accidentally left out of her speech to the Polish parliament.</p>
<p></td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<b>Schools</b> &nbsp;
Gillian Shephard, the education secretary, announced plans to give schools more control over their budgets, and to encourage them to select some pupils by ability.</p>
<p><b>Winner</b> &nbsp;
Diane Modahl, a British athlete, won a 19-month battle to clear her name when the International Amateur Athletic Federation ruled that the drug test that led to her suspension from competitions was not reliable.</p>
<p><b>The power of money</b> &nbsp;
The government offered a &#163;230m contribution to a new fund for the eventual dismantling of nuclear-power stations, to persuade investors to buy shares in the stations when they are privatised this summer.
</p>
<p><b>Corporate custody</b> &nbsp;
Thirty bosses, chosen by their staffs, agreed to spend a night in Dartmoor jail to raise money for charity.

</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
