<html><head><title>In Brief</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain">
<h2>BAGEHOT</h2></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>


<h1>Mass slaughter at Harrogate</h1>

<p>IN PRESENT circumstances, it would be a bold delegate to the Tory mid-year conference at Harrogate who greeted John Major's speech on Saturday morning with a cry of "Where's the beef?" Nevertheless, ten days with <font size=-1>BSE</font> has done terrible things to ministers. Like the poor cows on the nightly news, they twitch and stagger as they bang their deluded heads against the iron rails of public distrust. Mass slaughter would seem a mercy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In politics, when your luck's out, your luck's out; and the timing of the beef stew could hardly have been worse. Party strategists have long planned that the Harrogate conference of the party's central council would be their turning point. There, they would deploy the results of "Our Nation's Future", an elaborate year-long consultation with party members, showing (to no one's surprise) that Tory activists would like more money and less crime and better education. Then, the prime minister would unveil the corresponding themes of the election manifesto: less tax, more jail and more selective schools. Then or thenabouts, up would shoot the Tories' poll ratings.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;They need to if the next election is not to prove an abattoir for Tories. According to <font size=-1>MORI</font>'s opinion polls, Tory ratings over the year since March 1995 have reached a low of 22% and a high of 29%. The latest figure, taken as the <font size=-1>BSE</font> row raged, is 28%. Though statistical analysis shows some recovery over the period, its pace is glacial. If the election is in May 1997, and if the Tories' poll ratings recover at the same pace over the next year as they have over the past year, the party will win 32% of the vote, and fewer than 200 seats. This would be defeat on an unprecedented scale. "The cabinet hasn't realised just how bad it will be," says one senior Tory backbencher.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet recovery will at best be delayed, at worst cancelled, by the mad-cow fiasco. In the Commons, ministers adopted the brazen tactics which saw them through the Scott report on arms sales to Iraq. They blamed public alarm on the opposition. If only Labour would shut up, John Bull would go back to his beefsteak.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But what worked with Scott may not work with mad cows. Scott was about matters remote from voters' central concerns. The beef crisis is about the thing they care about most, their health. Ministers who use the Harrogate rostrum to berate Labour (and, of course, Europe) on mad cows may reckon on the applause of the party faithful. But voters may come to think that the Tories are playing politics with their lives.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That is guesswork. But the mad-cow fandango also threatens to strike a more serious blow to the Tory strategy. It could easily deprive them of what they most need, which is to recover their reputation for competence.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The British economy is doing fairly well. Production is growing. Unemployment is falling. Inflation is steady. Most European countries envy Britain's performance. The Conservatives sought to capitalise on this in a recent political broadcast, in which various foreigners said how they wished their country was doing as well as Britain. In these circumstances, the party might hope to resurrect the trusty old slogan "Don't let Labour ruin it." Ministers, led by Michael Heseltine, the deputy prime minister, still hope that rising disposable incomes over the next year will lead to rising Tory poll ratings.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But Mr Heseltine may be wrong. The Tories' problem is that the electorate is giving them no credit for economic recovery. According to <font size=-1>MORI</font> again, the link between voters' optimism about the economy and their voting intentions broke down when Britain left the European exchange-rate mechanism on "Black Wednesday" in September 1992.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nor is this surprising. The episode, when interest rates went up 5% in a day, is vividly described in Philip Stephens's new book "Politics and the Pound" (Macmillan, &#163;20). Save that Mr Stephens finds no support for the theory that the prime minister cracked up that day, his account confirms voters' fears that the government simply lost control.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Since then, they have been unwilling to give the Tories credit for anything. David Sanders, an academic at Essex University who specialises in models relating voting intentions to economic data, says that he has never had less confidence in the link between the two than he has now.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Moreover, the mad-cow storm has broken just as real voters are about to go into real polling booths to give real verdicts on the government. The Tories scarcely dare hope to win the Staffordshire South East by-election on April 11th, despite their 7,192 majority in 1992. Defeat would cut the Tory majority in the Commons to one. Time is essential for recovery, yet the loss of a further seat will make it less likely that the government can last until May 1997. Senior politicians now doubt whether the Tories can make it past the autumn.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Then there are the local elections on May 2nd. Early results from<i> The Economist</i>'s regular survey of local by-elections show some Tory recovery in January and February of this year. But March, so far, has not been so hot. Moreover, the seats up for grabs in May were last fought in May 1992, when the Tories were riding high. Large losses are inevitable.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Major relishes an uphill struggle. But to recover, the Tories need to land a treble. The economy must continue to do well; the voters must give them the credit for it doing well; and the party must persuade them that Labour would mess it up. Even before Britain went mad about mad cows, that looked a tough task. As it is, bad luck and bad management may mean that, whether or not the disease kills people, it kills the Tories' remaining chances of winning a fifth term.</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?828136800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="fn1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
