<html><head><title>An unholy mess</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Competition policy</b></p>
<h1>An unholy mess</h1>


<p>THOSE who dislike the government's approach to competition policy, ranging from the Labour Party to consumer organisations, say it is muddle-headed, weak and contradictory. The critics are about to be handed a perfect example of regulatory chaos.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Department of Trade and Industry (<font size=-1>DTI</font>) is on the point of abandoning a criminal investigation of Unilever's subsidiary, Birds Eye Wall's, for misleading the Monopolies and Mergers Commission (<font size=-1>MMC</font>). The <font size=-1>DTI</font> has been forced to abandon its investigation by the <font size=-1>MMC</font>'s refusal to accept that it was misled by Birds Eye Wall's when it cleared the company of unfair trading practices in its 1994 inquiry into the &#163;250m market for wrapped ice cream.This market for the goodies sold direct from shops' freezer cabinets, known in the trade as "impulse ice cream", is dominated by Wall's, which has a 66% share of it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>MMC</font>'s position is causing considerable friction in Whitehall, with officials from the Office of Fair Trading (<font size=-1>OFT</font>) in open disagreement with it. The <font size=-1>DTI</font> is also at loggerheads with the <font size=-1>MMC</font> because the agency has refused to supply transcripts of oral evidence given to it. These are needed to make an assessment of whether a prosecution could succeed. Officials believe the <font size=-1>MMC</font> is taking such an obdurate line because it fears that a prosecution would raise embarrassing questions about its handling of the case and the thoroughness of its procedures. The <font size=-1>MMC</font> has issued a formal statement to <i>The Economist</i> claiming that it had "co-operated fully" with the <font size=-1>OFT</font>'s and <font size=-1>DTI</font>'s investigations. Other Whitehall sources do not agree.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This internecine Whitehall dispute stems from a year-long investigation conducted by the <font size=-1>OFT</font> into complaints that an <font size=-1>MMC</font> inquiry into wrapped ice cream sales in 1994 had been derailed by false evidence. Two months ago, the <font size=-1>OFT</font> concluded that there was a <i>prima facie </i>case that Birds Eye Wall's had "knowingly or recklessly misled" the <font size=-1>MMC</font>. This is an offence under Section 93B of the 1973 Fair Trading Act. Penalties on conviction range from a fine to two years in prison, though no company has yet been prosecuted under the law.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The row arises from undertakings given by Birds Eye Wall's that retailers were "under no contractual obligation whatsoever" to obtain supplies of Wall's ice cream exclusively from the company's concessionaires. In response to the <font size=-1>MMC</font>'s concerns about its trading practices, Slaughter and May, the company's solicitors, wrote on November 26th, 1993: "Steps have been taken that no pressure will be put on retailers." On November 30th of that year, the commercial director of Birds Eye Wall's, Alan Brown, was asked by the <font size=-1>MMC</font>'s deputy chairman, Hans Liesner, what precise actions had been taken by the company. Mr Brown replied: "Instructions have gone to all the sales staff that no pressure should be put on retailers." However, last November Birds Eye Wall's admitted that no such instructions had, in fact, been given.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It was on the basis of these assurances, nevertheless, that the <font size=-1>MMC</font> found that the company's trading practices were not operating against the public interest. But when the <font size=-1>OFT</font> began an investigation, it was sent copies of more than 50 contracts, some dated as late as last year, which required retailers to purchase Wall's ice cream only from one of the company's concessionaires. It was also given statements by several concessionaires confirming that the policy was backed by senior Birds Eye Wall's directors. At a very late stage in the <font size=-1>OFT</font>'s investigation, Birds Eye Wall's conceded that the company had inadvertently misled the <font size=-1>MMC</font>. It admitted that instructions to sales staff that retailers were free to buy Wall's ice cream from any wholesaler had not been sent out until after the publication of the <font size=-1>MMC</font>'s report in March 1994.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As a result of this admission, together with the documentary evidence of the contracts, the <font size=-1>OFT</font> concluded that Birds Eye Wall's had misled the <font size=-1>MMC</font>. But at a meeting earlier this month of competition officials and lawyers called by the <font size=-1>DTI</font> to assess the evidence, Tony Nieduszynski, the <font size=-1>MMC</font>'s secretary, insisted that the commission had not been misled. He claimed that since July 1990, retailers had not been required to buy their Wall's ice cream from the firm's concessionaires even if some of the authorised distributors had acted as if there were still such an obligation.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Faced by this position and the refusal of the <font size=-1>MMC</font> to supply essential evidence, lawyers from the <font size=-1>DTI</font> have concluded that there is no basis on which a prosecution of Birds Eye Wall's can succeed. The decision, which is unlikely to be announced for some weeks, may provoke an application for judicial review of the decision by competitor companies such as Mars and Treats.

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?827532000,iss">Search</a>
