<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw2.gif" alt="Business"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<h2>Shares shake</h2>(See <a href="wtw2.gif">chart</a>)<br>Good news on American jobs confirmed <b>Wall Street's worst nightmare</b>--that the American economy was making a comeback. The biggest jump in 13 years in employment in February caused the Dow Jones to plunge by 3%, dragged down by the sharpest drop in Treasury-bond prices since the Gulf war as investors realised that interest rates, far from being cut, could now rise. A 2% jump in the Dow in the next session was the biggest one-day rise in five years, but shares remained jittery, and bond prices proved even more nervous. Asian shares, clipped by Wall Street, continued to react to Chinese war games off the coast of Taiwan.</p>
<p><b>Japan's current account </b>ran into deficit in January, the first in five years and not affected much by a change in the method of calculation. The &#165;1.9 billion ($18m) gap compares with a surplus of &#165;328.2 billion a year earlier. February is expected to be back in the black but the trend now is towards a more modest surplus.</p>
<p><b>Russia's Central Bank </b>said several of the country's big banks were in trouble. They include Natsionalny Kredit, which claimed last year to rank as Russia's 17th-biggest bank by assets; and Avtovazbank, where the central bank has taken temporary control. Sergei Dubinin, the central bank's chairman, said the banking system was caught up in a " long-lasting structural crisis".
<h2>Smoking gun</h2>
Brooke Group's Liggett broke ranks with the rest of America's dismayed <b>tobacco industry </b>and settled its part of a smoking-related lawsuit brought by five states, without either admitting or denying liability. The share prices of other tobacco firms fell.</p>
<p>The day after <b>Netscape </b>struck a deal with <b>America Online </b>to license Netscape Internet software, allowing <font size=-1>AOL</font>'s subscribers to surf the World Wide Web, <font size=-1>AOL</font> also agreed to distribute <b>Microsoft</b>'s Internet browser to 5m subscribers.</p>
<p>Shares in <b>Cable &amp; Wireless</b> rose nearly 7% after it confirmed that it had held merger talks with <b>British Telecom</b>. The talks are thought to have foundered on <font size=-1>BT</font>'s failure to agree a price for the rival telephone company which, before the news, had a stockmarket capitalisation of &#163;10 billion ($15.3 billion).</p>
<p>America's <b>Williamette</b> agreed to pay $1.6 billion for the remaining timber interests of <b>Hanson</b>, a British industrial conglomerate in the process of demerging. The deal includes 440,000 hectares (1.1m acres), mainly in the Pacific north-west region.</p>
<p></td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>South Africa's biggest firm, <b>Anglo American</b>, bought 5.9% of <b>Lonrho</b>, a British conglomerate.</p>

<p><b>Germany's chemicals giants</b> reported record profits in 1995 and big boosts in their dividends. The biggest, Hoechst, produced a net profit up 65% to DM2.25 billion ($1.57 billion)</p>
<p>Bahrain-based Investcorp is poised to sell its 51.8% stake in <b>Gucci</b>, whose latest net profits, for the year to end-January ($81.4m compared with $17.3m a year earlier), suggest that the Italian maker of swanky clothes has returned to form. Since last October's public offering by Investcorp of 48.2% of its stake, the price of Gucci shares has nearly doubled.
<h2>All change</h2>
In a big shake-up at America's largest mutual-funds company, <b>Fidelity Investments</b> shuffled 26 equity-portfolio managers--nearly a third of them--to boost poorly performing portfolios.</p>
<p><b>Unilever</b> announced a far-reaching change in its management structure, designed, it said, to separate strategic leadership from routine business operations. But the Anglo-Dutch consumer group said it had decided against a break-up.</p>
<p>Soci&eacutet&eacute G&eacuten&eacuterale, a French bank, asked the European Court of Justice to block the FFr45 billion ($8.9 billion) <font size=-1>EU</font>-approved rescue plan for <b>Cr&eacutedit Lyonnais</b>, a state-owned rival that landed in trouble after reckless expansion at the end of the 1980s. Soci&eacutet&eacute G&eacuten&eacuterale said that it is willing to drop its case if the aid is limited.</p>
<p>One Cr&eacutedit Lyonnais property is <b>MGM</b>. The reinvigorated Hollywod studio was officially put up for auction with the hope of fetching $1.5 billion-2.5 billion.
<h2>Going nowhere</h2>
<b>Alitalia</b>'s chairman, Renato Riverso, gave up his attempt to restructure the crippled state-owned airline, with a warning that there should be no sell-out to the unions. But his replacement, Fausto Cereti, and the new chief executive, Domenico Cempella, immediately resumed talks with unions as Alitalia confirmed its 1995 losses could come to 250 billion lire ($154m).</p>
<p>General Motors filed an <b>industrial-espionage lawsuit </b>in Detroit against Volkswagen alleging that a former purchasing executive at <font size=-1>GM</font>, Jose Ignacio Lopez, took quantities of secret documents with him when he defected to <font size=-1>VW</font>.</p>
<p>After flagging <b>car sales </b>in the latter half of 1995, new registrations in Western Europe rose nearly 9% in January and February over the same two months last year. Fresh incentives in France brought an 18% increase in car sales in France. Germany also saw a near 11% gain. Britain, with 2%, registered one of the lowest rises.</p>
<p></p>
</td></tr></table></center>
