<html><head><title>Taiwan votes, China thunders</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/as.gif" alt="Asia">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>Taiwan votes, China thunders</h1>

<p><font size=1>TAIPEI
</font></p><p>THE bomb shelters in Taipei are being cleared of rubbish, and yellow stickers have appeared with directions towards improvised sanctuaries. There is no panic yet in Taiwan, but many Taiwanese are taking the precaution of converting their money into dollars and most flights out of the country are fully booked. The government is propping up the local stockmarket to the tune of $200m a day.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The source of the scare lies offshore in the Taiwan Strait, where China's military exercises reflect the rage of the Communist leadership in Beijing. China regards Taiwan as a rebellious province and fears it is moving towards a declaration of independence. Yet for all the alarm in Taiwan, the island is determinedly pressing ahead with its presidential election on March 23rd and seems likely to elect Lee Teng-hui, the main object of China's fury.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is not only Taiwan that is on edge. Just two months ago America's navy called in to Shanghai, for its first visit to China in seven years. Now it is deploying the largest naval task-force it has assembled in the Pacific since the Vietnam war, including two aircraft carriers, in an effort to deter Chinese threats.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The outside world, and indeed the Taiwanese, have consistently underestimated the lengths to which China is prepared to go in "striving for an early reunification of the motherland". Few thought that China's military exercises would extend to a partial blockade of Taiwan. When they did, calming voices murmured that the fuss would all die down after the Taiwanese election. Now, however, China is promising yet more, unspecified, war games after the election. After all, Mr Lee is odds-on to win.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nobody in authority, on either side of the strait, is willing to suggest that China is close to war with Taiwan, let alone with America. Even China's generals have admitted that their army lacks the means to wage a modern war against Taiwan. China has six times as many men under arms as Taiwan's 400,000, and ten times as many fighter aircraft and submarines. Yet Taiwan has a technological edge.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A quarter of Taiwan's government budget is spent on its armed forces, with their electronic-surveillance devices, anti-aircraft and anti-ship defences, and modern (compared with China's Vietnam-era air force) fighters. It is reckoned that, were it to launch an invasion, China could land only 30,000 troops at a time, and without the benefit of air superiority. An attempted invasion would be horribly bloody.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although Taiwan could probably stave off all but the most determined attack, the costs to the island would be severe. That is why Taiwan has long accompanied its high-tech deterrence with repeated assurances to the mainland that it is not set on a course of independence. Yet no one can be sure that China's actions will not get out of hand. China might choose, not an invasion, but a symbolic land-grab of one of Taiwan's many outlying islands. It might choose to turn a partial blockade into a full one: Taiwan, which relies upon open sea-lanes for its imports of oil, coal and steel, and for its exports of finished goods, would be hobbled overnight. Even a misguided missile, if it fell on Taiwan, could be expected to provoke a military response, with dangerous consequences for the region's peace.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;China insists it has no ulterior motive other than to "struggle against the plot of splittism by some leaders" of Taiwan. Yet China's rhetoric risks boxing in its own leaders as much as it is meant to box in Taiwan's. President Jiang Zemin and his colleagues in Beijing used to assure Taiwan that only if certain unwelcome conditions were met would force be used against it. The two conditions most often cited were foreign intervention in Taiwan, and a declaration of Taiwanese independence. But China has recently begun to emphasise other much more subjective criteria, such as "civil chaos" in Taiwan. Chi Haotian, China's defence minister, even spoke recently of the need for the "liberation" of Taiwan--language not heard from a Chinese official for over a decade.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;China wants to secure its political goals by military threats. But such tactics may backfire. They have already provoked the foreign intervention that China is always warning against. And Chinese efforts to ward off Taiwanese independence may prove even more counter-productive.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;China has branded President Lee the "harlot of history" for his supposedly splittist tendencies. Its leaders appear intent on isolating Mr Lee--much as they earlier isolated Hong Kong's governor, Chris Patten--with the pretence that only he thinks treacherous thoughts. Mr Lee may indeed meet China's splittist criteria, in that he wants more international recognition of Taiwan, including a seat at the <font size=-1>UN</font>. But he does so in response to the desires of the broad mass of Taiwan's electorate. And the more that China bullies Mr Lee, the more the voters are heading for the Lee camp. The greatest risk to regional peace is an Olympian clash between the 500-odd Communist diehards who run China and 21m turbulent free-thinkers in Taiwan.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As it is, the Chinese threat has displaced all other issues in Taiwan's presidential race. Indeed, of the three presidential candidates, only Mr Lee of the ruling Kuomintang speaks of anything other than relations with China and how to extricate Taiwan from the current crisis.
</p><p><b>No rush to go it alone</b></b>
<br>On the China issue, there are three attitudes. Mr Lee argues against making concessions to the mainland, just for the sake of rapprochement. His long-standing foreign minister, Fredrick Chien, put it most forcefully this week. China, he said,<ul><font size=-1>could not care less about world public opinion; that is a sign of a hegemonical power. It tries to dictate foreign policy to us; that's another sign of hegemonical power... The world today must not accommodate such a creature. No government can afford to conduct negotiations under duress.
</font></ul>Even so, Mr Chien argues for Taiwanese self-restraint.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Peng Ming-min, the candidate of the Democratic Progressive Party, the biggest opposition group, is more inclined to give the finger to China and damn the torpedoes, which the party does not believe would be fired even if the island did declare independence. On March 12th Mr Peng's party boss, Shih Ming-teh, led two boatloads out to the rough waters on the edge of China's north-eastern target zone. Two acts of defiance followed. Mr Shih burnt Communist China's flag. And the stomach contents of the assembled members of the world's press rebuked gravity.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Lin Yang-kang, a former Kuomintang official, is the most pro-China of the three presidential candidates. Mr Lin and his running-mate, Hau Pei-tsun, once a military man, were booted out of the party last year. They now enjoy the support of the New Party, a splinter-group dedicated to reunification. But not even the New Party expects this to happen soon; its deadline is 50 years. Two parliamentary candidates who campaigned for election last December promoting the only formula that China will consider for reunification--" one country, two systems"--fared poorly, each winning barely 1,000 votes. So Mr Lin is careful to talk of a Chinese commonwealth in which neither side has the upper hand.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Those espousing wholesale independence are also finding it hard to gather votes. The Democratic Progressive Party's leaders have toned down their pro-independence line in recent months. They point out that Taiwan is already <i>de facto</i> independent, if only the rest of the world would recognise it as such. That is, in effect, what Mr Lee's Kuomintang also believes. The only real difference is whether the country should be called the Republic of Taiwan (the opposition party's wish) or the Republic of China.
</p><p><b>Any way out?</b>
<br>Joseph Wu, of the Institute of International Relations in Taipei, reckons that no more than a quarter of Taiwan's electorate is ardently for independence, and at most a quarter is for reunification. The great mass prefer the status quo: <i>de facto</i> independence coupled with a push for greater international recognition. That mass will vote for Mr Lee on March 23rd.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If Mr Lee is indeed victorious, he will face a heavy responsibility. And quite how this private and stubborn man will behave, even his closest supporters dare not guess. Some believe that he will press ahead with his campaign to raise Taiwan's profile, regardless of the reaction on the mainland. But most people think he will have to try to reduce tensions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;How might he achieve that? China's foreign minister, Qian Qichen, says that relations cannot improve unless Taiwan drops its bid for a <font size=-1>UN</font> seat and, by extension, its multi-billion-dollar policy of "pragmatic diplomacy". But it might well be political suicide for Mr Lee to bow to Mr Qian's will. Taiwanese know that China has, in the recent past, given the nod to formulas designed to give Taiwan the space it craves, for example, through its presence at meetings of the Asia-Pacific Economic Co-operation forum. Taiwan simply wants more of the same.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And the Taiwanese have some cards to play. China, even as it waves its fist, still has its other hand out for Taiwanese investment. This strikes many Taiwanese as the height of cheek. Policymakers point out that there are plenty of other places in South-East Asia, and even in Eastern Europe, where Taiwanese could invest.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The growing gap between the two societies, and between governments on either side of the Strait, will make it extremely difficult to restore calm. But it is clear that if the crisis is to be defused the two sides will have to start talking again. Cross-strait talks were rudely broken off by China last year, after Mr Lee made a "private visit" to America, to visit his old university.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet there is a belief, even in Taiwan, that the talks, which had begun a few years earlier, were not being taken seriously enough by the Taiwanese side. They were meant to get down to details on such matters as fishing rights. China hoped they would then encompass bigger issues like sovereignty, but they got nowhere close. Even China's long-demanded "three links"--by air, by sea and by post--were not broached. It is possible that, if Taiwan were to make concessions on the "three links", tensions might ease.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Taiwanese may suspect that nothing short of reunification on China's terms will ever satisfy Beijing. But talking is probably still Taiwan's best option.

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,iss">Search</a>
