<html><head><title>Dial M for mortgage</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Building societies</b></p>
<h1>Dial M for mortgage</h1>

<p>THE effects of the price war between the building societies, the banks and a new breed of telephone mortgage-sellers are beginning to be felt. Banks' share prices fell sharply on March 12th after the telephone-sales offshoot of Bradford &amp; Bingley cut its mortgage rate to just 5.99%, compared with most lenders' standard rate of 7.25%. But this is only the beginning. Among building societies in particular, costs will have to be reduced, branches closed and jobs cut before the war is over.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Earlier this month, the Bank of England said it was worried that this competition was driving banks to accept dangerously thin profits. And a report last month by Bob Pannell, an economist at the Council of Mortgage Lenders, shows that home owners are increasingly fickle. In the two years to September 1995, remortgages (loans that are changed without the borrower moving home) rose from 11% to 28% of all mortgage lending. According to Mr Pannell, home owners increasingly think of mortgages as consumer goods bought on price, not brand loyalty.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With several of the largest building societies about to be floated on the stockmarket or taken over, resulting in handouts worth hundreds of pounds for their customers, many home owners may be staying " loyal" to their present lender only until they collect this bounty. After that, they will transfer to a cheaper lender.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So it is likely to become harder still for the high-street branches of banks and building societies to fend off the new telephone-based mortgage sellers, such as Direct Line, a subsidiary of Royal Bank of Scotland. Direct Line has already cut a swathe through the insurance industry with its cut-price policies. Selling mortgages over the telephone is cheap. An analysis last year by Merrill Lynch, an investment bank, found that Direct Line's staff could each sell 30-40 times as many mortgages as their equivalents in building-society branches.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So far, the telephone-based sellers have a tiny share of the market: Direct Line has lent only about &#163;350m, or less than 0.1% of Britain's total household mortgages. But this share will grow quickly: some building societies, including Bradford &amp; Bingley and Nationwide, have now decided to fight fire with fire and set up their own telephone-sales operations.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unlike the foreign banks which entered the British mortgage market in the 1980s only to get their fingers burnt as bad debts mounted, the new telephone-based sellers are concentrating on poaching the most creditworthy customers. They are also offering savings accounts. That will lessen their dependence on financial markets for funding, and in the process take a slice of the building societies' other main market.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Most building societies are highly profitable and have plenty of spare capital. This reduces the pressure on them to close branches in order to remain competitive. But their hands may be forced by the threat of takeover. Management at National &amp; Provincial agreed to takeover talks with Abbey National after realising that, whether they approved of the bid or not, their customers would probably accept the Abbey's terms, worth up to &#163;4,250 each. A new building-societies bill, to be published on March 18th, will not contain the further protection against hostile bidders that societies had campaigned for.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The banks cut around 70,000 jobs between 1989 and 1994, and closed 18% of their branches. Though the building societies closed around 12% of their branches in the same period, their staff numbers continued to rise until 1993 as they entered new areas of business such as estate agency and life assurance. Adrian Coles, director-general of the Building Societies Association, admits that branches and jobs will continue to be cut, though he is unsure by how much. A glance at any of Britain's town centres shows the answer only too clearly: high streets containing a dozen or more branches of banks and building societies are not uncommon. That will change.

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826927200,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br2.html">Next article</a>
</p>
