<html><head><title>The peace process at breaking-point</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/ir.gif" alt="International">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>The peace process at breaking-point</h1><p><font size=1>JERUSALEM</font></p><p>ISRAELI-PALESTINIAN peace, and the political lives both of Shimon Peres and of Yasser Arafat, on which at present it seems to depend, hang together by the slenderest of threads after the latest suicide-bombings in Jerusalem and Tel Aviv.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Peres is trying to rescue things by waging what he calls " total war" against Islamic militants without, he hopes, sweeping away Mr Arafat's infant self-government. The choice, says Mr Peres, is Mr Arafat's: if he commits his forces to the battle against Hamas and Islamic Jihad, Israel will not send its troops back into the Gaza strip and most West Bank towns. So long as that step is avoided, Mr Peres argues, the peace process can be kept alive and Mr Arafat's rule preserved. Perhaps, but as Palestinian opinion swings from revulsion at the bombings to anger at the new security measures, Mr Arafat is wholly insecure.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Peres himself has not much choice. The Jerusalem bus-bomb on March 3rd, killing 19 people, revived all the Israeli anger of the previous week. Within a day, a Tel Aviv shopping mall was the target, and 14 more people were dead. In rural Palestinian areas, where Israel still has "overall security responsibility", male relatives of suspects were arrested by Israeli troops, and family homes were sealed, to be demolished after a summary legal process. Movement within the West Bank was barred except for a short break on March 7th to allow people to shop, and members of the Palestinian Council to go to Gaza for its first session. Six Islamic colleges and charities have been shut, including the Islamic University in Hebron; ten more institutions may be closed in Jerusalem. The cabinet is considering deporting Hamas activists.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Arafat's Palestinian Authority, for its part, has arrested some 350 Islamist suspects, including four of the 13 men on Israel's "most wanted" list. Its security forces conducted house-to-house searches in Ramallah, Bethlehem and Gaza, where they raided the Islamic University, a Hamas bastion. Mr Arafat had some success in persuading Hamas's civilian leaders that they must call off terror or be outlawed as a political organisation. "In the name of God," said one in Jerusalem, "we implore you to stop these atrocious acts if only to preserve the achievements of the Palestinian people." A March 6th communiqu&eacute from Hamas's military arm, Izzadin al-Qassam, said it was willing to hand in its arms. But communiqu&eacutes have been contradictory--nor do the Israelis believe the bombers came from the mainstream militia.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet Mr Arafat, say the Israelis, is not doing enough. The foreign minister, Ehud Barak, passed him a message, through the visiting president of the European Union's Council of Ministers, that he now had his "last chance" to make a convincing move against Islamic terrorism. Israeli officials feel that, despite all that has happened and the readiness of Mr Arafat's police to work together with Israeli troops, the Palestinian leaders still do not understand the depth of the crisis in Israel or the tenuousness of Mr Peres's authority.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The mood in Israel is so grim that one commentator could write in his newspaper that what Mr Peres needs, if he is to win the election on May 29th, is for Mr Arafat to hang half-a-dozen Hamas terrorists in Gaza's main square. The four suicide-bombings in ten days, taking at least 60 lives, have cast a pall of fear on the country, made worse when reports came out that the man who had driven the Tel Aviv bomber from Gaza was an Arab Israeli. Many people are afraid to take buses. Some are even afraid to drive their cars alongside buses. As a result, a wartime emptiness pervades the streets of Jerusalem and Tel Aviv.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Old-timers hark back to the outbreak of the Yom Kippur war in October 1973, when Egypt and Syria launched a devastating surprise attack. Then too a dearth of intelligence information left Israelis feeling unprotected in the face of deadly blows. In an unvarnished report to the Knesset's defence committee on March 4th, the head of the Shin Bet security service admitted that he did not know where some of the bombers were coming from, and therefore could not strike at the men behind them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For the Likud opposition, now soaring ahead in the opinion polls, the admission was electoral manna. Likud leaders have insisted throughout the peace process that withdrawal from Gaza and the big West Bank towns would leave Israel ignorant of what the Islamists were plotting.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Labour government counters that there was terrorism when Israel occupied all the territories. The Palestinian Authority, co-operating with the Israelis, has in fact foiled some attacks, and even the Likud is not advocating a return to Gaza or Nablus. But this logic rings hollow when, day after day, cemeteries are filled with traumatised mourners.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Politically, the question now is not whether Mr Peres will win the election, but whether his government can, or should, survive until then. The historical analogy for many Israelis is again a war: the tense waiting period in 1967 when the prime minister of the day, Levi Eshkol, was seen to be hesitant and began losing public confidence. Mr Peres, then secretary-general of an opposition party, Rafi, manoeuvred for the creation of a government of national unity. Eventually, his party chief, Moshe Dayan, was co-opted by a reluctant Eshkol as minister of defence, and went on to take much of the glory for the six-day war. Now Mr Peres finds himself in Eshkol's role.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;His own old role is being played by Ariel Sharon, a former defence minister and Likud hardliner, who is campaigning for "a government of national emergency" to be installed for one year with an overarching mandate to fight terrorism. Mr Sharon has not pleased his party leader, Binyamin Netanyahu, who is loth to see the elections deferred and finds no reason to join Mr Peres's beleaguered government.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Sharon's many enemies, in Labour and the Likud, suspect that the old warrior is hoping for a short-cut back to power for himself (he lost the defence ministry in 1983, after two notorious massacres of Palestinians by Lebanese Christians in Israeli-held parts of Beirut). One more suicide-bomb, it is argued, could generate the kind of outcry that would oblige Mr Peres to step down. Mr Sharon, if he were in the government, might, at a pinch, become a panic-stricken public's choice.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Partly to head off any such thing, senior Labour people are urging Mr Peres to appoint Mr Barak as defence minister, instead of continuing to hold that portfolio himself. Some are even saying, privately, that Mr Peres should stand down in Mr Barak's favour. As a former military man, Mr Barak might be better placed to win the election. But Mr Peres, glummer-looking than ever, is still determined to lead the fight himself: both against terrorists and against the Likud.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826322400,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
