<html><head><title>Home cheap home</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>


<h1>Home cheap home</h1>

GIVEN the number of false starts in the housing market in recent years, it is a rash economist who proclaims that the real thing is here at last. However, the Halifax, Britain's largest mortgage lender, said on March 5th that its house-prices index rose by 0.9% in February, the seventh successive monthly increase. Bank of England figures show that mortgages worth &#163;3.6 billion were arranged in January, up 14% on a year earlier. And there is another good reason for optimism: a forecast by the <font size=-1>TSB</font> bank that by the end of this year, even though prices will continue to rise, houses will be at their most affordable since 1978.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>TSB</font>'s affordability index (see <a href="br1.gif">chart</a>) measures how much of a typical buyer's take-home pay is needed to meet the mortgage repayments on an average-priced home. So it takes into account taxes and interest rates as well as incomes and property prices. The <font size=-1>TSB</font> reckons the current cost is &#163;28.60 for each &#163;100 of a single earner's net pay, and forecasts that the figure will fall to &#163;25.70 this year. In fact, homes may be even more affordable than the index shows because it is based on lenders' standard mortgage rates and does not allow for the huge discounts and cashback deals that many are offering.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But these are only the first signs of spring. Prices are still about 12% below their peak. Around 1m people are reckoned to have negative equity (mortgages larger than the current value of their homes), which makes it difficult for them to move house even if they want to. Estate agents should not crack open the Bollinger just yet.

</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826322400,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
