<html><head><title>Sale time</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Local government</b></p>
<h1>Sale time</h1>

<p>ONE of Britain's largest local authorities is preparing to hand over its blue-collar services, from cleaning to housing maintenance, to a private company. This huge privatisation, which is likely to be announced in the next month, would be something to notice even if the council in question were deep-blue Conservative. When you consider that it is in fact Lambeth in south London, once a stronghold of far-left Labour politics, and where Labour is still the biggest party, it is little short of revolutionary.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Many councils have hived off services in a piecemeal way following the government's introduction of compulsory competitive tendering (<font size=-1>CCT</font>) for local-authority services from 1980 on. However, <font size=-1>CCT</font> has drawbacks, including bulky paperwork in preparing contracts with suppliers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Lambeth, plagued by inefficiency and corruption, has hit on its novel approach in an attempt to break with the past. The council, with the support of the Department of the Environment, intends to transfer the provision of services to a company in which the authority will retain perhaps a 20% share. It hopes to model its relationship with the new company on the co-operative relationship between Marks and Spencer, a retailer, and its suppliers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The new initiative symbolises the wind of change blowing through the council, now being turned upside down by a new chief executive, Heather Rabbatts. It follows the local elections of 1994, when Labour was rudely shocked to lose its majority. Liberal Democrats made 20 net gains on the council of 64, taking safe Labour seats where tenants on the council's neglected estates vented their frustration on local councillors.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The council remains hung and without a political leader. Committees are chaired by rotation between the parties. Leadership comes from Ms Rabbatts.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ms Rabbatts was recruited at a time when the council had "one of the worst reputations of any in the <font size=-1>UK</font>"--and that was a quotation from the advertisement for her job. "The organisation had ceased to exist. There is a consensus that Lambeth needs to be sorted," she says. Already she has replaced her top management team; taken 120 staff to court charged with benefit fraud; and forced staff to pass competency tests to keep their jobs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Under previous management, the District Auditor who monitors the council had issued 17 public-interest reports on its shortcomings in 12 years. But in January, the auditor's annual management letter noted "a genuine commitment to securing beneficial change."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On March 6th, Lambeth decided to cut its council tax for next year by &#163;2 a week for a mid-range property. That will mean cuts in spending of &#163;33m on a budget of &#163;315m. Meanwhile adverts in local newspapers threaten court summonses, bailiffs and even prison for council-tax defaulters, marking the end of an era in which paying tax in Lambeth was optional--and its council was a national joke.

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?826322400,iss">Search</a>
