<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p align=center><table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" alt="Britain"></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<p><b>Rights and wrongs</b> &nbsp;
The government is considering removing the employment rights of the millions of people who work for small firms, a leaked letter between ministers revealed. Ian Lang, trade and industry secretary, wrote to Michael Heseltine, deputy prime minister, expressing " grave doubts" about the proposal.</p>
<p><b>No gays</b> &nbsp;
Nicholas Soames, the armed-forces minister, said the government would fight "tooth and nail" to keep the ban on homosexuals in the services, after a survey showed overwhelming support for the ban in the armed forces.</p>
<p><b>Classroom crackdown</b> &nbsp;
The government said police would be given powers to stop and search children for weapons in schools, and promised &#163;18m for "hit squads" of discipline experts who would visit schools with disruptive pupils.</p>
<p><b>Fraud fears</b> &nbsp;
Ministry of Defence police raided the offices of Tarmac and Matthew Hall, two construction firms, as part of investigations into alleged financial irregularities on a large construction project at the Coulport nuclear-weapons depot on Clydeside.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Howard judged</b> &nbsp;
Judge David Pearl, the chief immigration adjudicator, overruled a decision by Michael Howard, the home secretary, to deport Muhammad Massari, a leading Saudi dissident, to Dominica.</p>
<p><b>It's a gas</b> &nbsp;
British police used <font size=-1>CS</font> gas spray for the first time, in an incident outside a nightclub in Oldham, Greater Manchester in which Barrie McDermott, a rugby-league international, was arrested.</p>
<p><b>Saved</b> &nbsp;
After a revolt in the House of Lords, the government agreed to ban satellite-television channels from buying up exclusive coverage of eight leading sporting events, including the <font size=-1>FA</font> Cup Final and the Grand National.</p>
<p><b>Holy orders</b> &nbsp;
The Vatican ordered a hundred pairs of "Doc Martens" boots from their makers, R. Griggs of Northampton, including a pair for the pope--in white, to match his vestments.
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
