<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></p><p align=center><img src="../images/wtw2.gif" alt="Business"></p><center><p align=center><hr size=6 align=center width=65%><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%><h2>Chasm</h2><p>(<a href="wtw1.gif">See chart</a>)<br><b>America's deficit</b> on trade in goods and services in 1995 was at its widest in seven years. Although the gap with Japan narrowed for the first time in five years, dropping nearly 10% to $59 billion, its deficit with China grew by 14.6% to $34 billion, and its surplus of $1.4 billion with Mexico in 1994 turned into a $16.2 billion deficit.</p><p><b>Growth in America </b>last year, at 2.1%, was at its most sluggish since the recession of 1990-91. It slowed in the fourth quarter to an annualised 0.9%, half the expected rate and down from 3.6% in the third quarter. January was better; retail sales fell only 0.3% despite heavy snows, and consumer confidence rose in February.</p><p>For the third year in a row, household spending in <b>Japan </b>declined, falling by 1.1% in 1995. But there was some good news: industrial production rose last year by 3.3%, and in January department-store sales rose 5.4%, the biggest rise in nearly five years.<ro><h2>Networking</h2>In the biggest merger yet between a Baby Bell and a cable-<font size=-1>TV</font> business, <b>US West</b> agreed to pay $5.3 billion for <b>Continental Cablevision</b> and assume $5.5 billion in debt to gain access to more than 4m potential new subscribers across 11 states. The merger is the first of its kind since sweeping changes in the law regulating America's telephone and television markets.</p><p><b>British Petroleum</b> and <b>Mobil</b> are responding to overcapacity in refining and a price war in petrol by merging their lubricants and refining operations in Europe, businesses with combined annual sales of $20 billion.</p><p>In a rare French demerger, <b>Chargeurs</b> is to split itself into two publicly quoted companies, with Path&eacute retaining the film, <font size=-1>TV</font> and newspaper operations, including a 17% stake in <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font>, and Chargeurs International running the textile and distribution businesses.</p><p><b>De Beers</b> strengthened an agreement with Russia to buy its rough diamonds. Previously, loopholes allowed Russia to keep many of the best gems for itself and to sell others direct to the world market, by-passing De Beers; under the new deal Russia could keep more stones, but of a wider quality. In exchange De Beers will pay Russia some $2 billion a year.</p><p><b>Kvaerner</b>, a Norwegian ship builder, is considering a bid for <b>Trafalgar House</b>,a loss-making British construction-to-shipping conglomerate.</p><p>California's <b>Silicon Graphics</b>, under pressure in its <font size=-1>PC</font> business, has decided to push into the higher end of the computer business. It is buying <b>Cray Research</b>, a struggling maker of supercomputers, for a modest $770m or so. This should create the world's leading supercomputer company.</p></td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%><p>A Canadian publishing and travel firm, <b>Thomson</b>, is to pay $3.43 billion for West Publishing to expand its American legal-publishing operations.</p><p>Acquisitive <b>Heineken</b> completed its purchase of <b>Birra Moretti </b>from Belgium's Interbrew for around $170m to give the Dutch brewer the top spot in Italy with nearly 40% of the beer market.<ro><h2>Housekeeping</h2><b>Tokai Bank</b> of Japan will write off its &#165;800 billion ($7.7 billion) or so of bad loans in the current financial year. In the year to end-March it expects to declare a net loss of &#165;350 billion compared with a profit of &#165;21 billion the year before.</p><p>An American court found <b>Daiwa Bank</b> guilty of conspiracy, fraud and obstruction, and imposed a $340m criminal fine. The Japanese bank had originally denied trying to conceal losses of more than $1 billion from regulators. It later changed its plea to guilty.</p><p>Britain's <b>Barclays Bank</b> declared a 12% rise in pre-tax profits last year to &#163;2.08 billion ($3.28 billion). But the markets were disappointed by a 5% drop in operating profits to &#163;2.25 billion, with operating costs up 9.4%. Barclays then spent &#163;306m on buying back 40m of its shares, equal to 2.5% of its total capital; a few months ago it bought back 25m shares.</p><p><b>Groupe Paribas</b>, a French bank holding company, announced losses of FFr4 billion ($802m) last year, compared with a profit of FFr1.7 billion in 1994. The loss was due to provisions against losses in property, industrial holdings and a retail-banking subsidiary.<ro><h2>Air currents</h2>State-owned <b>Sabena </b>of Belgium ousted the chief executive, Pierre Godfroid, and gave the job to Paul Reutlinger of <b>Swissair</b>, which took a 49.5% stake in the airline last summer. Sabena lost BFr530m ($18m) in 1995, after losing BFr1.2 billion the year before.</p><p>Philip Condit is to become the seventh chief executive in <b>Boeing</b>'s 80-year history, replacing Frank Shrontz, who will remain as chairman.</p><p>Germany's biggest shipbuilder won a stay of execution from its creditor banks. Over the next two months <b>Bremer Vulkan</b> will get a modest DM100m ($68m) or so--the group lost around DM1 billion last year--while management comes up with a restructuring plan.</p><p>Italy's <b>Gianni Agnelli</b> retired only two weeks before his 75th birthday as chairman of the Fiat industrial group.</p><p><b>Jimmy Lai</b>, a controversial Hong Kong publisher, sold for $189m his remaining 27% in Giordano, a fast-growing clothing chain he founded in 1980. Giordano's main store in Beijing was closed after Mr Lai described China's premier, Li Peng, as a moron.</p><p></p></td></tr></table></p></center><p align=center><a href="wtw1.html">POLITICS THIS WEEK</a></p><br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?825717600,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="ld1.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
