<html><head><title>Arafat's dilemma</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/ir.gif" alt="Section heading"><td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table><h1>Arafat's dilemma</h1><p><font size=1>GAZA</font></p><p>YASSER ARAFAT was swift to condemn the bombings as terrorist operations. His immediate response was to arrest 150 people for suspected links with Hamas's military wing,Izzadin el-Qassam. His police chief then ordered all Palestinians in the self-rule areas to hand in unlicensed weapons. But he has so far resisted Israeli and American pressure to go after Hamas, root and branch: to dismantle the Islamists' infrastructure of schools and charities which, says the Israeli government, camouflage their military operations.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"We want more stick and less carrot from Arafat. The process of co-opting has failed," says Martin Indyk, the American ambassador to Israel. Mr Arafat's stick-and-carrot policy towards Hamas has indeed been sabotaged by the new outrages. It had been showing slow, incremental results. For nearly a year, the Palestinian leader has been acting forcefully against Islamist activists. In Gaza, his security forces have arrested several hundreds of suspects, earning stern rebukes from Palestinian, international, even Israeli human-rights organisations in the process. In the West Bank, Palestinian police forces have worked with Israeli security services, a liaison that led to the destruction of Qassam cells in Jenin, Jerusalem and Hebron.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But Hamas is much more than its military arm. It is a social and religious organisation, running an array of civic institutions. Mr Arafat has left these institutions intact--and initiated a quiet dialogue with Hamas's civilian leaders, attempting to co-opt them into the political process. He did not convince all of them, but his efforts produced a more pragmatic Hamas leadership, particularly in Gaza. These are men whose aim is less to scupper the peace process than to exist politically within it.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In December officials from Mr Arafat's Palestinian Authority (<font size=-1>PA</font>) met Hamas representatives, both from Jordan (where a harder line predominates) and from the self-rule territories, for "reconciliation" talks in Cairo. Hamas promised "a ceasefire with the occupation" on condition that the <font size=-1>PA</font> used its offices with Israel to "protect" Islamist military fugitives from the Israelis. Mr Arafat demanded an unconditional ceasefire. Hamas broke up the talks, saying it would boycott the Palestinian elections but still promising not to embarrass the <font size=-1>PA</font> in its commitments to Israel. But then, a month later, an Israeli booby-trap killed Yehya Ayyash, a Hamas bomb-maker who was Israel's number-one target, the biggest fugitive of all, in Gaza.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even so, some Hamas leaders stuck to the pragmatic line. The group's Gazan spokesman, Mahmoud Zahar, said it would take part in June's municipal elections. Another senior man, Ghazi Hamad, said publicly that "the majority of Hamas members are now ready to give up--temporarily--the armed struggle against Israel and turn to political activity."<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A minority, clearly, are not. These, it is said, are Qassam activists based mainly in the West Bank, for whom an unconditional reconciliation could spell their own obituaries. Their return to the politics of terror was, they say, to avenge the killing of Ayyash and other Islamist activists. But it was also a message--to Israel, to Mr Arafat and to their own political leaders--that any rapprochement or truce must include them. The day Israel "stops terrorism against Hamas and releases our prisoners ... we will reach an historic position ... not to shed blood in Palestine," said a Hamas statement after Sunday's bombings.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Arafat's dilemma is acute. His instinct tells him that the way to neutralise Qassam is through Hamas's political leadership, perhaps by prising the two apart. But Israel and America are telling him to crush Hamas, military and political wings alike. Polls show that the overwhelming majority of local Palestinians oppose terrorist operations; Hamas's own support among them is down to 10%. But if Mr Arafat acts against the group in the way that the Israelis are urging, the whole organisation could become an outlawed, and even more murderous, religious militia.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?825717600,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br1.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
