<html><head><title>Back from the brink?</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain"></td><td></td><td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table><h1>Back from the brink?</h1><p><font size=1>BELFAST AND LONDON</font></p><p><b>The British and Irish governments have patched up their differences and agreed to a plan for all-party talks on Ulster's future</b></p><p>ONCE again a series of late-night telephone calls, a rushed summit in Downing Street, a carefully worded joint communiqu&eacute and a flurry of television interviews seem to have breathed new life into Northern Ireland's peace process. And none too soon.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If John Major and John Bruton, the British and Irish prime ministers, had not been able to agree on a way forward on February 28th, hours before both men left for a Europe-Asia summit in Bangkok, the peace process might well have died. Both governments had agreed, at another hastily arranged summit in November, that the end of February should be the target date for all-party talks. But the <font size=-1>IRA</font> had ended its ceasefire early in February and bombed London, saying it believed such talks would never happen. Pressure to do something was intense.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At their summit, the two leaders agreed that consultations with the political parties in Northern Ireland would begin on March 4th. They will cover the form of elections to lead "directly and without preconditions" to all-party negotiations. The consultations will also examine the possibility of holding referendums on both sides of the border asking people to repudiate violence and support talks. These consultations will end on March 13th. Whether or not there is agreement, the British government will pass the legislation needed to hold the elections--"based on a judgment on what seems most broadly acceptable"--some time in May, and then all-party negotiations will begin on June 10th.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Attention will now shift to the <font size=-1>IRA</font>, and its political wing, Sinn Fein. When it called off its ceasefire on February 9th, the <font size=-1>IRA</font> said that it was doing so because the British had failed, for the 17 months of its ceasefire, to move towards an "inclusive negotiated settlement". Again and again Sinn Fein leaders have said that this was a demand for all-party talks "without preconditions". Irish republicans now have a British promise, endorsed by Dublin, that all-party talks will begin at a fixed date.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The immediate reaction from Sinn Fein was cautious. Gerry Adams, the party's president, said that many republicans would be sceptical in the face of "consistent British bad faith and stalling". Martin McGuinness, another Sinn Fein leader, said that his party needed "more clarity" before asking the <font size=-1>IRA</font> for a new ceasefire. But both men also said that their party would look at the proposals "positively".<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;More significantly, Sinn Fein announced the following day that, hours after Mr Major and Mr Bruton unveiled their deal, Mr Adams and John Hume, the leader of the Social Democratic and Labour Party (<font size=-1>SDLP</font>), Northern Ireland's largest nationalist party, had met <font size=-1>IRA</font> leaders and "reiterated their commitment to restoring the peace process". It was Mr Hume who persuaded Mr Adams, after years of talks, to lead the <font size=-1>IRA</font> to their first ceasefire.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Indeed, it is difficult to see how the <font size=-1>IRA</font> can now justify, even to its own supporters, refusing to call a second ceasefire. The only hurdle between Sinn Fein and all-party talks, an election, also applies to all other parties, and has been accepted by Dublin and the <font size=-1>SDLP</font>. Sinn Fein knows that it can win its customary 10% of the vote in such an election. In interviews Mr Major also said that the government could not bar Sinn Fein from running in the election even in the absence of a new <font size=-1>IRA</font> ceasefire. But with no ceasefire, Sinn Fein will not be allowed to take its place at the negotiating table. The <font size=-1>IRA</font> might decide to see this as a precondition. But this would be absurd. Taken at its word, the <font size=-1>IRA</font> would then be bombing and killing solely to get the British government to drop its demand for a ceasefire.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The deal announced by the two prime ministers has something bitter, as well as pleasing, for everyone, not just Sinn Fein. Both the Irish government and the <font size=-1>SDLP</font>, like Sinn Fein, have sought a firm date for talks. But both have also had to accept elections, which they have opposed as divisive and obstructive.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The two largest unionist parties--the Ulster Unionists and the Democratic Unionists--get the elections they demanded, but not the assembly or "body" they wanted, and which they would have dominated. Nor will the <font size=-1>IRA</font> be required to make a gesture on decommissioning weapons before Sinn Fein is allowed into talks, as the unionists have long demanded, though decommissioning will be near the top of the agenda once the talks begin.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Most of all, unionists will be unable to delay all-party talks. Both governments have said that, if the <font size=-1>IRA</font> calls a new ceasefire, they will expect the unionist parties to sit down with Sinn Fein on June 10th. If the unionist parties refuse to do this, they will be the ones who thereby exclude themselves from negotiations--and it is they who will be blamed for wrecking the talks. Neither unionist party was overjoyed at this, but neither rejected the package.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The first argument will be about the form of the election. The Ulster Unionists, the largest unionist party, wants the election to be based on the province's 18 parliamentary constituencies, which would play to its organisational strength. Ian Paisley's Democratic Unionists and the <font size=-1>SDLP</font>, in a surprising alliance, want a province-wide, party-list system, which will benefit both of them. The British government is likely to opt for the party-list system. Not only does it have support across the sectarian divide, but it will also make it easier for fringe loyalist parties to win a seat at the negotiating table.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So have the <font size=-1>IRA</font>'s London bombs achieved their purpose--a firm date for all-party talks? Mr Major and Mr Bruton insisted that they were not responding to <font size=-1>IRA</font> violence and that the peace process was proceeding as they had promised back in November. Unfortunately, no one believes this. One Tory backbencher, David Wilshire, lambasted the deal as "another Munich". Few go that far. And yet talks looked a distant prospect before the bombs went off. They have clearly concentrated minds on how to get talks going.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nevertheless the <font size=-1>IRA</font> is deluding itself if it now believes that it can turn violence off and on once Sinn Fein is into talks. Its bombs have alienated Sinn Fein sympathisers in America, alarmed the White House, enraged Dublin and filled many in the <font size=-1>SDLP</font> with disgust. The vast majority of people north and south of the border, nationalists and unionists, want both talks and peace. Sinn Fein leaders have repeatedly claimed that they will accept the outcome of all-party talks. Once such talks begin, more <font size=-1>IRA</font> bombs would split the republican movement wide open, or shatter Sinn Fein's credibility once and for all.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?825717600,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br2.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
