<html><head><title>Gosplan lives</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain"><p><font size=-1>These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.</font></p></td><td></td><td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table><p><b>Local government finance</b></p><h1>Gosplan lives</h1><p><b>The way central government hands out money to local government is incomprehensible, undemocratic and increasingly unmanageable</b></p><p>IN THE battle to extract as much money as possible from central government, Cornwall and the Isle of Wight recently won a famous victory. They persuaded civil servants to include the length of a council's coastline among the factors used to determine how much its fire service should get. The rationale? That areas with lots of coastline had fewer neighbouring fire services to call on in time of difficulty. This decision has given hope to West Yorkshire, which is arguing that hilly areas should get similarly favourable treatment.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is local-government season again. In the first half of March, councils tell local residents how much council tax they will have to pay during the current year. Some councils have been threatening huge rises: Southwark, for instance, suggested its bills might have to go up by 94%. Actual increases will be lower, probably up to 25%.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;During April, after the council-tax bills have been sent to residents, the run-up to local-government elections starts. Central government points to high increases and accuses (mostly Labour-run) councils of being profligate, while the councils accuse central government of failing to finance services properly. At the elections in May, the electorate gets the chance to vote. But voters will, as usual, stay away from the polls in droves.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The voters' apathy is rational. Local government has little discretion over spending, and less over money-raising. These days, 80% of local government's money comes from central government, and its total spending is capped. The important battles are not about the council tax, but the backroom battles of the sort that Cornwall and the Isle of Wight have recently won.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some &#163;40 billion (13% of government spending and 5.5% of <font size=-1>GDP</font>) is allocated by a nine-month process. It starts in the first week of March to determine the Standard Spending Assessments (<font size=-1>SSA</font>s), the government's estimate of how much a council needs to spend. (<a href="br1.gif">See chart</a>).<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Needs are assessed according to an area's social, demographic and geographical characteristics. The more children an area has, for instance, the higher its educational needs will be. Equalisation, however, does not stop there. Some children appear to be more expensive to educate than others. Using past spending patterns, civil servants try to work out why this is so. Their conclusion is that more poor, unemployed, lone parents, ethnic minorities and a thinly-spread population put the bills up; so Tower Hamlets' <font size=-1>SSA</font> per head for education in 1996-97 is &#163;720 and Kensington and Chelsea's is &#163;226. Whitehall goes even further in its pursuit of fairness. The mathematics show that children "at risk" in some areas cost more than others; so a child "at risk" in Lambeth will have more money allocated to it than one in Cambridge.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such conclusions worry some: does past spending really say much about an area's need, or is it picking up other factors? In other words, does the higher cost of educating a child in a poorer area tell you that the child has greater needs or that its local authority is inefficient? Is the system rewarding failure?<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The capping of local-authority spending, which started in the mid-1980s, complicates such calculations even further. These assume that past spending is an expression of an area's needs; but, increasingly, past spending has been determined by central-government fiat, which limits its usefulness as an indicator.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As well as being flawed, the system is obscure. It is, according to the Audit Commission, the most complex in the world, save possibly that used in Australia. Nobody knows how many variables it employs. Civil servants admit that the struggle to make it comprehensible has been lost.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It gets worse as time goes by. Councils argue constantly for extra factors to be taken into account that might shift cash in their direction; and they all employ consultants to make their case to ministers. Local authorities gang up to put a common case. A band of councils in South Yorkshire and Lancashire have won a long campaign to include a long-term sickness indicator to shift cash in their direction. Some pretty areas have managed to get a National Park indicator included in the calculations.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The biggest recent battle has been that between the south-east and the rest of England about what level of compensation the region should get to make up for its higher costs. The government has now set up a commission to settle the argument. The level of distrust between the two English camps is such that the commission is staffed by Scotsmen and one Ulsterman. It sounds a small matter, but the argument is about &#163;1.5 billion.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The more variables are fed into the system, the more unmanageable it becomes. Once every few years, the system's minders admit that it has imploded. They then throw it away and start again, trying to build something that they can cope with. The system was last rebuilt in 1989. The current one is, true to form, showing signs of breaking down.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Civil servants justify the system's complexity by arguing that to be fair, it must be sensitive; and to be sensitive, it must be complex. To count the heads of school-age children, the argument goes, is to ignore the greater needs of some. Yet the "fairness" of the system seems somewhat arbitrary. Wales calculates its <font size=-1>SSA</font>s differently to England; when the Audit Commission recalculated English <font size=-1>SSA</font>s on the Welsh basis, it got results of up to 27% more and 36% less than the councils' actual allocations.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Anyway, handing out more money per child to a county whose average incomes are low does not necessarily help poor children as much as Whitehall mandarins claim. As the illustration from Berkshire's education spending shows (on the previous page), local authorities tend to spend similar amounts on educating all their children, rich and poor alike, ignoring central government's careful calculations of need.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some argue that the problem is philosophical rather than practical: that the struggle to create a mathematical model of fairness is misconceived, because it cannot be objectively measured. "We have," says Martin Pilgrim of the Association of Metropolitan Authorities, "an immensely sophisticated system to measure something which is not measurable."<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The struggle for fairness has combined with the government's centralising tendencies to produce a system that looks nothing like democracy. Tony Travers, a local government specialist at the London School of Economics, points out the irony that this bureaucratic, egalitarian system should have triumphed under a Conservative government. "It is," he says, "as centralised as anything Eastern Europe ever produced."<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The government is bothered enough about the system's problems to have asked the Institute for Fiscal Studies to examine its mathematics. But--as Labour accepts--bolder reform is needed: radical simplification to make the system understandable and a shift of money-raising powers back to local government to make it accountable. Until then, Britain's system of local-authority finance will stand as a monument to bad government and will contribute little to local democracy.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?825717600,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br3.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
