<html><head><title>Hidden value</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain"><p><font size=-1>These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.</font></p></td><td></td><td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table><p><b>Business investment</b></p><h1>Hidden value</h1>THOSE who do not share the government's optimism over the economy's potential for growth point to the failure of investment to recover since the end of the last recession. Measured as a proportion of the economy's total output (<a href="br2.gif">see chart</a>), investment has been on a downward trend since 1989. Part of the fall is explained by cuts in the public sector's spending on infrastructure, and by individuals' reluctance to buy houses. But investment by businesses is also weak, as figures published on February 23rd showed. Manufacturing firms' investment during the fourth quarter of 1995 was 9% lower than in the previous quarter and 5% lower than in the same period in 1994.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At present this reluctance to plough money into new equipment, offices and factories is all the more puzzling, because incentives to invest seem unusually strong. In principle, investments ought to be worth making when their cost is outweighed by the stockmarket valuation of the extra profits resulting from the investment. According to the Bank of England's estimates, the ratio between these two numbers has been favourable since the end of 1991, and has recently soared to its highest level for more than 25 years.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, the Bank suggests that the weakness of business investment is not as worrying as it might appear. First, investment is now close to its long-run average following a boom in spending--especially on property--in the late 1980s. Second, Britain's statistics seem to be underestimating the speed at which the cost of investing in computing power is decreasing, as Howard Davies, the Bank's deputy governor, pointed out in a speech on February 21st.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On this, a comparison with America is striking. Its investment statistics are based on a detailed analysis of changes in the efficiency and capacity of computers. They show that between 1985 and 1992 the underlying cost of computers fell by 55%. Britain's official figures, less sophisticated in this area, recorded a fall of only 25%. Britain's investment statistics also fail to record purchases of software bought separately from computer hardware (a shortcoming that will be corrected once Britain adopts new European standards for national accounts some time in the next two years).<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The increasing use of information technology to organise production and to predict sales may also be helping firms to make better use of existing capacity, reducing their need to splash out on new equipment. Andrew Sentance of the London Business School points to surveys by the Confederation of British Industry which suggest that manufacturers are now comfortable with much lower margins of spare capacity than they were in the early 1980s.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?825717600,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br6.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
