<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><center><p align=center><table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"><p><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" alt="Britain"></p><p><font size=-1>These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.</font></p></td></tr></table><hr size=6 align=center width=65%><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%><p><b>Divorce</b> &nbsp;The Princess of Wales announced that she had agreed to Prince Charles's request for a divorce. She claimed that she will keep her title, continue to live at Kensington Palace and be involved in all decisions regarding their two children.</p><p><b>Reform</b> &nbsp;Labour's national executive voted to end the sponsorship of individual members of Parliament by trade unions, to limit the scope for Conservative accusations of undue union influence on Labour policy.</p><p><b>Not a gas</b> &nbsp;Clare Spottiswoode, the gas industry's regulator, lambasted the industry's " truly atrocious" customer service in some areas. Complaints to her office, Ofgas, rose by 46% in 1995.</p><p><b>A lesson learnt</b> &nbsp;David Blunkett, Labour's education spokesman, admitted that many comprehensive schools had failed their pupils because of rigid adherence to mixed-ability teaching.</p><p><b>High-speed</b> &nbsp;</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>London and Continental Railways, a consortium of banking, construction and travel firms, has been selected to build the &#163;3 billion railway from London to the Anglo-French Channel Tunnel.</p><p><b>Gambling galore</b> &nbsp;The government announced a reform of gambling regulations. Thirteen more towns will be allowed to have casinos. Bingo halls will have restrictions on membership and advertising eased.</p><p><b>Greenwich wins time</b> &nbsp;Greenwich in south-east London, where the world's time zones begin, was chosen as the site for Britain's &#163;700m exhibition to mark the start of the next millennium.</p><p><b>Not cricket</b> &nbsp;The England cricket team apologised after its captain, Mike Atherton, called a Pakistani journalist a "buffoon" at a press conference following England's defeat by South Africa in the World Cup at Rawalpindi.</p><p><b>Wuff justice</b> &nbsp;The owner of 17 Alsatians was told by a high court judge that he can allow them to bark for only one hour a day, following complaints by neighbours.</p></td></tr></table></p></center><br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?825717600,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
