<html><head><title>Fresh light on primary colours</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="sf.gif">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>Fresh light on primary colours</h1>
<p><b>Pat Buchanan, a right-wing populist, won the New Hampshire primary. Is the system of presidential primaries good for American democracy?</b></p>

EVERY four years, candidates hoping to stand for the American presidency can be found shivering outside factory gates in the New Hampshire snow, fondling pigs in Iowa or joining old folks' singalongs in Florida. By performing such antics, state by wearying state, they hope to attract delegates to their cause and hence earn the Republican or Democratic presidential nomination at a party convention in August.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;America's primary season, which began this week in New Hampshire, is a bizarre ritual to brave in preparation for the most powerful job in the world. No other country has anything like it. A British Conservative is chosen to lead his party by an old-boy club of other members of parliament. Candidates for the German chancellery are picked before each election by a conference of party members, but there are no elections to the conference nor are delegates mandated to vote for particular candidates. The French and Russian candidates must win some support from voters first: in France they need the backing of 500 elected officials (such as mayors); in Russia, they must collect a million signatures; otherwise, candidates choose themselves by offering their candidacy directly to the electorate.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;No big democracy has America's combination of mass voting and a party slate. (Last year, France's Gaullist party thought about holding primaries but abandoned the idea because it could not decide who should vote, or who would foot the bill.) No big democracy forces incumbents to defend themselves so vigorously against rivals in their own party. No other country permits waves of popular opinion to determine who represents parties to voters.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The features which make the American primary system so distinctive are controversial. Critics condemn the primaries as a chaotic and degrading way of winnowing out candidates; so degrading, they claim, that it puts off well-qualified people. The process, they add, pushes peculiar states such as New Hampshire to prominence while ignoring larger, more representative ones. It undermines the moderating influence of party elders and, because of low turnouts, leaves politics vulnerable to extremists, producing presidential candidates supported by sectional interests rather than the mass of ordinary voters.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nor, say critics, is the system as democratic as it once was; big money plays an increasing (and, in their view, distorting) role. The sheer number of primaries means the election campaign drags on and on, producing voter fatigue long before the poll that really matters in November. Above all, the critics claim, the primary system damages the eventual nominee because he must endure months of bitter public criticism from his own side before he ever faces opponents from the other. This not only weakens him as a candidate but also damages his party by magnifying divisions that might otherwise lie dormant.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Supporters of the primary system reply that this supposedly chaotic and degrading system goes with the grain of American democracy, with all its populism and egalitarianism. It allows ordinary Americans to pick not just their representatives but their candidates, too. And not just to pick them: to talk to them, impress their worries on them, see them break a sweat.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Moreover, say the system's supporters, primaries work better than you might expect. Though they appear, at the early stages, to be vulnerable to extremists, they usually deliver, at the end of a long procedure, nominees who are widely known and widely approved of. The primary ritual means that voters judge candidates on performance; so, while money matters, it is not everything. Primaries are less corrupt than their alternatives. If they are exhausting (which they are), then that is no bad way to discern which candidates have the stamina to do the world's most demanding job. And if they are chaotic and parochial (which they also are), that is the nature of democracy in a country as sprawling and headstrong as America.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So who is right? Are primaries, on balance, helping or harming American democracy? And are they getting better or worse at what they do? The trail of discovery is as long and winding as the campaign trail itself.
</p><p><b>Against conventional wisdom</b></b>
<br>The primary system was set up in response to dissatisfaction with the smoke-filled rooms of old. Before the early years of this century, you cultivated party bosses and their friends in big business; they pushed you, if you were lucky, to the presidency. Deals were done in back rooms; no need to consult the plebs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The first modern-looking primary was held in Oregon in 1910. By 1916, after Teddy Roosevelt and his Bull Moose Party had challenged the Republican establishment (in an uprising which eventually earned Roosevelt the largest number of votes for a third party until Ross Perot in 1992), 26 states had introduced primaries.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For the next half century, there was little change. In 1968, more than half the votes cast by delegates at the famously anarchic Democratic convention in Chicago were still controlled by party bosses. But now 39 states have primaries, and they have become the essential first stage in the American electoral process. Even unopposed incumbents, such as Bill Clinton this year, must dutifully slog through them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The first effect of the extension of the primary system has been to reduce the role of the party convention, once the crucial first step in the election campaign. In the past, party conventions were places where delegates were (sometimes literally) fought over. Now, the primaries produce the nominee, and the convention merely crowns him. Bill Clinton attracted 2,511 delegates during the 1992 primary season, 366 more than he needed. George Bush, for the Republicans, got 80% of the delegates.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Actually, conventions may not always be redundant even now. In 1980 there was a wild attempt to draft Senator Edward Kennedy at the Democratic convention, even though he had lost to Jimmy Carter in the primaries. And many a Republican has been dreaming of a scene this year in which Bob Dole, Pat Buchanan and Lamar Alexander go to the convention with equal numbers of delegates, and the deadlock is broken by the arrival of the <font size=-1>US</font> cavalry in the form of General Colin Powell, riding triumphantly to nomination. But even in such a case, the primaries would still have served a purpose, showing that, in the end, no candidate was sufficiently appealing.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For the most part, however, the days of arm-twisting brokered conventions are gone. No longer are groups of delegates " floating" or "for sale". No longer will conventions go on, as did the 1924 Democratic one, for 17 days and an amazing 103 ballots. The disappearance of such spectacles, though reducing the entertainment value of politics, has made the process of picking candidates more open and democratic, and somewhat more predictable. Whatever else might be said against the primary system, this achievement at least should be chalked up to its credit.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But, say the system's critics, even if the convention system was bad, it is still wrong to pretend that it has been replaced by a nationwide campaign of 39 primaries. In reality, conventions have been largely replaced by just one or two primary polls--and pretty peculiar ones at that.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Think back over the careers of America's most famous modern politicians, and a surprising number will be found to have been made, or broken, in a couple of cold weeks at the beginning of February. In the 1952 New Hampshire primary, Dwight Eisenhower defeated Robert Taft, marking the first time a primary had shown its potential to upset a candidate anointed by party bosses; in the Democratic poll that same day, Harry Truman was defeated, and decided not to stand for re-election.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In 1968, Lyndon Johnson abandoned hopes of re-election after almost losing the 1968 New Hampshire primary to Eugene McCarthy, an anti-Vietnam campaigner. In the same state in 1972, Ed Muskie stood weeping on a flat-bed truck with the snow whitening his hair; his defeat led directly to the rise of George McGovern, another anti-Vietnam-war candidate whose radical programme alienated voters and returned Nixon to power. In 1968, the Republicans suffered a comparable fate when Barry Goldwater came from the far right of the party to capture the nomination after doing unexpectedly well in New Hampshire. In short, as "Primary Colours", the anonymous novel that is now Washington <font size=-1>DC</font>'s favourite bedside reading, puts it: "Folks up here [New Hampshire] don't mess around. They think it's their patriotic duty to choose a president for all the rest of us pathetic redneck shitheels."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The extraordinary influence of New Hampshire is controversial. No state may be called typical of America, but New Hampshire seems even less representative than most. It is small-town and relatively rural; it is strongly conservative, and has fewer taxes than almost any other state. Issues that catch fire there (this year, the flat tax) may give no thrill to westerners or southerners. And the state has a strong rebellious streak: it likes to make up its mind late, confound the wise, and go for outsiders. Party leaders view it with trepidation. Is this a good place to invest with such influence?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Actually, its power is overstated. Defeat there will not necessarily sink a well-prepared candidate with a good track record. Mr Clinton was beaten in New Hampshire by Paul Tsongas, a senator from Massachusetts; but because he clung on despite revelations of dalliance and draft-dodging, he did well enough to sweep his native South in the next set of primaries.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Conversely, a candidate who has not done his homework, has not raised enough money, is lackadaisical or prone to gaffes, will find his weakness glaringly exposed. This would happen anywhere, and is not connected with any issues or ideology that New Hampshire happens to favour. It is a matter of organisation and a man's internal fortitude: that "fire in the belly" that candidates love to talk about.
</p><p><b>Vote early, vote often</b>
<br><ro>That said, in so far as New Hampshire gets the campaign off to a peculiar start, the peculiarity is growing. Ironically, this is occurring as a result of attempts by other states to share New Hampshire's limelight.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Because early votes are vital, Arizona and Delaware have moved their primaries up to February, though New Hampshire has kept pole position. "Caucuses" (soundings of party members, as in Louisiana on February 6th), or "straw polls" (presidential preference votes, not attached to winning delegates, as in Alaska on January 29th) have been invented to steal a march on New Hampshire. Victory in both votes helped give Mr Buchanan momentum.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;More significantly, other states have advanced the dates of their primaries to follow soon after New Hampshire's and this so-called "front-loading" of the calendar is the most important single change to the American primary system in recent years. It has so compressed the primary schedule--at least in the biggest and delegate-heavy states--that, by April Fool's Day, almost all the delegates will have been selected. The vital primaries now come so thick and fast that there is no chance to pause or regroup between them. So if you do badly in New Hampshire, there is less time to recoup lost ground. Just as important, the influence of money has grown.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Traditionally, the joy of New Hampshire was that it required "retail politics": knocking on doors, talking to the people. This sort of campaigning is relatively inexpensive and allows lesser-known, poorer candidates to perform on an equal footing with better-known, richer ones. The bigger, money-devouring states (especially California, where campaigning has to be done on television), used to be further down the calendar, allowing more chance for underdogs to gather funds on the back of respectable performances elsewhere. Now California (on March 26th) comes barely a month after New Hampshire; and a man without at least $5m to spend simply cannot make the running there.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This reduction in the role of "retail politics" seems a discouraging development because it is a step away from the face-to-face characteristics that admirers of primaries claim to be one of the system's main virtues. It might also prevent poor candidates from entering the race at all.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet the first argument is odd. Face-to-face meetings are a way of getting information about candidates. Now, television is usurping that role. Television may provide different sorts of information and may be susceptible to manipulation, but it surely adds hugely to the volume of information about candidates. The second worry seems not to be justified either. This year's Republican field is as big as ever. There were ten hopefuls at the start, including six no-hopers. The compression of the primaries may have put off more cerebral types--Bill Bennett, Jack Kemp and conceivably Colin Powell; but the truth seems to be that if people really want the job, they will run despite the indignities.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The real importance of money in the primaries is, in any case, debatable. To get that vital early boost, Steve Forbes, a billionaire, spent $15m of his own money. To counter him, Mr Dole diverted $1.8m from campaigning funds for the south and west. Both did badly in New Hampshire.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A large wad of money is clearly vital. But a deluge of money for advertising does not seem to be cost-effective. That said, the ever-larger sums spent on primaries may hurt the system in one way. Every candidate this year has been drawn into a spiral of early spending. This means that some will fall out sooner than they might otherwise have done and the survivor will limp, short of cash, into the main election campaign.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What about the final accusation: that primaries are liable to throw up candidates who cannot win a nationwide election? Mr Buchanan's success gives Republican managers cause to worry for just this reason.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Primaries generally get a low (and declining) turnout. In 1992, the average for all primaries was 30% of registered voters. Among that low share will be disproportionate numbers of single-issue or fringe voters. The religious right has dogged the Republican primary trial this year, hence the surge for Mr Buchanan, even though his message--anti-immigrant, protectionist, anti-abortion, anti-gay--is not one most "ordinary" Republicans support. Hence, too, the drift to the right among moderate rivals chasing him for delegates.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Embarrassing as this may be for party bosses, they are not powerless in the face of it. The Democrats, especially, have fiddled with the rules since the 1970s in an attempt to avoid the nomination of unelectable "liberals" such as Mr McGovern or Walter Mondale, Jimmy Carter's vice-president. In 1984 they changed many of their primaries to caucuses, which are easier for party elders to control. In 1992, when they had a more moderate candidate in Mr Clinton, they changed the rules back again.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Tinkering does not always work. In 1988 southern Democrats invented (and the Republicans quickly copied) the idea of a southern regional primary, "Super Tuesday", which was meant to block the path of a liberal north-easterner (Michael Dukakis, governor of Massachusetts) in favour of a southern conservative, Al Gore of Tennessee. In the event, Mr Gore failed, and Mr Dukakis went on to lose the general election. But though the intervention of party elders can backfire, the front-loading of the primary calendar has helped them in their struggle to influence the primaries. The system now demands ever-earlier and better organisation, so the anointing power of parties has become more important. Mr Clinton in 1992 and (for what it is worth) Mr Dole in 1996 both went into the primary season with the weight of their parties behind them. In previous seasons, such backing would have waited until the convention. Now the elders dare not wait so long.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In San Diego in August, during the party convention, the Republican National Committee has promised to review this year's primary season to see if it can be "improved"--presumably in ways the elders approve of. What might these improvements be? Regional primaries have become popular: not only Super Tuesday (this year, on March 12th) but also a "Yankee primary" of the New England states (New Hampshire excepted) on March 5th. Regional primaries might help the party give a favourite son a boost on his home turf (though, as Mr Gore found, there is no guarantee of this).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One last suggestion is sometimes heard: a national primary, in which registered voters of all parties could vote on a single day. Such a primary would require an orgy of nationwide televised advertising by all candidates lasting for months. And, since the sums available from public finances would not go far in such conditions, a national primary would tie the fates of candidates to the party bosses almost as tightly as in the old days.
</p><p><b>In their primary?</b></b>
<br>In the end, then, the primary system looks likely to survive in something like its current form. States like it; potent myths of democracy surround it. Nor are these merely myths. Primaries force candidates to give an account of themselves in the flesh, to listen to what worries voters (which is not always what politicians think) and to see the country they wish to represent.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As a way of picking candidates, primaries may be less efficient than the smoke-filled chambers of old. But because they are less corruptible, the result is more likely to be accepted. Even if they produce a maverick--if, say, they deliver Mr Buchanan to the hustings--that would not necessarily be reason for saying the system is rotten; rather, it is grounds for saying the system is reflecting a substantial part of public opinion and that those who disapprove need to respond with their own voting power. It is their very democratic qualities that make the primaries such a struggle, torment and mess. And this uncomfortable trade-off, in primary elections as in so much else, is one America will simply have to live with.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?825112800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="am1.html">Next article</a>
</p></td></tr></table></body></html>
