</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Digesting New Hampshire</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="am.gif">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>Digesting New Hampshire</h1>
<p><font size=1>MANCHESTER</font></p>BOB LEVINE and Craig Benson are a classic American success story. They started their computer-networking business in a garage 13 years ago. Since then, Cabletron Systems has grown into a company with 5,600 employees and an annual revenue of more than $1 billion, 29% of it earned abroad. " Free trade is the best thing that ever happened to this company," Mr Benson told a rally for Bob Dole at Cabletron's factory in Rochester on the day before the New Hampshire primary. "We're not afraid to kick anybody's ass around the world."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What better setting for Mr Dole to contrast his view of the economy with Pat Buchanan's protectionism? But he blew it. "I didn't realise that jobs and trade and what makes America work would become a big issue in the last few days of this campaign," the Senate majority leader admitted.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The impression that Mr Dole is hopelessly out of touch with the real world helps to explain his failure in New Hampshire on February 20th. Not only was he unable to squash the challenge from Lamar Alexander, the ex-governor from Tennessee, who won 23% of the vote, just four points behind him. He also lost to Mr Buchanan, despite support from almost the entire New Hampshire Republican establishment. The Dole people blame the damage done by millions of dollars of negative advertisements from Steve Forbes, who hurt Mr Dole without helping himself (the flat-tax fanatic finished fourth, with 12% of the vote). But the bigger problem was Mr Dole's inability to generate any real enthusiasm about his candidacy--in stark contrast to the raw energy of the Buchanan campaign.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Buchanan has few assets save his fame as a televised political pugilist and the fire of his words. He writes his own advertisements, his sister manages his campaign, an army of volunteers man his phone banks. He visibly loves every minute of it, as well he might. In the past three weeks he has won in Alaska, won in Louisiana, come a strong second in Iowa and now stormed to victory in New Hampshire, with 28% of the vote. The barons of the Republican establishment are in a panic, he told a rally in Nashua last Sunday; the peasants are coming.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However far the Buchanan insurgency goes, it has already shown that many Americans are still anxious and angry, even in successful New Hampshire, where unemployment is down to 3.3%. Mr Buchanan's hatred of trade agreements such as <font size=-1>NAFTA</font> and <font size=-1>GATT</font>, and his fusillades against transnational corporations "with no loyalty to our country", resonate with blue-collar workers and, especially, with those earning under $30,000 a year. He excites nationalists with his rhetoric about America's sovereignty. Add to that his Catholic fundamentalism, and you have a potent mix.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;His devoted followers give the impression that they would jump over a cliff for Pat. Unlike the other candidates, they explain, he is honest and speaks from the heart, a real leader. At their packed victory celebration, amid the chanting, the drinking and the rocking-and-rolling, a construction worker called Eric, wearing Barry Goldwater and George Wallace buttons as well as his "Buchanan for President" badge, describes how he is sick of being told that if you were blue-collar you had to be a Democrat. Jack, an out-of-work pipe-fitter, stressed jobs. "If Japan wants to send a car over here, they've got to buy one. One for one. It's as simple as that."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In short, the populist Mr Buchanan stands for something. He is the only one among the three candidates now seriously in the chase who can plausibly lend his name to an "-ism". "This is a victory for a cause," he told his supporters on Tuesday night, after his out-of-tune rendition of "God Bless America".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But is it really a Republican cause? Mr Buchanan's design for a wall round America's economy is at odds with the free-trade mainstream of the party, and closer to the ideas of the Democratic left. His intolerance scares people. If he won the nomination, Republican big-wigs fear they would lose not only the presidential election but the House of Representatives as well.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Buchanan will almost certainly not win. True, since 1952 the Republican winner in New Hampshire has gone on to the nomination every time except in 1964, when Henry Cabot Lodge took the primary but Barry Goldwater became the Republican nominee. But Mr Buchanan will have trouble expanding much beyond his devoted base of supporters--his share of the vote in New Hampshire was nine points below the 37% he won against President George Bush there four years ago. The stop-Buchanan majority in the party seems certain to prevail in the end.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The trouble is that the majority forces are split. Had Senator Richard Lugar not taken his 5% of the vote in New Hampshire, for example, Mr Dole would probably have won. As it is, although a couple of minor candidates are now withdrawing, the race is turning into a Republican nightmare, with the divisive Mr Buchanan attracting the headlines and the anti-Buchananites fighting among themselves.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;How long will the nightmare last? From now on, the nature of the race changes, as it moves on from small-state retail politics to an expensive contest in more than 30 primaries within a month. Going into this frenzy of voting, all three of the main contenders have serious weaknesses.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Buchanan lacks money, he no longer enjoys the element of surprise and, his opponents claim, he has "no end-game". He will also face a surge of media scrutiny and attacks from his rivals. Already, a couple of senior people on his campaign have had their connections to racist groups exposed. In his commentaries over the years Mr Buchanan himself has left a trail of bigotry that invites exploration.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;According to Mr Buchanan, for example, Martin Luther King was "one of the most divisive men in contemporary history". The only people wanting the Gulf war were "the Israeli defence ministry and its amen corner in the United States". The central objection to the flood of illegal immigrants is that "they are not English-speaking white people from Western Europe". Promiscuous homosexuals "appear literally hell-bent on Satanism and suicide". Women are "simply not endowed by nature" with capitalist ambition.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Alexander will repeat ad nauseam the contrast between Mr Buchanan's "wrong ideas", Mr Dole's absence of ideas and his own "fresh ideas" (see <A HREF="am3.html">Lexington</a>). But he has emptied his coffers and needs to persuade Republican money-givers to cough up several million dollars in a hurry. His name is not even on the ballot in New York, Pennsylvania and parts of Illinois, making his quest for a majority of delegates that much harder.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All of which leaves the damaged, derided Mr Dole still--just--the likeliest eventual Republican winner. He has stumbled in New Hampshire, as he did in 1988. But the logistics of the next stage of the campaign favour him. He has $6.5m in the bank and a formidable number of governors working for him in the mainly winner-take-all primaries ahead.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even if Mr Dole does win by attrition, it will not remove the Buchanan problem for the Republicans. Mr Buchanan is already influencing their agenda and he will be a force to be reckoned with at the party's convention in San Diego. He has once again shown that there is a market in America for populist politics, a market third parties under the likes of Ross Perot and Ralph Nader are eyeing eagerly. All the more reason for one person to be almost as delighted as Mr Buchanan himself with the outcome in New Hampshire: Bill Clinton


