<html><head><title>Up, down and standing still</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="am.gif">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<p><b>Mobility in America</b></p>
<h2>Up, down and standing still</h2>


<p>ONE of America's most cherished ideas about itself is that, with enough pluck and hard work, anyone can achieve the ranch-style house with the two-car garage. A whole literature, starting with the Horatio Alger stories, spells out this belief. Yet now Pat Buchanan wins votes by claiming that for ordinary folks this notion of progress is over. Is he right?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Americans move both up and down the income ladder about as fast as they have in the past. Think of the country as being divided by income into five groups of equal size, with the poorest in the first group and the richest in the fifth. If you keep track of people of working age (between 25 and 55), within five years almost half will have moved up or down by at least one group, according to research by economists at Syracuse University. (<a href="amimg2.gif">See chart</a>).<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Syracuse trio have charted these economic mobility rates back to 1970: the results have barely budged. And with a million immigrants a year taking predominantly lower-paid work, those settled in the United States are likely to move up, while newcomers fill the bottom quintile--for a time. Newer figures from the Census Bureau extend the findings into the 1990s. Measuring year-to-year mobility between 1984 and 1992, the agency found that only once, in the recession year of 1990-91, did more families see their incomes fall than see them rise.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mobility seems to be highest among middle-income Americans, but it is brisk for poorer ones, too. According to the Census Bureau, only 5% of people were below the poverty line (roughly the bottom 15% of Americans, measured by income) for each month of 1991 and 1992. Almost none of those employed full-time stayed poor for the whole period, a hint that those who get into work are likely to be able to pull themselves up and out of poverty.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nor is it true that the "baby-boomers" (those born between 1946 and 1961) are worse off than their parents were at the same age. A study by the Urban Institute found that in 1989 pre-tax incomes for now-adult baby-boomers were half as high again, adjusted for inflation, as their parents' incomes in 1960. Consumption was 27% higher, and rates of home ownership and unemployment were much the same.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So what are Americans so grumpy about? "I don't know," says Douglas Holtz-Eakin, one of the Syracuse researchers. "The statistical measures look good but the mood of the people is not."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One concern may be inequality. In 1979, America's richest 1% held 22% of the nation's wealth, according to Edward Wolff, an economist at New York University and author of "Top Heavy". By 1992, they held 42%. If you use a different measure that includes the value of consumer durables, pensions and benefits, the difference shrinks considerably, but the trend is still striking--and increasing. At the beginning of the Clinton presidency, the top 5% of earners took in 18.1% of income; now they take in more than 21%, an unprecedented rate of increase. The fact that inequality is increasing and mobility is not explains some of the current unAmerican angst.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So does another figure. Few Americans resent the rich: most want to join them, if they get the chance. But median income, adjusted for inflation, grew only slightly during the 1980s, and fell every year between 1989 and 1993. The median household income is a bit less than it was in 1986. Mobility softens the blow for some: even if median wages are not rising, many individuals have seen their pay packets bulge. But remember that even in the most active quintiles, about 40% stay still.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even here, though, the reality may not be not quite so dismal. Although household income has scarcely risen, the number of households has grown sharply as students, singles and merry widows increasingly choose to live alone. Because families are smaller, the same income per family means more cash per head. And non-wage compensation, which includes pensions, health care and other benefits, has also increased steadily in real terms. Total compensation has therefore risen; but that is not the same as having cash in hand.
</p><p><b>The poverty trap</b></b>
<br>And, even when they work, some Americans cannot keep the wolf from the door. In 1977, 5.9% of workers were poor; by 1993 it was up to 7.4%. The percentage of poor families with children has risen by half, to 12%.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There are two reasons for this. One is the increase in single-parent households. Lone mums, and their children, are the most likely to be poor, and they stay poor longer. This is not a problem the federal government can do much about: if mothers were better at picking fathers, and fathers better at taking care of their children, America would have many fewer children living in poverty. The other reason for the rise in working poverty is that the average hourly wage for the lowest-paid 10% of workers has fallen, in real terms, since 1979. That pushes more into poverty; arguably, it is the price America pays to find jobs, and a start on the ladder, for people with few or no skills. The earned-income tax credit, now under threat from Republicans, means that low-wage workers with children receive more income, but they are still far from joining the middle class.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Buchanan may be right to suspect that climbing into the middle class is getting harder. The University of Michigan's Panel Study of Income Dynamics, which has tracked the same families since 1968, has found that although 65% of white American men who turned 21 before 1980 had reached middle-class earnings (defined as twice the poverty level) by the age of 30, only 47% of those who turned 21 after 1980 had managed to do so. For blacks, the respective percentages were 29% and 19%.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The less educated, it is clear, are finding well-paid jobs harder to come by. For younger people with a high-school diploma or less, only 32% reached the <font size=-1>PSID</font> middle-class standard by the time they were 30; for those who turned 21 before 1980, almost half did. Also using the <font size=-1>PSID</font> data, Greg Duncan of the University of Michigan found that before 1980 more than a third of low-income families joined the middle class over a five-year period; after 1980, only a quarter did.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;White-collar insecurity is another new concern. The effect of corporate "down-sizing" may have been exaggerated, but many middle managers have been hurt. If they wish to re-enter the market, these people generally have to accept lower pay. The average worker re-entering the job market between 1990 and 1992 took a pay cut of around 20%. No feel-good factor there.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even if things are not getting worse for Americans, they are, at best, improving much more slowly than in the past. Because Americans love progress, this can feel like failure. The chief reason is that the education premium in America is getting bigger, widening income distribution and feeding blue-collar anxiety. America still has its Horatio Alger stories--but these days the heroes start by going to college.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?825112800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="am3.html">Next article</a>
</p></td></tr></table></body></html>
