http://www.economist.com:80/issue/24-02-96/br1.html 199.173.162.110 19970113175402 text/html 10701
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 17:50:14 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 08-Aug-96 14:04:00 GMT
Content-length: 10515
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Consumers like the rest of us</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="br.gif" alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>The poor</b></p>
<h2>Consumers like the rest of us</h2>



<p>THE most wounding accusation made against Britain's Conservative era is that, while yuppies have benefited from rising salaries and cheaper cappuccino, poorer Britons have seen their standard of living deteriorate. Critics claim that social and economic disparities are greater in Britain than anywhere else in the European Union. Today, among similarly prosperous nations, Britain is uniquely harsh on its less-fortunate citizens.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is simply not the case, according to an analysis of household statistics in six western countries (America, Belgium, Britain, Germany, the Netherlands and Sweden) by the Luxembourg Income Study (<font size=-1>LIS</font>), an independent research organisation. The 20% of households in Britain with the lowest income fit well within the European fold.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In 1991, for example, the average working British household in the lowest fifth earned the equivalent of $14,773, or &#163;8,349 (before tax, after benefits, and based on purchasing power parity, which adjusts for exchange-rate distortions). This put poor Britons ahead of their counterparts in Sweden and America (calculating the same way); those in the Netherlands had the highest incomes, at $15,932. Non-working households had an income of $9,126, placing them ahead of those in Germany and Sweden, and close to those in America.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Overall, government policy makes no difference to the rankings. Poor Britons pay a lot of tax (the third-highest burden for working households, second-highest for non-working); but they also receive generous benefits. More than 90% of British homes in the lowest fifth received some kind of income-replacement benefit, more than in any other country except Sweden. On every basis--working households, non-working households, pre-tax earnings, post-tax earnings, with or without benefits--Britain's poor come third out of six in the <font size=-1>LIS</font> ranking.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Life has grown more comfortable for the bottom fifth in visible ways. There is enough disposable income to make televisions universal, washing machines ubiquitous and home computers not uncommon. Rates of ownership for all the items in the table have increased markedly during the Tory era. Housing standards have also improved. In each of 36 deprived areas of Britain surveyed by the London-based Policy Studies Institute, a think-tank, the percentage of households with more than one person to a room fell between 1981 and 1991 in all but one area, London's Tower Hamlets.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Finally, "mobility" is high: the members of the lowest fifth (and, indeed, the lowest tenth) change a lot each year. Climbing out of the lowest income quintile is not only possible, but a routine event. In January the Research Centre on Micro-Social Change, a group sponsored by the Economic and Social Research Council (<font size=-1>ESRC</font>), published a study entitled "Do the Poor Stay Poor?". It found that, of those in the bottom fifth in 1991, almost four out of ten had moved up to a higher income by 1992.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As you might expect, most of those moving out of the lowest level did not climb far. Also, the children of the lowest fifth are less likely than average to make it into the top ranks when they grow up. According to another study published last month, by the Institute for Fiscal Studies (<font size=-1>IFS</font>), 12% of the children born into the lowest fifth made it into the top fifth by the time they were 33; of those born in the top fifth, 34% managed to stay there. This is unfair, but hardly a portrait of a hopeless underclass. (<a href="brimg1.gif">See table</a>). <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That is the good news. The bad news is that several trends are pushing gently in the wrong direction. Although the physical wretchedness of poverty may be declining--poorer Britons, remember, have nicer, better-equipped homes than ever--the spatial concentration of poverty is accelerating. When rules of entry to council estates changed in the 1970s, with need becoming the primary criterion, social indicators worsened. The estates have become more different from the rest of Britain than before: younger, poorer, more racially segregated, with twice the rate of unemployed and three times the proportion of lone parents. The middle class has moved out. As late as 1974, one in three Britons with incomes in the top 40% lived on a council estate. That figure is now next to nothing.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This matters because, as the examples of America's inner cities and France's <i>banlieues</i> indicate, such areas tend to become self-perpetuating. Stigma means that business is reluctant to move in; working people move out as soon as they can. Public services suffer. Defeatism deepens.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although there is considerable movement up (and therefore down) the income ladder, an increasingly intractable group is stuck at the bottom. One reason for this is the growing number of one-parent families, which account for 7% of Britain's households but more than a third of the lowest fifth. Six years after beginning to receive benefits, 78% of Britain's lone mothers are still on social assistance, compared with 24% of Americans, 20% of Germans and 58% of Canadians. The longer people are out of work, the less likely they are to find a job. So these women are not going to find it easy to find work even when their kids grow up.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The same problem afflicts the long-term unemployed. Britain has one of the <font size=-1>EU</font>'s lower unemployment rates. But almost four out of every ten unemployed Britons has been without a job for a year or more. Of the six countries surveyed by the Luxembourg Income Study, Britain (73.6%) and Belgium (76.5%) had, by far, the highest percentage of non-earners in the lowest 20%.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Evidently, the way out of the lowest fifth is through work: employment enables even the poorest of the poor to escape. Figures on what happens to the unemployed in the lower half of the bottom fifth prove the point. Households in that unfortunate position in 1991 accounted for a fifth of those who had escaped poverty altogether by 1992--someone in the household had found a job, or married someone in work. Doing neither means staying stuck.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Worse, the effect may stretch across generations. According to the <font size=-1>IFS</font>, sons of men who were unemployed for a week or more in the year their boys turned 16 were twice as likely to end up on the dole themselves. Other research shows that daughters from fatherless homes are more likely to become lone mothers. Although the growth of both groups seems to have stopped, they remain large (2.2m unemployed, 1.5m lone parents) and include many who, at best, are only intermittently connected to the world of work. And Britain has a greater proportion of children in the lowest fifth than any other country in the Luxembourg research.
</p><p><b>More or less equal</b></b>
<br>Moreover, inequality is increasing. In 1978, the bottom fifth took home almost 10% of the national income. By 1990 that was down to 7%, according to the <font size=-1>OECD</font>. Inequality in the 1980s increased faster in Britain than anywhere in Europe, though not as fast as in America. Tories say it is ridiculous to call the poor worse off because the rest of society grew richer. On the other hand, harsher forms of poverty, such as homelessness and temporary shelter, are more common. Real incomes in the bottom fifth have risen only 6% since 1979, less than for any other quintile--and that is before taking housing costs, which have risen in real terms, into account. Incomes actually fell for those likeliest to be in work (couples and childless single people) due to higher unemployment, fewer full-time jobs and higher housing costs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is a bleak picture--but perhaps an exaggerated one. Consumption among lower-income households is often considerably higher than reported income; the lowest fifth say they spend about &#163;23 a week more than they take in. That explains what many would regard as an extraordinary finding by Eurostat, the <font size=-1>EU</font>'s statistical agency: that Britain has narrowed the consumption gap between the top and bottom quarters of the population faster than any <font size=-1>EU</font> country (except Greece), even as inequality measured by incomes was rising. The link between income statistics and the standard of living is unreliable: transfers between family members, and the shadow economy, make a big difference.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That is unlikely to calm those who see growing inequality as the scandalous failure of the Tory years. Services for the poor tend to decline into poor services, it is often said--which is why the Labour Party has long opposed selection in schools. Frank Field, a prominent Labour <font size=-1>MP</font> whom Tony Blair appears to heed, admits that there is "no general groundswell amongst middle-class groups for redistribution of wealth to the poor". Nevertheless, it is also true that the apparent growth of inequality has made many Britons uneasy. It is this uneasiness which Mr Blair has tried to address with his idea of the "stakeholder society". Finding policies which can reconcile concern over inequality with suspicion of the means to reduce it will be far more difficult.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?825112800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br2.html">Next article</a>
</p></td></tr></table></body></html>
