<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p align=center><table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"><p><img src="brbrief.gif" alt="Britain"><p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table><hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<p><b>Bang to rights</b> &nbsp;
The European Court of Human Rights said that the power exercised by British home secretaries to overrule court recommendations on how long young offenders should stay in jail was a violation of human rights.</p>
<p><b>Double standards</b> &nbsp;
A letter written by Andrew Smith, a shadow treasury minister, appeared to admit that the government's plans to cut the annual cost of the social-security system by &#163;1 billion were feasible, even though Labour had publicly denounced the cuts.</p>
<p><b>Less majesty</b> &nbsp;
A <font size=-1>MORI</font> poll for the <i>Independent on Sunday</i> found that, for the first time, fewer people think the monarchy has a long-term future than those who do not. Only one in three adults thinks Britain would be worse off without a monarchy.</p>
<p><b>Deflated</b> &nbsp;
British Gas announced 1995 pre-tax profits of &#163;986m--down from &#163;1.3 billion in 1994--and admitted "a deterioration" in customer services. Labour attacked Richard Giordano, its chairman, for taking half his &#163;500,000 salary in dollars to avoid tax.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Careless</b> &nbsp;
The government dropped the term "care in the community" following repeated criticism that it meant abandoning the mentally ill. Its new policy slogan is "the spectrum of care" , emphasising that some patients will continue to be kept in mental hospitals.</p>
<p><b>Down the plughole</b> &nbsp;
It emerged that South West Water, many of whose customers have endured months of drought restrictions, allowed a billion gallons of water to pour into the sea, because of poor forecasting of demand.</p>
<p><b>Interesting</b> &nbsp;
Minutes of the January 17th meeting between Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, and Eddie George, governor of the Bank of England, showed that Mr George had preferred to wait a month before cutting interest rates. Mr Clarke cut them the next day.
</p>
<p><b>Because it was there</b> &nbsp;
Britain's mountain climbers held their first national conference--not on Mount Snowdon or Ben Nevis, but at sea level in the resort of Llandudno.</p>
</td></tr></table></p></center>
