<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="politics.gif" alt="Politics"></p>
<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>

<center><p align=center><table width=65%><tr><td valign=top width=30%>
<h3>End of a ceasefire</h3>The British and Irish governments broke off ministerial contacts with Sinn Fein after the <b>IRA</b> ended a 17-month ceasefire by detonating a 1,000lb bomb at Canary Wharf in London, which killed two people and caused damage estimated at up to &#163;100m ($155m). As attempts were made to keep the peace process on track, the British government sent more troops to Northern Ireland.<br>
<p><b>Boris Yeltsin</b> offered himself for re-election to Russia's presidency in June. His main rivals, so far, are the Communist leader, Gennady Zyuganov, whom opinion polls put well in the lead, the extreme nationalist, Vladimir Zhirinovsky, Grigory Yavlinsky, a liberal, and Alexander Lebed, a former general.<br>
<p>Bosnia's <b>peace was threatened</b> by a row between the Bosnian Serbs and <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s implementation force, Ifor, after it had sent two Bosnian Serb suspects to The Hague, where the <font size=-1>UN</font> war-crimes tribunal will hold its first trial on May 7th. Since then, the Bosnian Serb government has refused to talk to <font size=-1>NATO</font> officials. The presidents of Bosnia, Croatia and Serbia will be pressed to honour their peace-deal commitments when they meet Russian and western officials in Rome this weekend.<br>

<p>In the midst of a general election campaign, a former head of Spain's Constitutional Court was <b>assassinated </b>in Madrid by Basque terrorists.<br>
<p>Ukraine's president sacked the head of the country's security service, apparently after three Chinese had been deported allegedly for trying to buy designs for long-range <b>ballistic missiles</b>.<br>
<p>(<a href="wwchart.gif">See chart</a>)<br>
<p>Italy's stockmarket plunged after the prime minister-designate, Antonio Maccanico, failed to form what would would have been his country's 55th government since the second world war. A <b>general election</b> is now likely.<br>
<p>France's Roman Catholic bishops incurred the displeasure of the pope by saying that <b>condoms </b>"could be necessary" to combat the spread of <font size=-1>AIDS</font>.<br>
<h3>Feeling better</h3>
Saudi Arabia's <b>King Fahd</b>, who after a stroke had handed over to Crown Prince Abdullah, re-emerged to preside over a cabinet meeting.<br>
<p><b>Yasser Arafat</b> was sworn in as the first elected Palestinian president.<br>
<p>Israeli, Jordanian and Palestinian representatives, meeting in Oslo, signed an agreement on the management of <b>water resources</b>. An Iraqi official said that Iraq and Syria were considering taking joint action against European companies helping Turkey to build dams on the Euphrates.<br>

<p>Algeria's <b>Armed Islamic Group</b> moved against the country's crucial export industry by threatening to kill oil and gas workers.<br>

</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>

<p>In a renewed bid to persuade its 1m <b>Rwandan refugees</b> to return home, Zaire is harassing them and cutting off services.<br>
<p>A South African commission set about investigating<br>
<p>political crimes committed during the apartheid era: the aim, said Nelson Mandela, is <b>truth and forgiveness.</b><br>

<h3>Doleful</h3>The <b>Iowa caucuses </b>gave Bob Dole a decidedly lukewarm endorsement; he won 26% of the vote, against 23% for his fire-breathing rival, Pat Buchanan. Lamar Alexander, the former governor of Tennessee, enjoyed a rising fame; he won 18%. Steve Forbes, the flat-tax candidate, became a flash in the pan with 10%. Phil Gramm of Texas (9%, $20m spent) abandoned the race. The survivors moved on to New Hampshire.<br>
<p><b>Bill Clinton </b>won the Democratic caucuses with 100% of the vote.<br>
<p>The governor of <b>Kansas</b>, declaring that it was obvious Mr Dole would win in his state, cancelled the primary.<br>
<p>Bill Clinton signed an order barring companies from winning new federal contracts if they knowingly hired <b>illegal aliens</b>.<br>
<p>In <b>British Columbia</b>, negotiators announced an agreement on Nisga'a Indian land claims. It could set a Canadian pattern--if it wins general acceptance.<br>
<p><b>Argentina's</b> leftish Frepaso opposition coalition fell apart as Jose Octavio Bordon, its presidential candidate last year, quit to back an ex-Peronist instead of Frepaso's man as would-be mayor of Buenos Aires.<br>
<h3>Asian tension</h3>South Korea and Japan quarrelled over the ownership of three small islands in the <b>Sea of Japan</b>; South Korea said it would conduct military exercises near the islands. There were anti-Japanese demonstrations in Seoul. The islands, known as Tokdo in Korean and Takeshima in Japanese, are surrounded by rich fishing grounds.<br>
<p>A North Korean demanding <b>political asylum </b>at the Russian embassy in Pyongyang shot dead three Koreans guarding the building. He was himself later shot. Reports grew of more defections from the communist state, including that of Sung Hae Rim, a former wife of the Korean leader, Kim Jong Il.<br>
<p>The Karen, an ethnic minority which has been fighting for an <b>independent state</b> in Myanmarfor 47 years, said it would hold peace talks with the government.<br>
<p>A rocket carrying a $100m <b>communications satellite </b>exploded after taking off in China. And Japan's fledgling space programme also had a setback when a 4.4 metre (14ft) rocket-powered vehicle designed to be recovered was lost on re-entry.<br>
</td><tr></table></p></center>

