<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center><img src="wb.gif" alt="Business"></p>
<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>

<center><p align=center><table width=65%><tr><td valign=top width=30%>
<h3>A far horizon</h3>Hans Tietmeyer, president of the Bundesbank, added to speculation about the postponement of a single currency in Europe. He said that a delay in implementing economic and <b>monetary union</b> would create fewer problems than a derailment after the launch.<br>
<p>The European Parliament voted to tighten limits on the number of <b>foreign films </b>shown on television. The present rule, in which schedules should have at least 51% European content " where practicable", should no longer be discretionary, said the legislature. This pleased France, which is desperate to keep Hollywood at bay. But, this being Europe, the parliament's vote is unlikely to lead to a real change in any government's policy.<br>
<p>America is taking a complaint over <b>recorded-music rights </b>to the World Trade Organisation in an effort to force Japan to extend its copyright-protection laws, which came into force last month. The new rules protect recordings only back to 1971, leaving Bob Dylan and the Beatles among many others $500m a year short of royalties; the Americans want a 50-year rule.<br>
<h3>Industrial relic</h3>Edzard Reuter</b>, who as head of Daimler-Benz in 1987-95 took the German industrial group on a course of expansion that his successor, J&uuml;rgen Schrempp, is now reversing, is to step down from the supervisory board. He had said last May that the group's problems were largely over; but Mr Schrempp disclosed last month that Daimler-Benz would record a 1995 loss of DM6 billion ($4 billion).<br>
<p>America's <b>Trans World Airlines</b> announced its first operating profit since 1989. It made $25.1m in 1995, following a loss of $279.5m in 1994.<br>
<p>America's Time Warner, a big entertainment group, and <font size=-1>MAI</font>, a British broadcasting group that last week unveiled a &#163;3 billion merger with United News and Media, will together build a &#163;225m ($346m) combined <b>theme park and film studio</b> to the west of London.<br>
<p><b>Reuters</b> reported pre-tax profits up 17% to &#163;599m ($946m) last year. The cash-rich news and information group expects double-digit growth again this year and hopes to launch a share buy-back before the end of the year.<br>
<p>(<a href="wwchart1.gif">See chart</a>)<br>
<p>At a time when hugely expensive semiconductor factories are springing up everywhere, a <b>chip mountain</b> looms. The industry's measure of growth in North American chip sales plunged to its lowest point since allegations of Japanese chip-dumping in the 1980s. The "book-to-bill" ratio slid to 0.93 in January, as supply outstripped orders. Chip makers claim that this is no more than a blip.<br>

</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>

<p>At the request of <b>Eurotunnel</b>, a French court named two former leading politicians, one French, one British, to mediate with 225 creditor banks on restructuring the firm's FFr65 billion ($13 billion) debt. The company suspended interest payments last September. Revenue last year climbed rapidly but still amounted to only FFr2.27 billion.<br>
<p>America's <b>Mobil</b> launched a hostile A$1.24 billion ($940m) takeover for Ampolex, an Australian energy group. The bid added a 34% premium; Ampolex's shares rose 33%.<br>
<p>The man headhunted from Procter &amp; Gamble, America's consumer-products leader, to revive slumping profits at Italy's largest pasta maker unveiled his strategy. Edwin Artzt will cut prices by an average of 12% at <b>Barilla</b>, which produces a third of the country's pasta, half its ready-made sauces and 40% of bakery products.<br>
<p><b>Unilever</b>, an Anglo-Dutch consumer-products group,is to pay $770m for all outstanding shares in <b>Helene Curtis</b>, an American company making hair-care and skin-care products owned by the Gidwitz family of Chicago.<br>
<h3>Dizzy</h3>Four days after pushing through 5,500, the <b>Dow Jones </b>industrial average continued to break records to breach 5,600. The drop finally came after seven straight highs.<br>
<p><b>Lloyd's of London</b>, the troubled insurance market, outlined its planned allocation of a &#163;2.8 billion ($4.3 billion) settlement offer to loss-making names (the market's capital providers) who are suing for negligence. The settlement will be biased towards the strongest legal cases; a big chunk will also be used to fix a cap of &#163;100,000 on losses beyond any name's deposit at Lloyd's. Most names say the &#163;2.8 billion must be increased before they accept the plan.<br>
<p>Trading opened on the <b>Nouveau March&eacute</b>, France's new stock exchange for small companies.<br>
<p>Albania, once Europe's hardest-line communist state, is to open the <b>Tirana stock exchange </b>next month. The bourse will start modestly, trading government treasury bonds, privatisation vouchers and foreign currencies. Shares will come at a second stage; a British company, <font size=-1>GMA</font> Capital Markets, is training brokers for the big day.<br>
<p>(<a href="wwchart2.gif">See chart</a>)<br>
<p>Warren Buffett will at last allow shareholders in his <b>Berkshire Hathaway </b>investment group to split their holdings if they wish. With shares costing around $33,000 each, new investors of more modest means have been denied a stake in Mr Buffett's money-making machine. One existing "<font size=-1>A</font>" share will be convertible into 30 "<font size=-1>B</font>" shares, to be traded, though, in ten-share batches--and with fewer voting rights.
</td></tr></table></p></center>

