<html><head><title>More trouble on the track</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="br.gif"><p><font size=-1>These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=center valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>


<p><b>Rail privatisation</b></p>
<h2>More trouble on the track</h2>


<p>A NEW obstacle has appeared on the track of rail privatisation: the National Audit Office (<font size=-1>NAO</font>) has decided to launch an inquiry into the sell-off after opposition claims that the taxpayer is being cheated and that public assets are being sold for a song. Officials say there will probably be a series of individual reports on the sales of the 60 separate businesses into which British Rail is being split.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The auditors have already started looking into a number of sales, including that of the London-Tilbury-Southend line. The sale of the line was aborted after it was discovered that ticket sales were being fraudulently shuffled between stations in order to increase its revenues at the expense of London Underground's.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>NAO</font>'s belief that the government has cut corners in its rush to privatise the railways was fuelled by the leak on February 12th of a Department of Transport memo which sought to conceal irregularities in the sale of a British Rail maintenance depot at Eastleigh. Written by a senior official in the rail-privatisation directorate, it gave a warning that the sale of the depot to a management buy-out team may have been financed by cash reserves which competing bidders had not been told about. The civil servants had marked the document "Restricted--not for <font size=-1>NAO</font> eyes", thus arousing the suspicion of the sharp-eyed auditors. The department claims this to be agreed practice for documents responding to proposals for investigations by the <font size=-1>NAO</font>.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The memo, from Mike Fuhr, the civil servant with the job of monitoring rail privatisation, to the department's permanent secretary, Nick Montagu, quoted a report by a firm of accountants, Price Waterhouse. The report found that the management had bought the depot for &#163;7m even though it had cash balances of &#163;5.4m and a net worth of &#163;18.7m. Mr Fuhr described his concerns about the question of hidden cash balances, then listed a series of official omissions in the conduct of the Eastleigh sale, notably the lack of detailed documentation. He asked whether there were "any similar skeletons in other completed sales".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Officials dismiss the memo as "foolishly worded" and "out of date" . They say that a further study of the Eastleigh sale, by another accountancy firm, Ernst and Young, will clear all parties of wrongdoing.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The imminent privatisation of Railtrack, the company that owns the country's track and stations, is causing the opposite embarrassment. In order to avoid accusations that it is selling Railtrack too cheaply, the government is insisting that the company carry with it a debt of &#163;1 billion. Railtrack's directors, however, say that it cannot support so much borrowing. The argument needs to be resolved within the next fortnight if the privatisation is to happen as planned.

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?824508000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="contents.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br2.html">Next article</a>
</p></td></tr></table></body></html>
