<html><head><title>Grand ideas</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="br.gif"><p><font size=-1>These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.</ont></p></td><td></td>
<td align=center valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>

<p><b>Constitutional reform</b></p>
<h2>Grand ideas</h2>
<font size=1>EDINBURGH</font>
<p>LIKE his predecessors as Scottish secretary, Michael Forsyth has campaigned incessantly against Labour's plans for a devolved Scottish parliament. But unlike previous Tory Scottish secretaries, Mr Forsyth has a new ploy. A Labour government, he says, would not need to create a Scottish parliament because he has already done it for them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Most people, including Labour <font size=-1>MP</font>s, seem to have missed this, which is not surprising. Mr Forsyth is talking about changes he has made to the Scottish Grand Committee, a hitherto obscure part of the parliamentary apparatus on which Scotland's 72 <font size=-1>MP</font>s sit. Until recently, the committee's 12 annual meetings to discuss Scottish affairs were mostly ignored by the Scottish media even though they were held in Edinburgh.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Forsyth wants to change that. First, he has turned the committee into a travelling circus. Some 200 people turned up for a meeting on February 5th in Inverness where Mr Forsyth handed out goodies, including giving state-owned land to crofters.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Second, ministers now appear before the committee. In Aberdeen on February 19th Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, will be grilled on how his policies affect Scotland. Next month John Major, the prime minister, will undergo a similar ordeal.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The power to quiz non-Scottish Office ministers was part of a package of reforms grudgingly accepted by opposition parties last December. Similar changes to the Welsh Grand Committee proposed by William Hague, the Welsh secretary, have divided Welsh Labour <font size=-1>MP</font>s who are so far refusing to implement them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Thirdly, Mr Forsyth has given the committee power to take votes on some legislation. As there are only ten Scottish Tory <font size=-1>MP</font>s, this law-making power will be exercised only on non-controversial matters, such as legal reform. More controversial measures, even those applying only to Scotland, will still go through Westminster, where the Tories can rely on their marjority.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This shows, says Labour, that Mr Forsyth's scheme is a sham compared to Labour's plan for real devolution. Mr Forsyth, however, says that a Labour government would not need to set up a Scottish parliament as it could leave all its Scottish legislation to the Scottish Grand Committee where it would have a majority (Labour has 49 Scottish <font size=-1>MP</font>s at present).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is a transparent political gimmick which is most unlikely to persuade Tony Blair to drop devolution. But that is not Mr Forsyth's plan. He wants to convince Scottish voters that the government is interested in their grievances and that they do not need a Scottish parliament to do something about them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour, riding high on polls which give it the support of more than half of the Scottish electorate, has been slow to counter Mr Forsyth's agile campaigning. This complacency may yet cost the party dearly. Polls show that the Scots are overwhelmingly in favour of devolution, but they give it a lower priority than having a job and good hospitals. As for paying more tax--which Labour's devolution plans allow--they fancy that not at all. Like the rest of Britain's shambolic constitution, Mr Forsyth's scheme may not look much in theory. But unless Labour takes steps to counter it, it might yet work well enough to salvage a few Tory seats north of the border.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?824508000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="contents.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br4.html">Next article</a>
</p></td></tr></table></body></html>
